<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COACH SENDS LAKERS TO THE MOVIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ What does the story of a neo-Nazi skinhead
have to do with the Lakers' pursuit of an NBA championship?
</P>
<P>
   Only Lakers coach Phil Jackson knows for sure, and presumably,
his players have some idea now. Jackson employed one of his unique
teaching methods Thursday evening, splicing scenes from 1998's
``American History X'' into the team's usual film session.
</P>
<P>
   It was up to the players to decipher the lessons as they applied
to basketball, and to the Lakers' first-round playoff series
against the Sacramento Kings, which begins Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message was basically just letting us know that we've got
to tighten it up, got to be a lot more focused, got to know what
we're dealing with and be ready to step up to the challenge,'' said
Glen Rice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was pretty good,'' said Shaquille O'Neal. ``It
made us shift our minds every now and then. The parts of the movies
that he threw in, they were giving us like subliminal messages. You
have to be smart to understand a guy like Phil.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie features Ed Norton as a reformed skinhead who, having
undergone a transformation in prison, tries to prevent his younger
brother from making the same mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lively distraction from basketball nonsense,'' Jackson said,
playing coy about the message he was trying to send.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will say it has something to do with your past, and also
something to do with your future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson claimed he had a difficult time finding the right film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't happy with the movies. I have to speak to some of the
producers and directors in Hollywood about the motivational choices
that I had,'' he quipped. ``Actually, it wasn't a bad group of
pictures to look from, `The Green Mile' and so forth. But the
ultimate result is I didn't find anything that really fit the bill
for all of our players. `The Matrix' is another one that I thought
had something to do with being `in the moment,' that kind of play
that we were looking for.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's some things I think that go into this that are
individual, and there are some things that are collective for the
group. And more than anything else, I never show the film clip more
than five minutes during the course (of the film session). We do
mostly basketball work and we skip around.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a teaching method Jackson employed during his tenure with
the Chicago Bulls, and one he hopes to use again in the next two
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've usually used three (movies) during the course of the
playoffs. Hopefully we go that long and we can use three movies,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   SLOW START: The Lakers held their longest, hardest workout in
weeks on Friday, trying to recoup the precision that was missing in
losing the last two games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't that pleased,'' Jackson of the practice. ``We
couldn't keep the flow going, it was such a long practice. And
sometimes that happens. ... But guys stuck with it. Their energy
was good. ... Most of all, we have to recondition ourselves after
really backing off on our conditioning for the last week. So we
were pushing a little bit on that end of it, and I think we
accomplished what we wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   SHAQ STATEMENT: O'Neal, addressing his Wednesday scuffle with
San Antonio's David Robinson for the first time, said the elbow he
put in Robinson's chest was not intended as a statement. It had
been suggested that O'Neal was sending a message after taking
several hard fouls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't saying anything,'' O'Neal said. ``I think our focus
is going to be on Sacramento. And if (the Spurs) are around in the
second round, then I'll answer those questions. I do things that I
want to do, not because I'm trying to retaliate or trying to hurt
somebody. I just do it because I want to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Were the hard fouls from Robinson a message to O'Neal?
``Probably. Just something I have to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   OUCH REPORT: Bryant attended his media session with a massive
bag of ice taped to his sprained right wrist and admitted the
injury has affected his shooting ``a little bit.'' But Bryant
insisted it would not be a concern come game time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Sunday the adrenaline will be rushing a little too
much. I don't think I'll really think about it,'' he said. ``It
can't get any worse. The pain is pretty consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's only injury-related concern Friday was backup guard
Derek Fisher, who had to sit out part of practice because of
soreness from a bone spur in his right ankle. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
