<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4138 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-SERIAL-KILLER-SPI &LR;      04-22 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERIAL-KILLER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE ID VICTIMS LINKED TO SUSPECT IN SERIAL KILLINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LEWIS KAMB  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPOKANE _ They were daughters, sisters and mothers.
</P>
<P>
   They included the wayward teen who strayed from a life of music
and good grades; the 39-year-old grandmother who volunteered her
time at two local hospitals; the check-out clerk at a local
supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   Each was tangled in a life of drugs or worked as a prostitute.
Investigators say they were all killed by the same man: Robert Lee
Yates Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, authorities officially released the names of a dozen
women they say were killed by Yates, an Army helicopter pilot and
father of five.
</P>
<P>
   Blood drawn from Yates directly links him to nine of those
victims. Each had been shot and dumped in remote areas in Tacoma
and Spokane.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, other evidence now being analyzed likely ties Yates
to at least three more victims, investigators said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Police are also trying to determine whether Yates killed as many
as six other women. Five were found dead in Spokane; another in
Kitsap County.
</P>
<P>
   However, because at least five of those women were killed before
Yates moved to Spokane in 1996, investigators say someone else
could be responsible for those slayings.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Yates, 47, was charged with killing
16-year-old Jennifer Joseph, of Spanaway.
</P>
<P>
   Yates remains in custody under suicide watch at the Spokane
County Jail in lieu of $1.5 million cash bail.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Fasy, the veteran public defender assigned Thursday to
represent Yates, said Friday he hasn't ruled asking that a trial be
moved out of Spokane.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a no-brainer,'' Fasy said. ``Any capable attorney would
consider a change of venue in a case like this.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Yates is charged with one count of first-degree murder.
Steve Tucker, the county prosecutor, said he is not in a rush to
file the other charges.
</P>
<P>
   Police released the names of the 12 women they suspect were
killed by Yates at a press conference near Yates' South Hill home.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement brought some sense of closure for Kathy Lloyd.
For two days, Lloyd has stood behind a crowd of reporters waiting
for investigators to release the names. She wondered if her
sister's name was among them.
</P>
<P>
   She got her answer shortly after 10 a.m.: Shawna McClenahan, a
former hospital worker found dumped in rural Spokane the day after
Christmas 1997, is among the nine tied to Yates through his DNA,
investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just needed to hear her name,'' Lloyd said, ``I needed to
know for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Weary detectives who have worked around the clock here for more
than a week looked forward to spending Easter Sunday with their
families.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation, which could take at least two years to
complete and cost millions of dollars, has slowed considerably.
</P>
<P>
   Since Yates' arrest Tuesday, detectives have focused their
attention around the split-level beige house. They erected a mesh
wire fence and blue tarp around the yard.
</P>
<P>
   Yates lived in the East 49th Avenue home with his wife, Linda,
and four of their five children since March 1997. His wife, an
11-year-old-son, and four daughters, have been put up in a hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Another 22-year-old daughter did not live with the family.
</P>
<P>
   A county chaplan is keeping the children up to date on their
school work. officials have also provided the family with food and
clothing and are soliciting donations for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to treat the family with a lot of empathy and
sympathy,'' said Spokane County Sheriff Mark Sterk.
</P>
<P>
   Friday morning, detectives for the first time began processing
evidence inside the home. They completed a first round of
sophisticated mapping on the home's interior with Total Station
devices, camera-like equipment that will create a 3-D map of the
scene.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives also have painstakingly combed the tidy yard.
Investigators marked many ``areas of interest'' with little white
flags.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives said Friday they still looking for at least four more
cars Yates has owned or has been known to drive. They include a
1980 orange or red Mustang that Yates owned for a short time in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   The list of automobiles already siezed by investigators includes
three Hondas, a Ford pickup truck, two vans, and a white Corvette
that broke the case.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Corvette, detectives found a and blood that
investigators linked to Joseph, the 16-year-old prostitute who was
killed.
</P>
<P>
   Yates served 18 years in the military. He worked from 1995 to
1997 assembling elctronics components at a local business. Most
recently, he worked for $13 an hour as an overhead crane operator
at the Kaiser Aluminum smelter in Mead.
</P>
<P>
   Bud Alger, a neighbor who lives across the street from him, said
Friday that Yates often played catch with his children and taught
them how to ride bicycles outside his home.
</P>
<P>
   ``From all appearances, he was a very, very normal fella,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Alger said Yates sometimes worked on cars, too. He remembered
him tinkering on the white Corvette.
</P>
<P>
   And it was that flashy car that broke the case.
</P>
<P>
   Yolanda Carey told investigators that she saw Joseph in a car
that looked like a white Corvette a few days before Joseph's body
was found in August 1997. Joseph was in it with a white man in his
30s or 40s, she told them.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators began frequenting local Corvette owners clubs.
They obtained registrations from every Corvette owner in Washington
and Idaho, dumping hundreds of names into a computer database. They
put out alerts to police to watch out for white Corvettes. They
also alerted police to write down any suspicious stops they made in
areas known for prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   Two Spokane police officers took note of those alerts. The month
after Joseph's killing, an officer stopped Yates in a white
Corvette a few blocks from where Joseph was last seen. The officer
wrote down the incident.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1998, another police officer stopped Yates after he
picked up a known prostitute. The officer didn't cite him, but he,
too, wrote the incident down.
</P>
<P>
   Those two routine reports helped spring Yates name from the
database, investigators said. But it took time. The Spokane
Homicide Task Force didn't have the budget to pay for a computer
analyst, making it difficult to sift through the database.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in September last year, detectives began puting the
connections together. They called Yates in for questioning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
