<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4141 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-1STLD-WRITE     04-22 1256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE OFFICIALS HOLD OUT HOPE FOR ACCORD ON ELIAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla.)   (ADDS grafs 4-8 with details of talks; DELETES original 4th graf;
ADDS attribution to 12th graf)  
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Clinging to what appeared to be a frail hope for a
last-minute settlement of the custody battle over Elian Gonzalez,
Justice Department officials said Friday night that unnamed
intermediaries were working on an agreement under which the boy's
Miami relatives would immediately turn over the child to his
father.
</P>
<P>
   The department said in a statement that ``outside parties in
Miami are in the process of putting together a plan for a
cooperative resolution that would include the immediate transfer of
Elian to his father's care.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear who the unnamed parties were _
although some officials identified them as Miami political leaders
_ or whether the proposed agreement would be acceptable to the
Miami relatives, Elian's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, or the
Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   Department officials said an out- line of the plan had been sent
to lawyers for the Miami relatives and a lawyer for Elian's father,
Juan Miguel Gonzalez. Friday night, they said, Attorney General
Janet Reno tele- phoned Gregory Craig, the father's lawyer, to
discuss the plan.
</P>
<P>
   But the officials said it was un- clear whether either side
would agree to the proposed arrangement. Under the terms of the
proposed deal, officials said, Elian and his father would live
together probably in the Washington, D.C., area, but not at the
home of the Cuban diplomat where the father has stayed since he
arrived in the United States two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   In a counteroffer, Elian's father rejected a proposal that the
relatives live with the father and son while the appeals court
decides whether the child can remain in the United States, but
proposed to allow the boy's Miami relatives to make scheduled
visits with the child.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the evening, Reno remained at her office, shuttling
in- formation between Elian's father at the office of his lawyers
and repre- sentatives of the relatives in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   A day that began with Justice Department officials dourly
resigned to using force to retrieve the child ended with the
unexpectedly buoyant prospect that unofficial efforts might succeed
where the government had failed.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's father met earlier Friday with Attorney General Janet
Reno in what officials described as an emotional plea for his son,
but Reno emerged saying she could offer no specific timetable for
their reunion.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials said that throughout the day that Reno held
out the possibility, however remote, that the Miami relatives would
at last yield to the government's demands to relinquish the boy,
realizing that she was poised to use force to obtain custody of the
child.
</P>
<P>
   But people who have been follow- ing the case said that those
fragile hopes seemed to collapse after a private meeting between
the Justice Department community relations officials in Miami and
Elian's great uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, and his daughter,
Marisleysis, who has helped care for the boy.
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting, they said, department officials offered Elian's
Miami relatives a final chance to negotiate the boy's surrender to
authorities. But the relatives stood their ground, unrelenting in
their refusal to give up the boy unless his father came to Miami to
get him _ precisely the same conditions that led to the impasse.
</P>
<P>
   At the Justice Department, Reno and Doris Meissner, the
immigration commissioner, met for about 15 minutes with Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, the boy's father, who has asked that the government
fulfill its commitment to deliver Elian to him immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez left the department looking grim as officials said the
meeting was an emotional session in which the father pleaded to be
reunited with his son, saying that he and his child had suffered
through the long custody battle.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, in a written statement, Reno said that she
had little optimism. ``I could not commit to a particular course of
action or timetable,'' she said. ``I was deeply moved by Mr.
Gonzalez's evident love for his son. I assured him I would continue
working toward the goal of reuniting him with his child.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Reno told reporters that she still hoped to
resolve the stand-off. ``I'm exploring every possibility I can to
see this resolved peacefully, promptly and properly.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she was ready to dispatch federal agents to take the
child, Reno replied, ``If I were going to do something like that, I
certainly wouldn't tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   As the possibility of a peaceful solution ebbed away, Reno's
advisers seemed to have little advice left to give, relying on
outside parties to negotiate a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   By day's end, Reno sat in her fifth-floor office at the Justice
Department agonizing about whether and when to send a team of
federal agents to retrieve the child from the home of his
great-uncle.
</P>
<P>
   The relatives' defiance of government threats to take him
forcibly energized the demonstrations in the neighborhood where
Elian has been staying since he was rescued from the Atlantic last
Thanksgiving after his mother and others drowned in an attempt to
flee Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the home of Lazaro Gonzalez, several hundred
Cuban-Americans continued to bask in Wednesday's court victory but
remained concerned that the government might try to remove the boy
and reunite him with his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``What worries me is that they'll try to get the boy at night,''
said Carlos Hernandez, 45.
</P>
<P>
   ``They might try to fool us. They might say one thing and do
another, so you never know.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban exiles, however, were determined to prevent efforts to
take the boy. Dozens of people, rosaries in hand or carrying wooden
crosses, prayed for divine intervention. Others chanted, ``Elian,
my friend, God is with you,'' in Spanish. Still others vowed to
give their lives should government agents appear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have fought for this and we won't get up,'' said Reynaldo
Ramos, 57. ``We won't leave until this thing is over.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd periodically was buoyed by the appearance of the boy,
who would scramble into the yard and wave to admirers before
ducking back into the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elian, you won't go! Elian, you won't go!'' the crowd chanted
in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Although Reno remained reluctant throughout the day to give the
final authorization to begin the operation, immigration officers
and federal marshals readied a plan to sweep unannounced in the
Little Havana neighborhood after days of surveillance to gauge when
they were likely to encounter the least resistance.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said that the operation could come at any time
over the weekend or early next week. The officials acknowledged
that any tactical maneuver would probably be complicated by the
increasingly vocal protesters who gathered Friday in the
neighborhood and said they would form a human chain to stop
authorities from removing the boy.
</P>
<P>
   As efforts to resolve the issue progressed, some Florida
political leaders sought more time for mediation. In a letter to
President Clinton and Reno, Gov. Jeb Bush of Florida, a Republican,
said that negotiations should be given another chance.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said using force was ``unwise and unwarranted'' and that
``mediation not confrontation is what is in young Elian's best
interest at this critical point in time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 0021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
