<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERSHISER GOES TO BULLPEN, FOR NOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Orel Hershiser was signed to pitch out of the
bullpen, and now he's there. For how long, though, is another
matter.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Davey Johnson said lefty Carlos Perez will start
Sunday's series finale against Cincinnati, right-hander Darren
Dreifort will throw Monday in New York and, providing everything
goes well with bullpen sessions the next two days, Kevin Brown will
return Tuesday in his native Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   If Brown, on the disabled list with a broken right pinkie, can't
pitch Tuesday, Hershiser would make the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it kind of fits having Orel backing up Brownie,''
Johnson said. ``Then I don't have to impact five other guys.''
</P>
<P>
   How long the plan remains intact is a question, particularly
given Perez's fragile existence in the rotation and the waning
patience of the organization.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers set him up to succeed, which Perez acknowledges.
They held him back from starting against Houston earlier in the
week and will throw him against a Reds team that has left-handed
Ken Griffey Jr., Sean Casey and Eddie Taubensee in their lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a good idea not to use me against Houston
because they don't have enough lefties in the lineup,'' said Perez,
who is 1-1 with a 5.65 ERA. ``Cincinnati has a bunch of lefties.
That's why I don't complain anymore of `Why are they doing this?
Why are they doing that?' Whatever they do to me is not a
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   But the consequences of failure could be dire for Perez. He's
pitched adequately with a big lead in a win against San Francisco
and settled down to pitch moderately well in relief after Hershiser
hit four batters and allowed seven runs in 11/3 innings Wednesday
against Houston.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the time issue. With five years of major-league
service, a player must accept a minor-league assignment. Perez
reaches five years May 6.
</P>
<P>
   However, Johnson said he's also looking down the road at having
a lefty in the rotation against Arizona and St. Louis during a
grueling four-city road trip in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel (Perez) is getting enough work to where he can locate
better, change speeds better, pitch out front,'' Johnson said.
``And he did that after that first (outing in Montreal).''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also wanted Dreifort to pitch against the Mets based on
past success. Dreifort held them to two hits (though he walked
eight) in five innings two weeks ago. Eric Gagne and Chan Ho Park
make up the rest of the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I end up in the bullpen for awhile, I don't think it's a
surprise because that was the role I was kind of signed to,'' said
Hershiser, who's 1-1 with an 8.76 ERA. ``If I end up in the
rotation, that's not a surprise, either, because I've done that my
whole life.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers want Brown to have his normal outing, and Johnson
said he doesn't want his ace pitching in New York, where he was
injured. Also, Brown's been successful against the Braves _ he's
4-2 with a 2.18 ERA in 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   However, Brown said he's not ready to declare himself back in
the rotation until his bullpen sessions are complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Brown) just wants back out there,'' Johnson said. ``You talk
to him long enough, and he says, `I don't want to mess up everybody
else, either.' But we still don't even know until (Saturday).''
</P>
<P>
   LARKIN INJURED, HAS SURGERY: Reds shortstop Barry Larkin had
surgery on the middle finger of his left hand after injuring it
while diving after Mark Grudzielanek's single in the second inning.
Larkin tore a ligament in the finger and is expected to miss 2-4
weeks. He was placed on the disabled list, and Gookie Dawkins was
expected to be added to the roster.
</P>
<P>
   ODDS AND ENDS: The umpiring crew's equipment was lost on its
flight from Toronto to Cincinnati, delaying the start of the game
27 minutes. The Reds had to buy equipment for them from a local
sporting goods store. ... Left fielder Gary Sheffield's right ankle
still hasn't healed, though he continues to play. It swelled during
the flight from Los Angeles to Cincinnati and was still swollen
before the game with the Reds. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
