<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4155 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-CASINO-1STLD-WRITE     04-22 1210
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CASINO-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-1100(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOHAWKS SIGN EXCLUSIVE DEAL WITH WORLD'S LARGEST GAMBLING COMPANY
</HEADLINE>
  (ADDS company agreeing to build gaming facilty within 36 months in
3rd graf) 
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT32 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The leaders of the St. Regis Mohawk tribe, who were
on the verge of gaining approval to build a $500 million casino in
the Catskills, have turned their back on that plan and signed a
highly unusual agreement with the largest gambling company in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would turn over exclusive rights to build, develop and
manage any Mohawk casinos in New York state to the company, Park
Place Entertainment, the owner of three casinos in Atlantic City,
according to copies of the agreement given to The New York Times by
people who deal with the tribe. Those rights could be worth
billions of dollars, gambling industry experts said.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the impoverished Mohawks would receive a $3 million
loan and a large percentage of the profits from any casino,
although some industry experts doubt that Park Place will ever
build a Mohawk gambling hall. That is one of the many unanswered
questions surrounding the deal. It is unclear, for example, whether
the agreement would stand up to federal scrutiny or a challenge by
the tribe's original casino partners. &UR;  &LR; The company says in the
agreement that it will begin building a ``gaming facil- ity''
within 36 months.
</P>
<P>
   What is clear is that the agreement _ negotiated by Arthur M.
Goldberg, the chief executive of Park Place Entertainment, with the
help of former U. S. Sen. Alfonse M. D'Amato _ will almost
certainly delay the coming of any casino to the Catskills for
years. Some analysts question whether that was the intent.
</P>
<P>
   The Catskill Development Group, which had planned to donate 30
acres to the tribe for a casino in Monticello, N.Y., in return for
a share of the revenue, learned only Thursday night about the
secret agreement, which was signed by six tribal chiefs and
Goldberg on April 14. Robert Berman, a partner in the development
group, which said the tribe was being misled by what he said were
Goldberg's promises to build a casino in the Catskills within four
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the greatest rip-off of an Indian tribe since the
Dutch grabbed Manhattan for $24,'' Berman said. ``We hope that the
tribe will understand that Park Place is a wolf in sheep's clothing
whose true intention is to kill the casino in Monticello to protect
their interests in Atlantic City. The tribe is selling out its
future for a $3 million loan. But I still believe there's an
opportunity for the tribe to salvage this.''
</P>
<P>
   Berman said he believes the tribe could renounce the Park Place
deal on technical grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Trump and other Atlantic City casino operators _ but not
Goldberg _ have spent millions lobbying in Albany against the
Monticello casino, which they believe would cut into their profits
by attracting gamblers from New York City and northern New Jersey.
Analysts have said the Monticello casino would draw 9.3 million
visitors a year and generate more than half a billion dollars a
year in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Goldberg nor the company's general counsel, Clive
Cummis, returned telephone calls Friday requesting comment. Both
men were at the Mohawks' Akwesasne Reservation Friday on the
Canadian border in Hogansburg, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Gus McDonald, the tribe's executive director, and the six chiefs
who signed the agreement also did not return telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   The tribal clerk, Carol Herne, and a former Mohawk chief,
Barbara Lazore, both said they were appalled by the deal with Park
Place. The two women said they confronted Goldberg at a restaurant
on the reservation Friday, where he was meeting with the tribal
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't allow this project to go down the drain,'' Lazore
said. ``I don't believe they're here to help the Monticello
project. It'd be the No. 1 competition to Atlantic City.''
</P>
<P>
   Casino gambling is unconstitutional in New York, but sovereign
Indian lands are an exception. Only 16 days ago, the federal
Interior Department approved a four-year-old proposal in which
Berman's group would get around the constitutional problem by
giving the federal government 30 acres next to the Monticello
Raceway in trust for the Mohawks. The Monticello casino plan is now
awaiting approval by Gov. George Pataki and, possibly, the state
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   But even as Berman's application was approved in Washington,
Mohawk tribal leaders were being wooed in secret by Goldberg and
his adviser, D'Amato, according to tribal executives, rival casino
operators and Catskill Development. The six tribal chiefs signed
the Park Place agreement without consulting the lawyers the tribe
had hired to work on gambling issues, according to two tribal
advisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This seems to add a whole new dimension to an already complex
situation,'' said Michael McKeon, a spokesman for Pataki. ``We'll
need to review the document closely. It appears to have some
significant implications.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato, a longtime adviser to Goldberg, is also close to the
governor. The former senator did not return calls, but Wayne
Berman, D'Amato's partner, said their consulting company ceased
representing Park Place on April 14, the day the agreement was
signed with the Mohawks. Wayne Berman, who is no relation to Robert
Berman, declined to discuss D'Amato's work on behalf of Park Place.
An official in the Pataki administration said that D'Amato had
stepped down as Park Place's consultant to prevent his friendship
with the governor from putting Pataki in an awkward position.
</P>
<P>
   The Park Place deal with the Mohawks is unusual, experts said,
because Indian tribes routinely grant casino development rights for
specific locations, but experts say that no tribe has ever given
exclusive rights to as large a territory as New York state.
</P>
<P>
   In return for granting Park Place exclusive development rights,
tribal leaders received a $3 million loan from the casino company
``for use by the tribe in its discretion.'' The tribe presumably
would use the money to bolster its small money-losing casino in
Hogansburg, where the Mohawks recently ousted the existing operator
as part of a separate deal with Park Place. The Mohawks would also
get 70 percent of the profits from every casino, after Park Place
is reimbursed for any advances.
</P>
<P>
   The casino development agreement would not cover the Hogansburg
casino or a proposal that just surfaced last year for a Mohawk
casino in Green County.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Ader, an analyst with Bear Stearns, said Goldberg was
playing a shrewd game of chess. On the one hand, he said, Goldberg
could be using the prospect of a first-class casino in the
Catskills to scare off other companies that are considering
building new casinos in Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, does he ever want to get it built?'' Ader
said. ``With one-third of his profits coming from Atlantic City,
the expansion of gaming in New York could be detrimental to this
franchise.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There is little question that the Mohawks want new casinos to
provide the tribe with money and jobs. Unemployment on the Mohawks'
Akwesasne reservation ranges from 35 to 40 percent. But the
year-old casino on the reservation in Hogansburg loses about
$300,000 a month. This week, the tribe ousted the operator, Ivan
Kaufman, a Long Island businessman. The tribal leaders plan to
operate that casino themselves, under a separate consulting
agreement with Park Place.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview earlier this month, one tribal executive
expressed concern that Alpha Entertainment, a gambling company that
is working with Catskill Development, would not gain the approval
of the National Indian Gaming Commission, which oversees casino
management contracts signed by Indian tribes. Desperate to avoid
another Hogansburg catastrophe, the tribal leaders looked to the
largest casino operator in the world for salvation.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of simply buying out Alpha Entertainment and replacing
it, however, Goldberg sought to take over completely. But one
tribal adviser said that Goldberg's promise to build a casino for
the tribe in Sullivan County within four months was absurd. The
Interior Department approved a specific proposal at the Monticello
Raceway. Any new proposal would have to undergo environmental and
regulatory approval, which could take years.
</P>
<P>
   Questioning whether Park Place's promises to the tribe could
ever be delivered, one Mohawk adviser said, ``The chiefs are so
obsessed with the on-reservation casino that they've lost sight of
the larger picture.''
</P>
</TEXT>
