<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CONN-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CONNECTICUT'S CAMPAIGN FINANCE BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, April 22:
</P>
<P>
   The cause of campaign reform has long commanded broad support in
Connecticut. Last week the Legislature passed an ambitious bill to
impose voluntary limits on campaign spending, require disclosure of
donors and provide public financing of campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would go a long way toward cleaning up the state's
politics, which were marred by a scandal involving a former state
treasurer last year. However, Gov. John Rowland has said he finds
the bill flawed and may not sign it. Rowland should sign, and if
necessary work to correct any problems that emerge as the measure
is put into effect.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland, a Republican, has never made campaign reform a major
issue, and like many members of his party he is skeptical of the
idea of public financing of campaigns. But the traditional
Republican argument against using taxpayers' money for politics is
undercut by many polls showing widespread popular support. In any
case, the money for campaigns would come from a taxpayer checkoff
on tax forms, which is how federal funding of presidential
campaigns has worked for many years.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut approach is creative. Statewide candidates would
receive significant subsidies, and legislative candidates would get
money only if their opponents exceeded spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   The governor cites the fact that few Republicans supported the
measure when it was going through the Legislature, which is
controlled by Democrats. But among Connecticut Republicans,
campaign reform is a strong issue. Rep. Christopher Shays is a
champion in Congress, and Sen. John McCain won the Connecticut
primary by making reform a centerpiece of his presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It is rare that a bill on campaign reform gets through any
legislative body. Rowland should approve the measure, and if any of
the spending limits are unworkable, as he suggests, he can try to
change the law in the future. For now, he should honor the desire
of Connecticut citizens to give reform a chance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
