<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TWINS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLUMPING RANGERS SUCCUMB TO TWINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ One of the cardinal rules for a big-league
pitcher, right up with ``throw strikes'' and ``keep the ball
down,'' is ``retire the side in order the inning after your team
takes a lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Clark violated the rule last night, and he and the Rangers
paid dearly.
</P>
<P>
   The penalty for the rules violation was a 10-5 loss to the
Minnesota Twins last night at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   The defeat ended a 13-game winning streak against the Twins
dating to Sept. 7, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the monkey off our back,'' Twins manager Tom Kelly
said. ``We hadn't beaten them in 17 years.''
</P>
<P>
   It also extended the Rangers' losing streak to a season-worst
five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is we're not playing very well,'' Rangers
manager Johnny Oates said. ``We're not getting hits at crucial
times of the ballgame, we're not making pitches at crucial times,
we're not making defensive plays at crucial times, and the manager
isn't making the right decisions at crucial times.''
</P>
<P>
   The record will show Twins first baseman Ron Coomer clubbed the
Rangers into submission with two homers and seven runs batted in,
including a game-clinching three-run shot in the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Coomer might not have had a chance to be a hero, though, if
Clark had made the pitches in the crucial sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers scored two runs in the fifth to take a 5-3 lead,
which given their recent history against the Twins appeared to be
plenty.
</P>
<P>
   But Clark, who was 7-0 with a 2.62 earned-run average in his
career against Minnesota, walked Butch Huskey on four pitches to
lead off the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's like a sin,'' Clark said. ``Your team goes ahead and
you walk the first guy on four pitches. I wanted to shoot myself. I
was trying to throw it right down the middle, and I couldn't throw
a strike.''
</P>
<P>
   He threw a strike to Midre Cummings, but he doubled. Clark threw
a wild pitch to allow Huskey to score, and Coomer then singled to
drive in Cummings with the tying run and knock Clark from the game.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Munoz came in and gave up a single and a ground ball that
allowed Coomer to score the go-ahead run.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you score two runs to take the lead, the last thing you
want to do is walk the leadoff guy,'' Oates said. ``Then boom,
boom, two base hits later, we're behind again.''
</P>
<P>
   That changed the whole complexion of the game.
</P>
<P>
   If Clark did the job in the sixth, Oates could play matchups
with his bullpen in the seventh, go to setup man Tim Crabtree in
the eighth and closer John Wetteland in the ninth. Instead, he had
to go to the bullpen early and use his relievers in positions he
doesn't like to.
</P>
<P>
   Munoz had to finish the sixth and start the seventh, and gave up
a run on two hits. Right-hander Francisco Cordero pitched two
scoreless innings to get the game to the ninth, but instead of
Wetteland in the game with a lead, lefty Mike Venafro was in with a
deficit. It grew when he served up Coomer's three-run shot.
</P>
<P>
   The bad outings by Clark, Munoz and Venafro came at a bad time.
Justin Thompson is close to returning from his rehabilitation
assignment, and when he comes back Oates said it could impact the
entire pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't get too comfortable,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Clark lost for the first time after two victories, but his ERA
rose to 7.47. Thompson could take his spot in the rotation as early
as May 2.
</P>
<P>
   And with the Rangers continuing to lose, Munoz (16.87 ERA) and
Venafro (7.20 ERA) could feel some heat to keep their jobs if they
don't start performing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our left-handers aren't getting too many people out right
now,'' Oates said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
