<HEADLINE>
BRETT HULL _ WHO ELSE _ SCORES THE WINNER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Stars winger Brett Hull hadn't been talking lately. He
said he didn't have anything to say, felt he had been struggling a
bit, too.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of days ago, though, he winked that sly wink he has and
said: ``I'll be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, just when you think Hull is dead and buried, he comes
bouncing back, scoring the goals he loves to score _ Cup-clinching,
series-snatching, game-winning, and always dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   Last night's was the series-snatching variety, a wrist shot to
propel the Stars past the Oilers, 3-2, in Game 5 of first-round,
best-of-seven series. With a snap of his wrist, he sent the Oilers
back to Edmonton and the Stars to the second for the third
consecutive summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference is just a mistake and a hell of a shot by
Hull,'' Oilers coach Kevin Lowe said. ``He has an uncanny ability
to do squat the whole game and come up with big goals late.''
</P>
<P>
   The puck slipped over Oilers goalie Tommy Salo's shoulder with
5:02 remaining in the game, not to mention Edmonton's season. The
play began when center Joe Nieuwendyk, who finished with two
assists, skated across the blue line. He left a drop pass for Hull,
who unleashed the wrist shot that won the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I am supposed to do,'' Hull said. ``That's my job.
I live to score goals. ... I just shot that one, to be honest with
you. It was a big one for everyone. The last thing we wanted to do
was go back to Edmonton.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars will play Colorado or San Jose, depending on who wins
the Sharks-Blues series. The Sharks lead 3-2 with Game 6 scheduled
for tomorrow in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of good teams right now, and we are one of
them,'' Nieuwendyk said. ``This is a confidence builder for us to
get out in five and get a rest.''
</P>
<P>
   They had to fight and claw for every inch of it, too.
</P>
<P>
   That's the beauty of the Oilers. That's the beauty of what Hull
did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God, we got Brett Hull,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock
said. ``The difference is one shot by a player who can score goals.
He has scored some big goals for this organization, and he did it
again. That was the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the game-winning goal came off the stick of Hull as time
dripped away in Period No. 3. But the Stars were in the game
because of the saves made by Stars goalie Ed Belfour up until that
point.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us celebrate our birthdays by blowing out candles on a
cake.
</P>
<P>
   On his 35th birthday, Belfour extinguished the Edmonton Oilers
instead. On the verge of elimination, the Oilers threw everything
they had _ wrist shots, slap shots, bouncing nubbers _ at him in
the third period.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Belfour was done with the Oilers, all that was left
was the end-of-series handshakes.
</P>
<P>
   He finished with 24 saves, including eight in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was huge tonight,'' Stars forward Kirk Muller said. ``It
was one of the best games he's had in the series. He made every big
save tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Say this for Edmonton, they refused to go away.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars had a 2-1 lead heading into the third period. Twenty
minutes was all that stood between them and the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Oilers forward Jim Dowd ruined that one minute and seven seconds
into the period. He banked a shot in off Stars defenseman Derian
Hatcher's skate to tie the game at 2-all.
</P>
<P>
   This was the second Stars lead they erased.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars took a 1-0 lead at 5:35 of the second period on a goal
by Stars winger Jamie Langenbrunner, his first of the series.
Believe it or not, it was on the play. They finished the series
2-for-26 with a man advantage.
</P>
<P>
   They actually had a five-on-three. But as Oilers winger Bill
Guerin scrambled out of the box, Mike Modano floated a pass down to
Nieuwendyk alongside the Stars' net. Nieuwendyk faked a shot and
instead hit Langenbrunner in the deep slot.
</P>
<P>
   Oilers winger Todd Marchant tied the game at 12:45 of the second
period when he tapped his own rebound past Belfour. It wasn't two
minutes later that Stars captain Derian Hatcher sent a wrist shot
flying past Salo for a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Which is how it stayed until Dowd did his work.
</P>
<P>
   So back and forth they went, trading chances and trading panic.
Edmonton is, after all, the team that upset Dallas in the first
round in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty emotionally draining,'' Stars winger Brenden
Morrow said. ``And in a back and forth game like that, it comes
down the stretch. It would've been easier on us if we would've had
a couple-goal cushion. It was close right to the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly the spot Hull was signed for.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that everybody knows that's he's got the gun and he
can change a game,'' Muller said. ``Tonight's it's a tight game and
all of a sudden `Boom.' '' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
