</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-DISCONTENT (Dili, East Timor) _ The desperation of East
Timor's unemployed, and the first spasms of violence it has
spawned, are the sharpest signs of a swelling discontent in this
physically and emotionally traumatized land. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-THERAPY (Undated) _ Now people are even turning to the
Internet for counseling: They plug in a credit card number and
begin engaging in e-mail counseling with a psychologist or other
therapist. To the excitement, and alarm, of experts in the field,
new mental-health sites are beginning to pop up on the Web almost
daily, and many are offering the type of counseling once offered
only in the intimacy of a psychiatrist's office. By Ellen Almer.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-COURT (Undated) _ Although the 11th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals suggests that Elian Gonzalez is entitled to apply for
asylum on his own, what exactly are the precedents for a court's
listening to a child as young as 6? By William Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   DEATHROW-TERRELL (Houston, Texas) _ A profile of Charles
Terrell, a former corrections commissioner for whom Texas' very
active death row facility is named. By Jim Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CONSERVATIVES (Washington) _ In an extraordinary retreat
from traditional Republican tenets, Gov. George W. Bush has in
recent weeks advocated an expansion of the federal role on programs
ranging from education to low-income housing to health care. And he
has made overtures to constituencies, like gays and gun-control
proponents, that have never been mainstays of his own party. Yet
what is most striking about Bush's repositioning in the nine weeks
since the South Carolina primary, when he presented himself as an
unflinching conservative, is that prominent fiscal and social
conservatives _ many of whom have been outspoken about past
nominees _ have been silent. Not one leading conservative
organization has aggressively spoken out against Bush. By Richard
L. Berke.
</P>
