   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-DRUGS (Washington) _ White House officials are
assessing Republican proposals for Medicare coverage of
prescription drugs, which President Clinton so far sees as totally
inadequate. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-TELECOM (London) _ The British government will likely
end its auction of next-generation mobile phone licenses next week,
and then the next telecommunications battle begins: A furious
bidding war is set for Orange, the British wireless provider that
Vodafone AirTouch must shed. France Telecom, MCI Worldcom and
Telefonica are expected to make offers. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FANNIE-MAE (Washington) _ Fannie Mae, the giant company created
by the government decades ago to help make mortgages available to
home buyers, is in the middle of a firestorm. Together with several
smaller government-chartered corporations, Fannie Mae could soon
supplant the federal government as the benchmark for
creditworthiness in the bond market, a possibility that has already
set off emotional sparring between the company and the Treasury
Department. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
