<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4182 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-TELEVISION-NEWS-LADN     04-22 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELEVISION-NEWS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIEWERS ABANDON HYPE, SENSATION OF TV NEWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;     Eds: L.A. Daily News Staff Writer Jason Kandel contributed to
this story  
 &HT;    
 &HT;     By HARRISON SHEPPARD 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  LOS ANGELES _ Coming up next! A story that we'll promote
endlessly without telling you what happened! Live at 11!
</P>
<P>
   If that sounds familiar, then you probably agree with the 28
percent of TV viewers who said in a new nationwide survey that
local television news promotions are misleading and downright
irritating.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also found 45 percent believe local TV unduly
sensationalizes the news, and 10 percent now refuse to watch any
news shows _ twice as many as a decade ago. In some metropolitan
areas, the figure was as high as 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a sense among a large portion of the audience that the
stations just don't respect their intelligence,'' said Scott
Tallal, whose marketing research firm, Insite Media Research of
Malibu, conducted the scientific phone survey of 402 people in
October.
</P>
<P>
   Television news directors and anchors said they have gotten the
poll's message and are working to tone down coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the appetite for what was acceptable has changed,''
said Jose Rios, news director of KTTV (Channel 11).
</P>
<P>
   ``You no longer have a `Hard Copy' or `A Current Affair.'
There's a reason people got tired of it. I think local news
stations, many of whom do a fairly credible job, are looking to
continue doing that. And some of them who were involved in hype are
less so now.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger Bell, news director at KCBS (Channel 2), said the survey
points out questions he and his colleagues grapple with every
newscast.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we ignore the viewers, they're going to ignore us,'' he
said. ``I don't think there is a station in town that wants this.
There's constant discussion in our newsroom: `Did we write the
story properly? Did we write the promotion properly?' This is
what's called journalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope every newsroom in town does that. Are we human? Do we
make mistakes? Yes, we do. Things move fast in television. There's
a lot of pressure on TV to perform.''
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, many people still watch local television news in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The latest Nielsen ratings, for the February 2000 sweeps period,
shows the top station at 1 p.m., KNBC (Channel 4), got an 8.1
rating _ or about 405,000 homes. Each point represents 50,000 local
households.
</P>
<P>
   According to one expert, that number is down significantly from
the 1970s when he said the presentation of TV news was more
straightforward, honest and sober.
</P>
<P>
   In the '70s, it was common for a station to have a 12 or 14
Nielsen rating, said Joe Saltzman, who worked for CBS news and now
is associate dean of the University of Southern California's
Annenberg School for Communication.
</P>
<P>
   Some of that loss is due to more competition from more
newscasts, plus cable, satellite and the Internet, he added.
</P>
<P>
   But much of the loss in viewership is a result of frustration
and irritation over promotions and sensational coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to choke them,'' said Saltzman. ``I've thrown things
at the TV set, I've been so angry.''
</P>
<P>
   When Saltzman worked in TV news, the promos at least explained
the story, he said. For example, they would say that ``The Dodgers
won tonight. We'll have details at 11,'' instead of ``The Dodgers
played tonight. We'll tell you what happened at 11.''
</P>
<P>
   He said today's style was an effort by station owners to win
over a younger, hipper audience _ one presumed to have a shorter
attention span _ rather than the older viewers who long were the
mainstay of TV news. But what happened, he said, is TV lost older
viewers without making up the loss with younger ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``They alienated that audience and kicked it in the shins and
chased it away,'' Saltzman said. ``And you can't get it back now.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the poll, about half of today's viewers said they
don't care which station they watch, indicating a declining loyalty
to particular newscasts and anchors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's irritating,'' said Bryce Neff, 75, a retired West Hills
resident. ``Some of the stuff sounds very important when they give
you a little bit _ then you're supposed to wait around for four
hours to hear the rest of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The practice has driven Neff, a retired attorney, to switch away
from viewing the major network stations and start watching Fox
affiliate KTTV, which he says is not nearly as annoying.
</P>
<P>
   Another study found in 1998 much more positive opinions about
local TV news.
</P>
<P>
   The study by the Radio and Television News Directors Foundation
suggests that the public relies on and trusts local television
news. Sixty-six percent of viewers deemed local television news to
be excellent or good, while only 8 percent gave it a grade of poor.
</P>
<P>
   Insite typically conducts confidential studies for television
news and entertainment companies, none in Los Angeles. Insite
conducted this study, at a cost of about $20,000, to draw attention
to an issue that affects all its clients, Tallal said. Insite's
clients were given the results privately in November.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 0203EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
