<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-STANFORD-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANFORD DODGES DISASTER, BEATS USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC's baseball team managed to beat the odds
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans loaded the bases three times without scoring a run
as they fell to No.4 Stanford 4-1 in a Pac-10 game in front of 825
at Dedeaux Field.
</P>
<P>
   USC (27-16, 8-6) stranded 10 runners total and had its most
dubious shortcoming in the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   With Stanford (30-10, 10-4) holding a tenuous 2-1 lead, the
Trojans seemed done in the inning after Beau Craig grounded into a
double play, but they loaded the bases with two outs on a single,
an infield error and a walk.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bruksch, who relieved Jason Young, struck out USC's Bill
Peavey on a 3-2 pitch to end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   After Craig Thompson hit a two-run home run in the ninth to pad
Stanford's lead, Bruksch earned his conference-leading ninth save.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys have been doing that all season,'' Stanford coach
Mark Marquess said. ``Obviously we weren't real comfortable in that
situation, but we made some big pitches and we had a couple big
hits earlier in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford owed its early lead to former Camarillo High two-sport
star Joe Borchard, who singled and scored in the second inning and
hit a solo home run to lead off the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were just two good pitches to hit,'' said Borchard,
splitting his spring time between baseball and football, where he
is also trying to become the Cardinal's starting quarterback. ``I
was able to stay on both of them long enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Borchard, who struck out in his final two at-bats, also hit a
home run in Thursday's loss to the Trojans. The junior
switch-hitter has 10 home runs and 42 RBI and was hitting .288
going into the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a little upset about his batting average, but he's
been doing a good job,'' Marquess said. ``He seems to be doing
better since football practice started, so maybe the football coach
deserves a little credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Borchard's homer gave Stanford a 2-1 lead, and one run was all
the margin needed by Young. He survived a rocky first inning to
dazzle the Trojans and improve to 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Trojans tagged Young for four runs in five
innings, but the junior right-hander kept USC off-balance Friday
with a piercing fastball and good movement on his breaking pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't say enough about the way Jason pitched,'' Borchard
said. ``He got in some tough situations put he did exactly what we
needed him to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans took a 1-0 lead when Craig's slow grounder got under
the glove of Stanford second baseman Chris O'Riordan. Justin Gemoll
followed with a single and Rob Garibaldi walked to load the bases,
but Young escaped by getting Anthony Lunetta to line out to short.
</P>
<P>
   Young wouldn't allow another hit until the eighth, but he did
load the bases in the fifth by plunking three Trojans with errant
pitches. With two outs, however, Craig tapped a grounder to first
to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans made starting pitcher Mark Prior a tough-luck loser
again. Prior, who started the season 4-1, has not earned a victory
since March 3 and in winless in conference play.
</P>
<P>
   Prior pitched his best game in over a month. He scattered eight
hits and struck out 10, his second-best total of the season. Prior
allowed two earned runs in eight innings and left the game after
hitting Andy Topham to lead off the ninth with his 118th pitch.
</P>
<P>
   USC and Stanford conclude the three-game series today at 1 p.m.
PDT. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
