<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-DEVILRAYS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS PLAY LONG BALL TO BEAT TAMPA BAY, 9-6
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Before Friday, the use of lumber by Mo
Vaughn and Tim Salmon didn't justify cutting down the trees it took
to make their bats.
</P>
<P>
   But Vaughn, Salmon and Troy Glaus made use of their wood in a
historic fashion Friday night, each hitting two home runs to power
the Angels to a 9-6 victory over the Tampa Bay Devil Rays at
Tropicana Field.
</P>
<P>
   The six home runs tied a club record, and it was the 13th time
in major-league history _ and the seventh time in American League
history _ that three players on one team hit more than one homer in
a game. The Angels are the only team to do it twice _ Dave
Winfield, Dante Bichette and Brian Downing did it in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn and Salmon entered the game with one home run each all
season. But they went back-to-back in both the fourth and ninth
innings. The homers in the ninth off Roberto Hernandez broke a 6-6
tie.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus hit his in the same innings, just one batter later. Garret
Anderson walked and struck out in his two at-bats separating Salmon
and Glaus, but Glaus hit the most impressive homer of all.
</P>
<P>
   His first homer in the fourth inning hit one of the four
catwalks that hang above the field. The ball hit the catwalk that
is 110 feet above the ground and never came down. The fans, Devil
Rays left fielder Greg Vaughn and the umpires stood in confusion
for a few moments before it was ruled a home run. It was estimated
at 470 feet, the longest home run in Tropicana Field history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never hit a home run that didn't actually go over the
fence,'' said Glaus, who leads the team with five homers. Asked
whether he's ever hit a ball harder or farther, he said, ''With a
wood bat, no.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard the saying, you hit a ball so hard it doesn't come
down,'' Angels manager Mike Scioscia said. ``I guess we saw it
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Then in the ninth, after Vaughn and Salmon went back-to-back for
a second time, Glaus waited his turn on deck with Anderson batting
and started thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was weird,'' Glaus said. ``I was standing on deck, and it's
not like I had a premonition, but after Fish (Salmon) hit his, I
said I gotta hit one now. It was a strange night. You don't see
that too often.''
</P>
<P>
   After Salmon hit his second homer, the normally stoic outfielder
had a little extra on his high-fives with teammates as he entered
the dugout. Such is the temperment of a player who had only one RBI
all season until a couple of days ago but has driven in five in the
past two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just pumped up,'' Salmon said. ``I've never gone
back-to-back with a guy twice. Mo pumped me up with his home run
that gave us the lead. I haven't had a lot to get excited about.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn said simply it's a matter of hitting pitches that are
meant to be hit, and he and Salmon will start hitting home runs
like they can.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitting home runs is mainly about hitting mistakes and not
missing them,'' Vaughn said. ''Earlier in the season, guys were
missing mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   On Glaus' first homer, Vaughn said: ``He's got that type of
power. He's 6-foot-5, 230 pounds, he's got the leverage to show
that kind of power.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are strong, man, these guys are strong,'' Scioscia
said.
</P>
<P>
   After stellar outings in his previous two starts, Angels starter
Scott Schoeneweis couldn't make it out of the fourth inning Friday.
He was the third starter in a row _ joining Ken Hill and Kent
Bottenfield the previous two nights _ to get knocked out of the
game early.
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis gave up six runs (five earned) and seven hits in 3
innings, but was saved by the bullpen. Al Levine (2 scoreless
innings), Mark Petkovsek (2 scoreless innings) and Troy Percival
(1-2-3 ninth, fifth save) kept the Devil Rays off the scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   Petkovsek (1-1) got the victory, the first by an Angels reliever
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bullpen stepped up big-time,'' Scioscia said. ``It was
great to see.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
