<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MADDON IS OK AFTER TRIP TO HOSPITAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Bench coach Joe Maddon was released from
a hospital Friday in Tampa, Fla., after experiencing shortness of
breath and a tingling sensation in his arm.
</P>
<P>
   Maddon had left SkyDome in Toronto before Thursday's game to get
checked out at a local hospital, felt better and returned for the
game. He flew with the team to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   But after landing early Friday morning, Maddon, 46, felt ill
again and was taken to St. Anthony's Hospital in Tampa, where test
results were normal. He returned to Tropicana Field for the game
but did not suit up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it was,'' Maddon said. ``I just didn't feel
right. I was light-headed. I knew something was wrong, but I can't
put my finger on it. I felt I had to see somebody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it was fatigue, but I had a really strange
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Under doctor's orders, Maddon ate a big plate of spaghetti after
the game. Maddon had lost 20 pounds over the past year while on a
diet of eating proteins but no carbohydrates. He said the doctor
doesn't think the diet was the cause, but he was told to stop the
diet for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I was totally on empty,'' Maddon said. ``I'm going
to eat a lot tonight and have a good breakfast tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   ALWAYS GREENER: It looks like real grass. It feels like real
grass. But it's not real grass.
</P>
<P>
   The turf at Tropicana Field, known as FieldTurf, is the latest
in synthetic turf technology. And according to players who have
played on it, it's just like the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   The turf has individual blades of ``grass'' made of a blend of
polyethylene and polypropylene. Those blades are planted in
artificial dirt, made up of ground-up crumbs of old tires, tennis
shoes and silica sand.
</P>
<P>
   The turf was first developed for golf use, for tee and chipping
boxes. Last year, the University of Nebraska installed it in their
football stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``This stuff is awesome,'' Scioscia said. ``I'm walking on it,
and I'm going, `Wow'. It's so far ahead of other artificial turf.
Hopefully it plays close to grass.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia said the worst artificial turfs he played on were in
Montreal and Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were the worst surfaces I've ever seen in my life,'' he
said. ``Until the Steelers started to complain, they wouldn't do
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   BACK SOON, BUT NOT TOO SOON: Gary DiSarcina is expected to be
activated from the disabled list Monday. But DiSarcina, who bruised
his left thumb April 8, will be worked back into the lineup slowly.
DiSarcina tried to come back from a broken left forearm last season
too quickly, and it hindered him all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he learned from last year, about time off and trying
to get back,'' Scioscia said. ``As hard as he's been working, he's
not going to do too much. I'll look at him as a bench guy that
hasn't had an at-bat in two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have been happy with the play of Benji Gil, who has
hit .263 (10 for 38) and made two errors in 12 games starting in
DiSarcina's place at shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSELL ADJUSTING TO AL: Former Dodgers shortstop and manager
Bill Russell says he is happy in Tampa as the Devil Rays bench
coach, but he is adjusting to life in the American League.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're like everybody else in the league,'' he said. ``We could
always use more pitching, especially with (Wilson) Alvarez and
(Juan) Guzman hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell spent some time with Scioscia and Angels coaches Mickey
Hatcher and Alfredo Griffin _ teammates of Russell's with the
Dodgers _ before Friday's game.
</P>
<P>
   GOOD START: Pitcher Tim Belcher, recovering from offseason elbow
surgery, threw five scoreless innings in a rehab assignment game
Thursday for Single-A Lake Elsinore. Belcher gave up only one
single while striking out four and walking none.
</P>
<P>
   He'll probably make two more rehab starts before he's ready to
join the big-league club the first week in May. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
