<HEADLINE>
CARDINAL MAHONY OFFERS EASTER COUNSEL TO L.A. DRIVERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
Eds: Resending to correct slug. 
 
 
By RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  LOS ANGELES _ Can the road to inner peace be found on the
gridlocked 101-405 interchange? Cardinal Roger Mahony raised this
provocative message Friday in his Easter message.
</P>
<P>
   The Roman Catholic head of the Los Angeles archdiocese _ the
nation's largest, located in the fatherland of America's freeways _
issued an Easter message highlighting where believers can ``remove
obstacles, lower barriers and eliminate roadblocks.''
</P>
<P>
   People need to consider how to resolve conflicts in their
families, with neighbors and at work. And on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``What about the obstacles we encounter on our freeways _ not
the construction delays but those frayed nerves that often cause us
to lose our tempers and take it out on fellow motorists,'' Mahony
said. ``How do I allow Easter grace to bring me a deeper sense of
peacefulness and patience?''
</P>
<P>
   Religious leaders joined the chorus of transportation officials
applauding Mahony's message.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the worst things that can happen to us as individuals
is the loss of our temper,'' said Rabbi Harvey Fields of the
Wilshire Boulevard Temple. ``I often point out that Moses didn't
make it into the promised land because of his loss of temper.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, as Fields acknowledged with a laugh, Moses didn't
have to traverse the 405-101 interchange on a Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's true,'' Fields said. ``I was at a couple of Seders this
week where people were late because they were stuck on the 405. I
sympathize with drivers. But we have to be patient with one another
when we are put in these kinds of situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles police Capt. Greg Meyer, commanding officer of the
Valley Traffic Division, praised Mahony's driving message as being
long needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a continuing problem and I very much applaud the
cardinal's emphasis on the issue,'' Meyer said. ``It does cost
lives. It does cost injuries. And it does cost property damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens is people get frustrated with the amount of
traffic, they get in a big hurry and then someone cuts them off.
They react in an immature fashion and get mad, and suddenly it's a
war zone out there. It's a crowded world out there and we all have
to make a little room for everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of Mahony's message was also about tolerance and
celebrating the ethnic diversity of the city and eliminating racial
division.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, Mahony is overseeing construction of a new
cathedral near one of the nation's busiest freeways. Once
completed, patrons of the Cathedral of Our Lady of the Angels
downtown will need all the patience they can muster to drive to it
on the Hollywood Freeway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
