<HEADLINE>
ON THE LAKERS, AND EVERYTHING ELSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's sizing-up-the-opposition edition of The Sporting Muse:
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers begin their playoff run Sunday against Sacramento,
and all of the alleged experts say the other 15 playoff teams have
as much chance of winning the title as Pussy of ``The Sopranos''
has of returning to next season's cast.
</P>
<P>
   Pussy became fish food in the season finale. The Lakers' season
finale was pretty dead, too, with back-to-back losses to Dallas and
San Antonio. But these were so-what games, and Phil Jackson coached
accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   Throw out those last two games and a midseason nap _ six losses
in nine games _ and the Lakers went 64-7. They were 31-10 on the
road, and the team fulfilled every item on its offseason list of
things to do: Learn the Triangle Offense, play better defense and
stop the childish locker room behavior.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of that, it's hard to envision any team capable of
winning a best-of-seven series against them. The first-round series
against Sacramento actually has more edge to it because the Kings
play without a brake and anything can happen in a short series.
</P>
<P>
   But truly, no one has the look of an upsetter.
</P>
<P>
   Second-seeded Utah? I expect the Jazz to play hard in the first
round after last season's near miss, and Seattle isn't very good.
But all of the Rogaine in the world can't make Karl Malone and his
mates any younger. They go out in round two.
</P>
<P>
   Third-seeded Portland? The Blazers were the hottest team in the
league until the Lakers demolished them in Portland on Feb. 29.
Jackson knows what goes on in Scott Pippen's head, so the Lakers
will likely negate him, and no one needs insight into the brain of
the new Mr. T, Rasheed Wallace (38 technical fouls).
</P>
<P>
   Others in the West? The NBA crown wobbled on the Spurs head this
season with some clubhouse bickering, and now Tim Duncan has a bad
knee. Phoenix isn't a threat without Jason Kidd.
</P>
<P>
   The East? Top-seed Indiana was 20-21 on the road. Charlotte and
Philadelphia are intriguing, but they're unlikely to string
together three straight solid playoff series. And as much as NBC
wants to see a Lakers-Knicks final, the Knicks aren't going to
surprise anyone this season, least of all first-round foe Toronto,
which won three of four games against the Knicks in the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   Miami worries me. Alonzo Mourning appears to have matured, their
talent (when healthy; Tim Hardaway is questionable) is A list, and
it's dangerous to look past Pat Riley. But the Heat's likely
second-round opponent is their nemesis, New York. Even if they beat
the Knicks and Pacers to reach the finals, would they have anything
left for Shaquille O'Neal and the Justice League of America?
Probably not. ...
</P>
<P>
   --The first blush of the baseball season has the Dodgers looking
and acting like a better ball club than last year's underachievers.
But it isn't a good sign to see Arizona playing the best ball in
the N.L. without third baseman Matt Williams and closer Matt
Mantei.
</P>
<P>
   The D-Backs have as many bats as anyone in the league, but what
separates them is more pitching than any team outside Atlanta and a
No. 1 starter, Randy Johnson, who will keep them from any lengthy
slumps.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are still weak up the middle, and the stage is
crowded with wild card candidates. What the Dodgers need most is
consistency from Darren Dreifort and Chan Ho Park, because .500
seasons from your nos. 2 and 3 pitchers won't get you games in
October. ...
</P>
<P>
   --It wasn't surprising to see Bill Parcells trade the New York
Jets' best player. He's a great coach, but he's always fancied
himself as a personnel guy, too, and that may be his undoing.
</P>
<P>
   Said Fox's John Madden on the trade: ``You get very few
superstars, and when you do get one, you don't let them go.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson should have an electric impact on the Bucs, whose
defense and running attack was good enough to get in the NFC title
game. Don't forget, too, that the Bucs signed free agent offensive
linemen Randall McDaniel and Jeff Christy, and drafted Georgia Tech
quarterback Joe Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton and Shaun King are similar in size and style. Head
coach Tony Dungy clearly has a plan that will take advantage of his
smaller but quicker quarterbacks. ...
</P>
<P>
   --Hamilton was just one of several deft draft day moves last
week. The three teams that helped themselves the most, besides
Tampa, were Baltimore, Indianapolis and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks took the best pro-style back in the draft in
Alabama's Shaun Alexander and the Colts drafted a ton of defensive
stalwarts.
</P>
<P>
   The Ravens somehow got Tennessee running back Jamal Lewis,
Florida wideout Terry Taylor, and Louisville quarterback Chris
Redman. All three should prosper in coach Brian Bilick's uptempo
attack. The Ravens fielded a good defense last year, and there now
is proof that Bilick was the key man in Minnesota's 1998 success.
...
</P>
<P>
   --Early NFL predictions, at no extra charge:
</P>
<P>
   NFC: Washington wins an improved East that should see the Giants
use Ron Dayne effectively and the young Eagles mature. Tampa Bay
dominates the Central while Minnesota regresses. St. Louis wins the
West by default. Wild cards: Green Bay, N.Y. Giants, Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   AFC: Indianapolis wins the East as controversy swirls around
Parcells in New York, Dan Marino-less Miami, two-headed Buffalo
(Rob Johnson-Doug Flutie) and Bill Belichick in New England.
Jacksonville wins the Central narrowly, and Seattle takes the West
in Mike Holmgren's second year: Wild cards: Tennessee, Baltimore,
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   --Five things I like about Arena Football: Only 25 seconds
between plays, a running clock, forward motion, quarterbacks may
not take a knee, and no punters.
</P>
<P>
   One thing I dislike about Arena Football: It's still a mutant,
cool rules or not. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 0221EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
