<HEADER>
A4191 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-REEVES-STARS-TEX     04-22 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REEVES-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY'S STILL OUT ON HOW GOOD THIS TEAM REALLY IS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ It's a well-known astronomical fact that few NHL teams
have more stars in their solar system than, well, your Dallas
Stars.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take an expensive telescope to see why the post-game
honors for the three stars of the game needed a little expanding
last night. Three just wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hull, Mike Modano and Eddie Belfour were judged to have
shone brightest, in that order, but anyone at Reunion Arena for the
Stars' series-clinching 3-2 victory over spunky Edmonton could have
just as easily made a case for Joe Nieuwendyk.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is simple: When those four all come to play on
the same night, the Stars will be difficult to beat, no matter whom
they're playing.
</P>
<P>
   Classify last night's taut, nail-biter _ the Stars twice blew
one-goal leads before Hull slammed the game-winner home late in the
final period _ as the Stars' first real must-win game of the
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to Edmonton and that hell pit called Skyreach Centre
for Game 6 was something none of the Stars had the stomach for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our players knew we had to close it out,'' coach Ken Hitchcock
said. ``The damage an extended \Rfirst\S series does is something
you just can't recover from.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory, coupled with the Blues' 5-3 win over San Jose to
keep that series alive (the Sharks lead 3-2), not only allows the
Stars to avoid the long and difficult trip back to the northern
plains of Alberta, it will give them a few days to rest and to
heal.
</P>
<P>
   That could be critical down the road in the Stanley Cup playoff
march, especially if it helps the Stars get defensive point man
Sergei Zubov and forward Jere Lehtinen back, as Hitchock suggested
it might after the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars could actually open the next series skating ``our real
lineup,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps then we'll better be able to judge whether this year's
Stars team is as good as last year's Stanley Cup champs.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't figured that out yet, don't worry; you're in good
company. Not even Hitchcock, general manager Bob Gainey or Oilers'
coach Kevin Lowe can say for sure either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year's team was special in the fact that it could adjust;
it played a different game,'' Hitchcock said. ``Last year's team
was methodical and forthright in the way it played.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is emotional, energetic. It has a higher upside and
makes more mistakes, but more energy and enthusiasm. It's the
youngness and newness, the general excitement of being in the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also a more physical team, Hitchcock said, which lends
itself to more emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're more physical there's more excitement and more
emotion,'' he said. ``At the end of the day, it's still a more
difficult team to judge until you get the two gunners in, until you
get the two big guys in _ Lehtinen and Zubov _ so I don't know
where it is, but I know right now it plays a more abrasive style
where last year's team played a more controlled game.''
</P>
<P>
   Because it's an emotional team, there might well be higher highs
and lower lows for this year's Stars. Trying to take a lead away
from the Stars in the playoffs a year ago was like trying to take a
bone away from a Doberman. Last night, however, the Stars showed
visible letups after taking 1-0 and 2-1 leads and coughed up both
before Hull's wrister beat Tommy Salo with 5:02 left to play.
</P>
<P>
   It was Hull's third goal of the postseason after he scored a
career low 24 during the regular season. Modano, as usual, was all
over the ice, Belfour stopped 24 of 26 shots and Nieuwendyk's line
pestered the Oilers all night long.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some shifts in the second and third periods when we
were pretty much \Runder\S siege,'' Hitchcock conceded. ``\RThe
Oilers\S made some changes in the second half of the game that were
effective. Thank God we've got a guy like Brett Hull.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference was one shot by a player who can score goals.
He has scored big goals for this organization and he did it
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe said it's impossible to get a real read on the Stars until
Zubov and Lehtinen are back on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're probably a little more relaxed because they've done it
before,'' the Oilers' coach said. ``The pressure is off. We'll just
have to see what happens with the other teams.''
</P>
<P>
   What Hitchcock likes is that he believes the Stars' best hockey
is still ahead of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a team that's still on the rise,'' he said. ``It's
going to take this whole playoffs to determine what this team is
all about and where it's going to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not maxed out. We're not playing at full potential.
We've got people who can get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Before this playoff run is over, it's something they'll have to
do.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 0250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
