<HEADLINE>
INTERNET HELPS BREAK COUNTRY'S PROFOUND SENSE OF ISOLATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, April 23) 
 
By DEBORAH HORAN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   QOM, Iran _ ``You can find books you didn't know existed!''
exclaims Ayatollah Ali Kawrani, a conservative Muslim cleric draped
in a collarless white robe, as he extols the merits of the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, Kawrani has directed the Mostafa Islamic
Research Center, a religious institute that provides Internet
access to its students in Qom, a holy city about 90 miles south of
Tehran. On this particular afternoon, four bearded young men sit
hunched over computers downloading Koranic teachings and
philosophical works.
</P>
<P>
   ``It speeds up the time it takes to learn,'' the mullah
continues. ``If we want to know about some Islamic teachings using
books, we need two years to study. With a computer, you need a
week!''
</P>
<P>
   Such praise may help explain why Iran's Islamic government has
not banned the Internet, even as it continues to enforce, albeit
sporadically, a prohibition on home satellite dishes, which also
provide easy access to unwanted influences such as pornography and
MTV.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet may be a gateway to entertainment and information
that the government would rather keep out. But its benefits as a
learning tool seem, at least so far, to be outweighing any concerns
that the mullahs might have.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more than anything else, the Internet has helped
Iranians break out of the profound sense of isolation they have
felt since the 1979 Islamic revolution, observers say. They point
out that the free flow of information makes any effort to keep
outside influences from seeping into the country more difficult and
allows the world to more easily find out what's happening inside
Iran.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to be cut off completely,'' says Siamak Namazi, who
runs a political consulting business. ``Now I can read the latest
news. I can keep up with everything that's happening in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Iranian papers are now online,'' Namazi adds. ``The
outside world can see things that are happening in Iran in real
time. A kid in a basement can send out a message that (the
government) is going to kill so-and-so.''  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; In the absence of a ban, Internet cafes, which cater mostly to
students and other young people yearning for a link to the world
outside Iran, have sprung up across the country. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; In Tehran, the cafes are filled with young people. And Western
influences are everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   At one cafe, users watch everything from ``Star Wars'' to the
``Lion King'' on CD. One long-haired 20-year-old, who says he is
``into industrial metal,'' surfs the Web in search of rock music
sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``The youth are able to find out about the youth outside Iran.
Then they do the same _ the same dress, the same music,'' one young
man enthuses as he surfs a Western television news site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can get the news, the real news,'' he says with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Like their counterparts elsewhere, Iranian businessmen have
tapped into the Web in an effort to increase sales.
</P>
<P>
   One Persian carpet seller in Esfahan, an industrial city about
200 miles south of Tehran, says he has started to sell rugs to
foreigners over the Internet. Other businesses offer to deliver
Mother's Day flowers to Iranian women whose children live abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The government requires the proprietors of Internet cafes to
sign forms stating that customers will not surf ``objectionable''
sites. But business owners say that authorities rarely enforce the
restriction.
</P>
<P>
   Still, government institutions and even some Internet cafes curb
access to sites featuring pornography and violence by installing
firewalls. At one Internet cafe in Tehran, a search for Playboy
brought up a stern notice that the site was unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   ``America has the Internet. You have satellites. You have
freedom. And now you have problems,'' says Mohammed Abedi, a
26-year-old clerical student in Qom, defending the use of
firewalls. ``We don't want to let these things in and have
problems, too.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the cyber boom seems to be confined mainly to Tehran and
a few higher-learning centers elsewhere. Outside the capital,
Internet cafes exist, but owners say that few Iranians use them.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Ghabadi, a 25-year-old cyber cafe owner in Esfahan,
installed a few computers in a corner of his Persian carpet store
as part of an effort to attract foreign buyers. Most of his
Internet customers, he says, are tourists who want to send e-mails
to friends.
</P>
<P>
   Cost and language are big barriers to Internet use for many
Iranians, people say. Surfing the Net at a cyber cafe for an hour
costs no more than $3 or $4. But the average Iranian takes home
less than $100 a month. And though some members of the older
generation grew up speaking English, the dominant language of the
Internet, many younger Iranians, particularly those outside Tehran,
don't speak it or are only now learning.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the Internet at home requires buying a computer, a
luxury that few Iranians can afford.
</P>
<P>
   Still, observers say, Internet use, particularly among the
young, is steadily rising. Those who surf say that most users know
how to get around firewalls by clicking on links from permitted
sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people are thirsty for information from outside'' Iran,
says Irag Riahi, the owner of an Internet cafe. ``The government,
they cannot stop us. No one can stop the mind of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
