<DOCNO> NYT20000422.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 10:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4197 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-IRAN-REFORMS-2NDTAKE-     04-22 1565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-REFORMS-2NDTAKE-$ADV23-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
TEHRAN, Iran: from that moment.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   The clerics' Revolutionary Courts can summon anyone for
``un-Islamic activities'' and hold secret trials without benefit of
appeal. And the mullahs' Council of Guardians can disqualify any
candidate from seeking elective office. In the months leading to
February's elections, the council barred hundreds of people, mostly
secular democrats, from running for Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Changeez Pahlavan, a graying political scientist and writer who
was banned from teaching at Tehran University because of his
leftist views, describes the political system as ``a very closed
circle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Secular people are not allowed to participate,'' he says. Now,
``the secular forces are thinking they might reach a change
indirectly.''
</P>
<P>
   Enter Ali Reza Nouri. A clean-shaven, bespectacled physician in
his mid-30s, Nouri was working at a Tehran medical clinic when
supporters of his jailed brother, a former government minister,
asked him to run for Parliament, because they knew he shared his
brother's reformist ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Nouri's elder brother, Abdullah, a cleric, had been imprisoned
for ``insulting the sanctities of Islam'' after advocating the
right of the people to choose their government. His supporters were
looking for a replacement whose views were unknown to the Council
of Guardians.
</P>
<P>
   Nouri slipped into the race and easily won a parliamentary seat;
largely, many believe, because of his brother's name. Like Nouri,
some of the other victors in the election had been urged to run in
place of recognized reformists who had been disqualified by the
Council of Guardians.
</P>
<P>
   Their candidacies, says Jaliehpour, the editor of Economic News,
were part of a strategy by leftist politicians to circumvent the
power of the religious body and fill Parliament with members who
would likely push for sweeping reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Nouri admits that he shares some of his brother's reformist
ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parliament should be the only place to pass laws and the only
decision-maker in this country,'' he says, taking a not-so-veiled
swipe at the Council of Guardians. ``We should not be under the
influence of any other institution.''
</P>
<P>
   The religious body, however, still wields immense power. Since
the February elections, the council has disqualified several
reformist winners and replaced them with conservative runners-up,
sparking riots in two villages.
</P>
<P>
   Reformists point to other signs of a conservative backlash. They
suspect that Islamic hard-liners were to blame for the recent
slayings of three leftist intellectuals. Last week, the elite
Revolutionary Guards issued a statement threatening to crush any
attempt to undermine the Islamic system, and the outgoing
Parliament passed a bill placing some curbs on newfound press
freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such developments, Peyman predicts that the incoming
Parliament, which convenes May 28, will overturn the new law and
liberalize rules governing the press even more. ``Closing down the
press and arresting journalists doesn't stop anybody anymore,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Both Peyman and Jaliehpour stress that change must come
peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``The political affairs should be discussed in the framework of
political institutions,'' Jaliehpour says. ``If it goes to the
streets, the conservatives have the military and police in their
hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't face them,'' he says. ``We would lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Last July, thousands of students rioted at Tehran University in
protest of a Revolutionary Court decision to ban a reformist
newspaper, fanning fears of greater civil strife.
</P>
<P>
   For five days, students and police clashed in the worst bout of
violence in Iran since the revolution. By the time the unrest died
down, five young men had been killed and hundreds had been
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   The violence shattered any illusion that Iran's spirited youth
might have harbored about the clerical establishment giving up
without a fight.
</P>
<P>
   Today, many young people say they want to see the power of the
mullahs diminish. They want Khatami's reforms to succeed. But they
don't want another revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Students don't want to face off with the police again, says
22-year-old Nushin Yari from a ski lodge north of Tehran. ``They
are armed,'' she says, ``and we are young.''
</P>
<P>
   The riots in July also shocked the country's entrenched
religious establishment. The political credentials of most students
at Tehran University were regarded as impeccable, because the
institution gives admissions preference to the offspring of loyal
revolutionaries.
</P>
<P>
   These children of revolutionaries did more than riot. They also
taunted the supreme leader _ revered by Iran's Shiite Muslims as
holy and infallible _ with such slogans as ``Down with the
religious dictator!''
</P>
<P>
   ``They were considered loyal, and even they can't tolerate the
present system,'' says Pahlavan, the political scientist. ``Mr.
Khatami will face a big dilemma if he is not able to do
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, asserts Ghorbanzadeh, the 21-year-old Iranian
film star, his movie ``Siavash'' would never have been made.
</P>
<P>
   A portrait of a young musician who can't relate to his father's
Islamic revolutionary ideals, the film, he says, challenges beliefs
held sacred in Iran since the shah fled the country.
</P>
<P>
   Critics charged that the film's portrayal of the generation gap
between Iran's middle-age revolutionaries and their children
implied disrespect for the hundreds of thousands of ``martyrs'' who
died defending the lofty ideals of the Islamic republic during the
1980-1988 war with Iraq, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of negative feedback,'' Ghorbanzadeh admits.
``The conservatives reacted and told us this film made the morals
police look bad. They wrote things in the newspapers. One of the
martyr's mothers complained about the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the film had no trouble getting made. The controversial
script glided past government censors. Once finished, the $50,000
production became a big commercial success, earning more than
$265,000 in Tehran alone, a small fortune in a country where
monthly salaries rarely exceed $100.
</P>
<P>
   Many Iranians cite the atmosphere of freedom that allowed
``Siavash'' to be produced as Khatami's greatest achievement.
Reformist newspapers keep challenging the conservatives' hold on
power, they note, and Iran's acclaimed film industry is
flourishing. Movie directors and playwrights silenced since the
revolution are tackling controversial themes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen a lot of changes,'' says Mohammed Bahrami, a
theater critic in Tehran who has been covering the industry for 16
years. ``The Iranian writers who were barred are coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Albourz Mountains on the northern edge of Tehran,
hundreds of people glide down glistening white slopes on skis and
toboggans.
</P>
<P>
   As the sun sinks below the horizon, a group of young people
blasts a mix of Western pop music and rhythmic Iranian tunes from
the tape deck of a car parked along the road. The women take off
their veils and dance in the snow.
</P>
<P>
   Here, perhaps more than anywhere else, the effects of Iran's new
openness can be felt. Nowadays, the morals police rarely venture to
these mountains to enforce the mullahs' rules, people say. Men and
women mingle on the slopes during the day and in the evening throw
parties.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these young people are among Khatami's staunchest
supporters. They are also his harshest critics. The new atmosphere
ushered in by the reformist president, they say, is not enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expected more,'' says Bita Khachnegar, 24, as she sits in
the ski lodge with friends. ``But Khatami is limited.''
</P>
<P>
   These Iranians were reared by the generation that fought for the
revolution. Now, they say, they are left with its legacy: a rigid,
religious government; a bloated bureaucracy; a stagnant economy.
</P>
<P>
   Few seem convinced that the new Parliament will manage to forge
new ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of mullahs at the top, so there won't be any
change,'' says a 21-year-old law student who gives his name only as
Ruzbekiah. ``There won't be any democracy. They are just doing this
so we can let off steam.''
</P>
<P>
   Every time they think the reformists have gained ground, many of
these young people say, something happens to remind them that
conservative forces remain very much in power.
</P>
<P>
   In a Tehran cafe frequented by artists and writers, Alex Lazar,
17, lifts his cotton jersey to show a back covered with bluish-red
welts. The day before, he says, he was lashed by the morals police
for being caught with his girlfriend. The girl, he says, also was
whipped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now do you think there is freedom here?'' asks Mahdi Safari, a
19-year-old sitting next to Lazar.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the Albourz Mountains, a popular Iranian tune blares
from the cassette player of the car stopped on the side of the
road. Young women shimmy and twirl as snowflakes fall on their
unveiled hair. Young men clap to the music. People in passing cars
stop to watch, and some join in.
</P>
<P>
   Away from the politics of the city below, an impromptu party
begins.
</P>
<P>
   These young people say they want more personal choice. They want
the morals police to dissolve. They want an end to so many
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm young,'' shouts one 19-year-old woman, as she dances in
the snow. ``I want to live.''
</P>
<P>
