<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4198 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-IRAN-REFORMS-2TAKES-$     04-22 1511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-REFORMS-2TAKES-$ADV23-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFORMS GIVE IRAN A TASTE OF FREEDOM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, April 23) 
 
By DEBORAH HORAN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran _ Seconds after Iranian actor Ali Ghorbanzadeh
takes a seat in the bleachers of a domed sports arena here, a
chorus of high-pitched squeals erupts from the women's section of
the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring the disapproving glares from bearded mullahs around
them, the teen-age girls whistle and clap. They wave black-clad
arms in the air. The more daring venture past uniformed guards to
the men's section to ask the teen heartthrob for his autograph,
shyly thrusting pen and paper into the young man's face.
</P>
<P>
   The episode lasts only moments. But it illustrates the social
changes that have swept across Iran since political reformers, led
by President Mohammed Khatami, burst onto the national scene three
years ago with promises of greater personal freedom and democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The press is freer than before. Films and plays once censored
are getting permission to be shown.
</P>
<P>
   Today, it is not unusual to see young men and women hanging out
in the same cafes or skiing down the same slopes, activities still
forbidden or discouraged by the stern religious rulers who have
governed this country since the 1979 Islamic revolution. Nowadays,
however, the authorities known as the ``morals police'' enforce the
rules less stringently.
</P>
<P>
   As the reformers slowly gain influence, some of their supporters
hope that even greater change is on the way. They dream of a
gradual transformation from a conservative theocracy controlled by
the mullahs to a democracy that better reflects the will of the
people. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``Little by little, step by step,'' says Hamidreza Jaliehpour,
a feisty 41-year-old editor whose publication, Economic News, is a
reincarnation of two earlier newspapers shut down by the government
for ``insulting Islam.'' ``The important thing is that a civil
movement is going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even though the reformers enjoy widespread support, many
remain skeptical of their ability to bring significant change soon
to the Islamic Republic of Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Since Khatami's 1997 election, reformers have been locked in a
political dance with the conservatives to determine the direction
of the country, moving in a pattern of two steps forward, one step
back. It is still unclear which side will ultimately prevail.
</P>
<P>
   In the days following the February elections that gave the
reformists a majority in Parliament, for instance, the morals
police launched a crackdown on young people flouting the rules for
segregation of men and women in the affluent suburbs of northern
Tehran and the snow-capped Albourz Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   In March, unidentified gunmen wounded Said Hajjarian, a
prominent strategist for the reformists, in a bungled assassination
attempt that many suspect was carried out by Islamic hard-liners.
</P>
<P>
   And this month, Mohammed Reza Khatami, the president's reformist
brother and a top vote-getter in the parliamentary elections, was
arrested on charges of libel in his capacity as head of the liberal
daily newspaper Mosharekat.
</P>
<P>
   Developments such as these deeply unsettle many Iranians, who
fear that they portend political violence. At the same time, such
incidents strengthen the resolve of those people, particularly the
young, who are rallying behind Khatami's reformers.
</P>
<P>
   More than 60 percent of the country's 65 million people are
under the age of 25. Many of them say they are fed up with the
unbending theocratic system that controls their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are tired of being ruled by religious extremists,''
says Bahar Jalali, a 21-year-old student whose blue, ankle-length
dress stands out in the sea of black that defines the women's
section of the Tehran sports stadium where the young actor appeared
during a reformist rally.
</P>
<P>
   As Jalali watches young women crowd around Ghorbanzadeh, a smile
spreads across her face.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should be free to choose their way to live,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Since Khatami assumed the presidency, Iranians have twice
endorsed his agenda for reform.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, they elected hundreds of reformers to local councils
in the country's first post-revolution municipal elections. In
February, they voted to pack the nation's Parliament with people in
favor of change.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. State Department responded in March by lifting a ban on
the import of Iranian rugs, pistachio nuts and caviar. &UR;  &LR; Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright said that the United States wanted a
``new relationship with Iran.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; But Iran's conservatives have not been entirely sidelined, as
the libel charge lodged against the president's brother
illustrates. Complainants in the case include the police, the state
broadcasting company and the Council of Guardians _
conservative-dominated bodies angered by his newspaper's coverage
of the elections.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the struggle between Iran's liberals and conservatives is
hardly new.
</P>
<P>
   The battle has been playing out since the early days of the
revolution, which ousted the U.S.-backed Mohammed Reza Shah
Pahlavi, when 400 college students stormed the U.S. Embassy, took
Americans hostage and helped shape Iran's politics for the next two
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged by radical mullahs, the students humiliated the
United States by dragging out the hostage crisis for 444 days. They
also caused the provisional Iranian government, set up in the wake
of the revolution and led by secular politicians opposed to the
Embassy takeover, to resign in frustration.
</P>
<P>
   With the advocates of a secular government out of the way, the
religious clerics, led by the late Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini,
began setting up the Islamic theocracy that governs Iran today.
</P>
<P>
   Their biggest legacy was to create parallel religious
institutions that rival each branch of government. Thus, the 12-man
Council of Guardians oversees Parliament; the Revolutionary Courts
watch over other courts; and the supreme leader, currently
Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, wields powers that supersede those of the
president.
</P>
<P>
   The mullahs also instated their extremist brand of Islamic law.
They made the head-to-toe gown called the ``hijab'' mandatory for
women and lowered the age of female maturity _ and thus of possible
marriage _ from 15 to 9. Adultery was made punishable by death for
women, even though men found guilty of the crime were usually
whipped. Alcohol was outlawed. Men and women were strictly
segregated.
</P>
<P>
   And anyone caught flouting the rules risked being executed,
jailed or lashed.
</P>
<P>
   In the two crucial years that followed the revolution, many of
the leftist intellectuals who had advocated the creation of a
secular democracy were imprisoned, exiled or killed.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the remaining secularists waited in the wings,
effectively shut out of public life. Only now are their
once-silenced voices beginning to rise up again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were jailed in our homes,'' Habibollah Peyman, an
ebony-haired intellectual who now works as a dentist, recalls from
his north Tehran office. ``Always our followers were arrested,
excluded from jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mullahs, these religious people, think they should guide
the people because they are connected to God,'' Peyman continues,
punctuating his words. ``It's a theory they have made. It's not in
the Koran.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we will use this new opening to come outside and speak to
the people,'' he says. ``We will tell them that God has invited the
people to think for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Peyman, who lifts bushy eyebrows for emphasis as he speaks,
doesn't think Iran will create a political system that separates
religion and state any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   A philosopher who specializes in the history of Islam in Iran,
Peyman says that most reformers recently elected to Parliament are
liberal-minded clerics who want to revamp the existing Islamic form
of government _ not secularists who want to do away with it.
</P>
<P>
   Even President Khatami, who in 1982 resigned as minister of
culture after being accused of ``liberalism,'' has always spoken
about democratic reform within an Islamic context. ``We must try to
show freedom is compatible with Islam,'' Khatami, a mullah who
claims descent from the prophet Mohammed, said in a May 1999
speech.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, converting the Islamic system to a secular democracy
would require eliminating something called the ``velayat i-faqih.''
The term, which means ``guardian of the religious jurist,'' has
come to signify the absolute rule of the mullahs and the dual power
structure that allows them to shadow the various branches of
government.
</P>
<P>
   Under the system, conservative clerics have an advantage at all
levels. As an elected president, for instance, Khatami can push for
reform, but Supreme Leader Khamenei, who is appointed for life, has
the final say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The person in charge of the Islamic government does not make
mistakes,'' Khamenei, the supreme leader, said in January. ``And if
he does, he will not be the supreme leader from that moment.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
