<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4199 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-ELIAN-RELIGION-HNS &LR;      04-22 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-RELIGION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIAN HAS BECOME RELIGIOUS CAUSE TO CATHOLICS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By EDWARD HEGSTROM 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Carrying crucifixes and Bibles, Cuban-Americans gathered
in Little Havana on Good Friday to pray for a little boy many of
them believe to be touched by God.
</P>
<P>
   The most loyal Miami backers of Elian Gonzalez have always
claimed his rescue at sea last November was an act of divine
salvation. But with the approach of Easter weekend, the religious
fervor of the protest movement spilled over in prayer and
exhortations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a miracle, that's the only way to describe it,'' said
Melida Vairo, an Argentine woman who wept as she prayed for Elian
in Little Havana on Friday. ``You have to love this child who was
saved by God.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, 6, spent most of the day in the home of his Miami
great-uncle Lazaro Gonzalez. Father Francisco Santana, a Catholic
priest, spent part of the day with the family, where they prayed.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic Church representatives say the prayer will continue
throughout the weekend, though it was not clear whether the family
will be able to go to church on Easter because of the swarm of
protesters and media surrounding the home.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, women dressed in black joined hands in prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Even local Spanish-language radio gave way from the usual
anti-communist vitriol to more talk of the Bible during Holy Week.
Many callers compared Elian to Moses, who was set adrift in the
river by a mother who gave him up to a better life.
</P>
<P>
   Others say they believe Elian was buoyed at sea by dolphins sent
by God.
</P>
<P>
   Still others talk of Our Lady of Charity of Cobre, the virgin
Mother Mary who is the patron saint of Cuba because she is believed
to have saved a little Cuban boy lost at sea nearly 400 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Images of the Lady of Charity were in abundance Friday _ on the
front door of the Gonzalez home, on a mural next door, and on large
banners carried by protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic leaders are not ready to officially declare Elian's
salvation a miracle, which is an involved process. But they clearly
believe the boy was saved by an act of God.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not expert in the subject of miracles,'' said Monsignor
Agustin A. Roman, the auxiliary bishop of Miami. ``But for a boy to
maintain himself floating on the sea for two days seems quite
extraordinary to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``An hour, maybe. But two days holding himself afloat? It
doesn't seem possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican has remained unusually quiet on the question of
Elian's fate. A top cardinal, Francis Cardinal Arinze, who toured
Miami this week, made no declaration on the boy.
</P>
<P>
   But Miami Catholics, many of them Cuban exiles, have emerged as
increasingly important supporters of the cause of keeping Elian in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Father Santana visits the family almost daily to offer guidance
and prayer. Sister Jeanne O'Laughlin, the president of Barry
University, originally supported returning Elian to Cuba, but now
sits on the side of those who wish to keep him here. Monsignor
Roman has written articles for the Spanish-language press
supporting Elian, including one in which he asked God not to let
``this symbol of freedom be transformed into an instrument of
slavery.''
</P>
<P>
   A poster widely distributed by local Catholics shows a photo of
the boy under a Spanish phrase that says: ``Elian met Jesus. Others
deny him.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before Holy Week, supporters at one large vigil formed a
large cross to show the religious backing of their belief.
</P>
<P>
   With Easter approaching, the protesters spoke ever more about
miracles and charity. But they still found ways to rail against
President Fidel Castro and his atheistic communism.
</P>
<P>
   ``That boy was saved because he sat on that inner tube and
prayed, just as his mother taught him to do,'' said Armond
Betancourt, a Cuban-American from Milwaukee who carried a cross
outside Elian's house. ``Usually, children in Cuba are not taught
to pray.''
</P>
<P>
   Symbols of the crucifixion, the resurrection and even dolphins
were in abundance Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But few icons have become as important as the Lady of Charity.
</P>
<P>
   According to Catholic tradition, three Cuban boys ventured out
onto the Bay of Nipe in northwestern Cuba in about 1612, looking
for islands of salt to cure their meat. A storm came up and swamped
their boat.
</P>
<P>
   Two boys, who were Indians, apparently perished. Only the third,
the 10-year-old descendent of African slaves, survived to tell how
he was saved by the vision he saw on the water of the Virgin Mary
with the Baby Jesus. The vision apparently spoke to the boy,
saying: ``I am the Virgin of Charity.''
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic Church declared the Virgin of Charity as the patron
saint of Cuba in 1916, according to Monsignor Roman.
</P>
<P>
   The image remains particularly important to Miami Catholics. The
church where both Monsignor Roman and Father Santana are based has
a large tile mosaic on its facade showing the three Cuban boys at
sea, with waves washing over their boat.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
