</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   McCain Flies a Flag of Contrition
</P>
<P>
   Now it can be told: Sen. John McCain always thought the
Confederate battle flag flying over the South Carolina Statehouse
should come down.
</P>
<P>
   He had hemmed and hawed about it during the South Carolina
primary, refusing to go out on a limb any further than his
Republican rival, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who would say only
that the flag's fate should remain in the hands of the people of
South Carolina. But at a luncheon Wednesday in Columbia, the
senator made his feelings plainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feared that if I answered honestly, I could not win the
South Carolina primary,'' he said. ``I broke my promise to always
tell the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's confession was seen by some as a betrayal. ``I'm
ashamed that he lied to the people of South Carolina,'' said Jake
Knotts, a state lawmaker and former McCain supporter. Yet the
revelation reminded others of McCain's enduring impact on the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Some colleagues even wondered if the former candidate wasn't
still running for something. On Comedy Central's ``Daily Show,''
Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., speculated, in all seriousness, that
``McCain may be subconsciously running for vice president.''
</P>
<P>
   On the national political stage, the Confederate flag may be a
peripheral prop. But at least it is an issue on which Bush has
staked out a position different from that of Vice President Al
Gore, who has declared that the flag should go. Bush, after all,
has come out with a series of planks that might not be out of place
in the Democratic Party platform. His latest: a $1.7 billion
proposal to encourage developers to build and repair housing for
the poor.
</P>
<P>
   That plan follows other Bush proposals to expand health care
services to the needy ($4.3 billion); give tax credits to
low-income families to buy health insurance ($41.6 billion) and
improve teacher training and childhood literacy ($7.9 billion).
</P>
<P>
   As Bush was offering new plans for spending money, Gore was
going to old friends to raise it. He appeared with President
Clinton at a Beverly Hills event that took in $2.8 million for the
Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Solving a Royal Mystery
</P>
<P>
   Examining all that remained of the boy who died in France's
Temple prison in 1795 _ a dried heart _ scientists ended one of the
nation's most enduring historical debates. The boy, the scientists
said, was indeed Louis XVII, the 10-year-old uncrowned king of
France, and not an impostor placed there so the young dauphin could
escape into exile.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 200 years, historians have argued over whether the
son of Louis XVI and Marie Antoinette might have escaped from
prison after his parents were guillotined during the French
Revolution. The dispute spawned hundreds of pretenders to the
throne, one of whom was convincing enough to get the government of
Netherlands to bury him under a tombstone indicating that he was
the true heir to the French throne.
</P>
<P>
   But scientists comparing DNA from the boy's heart with DNA from
locks of Marie Antoinette's hair said there could be no mistake.
The boy, who had endured two years virtually alone in a prison cell
without windows, barely fed or attended to, was the queen's son.
When he died, he had come a long way from the whirl of lace, sweets
and doting servants depicted in his official portraits. He was
riddled with disease, encrusted with sores and bloated with tumors.
</P>
<P>
   The specialists in human genetics who performed the tests,
Jean-Jacques Cassiman of the University of Louvain in Belgium and
Bernd Brinkmann of the University of Muenster in Germany, said the
DNA fragments they had been able to obtain from the heart were not
perfect, but enough for a conclusive match.
</P>
<P>
   The heart survived through a fluke. One of the doctors
performing the autopsy on the boy stole the heart as a souvenir,
wrapping it in a handkerchief and stuffing it in his pocket.
Eventually, it was returned to the royal family.
</P>
<P>
   The Bourbon family is now asking for a proper burial for the
boy.
</P>
<P>
   World Trade Officials Vow Effort to Fight Aids
</P>
<P>
   Some 50 million poor people in developing nations are infected
with the AIDS virus, and the number is rising so quickly that the
disease has become a leading impediment to economic development in
Africa and South Asia. That's the way the World Bank sees it. After
a spring strategy session in Washington, world finance ministers
endorsed a World Bank plan to spend ``unlimited money'' to finance
programs to prevent the spread of AIDS and treat its victims in
poor countries.
</P>
<P>
   Not coincidentally, the plan was announced while thousands of
protesters tried to block access to the meetings, claiming that the
bank has done too little to alleviate poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Report on Theft From Jews
</P>
<P>
   The seizure of Jewish assets in wartime France was so extensive
that all Jews, whether the richest bankers or the poorest tailors,
were touched by it. This was among the conclusions reached by the
Matteoli Commission, which began the first major study on the
subject three years ago. The study found that the theft of assets
was far greater than previously assumed. But it also found that
efforts to return the property or to reimburse Jews were extensive.
</P>
<P>
   Bad News on Fiber
</P>
<P>
   For nearly 30 years, many doctors and most of the public have
believed that high-fiber diets prevent colon cancer. But now two
studies involving thousands of people randomly assigned to eat
either high-fiber diets or their normal diets failed to find that
the high-fiber diets protected against polyps, which are tiny lumps
in the colon that precede many colon cancers.
</P>
<P>
   While some experts say there is still hope for the high-fiber
hypothesis _ maybe the diet needs to be started earlier or maybe it
only acts after cancers are well established _ others say it is
time to put the idea to rest.
</P>
<P>
   Vermont Gay Union Bill
</P>
<P>
   Vermont's legislature reached the verge of creating the closest
thing in America to gay marriage _ but left the final step until
this week, and no one is saying its over until its over. The state
Senate, in a 19-11 vote, passed a bill creating marriage-like civil
unions, but its bill was slightly different from the one passed
last month in the House. That means the House takes up the question
again in a session Tuesday. Gov. Howard Dean has said he will sign
the bill.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 1033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
