</P>
<P>
   Bad News on Fiber
</P>
<P>
   For nearly 30 years, many doctors and most of the public have
believed that high-fiber diets prevent colon cancer. But now two
studies involving thousands of people randomly assigned to eat
either high-fiber diets or their normal diets failed to find that
the high-fiber diets protected against polyps, which are tiny lumps
in the colon that precede many colon cancers.
</P>
<P>
   While some experts say there is still hope for the high-fiber
hypothesis _ maybe the diet needs to be started earlier or maybe it
only acts after cancers are well established _ others say it is
time to put the idea to rest.
</P>
<P>
   Vermont Gay Union Bill
</P>
<P>
   Vermont's legislature reached the verge of creating the closest
thing in America to gay marriage _ but left the final step until
this week, and no one is saying its over until its over. The state
Senate, in a 19-11 vote, passed a bill creating marriage-like civil
unions, but its bill was slightly different from the one passed
last month in the House. That means the House takes up the question
again in a session Tuesday. Gov. Howard Dean has said he will sign
the bill.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   New Drug for `Superbugs'
</P>
<P>
   Amid increasing concern over ``superbugs'' that can outsmart
even the most powerful germ-fighting medicines, the Food and Drug
Administration approved a new antibiotic, Zyvox, that doctors say
could save thousands of lives.
</P>
<P>
   The drug, manufactured by Pharmacia of Peapack, N.J., is the
first in an entirely new family of antibiotics, and is effective
against germs that can cause lethal bloodstream infections and
pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
   Weapon Sales to Taiwan
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration deferred the sale of four Aegis
destroyers to Taiwan that were intended to counter the Chinese
build-up of ballistic missiles. The White House also decided to
hold back on the sale of submarines and P-3 Orion anti-submarine
aircraft. Instead, the Taiwanese will buy three kinds of updated
missiles and were promised a naval study to find ways of improving
their outmoded navy.
</P>
<P>
   The administration hopes this middle course will mollify
Beijing, which has said the sale of the destroyers would be
unacceptable, and at the same time meet some of the defense needs
of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Bid to Condemn China Fails
</P>
<P>
   The State Department failed in its intense lobbying campaign to
persuade the U.N. Human Rights Commission to consider a U.S.
resolution criticizing China for its human rights record. The
53-member commission voted not to consider the resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright made a special trip to
Geneva last month to address the commission. But the Chinese
government also lobbied hard, and prevailed in part because
countries friendly to the United States in South America and Asia
abstained from voting.
</P>
<P>
   Arrest in Web Attack
</P>
<P>
   A 15-year-old Montreal high-school student with the online
nickname Mafiaboy was arrested by Canadian law enforcement
officials for his role in a series of computer attacks on some of
the biggest Internet sites in February.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, who was accused of attacking Cable News Network's
Web site, is the first to face charges stemming from the crippling
of Web sites of Yahoo, eBay and Etrade among others. The youth was
not charged in the other attacks, which hindered access to the
sites and exposed weaknesses in the emerging field of electronic
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   A Heart of Stone
</P>
<P>
   Paleontologists reported that they had found a dinosaur heart
the size of a grapefruit, encased in stone and fossilized.
Examining its internal structure, the scientists were surprised to
discover an advanced heart that was more like that of a bird or
mammal than any known reptile.
</P>
<P>
   This suggests that at least some dinosaurs had higher
metabolisms than other reptiles and probably were warm-blooded, a
discovery that could profoundly change theories of dinosaur
physiology and their place in evolution.
</P>
<P>
   2 Death Penalty Rulings
</P>
<P>
   ``Watch what we do, not what we say,'' may have been the Supreme
Court's message in a pair of death penalty cases interpreting a new
federal law that placed strict limits on federal courts' ability to
hear appeals from state inmates. By a 5-4 vote, the court read the
1996 law to mean that federal judges must defer to state court
rulings that, even though wrong, are nonetheless not
``unreasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   On paper, at least, this standard would appear to eviscerate
federal court power to issue writs of habeas corpus. But the court
then went on to set aside the two death sentences, effectively
demonstrating that federal courts do retain authority and that the
justices expect them to use it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
