<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 10:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4204 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-GLOBAL-CONTRASTS-REVI     04-22 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBAL-CONTRASTS-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT CAN THE NEW ECONOMY DO FOR PLACES WITHOUT AN OLD ONE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In early February, on assignment to seek out diamond
smugglers, I traveled straight from the World Economic Forum in
Davos, Switzerland, to a place in central Africa where the borders
of three nations _ Congo, Angola and Zambia _ fuse in a triangle of
poverty and strife. It was a trip in every sense of the word,
across the chasm separating the truly rich and the achingly poor.
</P>
<P>
   Vivid memories of that journey returned as I watched footage of
last weekend's demonstrations in Washington against the
International Monetary Fund and the World Bank _ a rich-vs.-rich
argument over the rich-poor divide, between protesters from the
wealthiest nation on Earth and well-heeled officials over the
destiny of the world's poor, who were not, of course, present.
</P>
<P>
   One minute, I was rubbing shoulders with dot-com billionaires,
oil industry barons and sleek investment bankers, in an Alpine
village set among the pristine snow fields. The elect of the World
Economic Forum seemed almost to glow in contentment, suffused by
the huge prosperity of the New Economy.
</P>
<P>
   The next minute, on the Angola-Zambia border, I found myself
among the poorest of the poor, in a setting where the meaning of
the word economy had been distilled to the essentials of survival.
</P>
<P>
   In Davos, the talk had been of a global economic revolution,
with technology and knowledge as its standard-bearers. In Zambia,
north of a town called Mwinilunga, the talk was of whether the few
dollars in school fees levied by the state would be better used
buying food for the family.
</P>
<P>
   I had lived in Zambia in the mid-1970s, at the height of the war
between nationalist guerrillas from Zimbabwe and what was then the
white minority regime in Rhodesia. Hardship was visible then, too,
in the endless lines of women with babies strapped to their backs,
patiently waiting for corn or salt or sugar. But Zambians were told
that sacrifice was necessary, the price the nation paid for serving
as a base for the guerrillas in their struggle for majority rule.
</P>
<P>
   A quarter-century later, the appeals to a higher cause were
gone. Not globalization, but economic regionalization had arrived
with the ending of apartheid in South Africa. The beneficiaries
were a small urban elite, who carried cell phones and shopped at
stores transplanted from the malls of Johannesburg and Cape Town.
Anglo American Corp., the huge mining transnational based in
Johannesburg and London, was negotiating to buy back at fire-sale
prices the same copper mines it had lost to nationalization at
Zambia's independence from Britain in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the gleaming Shoprite supermarkets and the Steers
restaurants, in the urban shanties or in the countryside, was the
rest of the nation. The economy, victimized by years of
mismanagement and burdened by debt, was paralyzed, dependent on the
copper mines that earned badly-needed hard currency for state
coffers. The mines lost $150 million a year for the operators.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the 1970s, each Zambian's share of the national
wealth was tallied by the World Bank at a lowly $630; by the late
1990s it had fallen to $380. The currency, the Kwacha, had fallen
to something like one two-thousandth of its value in the 1970s, and
85 percent of the 8.2 million population lived on less than $1 a
day. AIDS infected 1.6 million people _ 20 percent of the
population _ killing the adults and creating a lost generation:
More than half the population is now under the age of 15, children
living in extended families with a dwindling number of wage
earners.
</P>
<P>
   In many parts of sub-Saharan Africa, of course, misery is just a
fact, rarely dramatic enough to draw the bright lights of a
visiting TV crew. In Zambia, for example, the economy had stagnated
long before globalization simply passed it by. Far to the northwest
of Lusaka, the Zambian capital, children of grade-school age tilled
dry fields instead of attending class. In the lee of the copper
mine dumps, which once symbolized Zambia's wealth, the highways
were so badly potholed that it was hard to see any asphalt surface.
Eleven-year-olds along the roadside sold stunted tomatoes at 15
cents a bunch from crudely woven baskets, earning pennies from
infrequent motorists.
</P>
<P>
   The global wealth imbalance between north and south is nothing
new. Indeed, in Africa, a pattern of dependency was established in
the colonial 19th century. Then as now, it was a leap in northern
technology _ the industrial revolution then, the Internet
revolution now _ that caused the gulf to widen. Then, as now, the
developed world set the rules. But if the new game of globalization
demands the free flow of money and trade, the question is whether
the parts of Africa I visited even have the chips to play.
</P>
<P>
   As the pace of change in the developed world _ embodied by the
Davos set _ has rocketed, buoyed by globalized trade and currency
flows, by soaring stock valuations and the stunning wealth created
by America's record growth, much of Africa has, at best, stood
still. And investment, the grease on which the global economy
glides, has largely dried up in the face of the continent's chronic
instability.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
