<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 10:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4208 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-PIPEDREAM.COM-REVIEW-     04-22 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIPEDREAM.COM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DOT-COM THAT'S, LIKE, AWESOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By GARY KRIST   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In this time of dizzying volatility on Wall Street, no company's
fortunes have seesawed quite so dramatically as those of
PipeDream.com, since its (imaginary) initial public offering in
January.
</P>
<P>
   PipeDream's stock zoomed from an initial price of $2 a share to
468 5/8 in its first week of trading, making its founder and chief
executive, Ethan Proctor, the youngest dot-com billionaire on
record. During the recent sell-off in technology stocks, however,
PipeDream plummeted to 2 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   To find out how the fledgling company was weathering the storm,
we arranged to meet Proctor at the Silicon Valley Video Arcade in
Mountain View, Calif., where the 17-year-old visionary was leading
his senior managers in a team-building exercise involving the
obliteration of slime creatures.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times: Mr. Proctor, what has been your greatest
challenge in starting this company?
</P>
<P>
   Ethan Proctor: Homework.
</P>
<P>
   The Times: Homework?
</P>
<P>
   E.P.: Well, yeah. I've got this English teacher? And she's
making us read Beowulf? It's sort of hard to develop international
marketing strategies when you know you're getting quizzed on the
genealogy of Hrothgar and Unferth right after lunch period.
</P>
<P>
   The Times: So it's been a struggle?
</P>
<P>
   E.P.: Absolutely. If it weren't for The Geekmeister here (chief
financial officer Thomas Benson Jr.), we'd never have been able to
get granular on our business plan in time for the IPO.
</P>
<P>
   The Times: Mr. Benson, is it true that you and Mr. Proctor
started PipeDream in the basement of your mother's ranch house in
suburban San Jose?
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Benson: Totally.
</P>
<P>
   The Times: Where is corporate headquarters now?
</P>
<P>
   T.B.: In the garage, behind the broken sofa-bed.
</P>
<P>
   The Times: It must have been a thrill to engineer one of the
most successful IPOs in Nasdaq history. How do you explain your
company's initial success?
</P>
<P>
   E.P.: Obviously the market understood that PipeDream's unique
position _ straddling the B2B and e-commerce sectors _ would allow
us to really pancake the value chain, injecting old economy
revenue-growth models at new economy valuations. Plus, a lot of
people seemed to like the name.
</P>
<P>
   The Times: Nonetheless, PipeDream is an untested company run by
young, inexperienced executives, without even the remotest
expectation of a profit. What do you say to people who claim that
prices of companies like PipeDream were ripe for a correction?
</P>
<P>
   E.P.: All I can say is they sound like my mom (vice president
for commissary operations Helen Proctor). We gave her the chance to
load up on stock options at the very beginning, but she did a total
self-toast. Told me that the only thing she wanted in exchange for
her services was that I clean up my room.
</P>
<P>
   The Times: And what does she say now?
</P>
<P>
   E.P.: She stopped being mad at me when I bought her a
controlling interest in Mary Kay Cosmetics for her birthday. But
now, after the correction, she keeps going ``I told you so, I told
you so.'' I hate that.
</P>
<P>
   The Times: But doesn't she have a point? Given the drop in your
market capitalization, won't you have trouble raising the money you
need to achieve your growth targets?
</P>
<P>
   E.P.: OK, the VCs have sort of stopped returning my phone calls.
But my management team and I are exploring alternative funding
sources.
</P>
<P>
   The Times: Such as?
</P>
<P>
   E.P.: Paper routes. And Dad's raising my allowance.
</P>
<P>
   The Times: Some of your critics have complained that PipeDream
seems to lack focus. What is PipeDream's mission in the
marketplace?
</P>
<P>
   E.P.: Well, like, we represent a new, you know, paradigm, geared
to the rapidly-changing realities of the 21st-century virtual
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   The Times: But what kind of product or service do you provide?
</P>
<P>
   E.P.: ``Product'' and ``service'' are totally last millennium
concepts. PipeDream is the future, and so whatever the future turns
out to be, PipeDream's going to be right there. What more do
investors need to know?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 1046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000422.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4209 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-HEALTHCARE-PERKS-REVI     04-22 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTHCARE-PERKS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CASH COWS: A LA CARTE AT THE HOSPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   At Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in New York City,
patients can enjoy a live midday classical music concert between
chemotherapy treatments. In Newport Beach, Calif., Dr. George
Brennan, a dermatologist, sells his skin-care creams out of his
office. At a hospital on New York's Long Island, nurses are
learning how to massage premature babies, a skill they will pass on
to new parents.
</P>
<P>
   Today Americans have new expectations about their health care
system. They want the very latest in medical technology to cure
their diseases, just as they hunger for the latest sports utility
vehicles and other jazzy consumer goods. But they are also seeking
balms for psyches often embattled by illness, and ways of dealing
with pain and discomfort that do not come in pill form. They are
also looking to medicine to improve their looks, often in an
environment where a checkup, a cancer screening and a facial can
all be done under one roof.
</P>
<P>
   And the health care industry is responding to consumer demand.
Not only are doctors offering more aesthetic procedures, but
hospitals are also adding complementary services _ departments that
enhance traditional care, hospital administrators say, but do not
replace it.
</P>
<P>
   Services like massage therapy for a cancer patient or anti-aging
creams for a dermatology client give doctors and hospitals a
competitive edge. Patients pay for much of this care, especially
aesthetic procedures, in full and in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital executives realize that they need to borrow a page from
the hotel industry to attract patients. It is not enough to be set
up on the beach when all your competitors are there, too _ extras
count.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very clear that in the consumers' mind, the notion of
what is health care has broadened considerably in the last
decade,'' said Dr. George Tyson, an administrator at University
Hospital and Medical Center at Stony Brook, N.Y., which offers
infant massage among the services in its complementary medicine
department.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want a health care system that above and beyond illness
improves their quality of life,'' Tyson said. ``At the same time,
this industry is looking for new sources of revenue and has the
capacity to meet this demand. So it seems to be the ideal match.''
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals have ample evidence that Americans are looking outside
of traditional medicine in their pursuit of good health. Americans
spent $27.2 billion on alternative, nontraditional care in 1998. A
recent study published in the American Cancer Society's journal
found that 37 percent of prostate cancer patients turned to
vitamins, massage therapy, herbal remedies and relaxation therapy
as part of their treatment; other studies have gleaned similar
results.
</P>
<P>
   Many health care experts say that part of what drives patients'
interest in this area is their desire to play some role in their
own care. ``Patients these days are not passive recipients of
care,'' said Barrie R. Cassileth, who runs the complementary center
at Sloan Kettering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Care in cancer medicine can be very scattered,'' Cassileth
said. ``Patients usually have several physicians, and it is very
difficult to interact with all those individuals and have a sense
of wholeness. People want connections and to better understand what
is going on.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Americans now treat health care much like any
other consumed good _ they comparison shop, check the Internet for
new information about their illness and quiz doctors about
treatments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Providers have to work hard to favorably differentiate
themselves,'' said Tyson. ``But because the quality of care is not
measured in any precise way, another strategy is to offer services
that the public is looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson points to cancer as one example. ``With cancer, a
considerable number of patients are looking for cutting-edge
conventional care combined with a kinder, gentler form of
medicine,'' he said. ``This can be used to differentiate your
cancer care center from the one across town.''
</P>
<P>
   About 20 percent of the members of the American Academy of
Medical Acupuncture have hospital privileges; five years ago that
number was closer to 5 percent, said James Dowden, executive
administrator for the group.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Richard C. Niemtzow is the military's first acupuncturist.
He runs a pilot program at the Naval Medical Center San Diego to
treat pain and nausea in the center's pain clinic and breast health
center.
</P>
<P>
   The John S. Marten Center for Complementary Medicine and Pain
Management started nine years ago at St. Vincent's Hospital in
Indianapolis after its benefactor, who was dying of prostate
cancer, proclaimed he wanted a center for pain that did not depend
on narcotics. The program, which is expanding, includes
acupuncture, herbal medicine and nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Wesley Wong, who is the medical director of the medical
specialities service line at St. Vincent's Hospital, said the
complementary services are hugely popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``We book up four weeks in advance,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 1049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000422.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6840 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-PIPEDREAM.COM-REVIEW-     04-22 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIPEDREAM.COM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DOT-COM THAT'S, LIKE, AWESOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By GARY KRIST   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In this time of dizzying volatility on Wall Street, no company's
