<DOCNO> NYT20000422.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 10:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4210 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-VIETNAM-MEMORIES-REVI     04-22 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIETNAM-MEMORIES-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO VIETNAM AND BACK. AND BACK. AND BACK. 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By SERGE SCHMEMANN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Our memory of Vietnam, like any other, is shaped in part by what
we allow ourselves to say, and that has changed over the years, as
have my generation and the country that sent many of us to Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   When I went there in 1969, and when I returned home a year and
12 days later, Vietnam was a subject my friends and I avoided
talking about. For those who had not gone, there was something
embarrassing about talking to someone who had, after all the
energies they had all expended on damning the war and anyone who
was part of it, and on eluding the draft. And for my part, I had no
interest in defending a war that all the guys in my unit hated just
as much, only in a different way.
</P>
<P>
   We were not grunts, the sweat-soaked kids in jungle fatigues so
familiar now from movies and that bronze sculpture of three
servicemen next to the Vietnam memorial in Washington. Drafted out
of graduate school, I was trained in artillery fire direction
control, assigned to the 23rd Artillery Group in II Field Force,
and, in the enigmatic wisdom of the Army, set to work as a
personnel clerk, first in Long Binh, the huge base not far from
Saigon, then in Phu Loi, on the highway to Cambodia. Many of the
guys in the headquarters were also older, drafted from college and
graduate school, but we counted days like everybody else, wore
peace symbols, pulled guard duty and proclaimed that 'Nam was ``No.
10'' _ bad.
</P>
<P>
   But our 'Nam was not the Vietnam back home: These were entirely
different concepts that shared only the name of a lovely and badly
scarred country in Southeast Asia, whose delicate-looking people,
history and customs very few of us _ ``in country'' or ``in the
world'' _ ever bothered to learn about. Over there we lived in a
world of our own, a sweaty, sometimes dangerous place where we wore
loose jungle fatigues, slept in hootches, wrote long letters home,
longed for R&AMP;R and counted days to DEROS (``date of estimated
return from overseas'') and the Freedom Bird that would take us
home. It was a place with a GI culture and language all its own,
where grunts humped the paddies to waste Charlie or get blown away,
where angry brothers fragged white officers, where Vietnamese
squatting by the roadside sold No. 1 (best) grass in deftly
resealed Marlboro packs and there were always several choppers
slapping through the rancid black plumes from burning latrine cans.
</P>
<P>
   We were young, we bonded, we changed. And we returned home to
the other Vietnam, the domestic battlefield of hard-hats and
peaceniks, the Vietnam that one side proclaimed the front line
against godless communism, and the other a symbol of all the greed
and immorality of a perfidious Establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after I came back, the protests waned, but we still avoided
talking about the war. Some veterans felt alienated among peers
who, they felt, looked on them with condescension, as sad guys who
had been fooled into fighting an immoral war. Most of us simply
didn't know what to say, both those who had been there or those who
had not, especially after the Americans abandoned Vietnam in that
excruciating display of shame, panic and betrayal. There was the
beginning of a literature, most notably Michael Herr's brilliant
``Dispatches,'' David Rabe's off-Broadway staging of ``The Basic
Training of Pavlo Hummel,'' Ronald Glasser's ``365 Days.'' But they
were glimpses of 'Nam, not a reckoning. That began in earnest only
with the Vietnam memorial in 1982, possibly the most honest shrine
ever raised to the fallen soldier.
</P>
<P>
   But the image of Vietnam and the veterans that developed in the
1980s was far different from any Vietnam, or any grunt, I had
known. Movies like ``Apocalypse Now,'' ``Full Metal Jacket'' or
``Platoon'' created a swampy, fiery hell peopled by psychopaths
(``I love the smell of napalm in the morning''). They complemented
emerging images in the media of the ``Vietnam vet'' as a troubled
and neglected victim _ a scraggly and deranged outcast with a
rumpled boony hat, a legless victim converted to pacifism, a
returning POW scarred by unspeakable horrors. There were all these,
to be sure, and others: For some veterans, the emotional conflict
between the abiding loyalties of shared danger and the shame of a
failed and unpopular war coalesced into an impassioned crusade to
account for all missing GIs. For military officers, Vietnam became
a nightmarish memory of body bags, humiliation and division, until
any mission that carried even the remotest hint of ``another
Vietnam'' encountered instinctive resistance.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the conflicting and bizarre images, at least we
could talk about it now. Writers like Tim O'Brien (``The Things
They Carried''), Neil Sheehan (``A Bright Shining Lie: John Paul
Vann and America in Vietnam'') and many others began to look more
deeply into the war and the men who made and fought it. We also
began to talk about it among ourselves and with our children, for
whom the '60s and Vietnam already had the pallor of history and
myth. The recriminations could still surface, but as we grew older
we could look on old passions with forbearance, even nostalgia.
With time, the Vietnam vet became a respectable, even slightly
romantic figure, and politicians like Sens. John F. Kerry, Bob
Kerrey and John McCain, who had served in Vietnam, acquired a moral
edge over those, like Bill Clinton, who had not.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In moments of honesty, we began admitting to one another that
our actions all those years ago were not always as noble as we
liked to think they were.
</P>
<P>
   At the 25th reunion of my class at Harvard in 1992, a panel
discussion titled ``The Choices We Made,'' turned into a stunning
exercise in brutal candor, almost confession. Hundreds of us sat
spellbound hour after hour as one classmate after another explored
why he or she had opposed the war, or participated in it. Only
after the custodians threatened to turn off the lights and lock us
in did the meeting break up. One man acknowledged, to my silent
empathy, that he went only because he would never be able to face
his father if he didn't. My family were immigrants, I might have
added, and my father would have taken my dodging the draft as rank
ingratitude. The speaker tried to tell about a friend who was blown
away before his eyes, but could not, leaving us all in a long and
terrible silence. A woman then acknowledged that she became active
against the war also, and only, out of deference to her parents.
Then: ``Actually, they were Communist Party members.'' Then,
quietly, ``So was I.'' Another classmate told of never building a
life after years of protests and jails, and of finally landing work
as a train conductor. When one former member of the Students for a
Democratic Society _ the radical SDS _ launched into an aggressive
recital of old charges, he was universally jeered into silence. We
had tacitly agreed that day that only conscience could judge the
choices we had made.
</P>
<P>
   The old controversies still surface sometimes. But by and large,
the war is fading from the public consciousness. There is no
communist threat any more, and a wholly new Army has been built, in
which only a handful of senior officers served in Vietnam. In the
rare movie that uses Vietnam, like ``Rules of Engagement,'` the war
is little more than a handy cliche. For today's children, I
sometimes think with amazement, Vietnam is almost as remote as
World War I was for us _ only lacking the glow that national memory
reserves for victories.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 1051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
