 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
 FOR SUNDAY AMs 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of SUNDAY, April 23:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ROME-PILGRIMS (Rome) _ Only a handful of the estimated 500,000
Roman Catholics who flocked to Rome to celebrate Holy Week came on
foot. But beneath a shiny veneer of modern comfort and efficiency _
Internet-ready visitors' centers, air-conditioned Jubilee buses,
microchip-equipped pilgrim cards that automatically book church
services, tours and restaurants, chemical toilets and electric
votive candles _ the Holy Year 2000 is laced with the kind of
humble piety and awe that drew the first Jubilee pilgrims here in
1300. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   DUTCH-WORKER-SHORTAGE (Amsterdam, Netherlands) _ Recruiting the
elderly _ men and women who want to occupy their days, battle
loneliness or top up their pensions _ has become a Dutch growth
industry. While unemployment hovers around 10 percent in other
parts of Europe, the Dutch have the opposite problem: With only 2.7
percent jobless, the country is seriously short of workers. By
Marlise Simons.
</P>
<P>
   ANDES-UNREST (Undated) _ Guerrillas and the cocaine trade batter
Colombia. A strongman rides roughshod over a discredited Congress
and courts in Venezuela. Ecuador reels from an economic crisis and
a coup. Bolivia has just emerged from a state of siege. And Peru
awaits an election between an autocrat accused of trying to steal
the presidency and a political firebrand. Suddenly it seems as if
all the Andes are in tumult. By Larry Rohter with Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   ETHIOPIA-WAR (Addis Ababa, Ethiopia) _ There are few issues as
sensitive in Ethiopia and none as obvious: The nation is waging a
hugely expensive war, estimated to cost at least $500,000 a day in
salaries alone, while 8 million of its people struggle through the
worst food shortage here in nearly 20 years. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-LANGUAGE (Dili, East Timor) _ What will be the spoken
language of East Timor? It is a hotly emotional issue, one that
goes to the heart of the self-definition of the world's newest
nation. Will it be the language of the international marketplace,
English? Will it be the dominant local language, Tetun, with its
broad usage but limited vocabulary? Will it be the historical
colonial language, Portuguese, the sentimental favorite of the
older generation? Or will it be Indonesian, the common language of
the young and the educated? By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN-POLICY-POLL (Undated) _ The more Americans know about
the world, the more likely they are to favor diplomacy over
punitive sanctions in dealing with troublesome foreign countries, a
poll has found. Embargoes, they say, not only isolate the nations
at which they are aimed but also hurt American business. By Barbara
Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ENTREPRENEURS (Tokyo) _ Changes in the relationship
between employer and employee, the liberalization of the financial
markets and the explosion of new business models in the
freewheeling arenas of the Internet and information technology are
spawning a whole new breed of entrepreneurs who care little for the
conventions that have dominated Japan Inc. for decades. By
Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-CORRUPTION (Dublin, Ireland) _ After nearly three years
of relatively fruitless investigations into property development
fraud, one of Ireland's longstanding tribunals broke new ground
last week when a lobbyist admitted paying local politicians the
equivalent of $136,000 to win approval for a supermarket
development. The admission by Frank Dunlop, a lobbyist and former
press officer with the Irish government, is likely to cast a
harsher spotlight on the corruption of Ireland's politics. By Brian
Lavery.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Dateline TK) _ Federal agents seized Elian Gonzalez
from the home of his Miami relatives before dawn Saturday, firing
pepper spray into an angry crowd as they took away the 6-year-old
boy for a reunion with his father. The father, Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, was waiting at Andrews Air Force Base near Washington
when Elian arrived from Miami. (Summary from wires.) By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   With the following sidebars; lineup subject to change depending
on developments.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-SCENE (Miami) _ The scene at the house when federal
marshals moved in.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-MIAMI (Miami) _ Reaction in Miami.
</P>
