<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-FINAL-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, April 23, moved Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM-MEMORIES-REVIEW (Undated) _ Serving in Vietnam, we
bonded, we changed. And we returned home to the other Vietnam, the
domestic battlefield of hard-hats and peaceniks, the Vietnam that
one side proclaimed the frontline against godless communism, and
the other a symbol of all the greed and immorality of a perfidious
establishment. The protests waned, but we still avoided talking
about the war. Many people viewed veterans of the war with
condescension. But the image of Vietnam and the veterans that
developed in the 1980s was far different from any grunt, or any
Vietnam I knew. By Serge Schmemann. (Moved in the `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   TECH-SNOBS-REVIEW (Undated) _ In these digital days, not knowing
the difference between memory and hard disk space can be grounds
for social ostracism. Cell phones are required for professionals
from a certain class background, and it helps to flaunt a personal
digital assistant _ preferably one with data-beaming capabilities.
``Early adopters'' have always been a bit obnoxious. From the first
proud few to replace slide rules with calculators to CB radio
hobbyists to the audiophiles who paid thousands of dollars for the
first CD players, gadget freaks have often seemed to exist in a
jargon-filled matrix of their own, oblivious to the mundanities of
civil society. By Amy Harmon. (Moved in the `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHCARE-PERKS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Americans have new
expectations from their health care system. They want the latest in
medical technology, just as they hunger for the latest sports
utility vehicles and other jazzy consumer goods. But they also seek
balms for psyches often embattled by illness, and ways of dealing
with pain and discomfort that do not come in pill form. They are
also want medicine to improve their looks, often in an environment
where a checkup, a cancer screening and a facial can all be done
under one roof. And the health care industry is responding to
consumer demand. It is offering more aesthetic procedures and
complementary services. By Jennifer Steinhauer.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-BOY-REVIEW (Undated) _ The Elian Gonzalez case illustrates
that courts run on adult time while children suffer the
consequences. For many American children, their destinies remain
uncertain, sometimes for months and years, as their custody and
child welfare cases wind through the courts. Experts see tension
between two competing notions of time: the deliberate, adult pace
of the law, in which a day, or a week or a month may be seen as not
significant, and the the highly compressed time of child
development, in which bonds can be made, or poisoned, in the same
space of time. By Somni Sengupta.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-HISTORY-REVIEW (Undated) _ Both sides in the gun control
debate assume that America's earliest experiences with guns shaped
the modern American character. Where they differ is on whether
Americans should embrace their frontier heritage and reliance on
guns, or resist it. But in a new book due this fall, a historian
challenges what he calls a modern myth and argues that gun
ownership in the frontier era was far from universal. By Anthony
Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   PIPEDREAM.COM-REVIEW (Undated) _ In this time of dizzying
