<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000422.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 12:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4249 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-LA-SUPES-2Takes-LADN     04-22 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-SUPES-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. COUNTY BOARD MAY FACE CHANGES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY ANDERSON  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES - With support from conservative forces, a powerful
Eastside Democratic legislator has shaken that impregnable bastion
of Los Angeles County government, the Board of Supervisors, with
the threat of imposing term limits on supervisors and slashing
their personal budgets as part of board expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Richard Polanco's proposal to put the
issue on the November ballot by legislative action and without the
support of the supervisors triggered a mad scramble at the county
Hall of Administration, where supervisors once elected are
virtually guaranteed lifetime positions.
</P>
<P>
   Polanco _ widely expected to seek a City Council seat next year
_ on Friday added 12-year term limits to his bill expanding the
board from five to nine members and holding the board's $15.3
million-a-year budget for staff and expenses, effectively cutting
nearly in half the $3 million a year each supervisor now gets.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot increase the size of government without increasing
the costs,'' Supervisor Michael D. Antonovich fumed. ``It's like
cotton candy. It's all fluff with no substance.
</P>
<P>
   He said Polanco's bill is an attempt ``to get a job for himself
by expanding government in Los Angeles County. ... He's
term-limited and this is his one opportunity to keep his political
life alive.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Polanco plan got a warm reception from political leaders
in outlying areas that often feel underserved by the supervisors,
who each represent some 2 million constituents, a number that would
be cut nearly in half by expansion.
</P>
<P>
   And taxpayer watchdogs also looked favorably at the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Coupal, president of the Howard Jarvis Taxpayer's
Association, said the association may not object to an expanded
board.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact of the matter is each of the supervisors represents
an inordinately high number of constituents,'' Coupal said. ``If
this proposal would enhance constituent services without costing
taxpayers more money, we may not object. I think term limits would
be a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Board of Supervisors, which has resisted term limits and
cuts in its budgets, the Polanco expansion could be the most
serious threat yet to its power as it comes from a powerful and
ambitious state senator and answers the key concerns of voters, who
have rejected board expansion three times in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the supervisors lined up in opposition to the measure
while their staffs grappled with the prospect of many of their jobs
being eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Mabie, a spokesman for Polanco, said the senator believes
the November election is the right time to put the measure on the
ballot because the supervisors' districts will be redrawn after the
2000 census.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would divvy up the pie into nine pieces,'' he said. ``You
wouldn't have an increase in bureaucratic costs. The term limits
amendment would increase its likelihood of passing at the statewide
level.''
</P>
<P>
   County officials said they are skeptical that expansion can be
achieved without increasing costs. Four additional offices would
require an expensive office renovation, they said, and reducing
staffs would hamper the ability to monitor county departments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Supervisor Knabe believes the measure doesn't put more deputy
sheriffs on the street, reduce caseloads for probation officers or
improve services to children,'' said John Wallace, a spokesman for
Supervisor Don Knabe. ``All it does is expand government.''
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of Supervisors Gloria Molina and Yvonne
Brathwaite Burke said those two supervisors have supported board
expansion. But neither could be reached Friday for an opinion on
the term limits amendment. Supervisor Supervisor Zev Yaroslavsky
had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the ballot measure say it would give the San
Fernando Valley two seats, create opportunities for greater
minority representation and make board members more responsive.
</P>
<P>
   The total proposed 2000-2001 budget of the Board of Supervisors,
personal staffs and the Executive Office is $34.6 million. The
salaries of the highest paid of the supervisors' 130-plus workers _
their chiefs of staff _ range from $101,798 to $120,711 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are not exactly chopped-liver salaries,'' said Fernando
Oaxaca, chair of the Latino Republican Coalition and a proponent of
board expansion. ``Some of their senior staff members make more
than state senators and Assembly people.''
</P>
<P>
   Oaxaca said the supervisors could cut their budgets by reducing
travel costs and cutting back on their use of county automobiles,
helicopters and field offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The field offices are a self-perpetuating process. They have
field offices that help them market themselves in terms of
re-election. If they have less money to spend, they will have to
cut back there.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL 2ND TAKE FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Richard Close, an attorney and president of the Sherman Oaks
Homeowners Association, and chairman of Valley Voters Organized
Toward Empowerment, said he believes expanding the Board of
Supervisors would make the supervisors less responsive to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only the professionally paid lobbyists will be able to afford
to spend time lobbying nine supervisors vs. the current five,''
Close said. ``It would make our job more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Board of Supervisors is doing a good job and this
measure is not being promoted for good government. It's being
promoted so some term-limited politicians can find jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Clayton, director of equal employment opportunity for the
Los Angeles County Chicano Employees Association, challenged his
argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be better service to the community, more
opportunities for people to run for office, because the districts
will be 44 percent smaller, and we will overcome the current
situation where there is not one supervisor who lives in the San
Fernando, Antelope or San Gabriel valleys,'' Clayton said.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman George Runner, R-Lancaster, who is co-authoring the
bill, said the measure would provide more representation to the
cities in the San Fernando, Antelope and San Gabriel valleys
because those cities would make up a larger percentage of their
districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would allow them to have greater clout and lobbying
ability when it came to their interests,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mabie said Polanco had hoped the county supervisors would have
decided earlier this year to put the measure on the county's ballot
in November.
</P>
<P>
   The supervisors voted last August to direct the county counsel
to write language for the ballot to head off an attempt by state
legislators to place the issue on a statewide ballot.
</P>
<P>
   But the supervisors haven't taken any action on the draft since
it was released last December.
</P>
<P>
   ``We prefer them to handle this locally,'' Mabie said. ``But the
ball is in their court.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Diaz, chair of the Los Angeles City County Latino
Redistricting Coalition, said the supervisors have made attempts to
stall the measure because it threatens their power.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been called the five kings,'' he said. ``Now they are
three kings and two queens. You have to imagine the power they
have. The county population is larger than 42 other states. And
each supervisor's district is three times larger than a
congressional district.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are talking about real power. With term limits, they could
lose power in 12 years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 1234EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
