<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 13:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4261 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-DUTCH-WORKER-SHORTAGE     04-22 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUTCH-WORKER-SHORTAGE-ART-795&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETIRED, REHIRED: DUTCH FILL CRUCIAL WORK-FORCE GAP 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: The word PLUS in parentheses has been used instead of the
symbol, which is nontransmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MARLISE SIMONS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMSTERDAM, Netherlands _ Frans Tuijntjes, a former NATO test
pilot, has flown in the Arizona desert, across much of Europe and
over the African bush. But these days he is selling men's clothing
and loving it.
</P>
<P>
   The former pilot, who has just turned 69, was bored in
retirement. So when he heard of 65(PLUS), a new employment agency
designed for the elderly, it seemed just the thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've sold airplanes, so I figured I could sell a suit,'' he
said, returning from his part-time job at a local Marks &AMP; Spencer
store. ``It's fun because I meet all sorts of people and I can
practice my languages.''
</P>
<P>
   Recruiting the elderly _ men and women who want to occupy their
days, to battle loneliness or to top up their pensions _ has become
a Dutch growth industry. While unemployment hovers around 10
percent in other parts of Europe, the Dutch now have the opposite
problem: With only 2.7 percent jobless, the country is seriously
short of workers.
</P>
<P>
   Companies describe older employees as unusually motivated,
experienced and loyal. Demand is such that this year the 65(PLUS)
chain is expanding into 10 cities.
</P>
<P>
   Only a decade ago, the indulgent Dutch welfare state was
subsidizing inactivity. It encouraged the middle-aged to take early
retirement or disability pay in order to make room for the
unemployed young. Many people opted out, with almost full pay.
</P>
<P>
   But harsh cutbacks and investment incentives have turned the
tables. The economy grew quickly in the past five years, reaching
4.3 percent in 1999. Companies complain that the tight labor market
is now hampering growth, because they can no longer fill vacancies.
</P>
<P>
   The labor shortage has prompted a national debate on some
sensitive questions: How many more immigrants should be let into a
small country that is already one of the world's most densely
populated? Can the government force people to retrain? How much
should it raise retirement age?
</P>
<P>
   Last month the government formally summoned the elderly to
return to work, saying it needed their experience. It sweetened the
call with a package of incentives.
</P>
<P>
   Jos Veenhuis did not need such prodding. He got his job through
65(PLUS) and now spends two or three days a week as a guard at the
Rembrandt House museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets me out of the house, and it's fun when people ask
questions,'' said Veenhuis, 70, who retired at age 59 as personnel
chief at Amsterdam's main railway station.
</P>
<P>
   He has boned up on topics such as Rembrandt's stormy life and
the restoration of art works. And he enjoys going home at night
with a few stories. ``Americans ask things like `What wax do you
use?' because some restored paintings look so bright and shiny,''
he said. (No wax.) ``The Dutch want to know if the furniture in the
house really belonged to the Master.'' (It didn't.)
</P>
<P>
   Veenhuis has used the extra income for vacations with his wife
in Greece and Spain. ``And I've become a real Rembrandt fan,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   At the 65(PLUS) agencies, jobs being offered tend to be
part-time, which is what older people usually look for, said
Annemarie Egels, a branch manager in The Hague. Most of her
applicants are men, because, she said, after a long career they
seem to feel more frustrated or isolated in retirement than women,
who in that generation often stayed at home.
</P>
<P>
   Egels said there are more requests for receptionists, cashiers,
personnel managers and accountants than she can handle.
</P>
<P>
   The range is even wider at 55(PLUS), an agency for
over-55-year-olds in Rotterdam, which in the past 18 months has
seen demand soar for health-care workers, teachers and librarians.
``Companies tell us they find the older people not only more
experienced but also more polite, more patient and punctual,'' said
Christie de Groot, the agency director.
</P>
<P>
   Recruiters say there is also a need for former executives, who
may be called in to help start or reorganize companies, since
younger workers are often very specialized.
</P>
<P>
   Egels recalled one recent project that involved merging several
libraries for the blind and creating a common database. ``We found
a retired publisher, lawyer, real estate agent and mathematics
teacher,'' she recalled. ``They did the job in a year and they've
all been friends ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   Calling in the retired has other benefits. Employers can pay
them 20 percent to 25 percent less because they no longer need to
contribute to social security or other benefits.
</P>
<P>
   But additional earnings can push the pensioner into a higher tax
bracket. ``Of course my income taxes have gone up a bit,'' said
Bert Pel, 66, who used to head a federation of importers and now
does part-time bookkeeping for the Red Cross. ``It's worth it,'' he
said. ``I'm making new friends and I keep up with the new computer
systems.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Computers are one problem area. The elderly have little or no
experience in information technology, yet demand for even basic
computer skills is such that employment agencies are providing
training. Even 65(PLUS) thinks the investment is worthwhile. For
its clients it pays half the cost of the computer training course.
The client or the employer pays the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Because jobs are often short-term or part-time, no reliable
statistics are available showing how many retired people are now
working. Agencies like 65(PLUS) and 55(PLUS) handle hundreds of
applicants each month. But it is clear that the retired who have
gone back to work are just a small portion of the 2 million people
who are 65 or older in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   And this underscores another fundamental issue. Europe's overall
population is older than that of any other continent, and the
Netherlands is among the countries where every year a smaller
percentage of people are working and a larger percentage are
collecting pensions.
</P>
<P>
   Tuijntjes, the former test pilot, said three days per week at
the Marks &AMP; Spencer store were enough pressure. ``I'm already by
far the oldest employee there,'' he said with a chuckle. ``Of
course I'll keep going as long as I don't make a fool of myself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 1304EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000422.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4262 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-EARTH-DAY-ART-NYT &LR;      04-22 0442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARTH-DAY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
  
 PEACEFUL, EASY FEELING PREVAILS AT 30th EARTH DAY CELEBRATION  
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT12 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By JEFF GERTH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Under the banner of clean energy, Earth Day
participants Saturday celebrated in the nation's capital and at
thousands of events around the globe in an extravaganza of
entertainment, advocacy and politics.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists and supporters participated in events in 183
countries for the 30th Earth Day.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people gathered peacefully at the Mall in
Washington, less than a week after hundreds of demonstrators were
arrested here, protesting the global activities of international
lending agencies. Among other things, those protesters had objected
to the environmental policies of the World Bank and International
Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's rallies were organized by the Seattle-based Earth Day
Network, whose chairman, Denis Hayes, was the national coordinator
for the 1970 event. The teach-ins and rallies of that original
Earth Day, more informal and less global, helped inaugurate the
modern environmental movement in the United States and was the
spark for two landmark environmental laws signed by President
Richard M. Nixon, the Clean Air Act and the Clean Water Act.
</P>
<P>
   In his radio address Saturday, President Clinton announced two
new but relatively modest initiatives to combat global warming and
celebrate Earth Day. Clinton said he was going to require federal
agencies to reduce by 20 percent over five years the amount of
gasoline their vehicle fleets consume. This would save 45 million
gallons of oil a year.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also announced a program to allow federal workers to set
aside up to $65 tax-free every month to pay for public
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's celebration in Washington, called EarthFair 2000, was
not politically diverse. But the rally's loosely organized format
made for some interesting contrasts But the rally's loosely
organized format made for some interesting contrasts. The actor
Leonardo Di Caprio led the festivities. DiCaprio, 25, was scheduled
to be a host on an Earth Day special on the ABC television network
Saturday night. But Saturday's rallies also featured speakers who
back a campaign seeking to raise the environmental conscience of
some prominent corporations, like Walt Disney Co., which owns ABC
and will distribute a movie starring DiCaprio.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign, ecopledge.com, asks corporations to change
environmental practices, or face possible boycotts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
