<DOCNO> NYT20000422.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4286 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-JUSTICE-ART     04-22 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-JUSTICE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO MAKES TOUGH CALL MINUTES BEFORE DEADLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT4 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Their self-imposed deadline was 5 a.m. Saturday,
and as the minutes ticked away before federal law-enforcement
officials had to decide whether to seize Elian Gonzalez at
gunpoint, Attorney General Janet Reno was on the phone to the boy's
Miami relatives, appealing to them one last time to end the
impasse.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are running out of time,'' an aide to the attorney general
recalled that Reno said, describing her voice as emphatic but laced
with emotion and fatigue after all-night negotiations. ``You've got
to decide now,'' Reno said. ``That's all the time you have.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, as Reno held the phone in her office at the Justice
Department, a team of eight agents, some of them armed and wearing
body armor and jumpsuits, swarmed into the house of Elian's great
uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez. It was just the kind of raid, armed and
confrontational and carried out under darkness, that the officials
had called their worst alternative for weeks. The image of an armed
federal agent flushing the boy from a closet was displayed on
television Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Within three minutes the agents were gone, taking the child to a
waiting minivan, ending a five-month-long custody battle that had
haunted Reno, who had tried, and repeatedly failed, to conclude the
case without the use of force.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday morning after the raid, President Clinton said Reno
made the right decision and that he supported her. ``The law has
been upheld,'' he said, ``and that was the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She made the decision,'' Clinton said. ``She managed this. But
I fully support what she did. I think she did the right thing, and
I'm very pleased with the way she handled it.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal law-enforcement officials, who had scheduled the
operation for Saturday, had said that they had to begin the
operation no later than 6 a.m., when traffic lights in the area
would change from flashing amber to the normal red and green and
when crowds were expected to gather. Operational commanders had
informed Reno that the order to go ahead had to be given no later
than 5 a.m. in order to carry it out Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, which agents had rehearsed for nearly two weeks,
hinged on their ability to carry out a lightning raid, with little
warning to local authorities, who federal authorities feared were
sympathetic to Cuban-Americans in Miami and might compromise
operational security.
</P>
<P>
   The agents arrived in force, some wearing jumpsuits and carrying
automatic weapons. The weaponry, officials said, was needed to
ensure the safety of Elian and the agents. Moreover, the officials
said Reno had received unconfirmed reports that there might be
weapons in the house and authorities were concerned about the
possibility of violence from small numbers of political extremists
believed to be among the demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Saturday, Reno said that she had received
information that there might be guns ``perhaps in the crowd,
perhaps in the house'' and said that agents were armed as
justifiable precaution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been told on occasion that people would have weapons
to prevent it from happening,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   She said that Elian's Miami relatives left the government no
alternative but to take the child by force.
</P>
<P>
   ``I informed the parties that time had run out,'' she said after
an all-night session of negotiations that ended with the boy's
seizure before dawn.
</P>
<P>
   She expressed frustration over the actions of the relatives in
the long standoff. ``Every time we thought we had achieved what we
wanted, it wasn't enough,'' Reno said. ``It was just one step after
another in which they moved the goalpost.''
</P>
<P>
   Photographs taken by a photographer for the Associated Press in
the house during the assault operation showed one of the fishermen
who rescued Elian at sea five months ago backed into a closet,
holding startled-looking boy, as a helmeted agent in assault gear
held them at bay.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the photo, Reno said the gun ``was pointed to the
side'' and the agent's ``finger was not on the trigger.'' Reno did
not say whether any weapons had been found in the house and
officials said later they were unaware that any firearms or other
weapons had been discovered.
</P>
<P>
   As the hours ticked down to minutes, Reno held out hope for a
settlement as civic leaders in Miami tried to broker a last-ditch
deal. From her corner office at the Justice Department, Reno
relayed proposals and counteroffers between lawyers for Elian's
father and the Miami relatives, keeping hope alive for a negotiated
outcome, aides to Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   Aides grouped in ante room outside Reno's office worked through
the night, at times frantically consulting with colleagues on the
phone to interpret the offers and counteroffers, at times waiting,
sitting on the floor eating pizza as they waited through the long
predawn hours.
</P>
<P>
   The first proposals from the relatives were so vague, the aides
said, that Reno demanded more specifics before she took the
proposal to Gregory Craig, a lawyer for Elian's father. ``The
attorney general said she wasn't going to take an offer that did
not contain the components that we knew would be required,'' an
aide said.
</P>
<P>
   As the talks continued, Justice Department officials said, they
began to doubt that the lawyers in Miami were getting cooperation
from the family, who seemed to remain unwilling to surrender the
child unconditionally to this father.
</P>
<P>
   Prodded to come up with a more concrete proposal, the relatives'
lawyer suggested that Elian be moved to a group home in a neutral
location in which father and son would live with the Miami
relatives while a federal appeals decides whether the child should
remain in the United States, according to the accounts of aides to
Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Craig rejected the idea, officials said, countering with the
same demand that Elian be turned over immediately to his father,
but agreeing to move to a residence where the relatives would be
able to visit the child.
</P>
<P>
   The indirect discussion, carried out by telephone and fax
between Washington and Miami, bogged down and collapsed. Reno
polled her aides on whether time had finally come for the
law-enforcement action, officials said. Eric H. Holder Jr., the
deputy attorney general, said that Reno's advisers were unanimous
in urging her to go forward.
</P>
<P>
   After two telephone conversations Friday night between Reno and
Clinton, she advised the president of the status of the final
efforts to break the impasse, but did not focus on the timing or
specifics of the use of force to retrieve the child.
</P>
<P>
   Then at 2:45 a.m. the White House chief of staff, John Podesta,
telephoned Clinton in the White House residence. Aides said that
Clinton said he would support the tactical operation if the
negotiations seemed fruitless. Podesta woke the president at 5 a.m.
to advise him that the talks were at a stalemate and that Reno had
ordered the agents to seize the boy.
</P>
<P>
   At the Justice Department, as officials watched the pre-dawn
assault on the house, Holder said he felt sadness. ``Many of us are
parents of children that age,'' Holder said. ``It was not an easy
thing to see a boy of that age carried out like that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 1327EDT &QL; 
