<DOCNO> NYT20000422.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4291 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-SCENE-NYT &LR;      04-22 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGRY DEMONSTRATORS QUICKLY GATHER OUTSIDE THE GONZALEZ HOUSE IN
MIAMI 
</HEADLINE>
   By JUAN FORERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ In minutes, it seemed, the street in front of the home
where Elian Gonzalez had been sleeping awoke to a loud and raucous
protest, as neighbors spilled from their homes and Cuban-Americans
summoned by cell phone rushed to the scene. Their little boy was
gone _ taken by federal agents who stormed the house at 5:15 a.m._
and they were not going to keep quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Impassioned, anguished and angry, hundreds soon gathered in
front of the tiny white house on Northwest Second Street to direct
their anger toward Attorney General Janet Reno and President
Clinton. The strident anti-Castro Cubans charged that the two had
conspired with none other than Fidel Castro to remove the boy and
reunite him with his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought they would take him; I thought Clinton and
Reno would respect the laws of the United States,'' said Saul Mari,
62, who, like many here, believes that handing Elian to his father
is akin to handing him over to the Cuban government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a lover of liberty,'' Mari said, ``and I thought this
country was a lover of liberty, too.''
</P>
<P>
   For many, their anger was overwhelming. One young man burned a
small American flag. Others equated the operation to the
government's disastrous raid on the compound in Waco, Texas, which
had been ordered by Reno. Several people held up crosses, one with
a baby doll nailed to the wood, red paint smeared across its body.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is incredible that this happened,'' Jesus Jorge, 53,
muttered, shaking his head. ``Clinton and Reno will pay for this in
front of God's justice. This is unpardonable.''
</P>
<P>
   Some took their anger out on reporters, shouting them down. A
photographer for The Washington Post was hit in the arm by a man,
who was then pulled away by his companions.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd broke into spontaneous chants, shouting ``criminals''
and ``assassins,'' referring to the government force that swept
into the home where Elian had been staying since he was found
floating off South Florida on Nov. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrators called for mass protests and hunger strikes, and
by midmorning hundreds of protesters hoisting the Cuban banner had
spilled onto nearby streets. Some overturned garbage cans and
newspaper boxes. By late morning, several protesters had been
arrested for trying to block traffic on the wide thoroughfares
nearby. Motorists, meanwhile, clogged up several routes nearby. At
least one vehicle was overturned and set on fire. Hundreds of
police officers, meanwhile, tried to contain spontaneous marches.
</P>
<P>
   Many other people, meanwhile, simply gathered at ground zero in
the months-long saga: the plain house where Elian had stayed with
his great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez. Crowding up to the fence, they
shouted support to Elian's relatives and listened as Marisleysis
Gonzalez, Lazaro's daughter, and others recounted how agents had
smashed their way in and snatched the child.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Valdez, 64, said that as soon as he heard screaming and
shouting outside his house, he ran outside. Like others, he said he
has stood vigil outside the home for weeks, to show solidarity with
fellow exiles and protect the boy in the event of a government
operation to remove him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live a block away, so when it happened, I jumped out of bed
and ran out to the street,'' he said. ``I'm just so frustrated, as
you can imagine. I feel it here in my heart. I feel it right here.
It's so personal.''
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Mendez, 45, a real estate agent who lives nearby, said he
did not think the government would act the day before Easter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we expected this,'' Mendez said, standing with
his arms crossed as he looked at a crowd massed in front of the
Gonzalez home. ``People didn't think this could happen on Holy
Week. If they did something, we at least thought they would wait
until at least next week.''
</P>
<P>
   For some of the Cuban exiles, it was just too much. At least two
elderly Cuban-Americans were rushed from the scene by paramedics
after experiencing shortness of breath. Many simply held hands,
praying and crying silently and asking why. Why after Wednesday's
victory, when a federal appeals court extended an order to keep
Elian in the United States? Why in the middle of the holiest of
Roman Catholic holidays? Why when the boy had stressed that he
wanted to remain?
</P>
<P>
   Marta Galvez, a 62-year-old grandmother who for days has prayed
outside the home, said she knew the government could, without
warning, storm the house. When the agents arrived, she said, she
even tried to run to the house, in a vain effort to stop them.
Still, she said as the sun started to come up Saturday, she could
hardly deal with the anguish she was feeling at losing a boy she
and others in Little Havana had come to regard as a son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel so hurt, in so much pain,'' said Galvez, a housewife
who fled Cuba in 1970. ``My heart is broken, to have this happen in
a country that says it's free. The boy was at peace, not a
kidnapping victim, and he wanted to be free.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayra Ramos, 47, said she could not believe Elian was gone. To
her and many others, his arrival in Florida was a divine act. Meant
to be. He was never to leave. Not this way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in something spiritual about Elian,'' she said,
softly crying. ``He didn't survive so many days on the ocean
without the help of God. So it hurts so much to see him gone.
Anyone who has lived in the inferno in Cuba cannot imagine going
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the tears and the shouts, there were also pleas for calm.
Several of those who had gathered in front of the house took pains
to emphasize to reporters that theirs is a peaceful community,
respectful of the law.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the crowd was seething.
</P>
<P>
   With sweat coming off his face, Eddie Gonzalez, 40, angrily
recounted, his voice fevered and loud, how he tried to block the
agents Saturday morning but was pushed to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   All he could do, he said, was yell, ``You are a dirty woman, you
are a dirty woman,'' to the agent who carried a crying Elian from
the house.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
