<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4297 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-REUNION-495     04-22 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-REUNION-495&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBAN FATHER AND SON BACK TOGETHER AFTER MONTHS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CUBAN-BOY, CUBAN-BOY-SCENE, CUBAN-BOY-MIAMI,
CUBAN-BOY-JUSTICE, CUBAN-BOY-MEDIA, CUBAN-BOY-HAVANA) 
 By CHRISTOPHER MARQUIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Moments after 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez was taken
from a bedroom closet and the arms of a Cuban-American fisherman, a
female voice cooed into his ear.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may seem very scary,'' the woman, a U.S. immigration
agent, told him in Spanish. ``It will soon be better.''
</P>
<P>
   With that modest promise amid a burst of terror, Elian Gonzalez
began a wild ride Saturday morning that reunited him with his
father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, who had pressed for his son's return
for nearly five months.
</P>
<P>
   That was the version of Elian's transfer to the reunion
described in sober tones at a news conference by Attorney General
Janet Reno and Doris Meissner, the commissioner of the Immigration
and Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after 9:20 a.m. Saturday, the boy was in the arms of his
father at Andrews Air Force Base outside Washington. Camera crews
in helicopters flying over the secure military base showed Juan
Miguel Gonzalez, a ticket-taker from a Cuban tourist resort,
carrying his son into a building at the base.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, a Miami native, had anguished over the reunion, which was
bitterly opposed by the boy's Miami relatives and many
Cuban-Americans. Reno called for giving father and son privacy to
become reacquainted. They were to stay for a time at Andrews Air
Force Base and then move to an undisclosed location in the
Washington area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us give him and his father the space, the calm, the moral
support they need to reconnect and reaffirm their bond between
father and son,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a white T-shirt and shorts and swaddled in a white
blanket, the bewildered-looking boy, the subject of the world's
most notorious custody battle, was loaded into a van after a
spectacular predawn raid on the Miami home of Juan Miguel
Gonzalez's uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Agents whisked Elian to nearby Watson Island, where they boarded
a helicopter to Homestead Air Force Base in southern Miami-Dade
County.
</P>
<P>
   A doctor examined him there and made certain the boy had not
been injured in the transfer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a very emotional case for everyone involved,''
Reno said at the news conference. ``The most important thing is
that Elian is safe and that no one was seriously hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Continuing an extraordinary voyage for a boy who was shipwrecked
off Florida, Elian was then put on a U.S. Marshals Service plane
for Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Once aboard, the unidentified female immigration agent comforted
Elian, the officials said. She was joined by a psychiatrist, a
flight surgeon and the Immigration and Naturalization Service agent
who had led the rescue operation.
</P>
<P>
   The officials described Elian as subdued but calm on the flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of our reports so far are that the child has been very
calm, has not been anxious, has not been thrashing, has not been
crying,'' Meissner said. ``And the basic feedback that we have from
a series of people now, who have been directly with him, is that he
is a real terrific, tough kid.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Elian had already been showered with gifts by Cuban exiles, who
held him up as a symbol of their suffering and divided families. He
was offered a few more items on the flight _ some Play-Doh, a toy
airplane, a map and a watch _ an administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   Few details had been ignored. Psychologists had recommended the
Play-Doh as the ``best thing that you can do for a child who might
be experiencing stress,'' Meissner said.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Miguel Gonzalez was rushed to Andrews in a convoy of vans
to await Elian's arrival. The father had been staying at the
residence in Bethesda, Md., of Cuba's top diplomat in the United
States. The residence, like his uncle's Little Havana home, had
been besieged by camera crews and onlookers.
</P>
<P>
   After so much intense media scrutiny, Meissner said the pair
were being protected by federal authorities in an undisclosed
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need more space,'' Meissner said. ``And they need more
privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno, plainly relieved by the secure transfer of Elian, said the
boy needed ``to have quiet time and private time, and to be with
his father.''
</P>
</TEXT>
