<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4299 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-DOTCOM-FUTURE-ART-945     04-22 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOTCOM-FUTURE-ART-945(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOT-COM LEADERS AWAIT A SHAKEOUT OF LOSERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT11 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELLEVUE, Wash. _ Jackie Erickson, the customer retention
manager for drugstore.com, an online pharmacy, has no problem with
the notion that a shakeout is looming in the Internet industry.
``Pretty soon,'' she said, ``the market will separate the men from
the boys.''
</P>
<P>
   John Keister, the president and co-founder of Go2Net in Seattle,
a network of Web sites, said a stock-market shakeout would be ``a
very healthy thing'' for the industry. ``Not everyone should be a
winner here,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, after a turbulent week in which a dozen major Internet
companies here watched the value of their stocks hit record or
near-record lows, and then spike back upward, it is hard to find
any Internet executive who does not profess a belief that the
market will, and should, shake loose some dot-com losers in the
months ahead.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, such a prospect hardly seems to have sapped the air
of confidence that still pervades many companies here. They all
seem to have a ready answer for why it will happen to the other
guy, but not to them.
</P>
<P>
   For many in an industry and of a generation that have so often
appeared headed along a relentless path to greater prosperity, the
recent gyrations in the stock market represent an across-the-board
brush with vulnerability, and many people in the Internet field
hold stock options that are certainly worth much less today than
they were a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   However humbling the dips may have been, employees of many of
those companies are likely to say that none of the recent market
actions have altered their basic strategies, and the mantras of the
industry emerge in interviews: ``It's a marathon, not a sprint.''
``Keep focused on the customer.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as the 29-year-old Erickson put it: ``You don't worry about
the stock market. You can't. You worry about the numbers you can
control.''
</P>
<P>
   In her case, that means devising strategies to keep the business
of first-time customers who might have been enticed to come in the
electronic door with a promotional offer. Her best days at
drugstore.com, she said, have had nothing to do with where the
price of the company's stock wound up, but with sales figures
showing a lot of repeat business.
</P>
<P>
   Judith McGarry, the company's vice president for strategic
partnerships, said: ``What gets us really jazzed here, or what gets
us depressed, is how we do with our customers. And they vote with
their clicks.''
</P>
<P>
   With drugstore.com having recently announced that it had
completed a sale to its one-millionth customer, optimism is much on
display at the online pharmacy's headquarters, scattered among a
few buildings in an office park here, on the eastern shore of Lake
Washington just across from Seattle. (About half of the company's
675 employees are here, and many of the rest are at a distribution
center in Philadelphia.)
</P>
<P>
   Nobody claims that the markets were particularly rational when
they briefly drove the value of the company to $70 a share when it
went public last July, thus assigning a market capitalization of
more than $2 billion to a company that, at the time, had reported a
$30.4 million loss on sales of $4.2 million so far that year.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, and with much more fervor, drugstore.com
employees clearly believe that it also does not make sense for the
markets to have driven the stock all the way down to about $6 a
week ago. This was just after the company announced, among other
indications of fast growth, that it had a million customers.
</P>
<P>
   And the downward turn came after an agreement with Amazon.com,
the leading online retailer, that made drugstore.com the company's
pharmaceutical provider, the first instance of Amazon's featuring
such a partner permanently on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   So, as Mike Morelli, the beauty buyer for drugstore.com,
explains it, ``All I can say is that I truly believe now is a great
time to buy stock in the company,'' which is what he will do this
week. It closed for last week at $8 1/16 a share.
</P>
<P>
   The faith of employees here comes despite the flutterings of
nervousness among investors in high-tech companies, some signs that
the luster of working for a dot-com is fading for some young
college and business-school graduates, and even a recent report by
Forrester Research, based in Cambridge, Mass., suggesting that most
dot-com enterprises could be driven out of business over the next
few years amid a wave of consolidation in the Internet industry.
</P>
<P>
   But the same company has predicted that Internet spending by
consumers could increase to over $180 billion in the next five
years, up from $20 billion last year. And drugstore.com employees
offer passionate explanations for why their particular segment of
the market is ripe for online expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson, who came to the company last summer after graduating
from Northwestern University's business school, said she settled on
drugstore.com in part because she had a feel for the business (her
father and grandfather are pharmacists), and in part because she
believes that typical drugstore items are particularly well suited
to e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what you're getting if you order Crest toothpaste _
you don't need to go look at it in a store,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With other things, like buying a car, you want to feel it,
touch it, smell it, talk to the person who wants to sell it to
you,'' Erickson continued, citing an item that she thought might be
more difficult to sell directly over the Internet, and then adding
another: ``I think it will be a while before we buy diamonds on the
Internet. I mean, for $10,000 or whatever it's going to be, you
want to see it, touch it, try it on, not just have it show up in
the mail.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Martha Richter, 29, who gave her title as manager for ``all
things Amazon,'' said she was drawn to drugstore.com because of the
energy and the pace she felt there when she came for an interview
last year, after a less than successful spell with a start-up
cable-television enterprise in Kentucky. (``We started, but we
didn't up,'' she explained cheerfully.)
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the fastest legal department I've ever worked with,''
Richter said. ``At other places you want to get something done and
it's like, oh, God, it's bottled up in legal. Here, it's like legal
wants an answer right now so that we can get this done.''
</P>
<P>
   While almost everyone here predicts that the company will do
well in the long haul and that its stock price will ultimately
reflect that success, even what one employee described as a
``worst-case scenario'' is not viewed as a catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just an incredible opportunity to learn here,''
Morelli said. ``You've got people at a pretty young age getting to
plan strategy and make these momentous decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's president and chief executive, Peter Neupert, a
former Microsoft vice president, said that most employees had taken
the recent plunge in the stock price in stride, and that among its
silver linings was that it might get investors to take a harder
look at the difficulties of e-commerce, and reward those who wound
up doing it right.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot harder than it looks,'' said the 44-year-old chief
executive whose board of directors includes Melinda French Gates,
the wife of Bill Gates, Microsoft's founder; Jeff Bezos of
Amazon.com, and Howard Schultz of Starbucks. ``Putting the
technical infrastructure in place, getting and keeping the
customers, tracking all the merchandise _ it's not a trivial
exercise,'' he said. ``And I know how hard we're all working.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
