<HEADLINE>
NEWS PHOTOGRAPH IN GONZALEZ CASE SPARKS DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CUBAN-BOY, CUBAN-BOY-SCENE, CUBAN-BOY-MIAMI,
CUBAN-BOY-JUSTICE, CUBAN-BOY-MEDIA, CUBAN-BOY-HAVANA,
CUBAN-BOY-REUNION) 
 By JIM RUTENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Early television coverage of the Elian Gonzalez situation relied
heavily on a photograph by The Associated Press that quickly became
a focal point in the debate over whether the Justice Department had
used excessive force when it removed the boy from the Miami home of
his relatives early Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The photograph showed a federal agent in green riot gear and
goggles carrying a machine gun and facing off against a
frightened-looking man who was holding Elian.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Donato Dalrymple, one of the fisherman who rescued the
child in the Atlantic Ocean on Nov. 25, appears to be cowering in
the doorway of a closet in the Miami home of the boy's great-uncle,
Lazaro Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Washington, Attorney General Janet Reno
was asked to address the photograph, which was being shown on ABC,
CBS, NBC, MSNBC, Fox News Channel and CNN.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the beauties of television is that it shows exactly
what the facts are,'' Reno said. ``And as I understand it, if you
look at it carefully, it shows that the gun was pointed to the
side, and that the finger was not on the trigger.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the early hours of the television coverage at least one
network, CNN, seemed to have cropped the photograph so that
Dalrymple was not visible, making it look as if the federal agent
was facing only Elian. Later, the full photograph was shown.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for CNN said there ``was no editorial decision''
to crop Dalrymple out of the picture.
</P>
<P>
   The photograph was taken by Alan Diaz, a free-lance photographer
for The AP. Diaz said he had been standing in the yard of the house
next to the Gonzalez home when the federal agents arrived. He said
he jumped over a chain-link fence and ran into the house, where he
was guided into the bedroom where the boy was being held.
</P>
</TEXT>
