<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4309 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ROME-PILGRIMS-1STLD-W     04-22 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROME-PILGRIMS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-1050(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT EXTRA-SPECIAL TIME, JUBILATION IN JAMMED ROME
</HEADLINE>
  (CORRECTS spelling of ``Pilate'' in 8th graf) 
By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ After walking 4,350 miles to Rome wearing a brown
traveler's cape and Tyrolean hat, and with a shell, the traditional
pilgrim's symbol, hanging from his neck, Walter Weigand, 53, stared
in disbelief at the huge crowd of less road-weary pilgrims milling
around him on St. Peter's Square.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not pilgrims,'' he said indignantly as he clutched a
staff trimmed with olive branches. ``They get off a bus then walk
300 feet to the church. That's just tourism.''
</P>
<P>
   But Weigand, who quit his job as a waiter in Berlin last
September to undertake a medieval-style pilgrimage to honor the
church's Jubilee year, stopping at shrines from Santiago de
Compostela in Spain to the Vatican, was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of the estimated 500,000 Roman Catholics who have
flocked to Rome to celebrate Holy Week, which began on Palm Sunday
and ends at Easter, came on foot. But beneath a shiny veneer of
modern comfort and efficiency _ Internet-ready visitors' centers,
air-conditioned Jubilee buses, microchip-equipped pilgrim cards
that automatically book church services, tours and restaurants,
chemical toilets and electric votive candles _ the Holy Year 2000
is laced with the kind of humble piety and awe that drew the first
Jubilee pilgrims here in 1300.
</P>
<P>
   Faith, and an almost giddy determination, drove 51 pilgrims from
Brazil to race straight from the airport to St. Peter's on Thursday
evening so they would not miss the Mass in which Pope John Paul II
washed and kissed the feet of 12 priests, a ritual he does every
Holy Thursday to recall Christ washing the feet of his apostles.
</P>
<P>
   Faith made a group of 32 pilgrims from Moldova _ 20 Eastern
Orthodox and 12 Catholic believers who traveled by bus for two days
and two nights _ skip dinner so they could pray outside the
Colosseum while the pope carried the cross during the Good Friday
re-enactment of Christ's passion.
</P>
<P>
   And faith got Gerri Ann Slaton of Tampa, Fla., up early on
Friday to walk on her knees up a flight of cold, damp stairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got here, I said to myself, `I'm not going to climb
that,' but God told me, `Yes, you are.' And I did,'' Slaton, 62,
said, still slightly out of breath from climbing the Scala Santa, a
holy staircase that believers say was fashioned from the floors
that Jesus trod on while being interrogated by Pontius Pilate in
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   She and 40 other Catholics from Tampa and Jacksonville were on a
pilgrimage to Rome and Medjugorje, a shrine in Bosnia where
believers say apparitions of the Virgin still occur. ``Rome is a
little fast-paced, but oh my, to kneel on the steps that Christ
walked on,'' she said, her eyes welling up. ``You know, I never
thought I would get to Rome, ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Not much has changed in 700 years. ``Medieval pilgrims used to
come to Rome for spiritual and medical care,'' said Herbert L.
Kessler, a professor of art history at Johns Hopkins University who
just finished a book on the first Jubilee in 1300. ``The popes
built pilgrims' hospitals like San Giovanni that are still working
today. They still come for spiritual reasons. Piety cannot be
overlooked _ these are believers, not tourists.''
</P>
<P>
   Pope Boniface VIII summoned pilgrims to Rome in 1300 when the
Crusades failed and travel to the Holy Land became too dangerous.
Jubilee is a Catholic term derived from the Hebrew word yobel, a
law handed down by Moses requiring that slaves be freed and debts
forgiven every 50 years. (Since 1475, Jubilees have been scheduled
every 25 years, improving each pope's chance of presiding over a
Holy Year.)
</P>
<P>
   Pope Boniface lured pilgrims accustomed to traveling to shrines
like Santiago de Compostela in Spain, where the pilgrims of the
Canterbury Tales were headed, to Rome by offering an indulgence, a
remittance on punishment for sins. (Legend has it that Martin
Luther, whose disapproval of the selling of indulgences led to the
16th-century Reformation, first balked at what he viewed as impious
superstition while climbing the Scala Santa.)
</P>
<P>
   For the year 2000, John Paul II has broadened the paths to an
indulgence. They can be earned in any of Rome's main basilicas (and
even the chapel at the Rome airport) as well as cathedrals and
churches around the world throughout the Jubilee Year.
</P>
<P>
   But Catholic tradition, 2,000 years of Christian history, and
the lure of this pope are expected to bring as many as 20 million
Catholics to Rome and other holy sites in Italy throughout the
year, the largest Jubilee ever held by the Vatican. Easter, the day
on which tradition says that Christ was resurrected, is one of the
holiest days on the Roman Catholic calendar.
</P>
<P>
   The city's efforts to accommodate _ and streamline _ the traffic
of religious visitors from all over the world has prompted less
reverent comments from hoteliers, souvenir sellers, shopkeepers and
tour operators. They complain bitterly that a city ban on tour
buses in the center of Rome has driven many ordinary tourists, and
even some pilgrims, to cancel reservations and stay away.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors who want to go from St. Peter's to other basilicas or
the Colosseum this year must board special blue Jubilee shuttle
buses.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot get a group of 40 elderly people onto one of the
buses,'' Ira Levin, 65, owner of Italia Esoterica, a tour agency,
complained. ``It's logistically impossible. It's created a whole
hullabaloo in the tourist industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Even that, however, is not really new. Dante, who wrote the
Divine Comedy shortly after the 1300 Jubilee, mentioned Holy Year
organizational zeal in his ``Inferno'' by likening the system for
streamlining some sinners in hell to Romans' efforts to organize
pedestrian traffic. There were some breakdowns, however. In 1450,
masses of pilgrims leaving a papal blessing mobbed the only bridge
over the Tiber and 200 people drowned.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year mishaps have been minor. Lost wallets, stolen
passports, and the occasional lost pilgrim have been reported to
Jubilee volunteers and visitors' centers. Pilgrims mainly seem
startled by Rome's chaotic traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Burgess, 64, of Tampa marveled at the sight of so many
priests and nuns on the street, and the nonchalance with which they
were treated by Roman drivers. ``I saw a car almost run over Bishop
Foley,'' she said, referring to Archbishop John Foley, an American
Vatican official. ``My gosh, he had to jump out of the way,'' she
recalled.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Lodging has been plentiful _ for most. Jubilee government funds
were used to refurbish hotels all over the city, and the Vatican
converted schools and convents into pilgrims' hostels, with rooms
costing as little as $25 a night. The Florida group, benefiting
from a package tour rate, stayed at the posh Hotel Columbus next to
St. Peter's. The Moldovans were assigned rooms at a Dominican
convent just inside the city limits. Like other poor pilgrims, they
were given free lunch boxes by a special papal charity.
</P>
<P>
   But employees at a Jubilee visitors' center near the Vatican
said they noticed that little planning had been made for lodging
poor pilgrims who show up without reservations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't get a lot of them, but solitary pilgrims turn up, and
we can't send them to a homeless shelter, and they can't afford a
hotel,'' Christian Benedati, 28, said. ``I called one convent on my
list for a young German pilgrim, and they wouldn't take him. They
said he wasn't Italian, he wasn't a priest, and he couldn't pay.''
He added, ``I think he ended up sleeping on the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Pilgrims, however, do not complain. ``Rome feels like a
festival,'' said Vitaly Tsurcanou, 46, a textbook editor from
Kishinev, Moldova, elated as he stood outside St. Peter's. ``It's a
city, but it smells of country flowers.''
</P>
<P>
   An Eastern Orthodox believer who said he found his faith reading
Mikhail Bulgakov's novel ``The Master and Margarita,'' came to
Rome, he said, because it was holy to all Christians. ``This is a
such a blessing to be here. It's something I thought I would only
do in my dreams.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
