<P>
   MEXICO-PRESIDENCY _ MEXICO CITY _ The most competitive
presidential race in Mexican history takes to the airwaves in a
televised debate April 25. This is a
</P>
<P>
   critical opportunity for candidates to show their stuff to the
nation as this historic campaign heats up and heads for Mexico's
July 2 election day. A crowded field of six candidates will be
included in this first debate. But the contest has clearly narrowed
to two: Francisco Labastida, who represents the same party that has
controlled Mexico's presidency for 71 years, and Vicente Fox, a
charismatic opposition candidate. Should Fox win, our neighbor next
door would have the first president from a different party in seven
decades. The rivalry is razor sharp. Fox, running strong against
corruption, called Labastida a ``leech'' recently. Labastida
labeled Fox a ``frenetic crazy man.'' (Ferriss, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MOVED Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-HUSTLERS _ HAVANA _ In Cuba, they call them ``jiniteros,''
or hustlers, and they are everywhere on the streets of Havana's
tourist district. Some stride boldly up and clap you on the back
and ask what you need; others ask the time or where you are from to
try to lure you into conversation; still others whisper, ``Amigo,
you want restaurant? Hotel? Cigars? Girl?'' While not as
overwhelming as in other tourist destinations such as Jamaica, the
hustlers are a sign of how desperately people want American
dollars. We profile Nereyda Li, a particularly discreet, subtle
hustler; a grandmother working in a market who befriended an
American reporter and took him on a week-long roller-coaster tour
of Havana, her life, her dreams and hopes. (MWilliams, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   MOVED Thursday.
