</P>
<P>
   ONCE-AND-AGAIN _ A few weeks ago, I was on the phone with a
publicist for HBO. After we chatted at length about The Sopranos,
we turned our attention to other TV shows we like and don't like.
``Do you watch Once and Again?'' I asked. ``Nah, it's too sappy,''
the publicist said. ``I saw the first two episodes and stopped
watching.'' Of course, I told her that was a mistake. A big one, in
fact. Not only is Once and Again, whose season finale airs Monday,
far from sappy, it remains TV's best new drama. Calm down, West
Wing fans. NBC's political drama comes in a close second.
(Thompson, Palm Beach Post). 14. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TV-WALLACE _ Austin film maker, Paul Stekler, examines roots of
George Wallace's strange politics in the PBS documentary ``George
Wallace: Settin' the Woods on Fire.'' (Holloway, Austin
American-Statesman). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SPRING BOOKS _ AJC SPECIAL SECTION (tab format)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-SOUTH-MYSTERIES _ Southern mystery writers have learned a
valuable lesson from such masters of the genre as Raymond Chandler
and Dashiell Hammett: Where a crime takes place is as important as
whodunit. Carl Hiaasen's novels of greedy developers destroying the
environment would not be the same outside of ecologically fragile
south Florida. James W. Hall's bone-fishing loner Thorn would be
lost away from the Florida Keys. And Kathy Hogan Trocheck's
Callahan Garrity would seem out of place cleaning houses anywhere
except in Atlanta. (OBriant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 60.
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the cover story in the tab.
</P>
