<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONCE-AND-AGAIN0423-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Once and Again' far from sappy, close to brilliant
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A few weeks ago, I was on the phone with
a publicist for HBO. After we chatted at length about ``The
Sopranos,'' we turned our attention to other TV shows we like and
don't like.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you watch `Once and Again'?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah, it's too sappy,'' the publicist said. ``I saw the first
two episodes and stopped watching.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I told her that was a mistake. A big one, in fact.
Not only is ``Once and Again,'' whose season finale airs Monday,
far from sappy, it remains TV's best new drama. Calm down, ``West
Wing'' fans. NBC's political drama comes in a close second.
</P>
<P>
   ABC is definitely convinced it has a gem of a program. The
network picked up ``Once and Again'' for next season. While not a
runaway hit, the series averages a respectable 11 million viewers
each week. It also averages a 5.5 rating among adults 18-49, making
it the top-rated new drama in that key demographic.
</P>
<P>
   Although I disagreed with the publicist, I understood her
argument. If not handled properly, ``Once and Again'' could've
turned into a mushy lovefest. After all, the first few episodes
only dealt with Rick (a boyishly handsome Billy Campbell) and Lily
(a downright delectable Sela Ward) going at each other like two
love-starved teens. But that storyline would've turned stale fast.
</P>
<P>
   Wisely, the show's forward-thinking producers
(``thirtysomething's'' Marshall Herskovitz and Edward Zwick) didn't
turn ``Once and Again'' into ``The Rick &AMP; Lily Show.'' The writers
also fleshed out the show's co-stars, turning them into
three-dimensional human beings we can relate to. In fact, in many
episodes, Campbell and Ward are more like supporting players on
their own show.
</P>
<P>
   If the publicist had kept watching ``Once and Again,'' she
would've learned, for instance, that Eli (Shane West) has problems
reading. Grace (an outstanding Julia Whelan) has a crush on a black
classmate. Karen (Susanna Thompson) struggles to have fun with her
much younger boyfriend. Judy's (Marin Hinkle) having an affair with
a married man (``West Wing's'' Steven Weber). Lily and Jake
(Jeffrey Nordling) continue to battle severe financial problems.
</P>
<P>
   She also missed watching a heartbroken Grace sob uncontrollably
after learning of her dad's affair. Best of all, she didn't see the
gut-wrenching episode in which Lily's overprotective dad (Paul
Mazursky) died of a stroke. That still remains the season's finest
television hour.
</P>
<P>
   Those aren't sappy stories. Far from it. Even jaded TV critics
understand that. What ``Once and Again'' does so consistently well
is give us a realistic peek inside an American family. We see their
joys. Sorrows. Triumphs. Heartaches.
</P>
<P>
   And we love to see their stories ... once and again.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
