<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4321 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-TV-WALLACE23-COX     04-22 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WALLACE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What fueled Wallace's fire?
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ With his jutting chin and cocky strut, George
Wallace always looked like a bantam rooster scratching for a fight.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he was standing in a schoolhouse door symbolically
blocking integration or taunting hippie demonstrators who were
taunting him, Wallace defied the politics of convention.
</P>
<P>
   The former boxer with the combative political style came to
symbolize racial hatred in the '60s and '70s, but his life and
career were never that simple _ a point proved with remarkable
skill and insight in ``George Wallace: Settin' the Woods on Fire.''
Artfully blending archival footage with revelatory interviews, the
film turns Wallace's strange journey into a fascinating cautionary
tale about power and corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers who watch PBS's two-part presentation of this
award-winning documentary may be surprised to learn that Wallace
started his career as a liberal judge in Alabama, championing the
poor regardless of color. But after he was defeated in a run for
governor by a hate-spewing segregationist, Wallace quickly ditched
progressive politics. When he was inaugurated as governor in 1963,
he sent forth the chilling battle cry,'' ... segregation now,
segregation tomorrow and segregation forever.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole film is about the consequences of using any means
for political ends,'' says filmmaker Paul Stekler, head of the
production unit at the University of Texas radio-television-film
department. ``Wallace was willing to say almost anything to win,
and that affected who he was as human being, as well as politics
and the political process. There's a lot to learn from his
success.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's good that education-minded PBS is affording the film
that was such a hit at the Sundance Film Festival a larger
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love playing it at film festivals, but we could play every
festival and not reach a fraction of the audience on PBS,'' Stekler
says. ``If a lot of people don't see it, why do it?''
</P>
<P>
   The question that wafts through the three-hour film, which
Stekler and his producing partner Daniel McCabe worked on for 2 1/2
years, is haunting: Was Wallace a decent man corrupted by his lust
for power or an evil racist from the get-go? Viewers will have to
weigh the evidence from witness accounts on both sides of the
question
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of Wallace's core beliefs, it's almost impossible not
to be disgusted by the governor's willingness to fan the flames of
racism for his own gain. But it's equally impossible not to feel
some compassion for him in his later years, crippled by an
assassination attempt and seeking forgiveness from the same black
leaders who had been attacked with fire hoses and police dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe millions of Americans didn't buy Wallace's repentance, but
many black people did. The point is poignantly made in the film by
civil rights leader John Lewis' recollection of a phone
conversation during which Wallace tearfully apologized. Lewis is
convinced the mea culpa came from the heart.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, as narrator Randy Quaid puts it, the rest of us are
left to wonder if Wallace was ``cramming for death'' or sincere in
his quest for redemption.
</P>
<P>
   Among those interviewed by Stekler and McCabe are reporters who
covered Wallace as an Alabama politician and as a national crusader
for ``states rights''; political henchmen, such as Seymore Trammel;
Wallace's children, Peggy and George, Jr.; his second wife
Cornelia; civil rights lawyer J.L. Chestnut; and former Nixon
speechwriter and presidential candidate Pat Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most surprising statements in the film comes from
Buchanan, who declares that if Wallace had not been handicapped
when he ran for president in '76, Jimmy Carter wouldn't have been
elected. Buchanan also says, without hesitation, ``In many ways,
the man was right.''
</P>
<P>
   The film is so powerful in image and words that it almost
doesn't need decoration, but original music by Mason Daring and
Duke Levine adds a haunting quality to the piece.
</P>
<P>
   ``Settin' the Woods on Fire'' is a drama of Shakespearean
proportions that is all the more powerful because it is truth
rather than fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
