NYT-04-22-00 1409EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000422.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4324 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-ANTI-AGING23-COX     04-22 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTI-AGING23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENCE/HEALTH: Growth hormone taps fountain of youth, doctor
says
 &HT;    By Clay Lambert
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ You are not getting older. You are,
however, diseased.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jordan K. Davis says so.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry. He thinks he can help. All Davis requires is that
you open your mind and wallet to the notion that you can live much
longer if only medicine would tackle aging with the same clinical
veracity it now reserves for cancer and other diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry. Davis is working on it.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Davis founded the American Anti-Aging Foundation,
the money-raising and research umbrella over his Integrative
Medicine Institutes of Boca Raton.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks boosting your human growth hormone _ by injection, if
necessary _ will help you live longer with better vision, less hair
loss and the sexual prowess of a much younger you.
</P>
<P>
   Though he is now a proponent of research into unproved
anti-aging theories, Davis has long been a respected member of the
mainstream medical community here. He is a retired neurosurgeon
still listed on the staff of Boca Raton Community Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   He said doctors focus on treating acute conditions at the
expense of prevention, adding that he knows why:
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was an active surgeon, people came to me with a brain
tumor and I took it out,'' he said. ``Most physicians don't have
time for prevention. They're too busy.''
</P>
<P>
   In all his years of delicate brain surgeries, Davis might have
never struck a nerve so raw as the one he unearthed with the
foundation's first-ever public event, a free seminar in March at
Boca Raton Community Hospital entitled ``Anti-aging 2000: Healthy
Longevity Can Be Yours.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 300 people clamored for a seat in the educational
theater. The crowd spilled out of the auditorium and into a break
room where events were televised via closed circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Among the presenters: Dr. Boyd Haley, chair of the department of
chemistry at the University of Kentucky, and Dr. Terry Grossman, a
former assistant clinical professor at the University of Colorado
School of Medicine and author of ``The Baby Boomers' Guide to
Living Forever.''
</P>
<P>
   The audience came as much out of frustration with their old
doctors as respect for new ones in the growing field of
``anti-aging,'' a term applied to therapies including nutritional
supplements and hormone replacement.
</P>
<P>
   THE POWER OF HEALING
</P>
<P>
   Allan Wasserman is a practicing veterinarian. He and his wife,
Kandi, are avid believers in the power of vitamins and supplements.
That is why they came to hear Davis speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty years ago my wife had breast cancer and they only gave
her five years to live,'' Wasserman said, adding that his
68-year-old wife combs books and the Internet for the latest home
remedies. ``I don't care if it's mysticism or what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   For many in the audience that night, the most intriguing aspect
of the new science is the prospect of a better life through
replenished human growth hormone, or hGH.
</P>
<P>
   Talk of hGH as an anti-aging miracle is 10 years old. It began
as a whisper published July 5, 1990, in the New England Journal of
Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Rudman, a professor at the University of Wisconsin, wrote
healthy men given hGH in his study gained 8.8 percent muscle mass
and lost 14 percent of their fat. He suggested that his subjects
also improved their eyesight, hair growth, sex drive, skin
elasticity, mood and sleep. Industry officials say treatment costs
about $1,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Human growth hormone is produced in the pituitary gland and
responsible for a wide range of youthful attributes. First
available only from human cadavers, hGH was scarce and used to
treat children with severe pituitary gland dysfunction. It was
first synthesized in 1985, leading researchers to begin looking for
other uses.
</P>
<P>
   For most people, hGH levels drop off dramatically by the age of
30. Proponents of anti-aging medicine say that is a major reason we
grow old.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the leading proponent of this hGH therapy, American
Academy of Anti-Aging, boasts 8,400 members and produces a Web site
(www.worldhealth.net) that claims 200,000 hits every month.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said he has two patients receiving injections of hGH and
many others who take dietary supplements designed to enhance hGH
levels without injections.
</P>
<P>
   The 65-year-old doctor said he is tired of waiting for the
sluggish response of most of the medical profession. And he is
unfazed by criticism from colleagues who suggest, as Hippocrates
did more than 2,000 years ago, that first a physician must do no
harm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't care,'' he said of such rebukes. ``This is a whole new
paradigm of medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one noted bioethicist cautions that new paradigms
should be approached carefully.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kenneth Goodman, the director of the University of Miami's
bioethics program, noted because hGH makes things grow, there is
reason to believe pre-existing cancer cells would also flourish
under such therapy. Also, high levels of hGH have caused over-grown
internal organs and the cave-man like appearance noted in steroid
misuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disclosure is critical. Life-extension science is about 20
minutes old. Look how long we have been studying cancer and we
still don't have all those answers,'' Goodman said. ``There needs
to be an accurate disclosure of the risks involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bernard Roos, director of the aging center at the Veterans
Administration Hospital in Miami and head of geriatric medicine at
the University of Miami, finds agreement with both colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   THE FOUNTAIN OF YOUTH?
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe eventually hormone therapy will help us grow young
again,'' Roos said.
</P>
<P>
   He is also sympathetic to Davis' argument that the medical
establishment prefers to treat acute conditions rather than prevent
them.
</P>
<P>
   But Roos agrees with Goodman, too, saying that time for
widespread hormone treatment is not yet at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The science is not there,'' he said. ``The precise hormone
prescription is a very big challenge and it will take a very long
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis wants that work to begin now. And he plans to use an
unusual key to unlock the mystery of aging:
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to address aging as a disease,'' he said. ``It is a
complex disease, of course, involving all of the systems of the
body.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman and Roos bristled at that.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is aging but an increase in the probability that we will
die?'' asked Roos. ``And why do we age? Because we are human.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman puts it this way: ``It's an interesting philosophical
question. Cancer is a disease. Is male pattern baldness a disease?
Is being short a disease?
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me if everybody gets it _ and everybody in the
history of time has gotten old _ then it's not a disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
