<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000422.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4325 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-EASTEREGGS23-COX     04-22 2371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EASTEREGGS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hunting for Easter egg ancestors
 &HT;    By Rachel Sauer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ Meet the Bumens: Albert and Alice and
their children, Alvin and Allie. They're a regular, happy family _
nothing exceptional or extraordinary about them.
</P>
<P>
   They live on Hennypenny Lane in a cozy home that Albert fondly
refers to as ``The Nest.'' Each morning, after a hearty breakfast
of bacon and toast, Alice sends the kids off to school _ with an
admonition not to run and to make sure their shoelaces are tied _
and Albert to his job as an executive for Elmer's Products Inc.
</P>
<P>
   On summer evenings, after dinner is eaten and the dishes are
done, the family enjoys gathering in the back yard. Alvin and Allie
roll down the hill, Albert and Alice work in the garden and the
whole family laughs and tells jokes. These are excellent times for
the Bumen family.
</P>
<P>
   But if there's one thing the Bumens love, it's genealogy. They
love to examine their roots, explain where they came from. It's
exhilarating to discover an exotic ancestor, and though the
research can be exhausting at times, it's exciting, too.
</P>
<P>
   ALICE TELLS A BIT OF HISTORY
</P>
<P>
   Why, just the other day Alice was exploring the Internet and she
found out the family is related to royalty _ Easter Egg. This is
what she learned:
</P>
<P>
   Before eighth-century English historian Venerable Bede reported
the origins of Easter _ named for Eostre, the Anglo-Saxon goddess
of spring _ as a mixture of pagan celebrations of spring, the
Hebrew Passover and Christian observance of Jesus Christ's death
and resurrection, many cultures were using eggs to symbolize the
spring holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Roman, Gaul, Chinese, Egyptian and Persian cultures looked at
the egg as a symbol of the universe. Some cultures believed the
world began with an egg: A great egg broke in half to form the
earth with the yolk for the sun. Eggs were colored, painted,
adorned and exchanged as gifts, and were shown great reverence as
symbols of fertility. To pagans, eggs represented the rebirth of
the earth each spring and were believed to have special powers.
Eggs were buried in the foundations of buildings to ward off evil,
French brides stepped on an egg before crossing the threshold of
their new homes and pregnant Roman women carried an egg in their
clothes to foretell the sex of their unborn children.
</P>
<P>
   With the growth of Christianity, the spring observances of
different cultures blended into Christian observance and Christian
symbolism. The egg came to represent not nature's rebirth, but the
rebirth of man, likening it to the tomb from which Christ rose.
</P>
<P>
   Historians debate when people first began decorating eggs for
Easter, though legends abound. An old Polish legend says that the
Virgin Mary gave eggs to the soldiers at the foot of Christ's
cross, weeping as she begged them to be less cruel. Her tears fell
on the eggs and dotted them with spots of bright color. Another
Polish legend says Mary Magdalene went to the sepulchre where
Christ's body was laid to anoint the body. She took with her a
basket of eggs for a meal, and when she got to the sepulchre and
uncovered the eggs she discovered the shells were tinted with
brilliant rainbow colors.
</P>
<P>
   Decorating eggs for Easter was a popular custom in England
during the Middle Ages. For the year 1290, the household accounts
of Edward I report an expenditure of 18 pence for 450 eggs to be
colored and gold-leafed for Easter gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Artist Peter Carl Faberge made the decorating of eggs an art,
and was famous for crafting eggs of platinum, gold and enamel and
decorating them with jewels.
</P>
<P>
   Today, many who celebrate Easter dye eggs and hide them for
children to find.
</P>
<P>
   (Source: ``Lilies, Rabbits and Painted Eggs: The Story of the
Easter Symbols'' by Edna Barth)
</P>
<P>
   ALLIE BREAKS DOWN FACTS ABOUT EGGS
</P>
<P>
   Alice was exuberant when she learned this fascinating piece of
family history. When Albert and the kids got home, she met them at
the door and explained the story to them. They could barely express
their joy.
</P>
<P>
   Then Allie stepped forward with some interesting news of her
own: ``Today in social studies we talked about our extended
family!'' she exclaimed. ``I was so excited!'' This is what she
learned:
</P>
<P>
   _ A hen requires 24 to 26 hours to produce an egg. Thirty
minutes later, she starts all over again.
</P>
<P>
   _ The egg shell may have as many as 17,000 tiny pores over its
surface. Through them, the egg can absorb flavors and odors.
Storing them in their cartons helps keep them fresh.
</P>
<P>
   _ Eggs age more in one day at room temperature than in one week
in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   _ About 240 million laying hens produce approximately 5.5
billion dozen eggs per year in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   _ The high point for per capita egg consumption _ a measure of
total U.S. egg production divided by the total population _ was in
1945 with 402 eggs per person per year. Per capita egg consumption
has declined since then, with a low point of 235.7 in 1995 due to
the death of many laying hens as a result of extreme weather in the
Midwest. In 1999 the per capita consumption was 254.7 and was
forecast to be 256.4 in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   _ The top 10 egg-producing states are: Ohio, Iowa, California,
Indiana, Pennsylvania, Texas, Minnesota, Georgia, Nebraska and
Florida. The top five egg-producing states represent approximately
50 percent of all U.S. layers.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the United States there are 58 egg-producing companies with
1 million plus layers and 10 companies with more than 5 million
layers. There are approximately 318 egg-producing companies with
flocks of 75,000 hens or more. These 318 companies represent about
97 percent of all layers in the country.
</P>
<P>
   _ During the first eight months of 1999, U.S. table egg exports
totaled 24.9 million dozen and these exports earned a value of
$17.17 million. Top markets for U.S. shell eggs include Hong Kong
and Canada. Hong Kong imported more than 10.5 million dozen eggs
during the first eight months of 1999 with a value of $7.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   _ White-shelled eggs are produced by hens with white feathers
and ear lobes. Brown-shelled eggs are produced by hens with red
feathers and ear lobes.
</P>
<P>
   _ To tell if an egg is raw or hard-cooked, spin it. If the egg
spins easily, it is hard-cooked, but if it wobbles, it is raw.
</P>
<P>
   _ If an egg is accidentally dropped on the floor, sprinkle it
heavily with salt for easy cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   _ During the spring (vernal) equinox, it is said that an egg
will stand on its small end. Although some people have reported
success, it is not known whether such results were due to the
equinox or to the peculiarities of that particular egg.
</P>
<P>
   _ Egg yolks are one of the few foods that naturally contain
vitamin D.
</P>
<P>
   _ Yolk color depends on the diet of the hen. Naturally
yellow-orange substances, such as marigold petals, may be added to
light-colored feeds to enhance colors. Artificial color additives
are not permitted by the U.S. Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   _ Occasionally, a hen will produce double-yolked eggs throughout
her egg-laying career. It is rare, but not unusual, for a young hen
to produce an egg with no yolk at all.
</P>
<P>
   (Source: American Egg Board, U.S. Department of Agriculture)
</P>
<P>
   ALVIN'S TEACHER TAKES EGG-STRA TIME FOR Q&AMP;A
</P>
<P>
   The Bumens oohed and aahed over this information, and felt
strangely close to all their second cousins in Ohio. It must have
been an interesting day at school for the Bumen children, because
Alvin told his family, when Allie was done sharing what she'd
learned, that in health education class the teacher had spent the
entire hour answering questions students had about what was going
on inside them. This is what he learned:
</P>
<P>
   Q: What causes blood spots?
</P>
<P>
   A: Small spots of blood, sometimes called meat spots, are
occasionally found in egg yolk. They do not indicate a fertile egg,
but are caused by the rupture of a blood vessel on the yolk surface
during the egg's formation. Most eggs with blood spots are removed
during the grading process, but a few may escape detection. As the
egg ages, water moves from the albumen into the yolk, diluting the
blood spot, so a visible blood spot indicates a fresh egg that is
suitable for consumption.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why do some hard-cooked eggs have a greenish ring around the
yolk?
</P>
<P>
   A: The greenish ring, which is harmless, is due to an iron and
sulfur compound that forms when eggs are overcooked or not cooled
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there a difference between brown- and white-shelled eggs?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, because shell color is determined by the breed of hen and
is not related to quality, nutrients, flavor or cooking
characteristics. Since brown-egg layers are larger birds and need
more food, brown eggs usually are more expensive than white.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How long will eggs keep?
</P>
<P>
   A: Fresh eggs can be kept refrigerated in their carton for at
least four to five weeks beyond the packing date. Hard-cooked eggs
can be kept in the refrigerator for up to one week.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the best way to store eggs?
</P>
<P>
   A: Store eggs in their carton because eggs can absorb
refrigerator odors.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why are some hard-cooked eggs difficult to peel?
</P>
<P>
   A: Fresh eggs may be difficult to peel. Those that have been
stored for a week to 10 days before cooking will usually peel more
easily.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the stringy white pieces in egg whites?
</P>
<P>
   A: The ropelike strands of egg white, called Chalazae, are not
imperfections or beginning embryos, but a natural, edible part of
the egg. They keep the yolk centered in the thick white.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why is an egg white sometimes cloudy or has a yellow or
greenish cast?
</P>
<P>
   A: Cloudiness of raw white is due to the presence of carbon
dioxide that has not had time to escape through the shell and is an
indication of a very fresh egg. A slight yellow or greenish cast in
raw white may indicate the presence of riboflavin.
</P>
<P>
   (Source: American Egg Board)
</P>
<P>
   ALBERT RELAYS YUMMY RECIPES
</P>
<P>
   Alvin finished and his family was impressed. Then Albert decided
it was time to share what he'd learned from a book he'd been
reading on the funeral rituals of their ancestors. Looking serious,
he said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Deli mustard,'' said Sylvia Schafer, a deli clerk at Westside
Delicatessen &AMP; Lounge. ``That's what we use here. It really perks
up the filling (of devilled eggs) instead of just plain mayo.''
</P>
<P>
   With the preponderance of left-over hard-boiled eggs after
Easter, most people wonder what to do with them. And then they make
devilled eggs. It's the American way. Unfortunately, you get those
people who just scoop out the yolk, mix it with mayonnaise and plop
it back in the egg halves. There's a better way.
</P>
<P>
   Schafer said adding deli mustard to the yolk mix gives it ``a
little sharpness, a little pizazz.'' She also suggested adding
finely diced celery or onion to the mixture, then topping the
completed eggs with paprika, a small celery leaf or a sliced black
olive, ``something to give it a little color,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lori Engle of Big Leo's Catering favors keeping the devilled
eggs simple: ``A little bit of Miracle Whip, a little bit of
mustard, a little bit of vinegar,'' she explained. ``Cut the eggs
in half, get the yolk out, mash down the yolks, mix everything in
until you have a real good consistency and spoon it back into the
egg.''
</P>
<P>
   The amount of each ingredient, as well as the type of vinegar
and mustard, depends on individual tastes, she said.
</P>
<P>
   For unique devilled eggs, Marylou Lawson of Cowboy &AMP; the Rose
Catering LLC adds ranch dressing. ``It totally changes the whole
flavor of them,'' she said. She adds a little Miracle Whip, a
little mustard and the ranch dressing instead of vinegar, and the
devilled eggs are distinctive and creamy, she said.
</P>
<P>
   She also suggested using ranch dressing in egg salad instead of
vinegar. And for another way to use up those left-over Easter eggs,
she suggested slicing the eggs and putting them underneath the top
layer in lasagne.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes the lasagne taste really, really good and it's
something different,'' she said. ``And it's a good way to use those
eggs up. It's like zucchini _ sometimes you've got to disguise
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The folks at Grand Mesa Eggs, producer of 13 million dozen eggs
per year, suggested the following recipes, each made with six eggs
and prepared in the normal devilled egg way:
</P>
<P>
   For Midwest Medley devilled eggs, add 1/3 cup minced carrots, 2
tablespoons mayonnaise, 1 tablespoon minced fresh mushrooms, 1
tablespoon horseradish mustard, 1 teaspoon lemon juice and 1/8
teaspoon salt.
</P>
<P>
   For Dairy Delight devilled eggs, add half of a 10-ounce package
of frozen spinach _ thawed, drained and pressed, 1/4 cup low-fat
cottage cheese, 2 tablespoons minced onion, 1 1/3 tablespoons milk,
1 1/4 teaspoons lemon juice, 1 teaspoon crushed basil leaves, 1/4
teaspoon salt.
</P>
<P>
   To make Lively Latin devilled eggs, add 2 tablespoons undrained
canned chopped green chiles, 2 tablespoons drained canned whole
kernel corn, 2 tablespoons minced green onions with tops, 2
tablespoons shredded Monterey Jack cheese, 2 tablespoons taco
sauce, 1/8 teaspoon salt.
</P>
<P>
   For Orchard Fresh devilled eggs, add 2 tablespoons plain low-fat
yogurt, 1 tablespoon minced unpeeled red apple, 1 tablespoon minced
celery, 1 tablespoon finely chopped pecans, 1 tablespoon honey, 1
teaspoon lime juice, dashes of curry powder and salt.
</P>
<P>
   Also, to hard-cook an egg, the American Egg Board advises: Place
eggs single layer in a saucepan and add enough tap water to come at
least one inch above eggs. Cover the pan and quickly bring to a
boil. Turn off the heat and, if necessary, remove the pan from the
burner to prevent further boiling. Let the eggs stand, covered, in
the hot water for 15 to 17 minutes for large eggs. Adjust time up
or down by about three minutes for each size larger or smaller.
</P>
<P>
   The family thanked Albert for sharing this valuable information
on a topic that can be unappealing. They had a moment of silence in
honor of those who had gone before, then smiled at each other and
agreed that it's an exciting time to be an egg.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
