<SLUG> BC-GOSPEL-GOSSIP23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gospel Music Week's sights and sounds
 &HT;    By James Lloyd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ One of the main points of Gospel Music Week
is music. Retailers and media can see and hear music in the
morning, music in the evening, music at suppertime _ and into the
wee hours of the morning. Nobody can take it all in, but the
following stand out as trends and highlights:
</P>
<P>
   FOLLOW THE LEADER
</P>
<P>
   If mainstream music does it, Christian music won't be too far
behind. This year's most obvious trend are Backstreet Boys and
Britney Spears wannabes. The five-member Plus One seems to be
getting the biggest push among the guys, though the Jake trio from
Canada was working the media, too. Then there's Squirt, the oldest
member of which is 15. Aurora, Shine and Zoe Girl were some of the
female groups, but the best of the bunch may be VEnna, a U.K./U.S.
duo put together by Worldwide Message Tribe founder Mark Pennells.
</P>
<P>
   TOUCHDOWN!
</P>
<P>
   The most unusual venue for a late-night concert was the
exclusive Stadium Club at the Tennessee Titans' home field,
Adelphia Coliseum. Michael W. Smith's Rocketown Records threw a
``Night at Rocketown'' party there with Chris Rice, Ginny Owens,
Wayne Kirkpatrick, Watermark and Smitty himself, who announced his
plans to record that instrumental album he's been wanting to do for
years.
</P>
<P>
   GET READY
</P>
<P>
   You'll be hearing these names more in the year ahead: Rachel
Lampa, a teen who is being touted as the next best thing; Salvador,
a Latino group from Austin, Texas, that is an appealing mix of
Burlap to Cashmere and, of all things, Blood Sweat and Tears; Tree,
a South African trio with a terrific pop sound; Kendall Payne,
whose worthy ``Jordan's Sister'' debut was released by Capitol last
year but is now receiving a push from Sparrow; and 1NC (One Nation
Crew), Kirk Franklin's new group. This one, made up of black, white
and Latino men and women between ages 20 and 26, may be the best
thing Franklin's done yet.
</P>
<P>
   BLOWN AWAY
</P>
<P>
   Hands down the best performance of the week was by
Cincinnati-born Nicole C. Mullen. During the Word and Myrrh Radio
and Retailer Dinner at the Wildhorse Saloon, she sang ``Redeemer''
from her new self-titled release. Before the first verse was over,
people were dabbing at their eyes and hands were raised heavenward.
Prediction: This song is an early front-runner to be song of the
year at the 2001 Doves. Mullen, by the way, will be in Middletown
June 17 with Smith.
</P>
<P>
   NEWSBOY EXTRA
</P>
<P>
   Phil Joel, bass player for the Newsboys, has a solo project
called ``Watching Over You'' coming out in late June on Peter
Furler's Inpop label. He previewed it Thursday. It sounds a little
softer than the Newsboys but is definitely worth a listen.
</P>
<P>
   LOUD FOR THE LORD
</P>
<P>
   Worship music continues to explode in the gospel industry.
Sparrow hosted an ``Extreme Worship'' late-night show that included
Form and the Parachute Band. Both are from New Zealand but have
diverse styles. Form lets it rip with raucous abandon, while the
Parachute Band leans more toward a blend of hip-hop, R&AMP;B and dance
music.
</P>
<P>
   UPCOMING ROAR
</P>
<P>
   The most eclectic group of artists on a release this year is
likely to be those gathered for the Squint's ``Roaring Lambs,'' ``a
celebration of artists who have reached out to a world that needs
salt and light,'' as urged by the late author Bob Briner. Duets
pair artist of the year Steven Curtis Chapman and best songwriter
Smith; Ashley Cleveland and dc Talk's Michael Tait; and Ladysmith
Mambazo and Charlie Peacock. Also included are Burlap to Cashmere,
Delirious?, Over the Rhine, Sixpence None the Richer, Jars of Clay
and, the biggest surprise, a reunion of PFR. ``Roaring Lambs'' is
set for release late in May.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
