<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000422.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4327 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-NEW-JESUS23-COX     04-22 1401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-JESUS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The New Jesus
 &HT;    By Stephanie Allmon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Jesus and his disciples went on to the villages
around Caesarea Philippi. On the way he asked them, ``Who do people
say I am?''
</P>
<P>
   They replied, ``Some say John the Baptist; others say Elijah;
and still others, one of the prophets.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But what about you?'' he asked. ``Who do you say I am?''
</P>
<P>
   Peter answered, ``You are the Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Mark 8:27-29 NIV
</P>
<P>
   If Jesus asked that question to his followers today, who would
they say he is? For some, spurred by new research and philosophical
debate, Jesus is no longer seen as the only way to salvation, but
instead as one of several spiritual leaders who point to eternal
life. Jesus, they say, is a teacher whose message of compassion
includes tolerance for other religions _ even those that do not
consider him the Christ.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last 10 years, there has been this enormous grass-roots
appetite for a different way of looking at Jesus,'' said Marcus
Borg, an author and professor of religion and culture at Oregon
State University and a scholar specializing in the study of Jesus.
``There's a passage in Hebrews that says Jesus is the same
yesterday, today and tomorrow. I think that's true, but the way we
think about Jesus is constantly changing.''
</P>
<P>
   But other Christians believe the interpretation of Jesus'
teachings should not change over time.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Ben Disney, senior minister at Central United Methodist
Church in Waco, said that as historians and theologians strip off
the layers of time to uncover the historical Jesus, they should not
strip away fundamental Christian tenets, namely, that belief in
Jesus as the son of God is the only path to salvation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a litmus test of faith. Do we think of Jesus as a
good, moral, ethical teacher, or do we say he was the son of God
who died and was resurrected? Ultimately, we make our decisions
based on fundamental beliefs that are non-negotiable,'' Disney
said. ``It seems like in spirituality today, there is a
cafeteria-style approach. But at times, we ought not to apologize
for who we are.''
</P>
<P>
   PERCEPTIONS CHANGE WITH WORLD
</P>
<P>
   Never before has Jesus been so scrutinized, historically and
philosophically, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade, seven books about Jesus have been
bestsellers, including Borg's ``Meeting Jesus Again for the First
Time.'' All three major American news magazines _ U.S. News and
World Report, Time and Newsweek _ have dealt with Jesus'
significance in the past five years. And in the next six weeks,
both CBS and ABC will air television programs about the life of
Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the discussion is the way Jesus is being
``humanized'' as his followers try to make his teachings fit
today's world, Borg said. This effort is part of people's natural
tendency to try to relate to someone they admire, said Garrett
Cook, associate professor of anthropology at Baylor University.
</P>
<P>
   For some, this means picturing Jesus, who has traditionally been
depicted by Christians as an Anglo man, in a more socially
acceptable way, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear that the church, like every other institution, is
having to respond to culture change,'' Cook said. ``In America, we
have an increasing sense of being a multicultural society in ethnic
representation, in gender representations and in religious
representations.''
</P>
<P>
   Those changes are reflected in the way people see and understand
Jesus, he said.
</P>
<P>
   HOW DO YOU SEE HIM?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most visual example of this is in the results of the
National Catholic Reporter magazine's Jesus 2000 contest. Last
year, the magazine asked people to depict how they thought the
Jesus of 2000 looks. More than 1,600 depictions were submitted, and
the winner was a painting of an African-American Jesus with some
feminine qualities and a look of sadness in his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The best place to start to understand the debate about who Jesus
is is to examine him as a historical figure, Borg said. The more
people know about Jesus in a historical context, the better they
can understand what his words should mean today.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, theologians have looked at the New Testament
writings, but new writings discovered in recent years should also
be examined, Borg said.
</P>
<P>
   One problem with focusing solely on the New Testament gospels is
that they may not be the earliest recordings of Jesus' teachings.
Some theologians believe there is a missing link between the Jewish
world that Jesus lived in and the way he was later interpreted by
the early Christian church.
</P>
<P>
   GOSPEL OF Q
</P>
<P>
   In 1945, an earlier gospel, the Sayings Gospel of Thomas, was
discovered. It referred to a book of Jesus' sayings written before
the four New Testament gospels. However, no complete version of
that book, The Gospel of Q, has been discovered.
</P>
<P>
   Borg said most scholars see the gospels as containing layers of
material. So by getting to the earliest gospels, they peel off the
layers into the earliest sources of who Jesus might have been. But
a deeper understanding of the historical figure of Jesus is only
part of the movement to redefine Jesus' teachings, Borg said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those searching for a new way of looking at Jesus are
doing so because they do not interpret the Bible as the literal
word of God, said Borg, who defines himself as a Christian. They
also think Jesus' teachings are not as relevant today as they were
in his time and culture, and they are struggling with the issue of
religious pluralism in Western culture today, he said.
</P>
<P>
   INQUISITIVE YOUTH
</P>
<P>
   Harvey Cox, a religion professor at Harvard University, said
young people in particular are searching for a new way to define
Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Cox, who for two decades taught a course on Jesus and who spoke
in 1996 at a seminar called ``Jesus at 2000,'' said this younger
group of Christians has been exposed to more religions than people
in previous generations, and they are reluctant to accept that
there is only one ``true'' way to salvation.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to bring the world's major faiths together, Pope
John Paul II took a historic journey to the Middle East last month
to visit holy sites of Christians, Jews and Muslims. The Pope
called for reconciliation and tolerance among the world's
religions, but, Borg said, he believes that if Jesus were on earth
today, he would have gone a step further.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Jesus would affirm religious pluralism, not out of
political correctness, but I think central to his teaching was the
immediacy of access to God,'' Borg said.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus was a Jewish mystic who had frequent spiritual
experiences, Borg said. Most religions emphasize ways in which
followers can have spiritual experiences, and Jesus would recognize
those other ways as valid, too, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Borg said he gets hundreds of letters each year from Christians
who say they view Jesus as just one of a few valid spiritual
leaders. Thinking of Jesus in nonexclusive terms makes more sense
to them in today's world, and they feel they can be better
Christians if their hearts agree with their minds, he said.
</P>
<P>
   FOR SOME, NO CHANGE
</P>
<P>
   Disney, however, said the interpretation of Jesus' teachings
should not change just because the culture is changing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesus talks about justice, love and mercy and how to deal with
people,'' Disney said. ``Those don't change, maybe the
circumstances change, but ultimately the teachings don't change.''
</P>
<P>
   What are the long-term implications for Christianity if the
quest to redefine Jesus continues?
</P>
<P>
   Cook said he thinks that a more tolerant, multicultural
representation of Jesus will help the Christian church proselytize
in regions of the world that would not relate to traditional
depictions of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Disney said the church should not feel threatened by
individuals' attempts to re-examine Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, it will be a wake-up call to the church that people
are constantly seeking spirituality, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think discussions are healthy and that the church should
never be afraid of people searching for spirituality,'' Disney
said. ``The church ought to rejoice in that. A community of faith
can help people understand, but we have to make sure we understand
that we don't own Jesus _ never have, never will.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
