<HEADER>
A4328 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-OPRAH-MAG23-COX     04-22 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPRAH-MAG23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `O' is for obvious
 &HT;    By Laura Dempsey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Oprah's new magazine _ she's calling it O: The
Oprah Magazine _ is just what you'd expect from the queen of almost
everything. It's big, glossy, full of makeup ads and feel-good
quotes from people ranging from Eleanor Roosevelt to Marianne
Williamson to the four fine folks featured on special ``Oprah to Go
_ Portable Inspiration'' cards to tear out and do with what you
will.
</P>
<P>
   Nice touch, offering Maya Angelou for take-out, but better yet,
the table of contents is right up front, where they used to be and
where they still belong. We raced right past it. The advertisements
come next, and they come in a glut. But that's to be expected _
even O has bills to pay, and everyone wants to be around Oprah.
</P>
<P>
   The May/June ($2.95) issue is O's debut: It's mission statement
is to create a magazine to celebrate women's lives. It's all about
personal growth, the kind of growth that runs the gamut from
fashion to food to home decorating to health. Oprah has tapped her
deep well of experts, hiring on Bob Greene to write about health
and fitness; Suze Orman on money (and emotions, naturally); Gary
Zukav on soul-ish issues; Phil McGraw on relationship advice.
</P>
<P>
   There's a special book section (surprised?) that highlights a
``simple yet so powerful'' book called ``The Four Agreements'' by
Don Miguel Ruiz (to save you time, here they are: 1) Be impeccable
with your word; 2) Don't take anything personally; 3) Don't make
assumptions; and 4) Always do your best.) Ruiz, of course,
illuminates each agreement in his book, and in the magazine Oprah
lets us in on how the second agreement changed her life. (How can
one life be changed so many times?)
</P>
<P>
   There are pages with probing questions and room in which to
write answers and a regular feature (she promises!) on Oprah's
favorite things, which this time includes $170 sunglasses by Fendi
and $110 pajamas _ hey, she sometimes wears them all day.
</P>
<P>
   We get excerpts from Jewel's diary (No thanks. We've read her
poetry), first in a series of features where people ``of note''
will open their journals. Another regular is ``Who Knew?'',
featuring Tina Turner this time, who ``reveals'' a ``secret love''
of horror movies and scary books. Yet another regular feature is an
inspirational photograph which, unfortunately, looks like an ad for
an empty chair.
</P>
<P>
   Stuff to know: Pastel hosiery is in this spring; spandex becomes
weakened if it's tossed in the dryer; calcium and raspberry-leaf
tea can ease cramps; Bob Greene (health expert) advises women to
stop smoking (where'd he get that idea?); Oprah's chef is named Art
Smith and his sweet-potato salad is out of this world.
</P>
<P>
   Also included are five nice bookmarks to tear out and tie a
tassel to. Oprah gives advice on how to use said bookmarks: ``Use
them to hold your place in a new novel,'' she suggests. OK _ Martha
Stewart she's not.
</P>
<P>
   A million copies of O hit the stands Wednesday. The first two
issues will stay out for two months each; in September, the
magazine will go monthly. Personal growth must be one bottomless
pit of story possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
