<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4364 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-VOUCHERS0423-COX     04-22 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOUCHERS0423-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida school deals with `failing' label
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PENSACOLA, Fla. _ One by one, second-graders in Patricia
Ferrell's class dropped objects into a glass bowl at the front of
the class. A wooden block. Next, a paper clip. Then a cotton ball,
crayon and marble. Marquis, one of the student volunteers, pinched
the marble between his fingers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will it sink or float?'' Ferrell asked her class of 20 kids.
``Who thinks it will sink?''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every hand shot up. Marquis released the glass ball.
``Yes! Yes!'' kids cheered as the ball sank.
</P>
<P>
   It's an unremarkable grade-school exercise in a lot of places,
as common as fishsticks and white milk in the cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   But here, any bit of learning is as cherished as a Ph.D.
</P>
<P>
   ``We celebrate small victories,'' said Judith Ladner, principal
at A.A. Dixon Elementary.
</P>
<P>
   Just like the marble, Dixon's 370 kids are in their own
fishbowl. They're scrutinized as products from one of the state's
only two ``failing'' public schools. The school has been labeled
under the education reform plan championed by Gov. Jeb Bush.
</P>
<P>
   At the core of Bush's reform are tax-subsidized vouchers, which
parents can use to help pay for private-school tuition. Legislators
in Georgia and Alabama have joined the nationwide throng debating
vouchers as a tool to improve public schools. Vouchers and a state
education lottery will figure prominently in this fall's
gubernatorial race in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, students gain voucher eligibility if their public
schools fail a controversial standardized test two years in a row.
Bush reasons the pressure of losing state financing _ up to $4,000
per voucher _ forces underachieving schools to improve.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 78 schools failed the test. When test scores are
released in June, nearly 60,000 students statewide may become
eligible for vouchers. Currently, just 52 students in Pensacola are
using the ``opportunity scholarships.''
</P>
<P>
   A state court in March ruled Florida's voucher system _ the
first statewide plan in the nation _ violated the state
constitution, threatening the quality of public education by
diverting tax money to private systems. Pensacola's voucher
students can remain at their private schools until the end of the
school year, the judge ruled.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the decision, a private group announced it has
raised $2 million to fund more than 1,100 new voucher students.
</P>
<P>
   POVERTY IS PREDICTOR
</P>
<P>
   For now, just two Pensacola elementary schools _ Dixon and
Spencer Bibbs Academy _ stick out as public institutions Florida
condemns as critically failing. The distinction makes their student
bodies eligible for vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   The designation is based on the Florida Comprehensive Assessment
Test, the so-called FCAT. At a ``C'' school, 60 percent of students
pass the reading and writing segments. At Bibbs and Dixon last
year, just one-quarter of students passed the reading test; less
than one-third passed writing.
</P>
<P>
   Administrators and parents bristle at the failing label. Before
Bush implemented his ``A-plus'' plan, Dixon and Bibbs scrambled to
improve the way they taught. Writing teachers were hired. New
reading programs emerged. Computers were purchased. Bibbs started
after-school and weekend remediation programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you that we haven't made mistakes,'' said Ladner,
who became Dixon principal in 1994. ``But we've come a whole long
way in six years.''
</P>
<P>
   Poverty, school officials say, is a key predictor of academic
success.
</P>
<P>
   Dixon and Bibbs are in the poorest sections of Pensacola, a Navy
town nestled near the sugar-white beaches of the Gulf of Mexico.
It's common for five or six kids in a family to share the same
mattress in public housing, teachers say. Some homes lack air
conditioning. Few kids from those schools have ever seen the sand
dunes 20 minutes across the Pensacola Bay Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   There's daily exposure to crime. Drug deals can be seen walking
to school. Often, a parent goes to jail and the child ends up with
a grandparent or other relative.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to take into consideration where the kids started,''
said Bibbs principal Linda Scott.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bibbs district, one-quarter of the 3,500 households fall
below the poverty level. Poverty hits two of every five families in
the Dixon district. When rent comes due, some families find a new
place to live.
</P>
<P>
   More than nine of every 10 kids at both schools qualify for free
or reduced lunches. All of Dixon's kids are entitled to free
breakfast. In poor homes, there's TV but little else. There's no
discussion. About anything. What language skills the kids develop
comes from whatever they saw on WWF wrestling the night before,
teachers say.
</P>
<P>
   In Linda Martin's Dixon kindergarten class, she runs through
simple exercises. ``Point to a girl,'' Martin commands. ``Now point
to a boy.'' Smiling kids swivel in their seats, pointing.
``Language is the big thing here,'' Ladner said. When adults do
talk with their children at home, ``it's not very positive.''
</P>
<P>
   But Florida schools in similar depths of poverty have earned
passing grades. At Cleveland Elementary in Tampa, for example, 96
percent of the students receive free or reduced lunches _ a level
similar to Bibbs and Dixon. Cleveland earned a ``C.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We know it can happen because schools are doing it,'' said
JoAnn Carrin, spokeswoman for the Florida Department of Education.
She said state Commissioner of Education Tom Gallagher ``feels very
strongly that inner-city schools should not have a different
standard. He feels all kids can learn and should have the same
standards.''
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTERS IN CLASSROOMS
</P>
<P>
   Dixon and Bibbs are undeterred by the state's unwillingness to
consider the environment that surrounds the school when assigning
grades. At Dixon, 65 kindergarteners can read. At Bibbs, tests show
the children are learning more than a year's worth of schooling
every year. Banks of Macintosh computers sit in every classroom at
Bibbs, a technology magnet for the Escambia County school district.
In the morning, students put together their own closed-circuit
television broadcasts of school announcements.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of things we do that aren't measured by the
(FCAT) test,'' said Scott, the Bibbs principal. As with Ladner at
Dixon, Bibbs knows nearly every student by name. They wave or rush
to hug her when she walks the halls or enters a class.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would put my kids up with anybody as being marketable for
jobs of the future,'' Scott said. ``To say they're failures, that's
not right. That's not true.''
</P>
<P>
   Antoniette Stallworth, a 32-year-old homemaker, agrees. She
moved out of district but chose to keep her three children _ from
kindergarten to fourth grade _ enrolled at Bibbs. Pro-voucher
groups tried convincing her to move her kids to a private school.
At her husband's accounting office, people always ask why they keep
their kids at an ``F'' school. Her parents ask the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of them have actually been to Bibbs,'' Stallworth said.
``We try to build a rapport with all of the teachers. From the
first day, we felt very comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   With an emphasis on direct instruction in reading, Scott is
confident Bibbs will come off the failing list when statewide
standardized test scores are released.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can learn just the same as anyone else,'' Scott said,
``they just don't have the same skills when they get here.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
