<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4366 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-PLAYOFFS-N     04-22 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-PLAYOFFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS' CHALLENGE: GET AN EARLY JUMP ON YOUNG RAPTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ The image is always the same. It is the opening
minutes of the game, and an exasperated Jeff Van Gundy is standing
in front of his team, with his jaw clenched as tight as a fist.
</P>
<P>
   He has called a timeout. It is maybe four minutes into the game.
And already there is a gaudy deficit, maybe eight points or 10.
Already, Vince Carter has driven, pulled up and unleashed a flurry
of fadeaway jumpers. Already, Latrell Sprewell and Larry Johnson
have had their confidence shaken like a carton of orange juice.
Already, Allan Houston's defense has been mocked by Tracy McGrady
or Dell Curry or Doug Christie. Already, Patrick Ewing has been
knocked on his 37-year-old duff by his former bodyguard, Charles
Oakley.
</P>
<P>
   Already, there is trouble. Deep inside the huddle of giants, the
diminutive Van Gundy thinks for a bit, then unleashes a vehement
plea for his players to get it together, only to see them fail time
and again to rescue the outcome. In the first quarter of their last
three games with the Toronto Raptors, the Knicks have trailed
32-16, 26-18 and 28-11. In each instance, they have gone on to lose
by double-digit margins.
</P>
<P>
   In a first-round, three-of-five-game playoff series, there is
little time for recovery. Under pressure to maintain home-court
advantage, the third-seeded Knicks could face a demoralizing
situation if they allow the sixth-seeded Raptors to seize quick
control of Game 1 on Sunday at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt they've dominated us in the first quarter,''
Van Gundy said after his team's first of two workouts on Friday at
SUNY-Purchase. ``They've been more ready earlier in the game than
we have to compete at the level you need to compete at. Their
intensity has been much greater than ours earlier in the game. I
think our starters have played fairly hard, but I think their
starters have been off the chart. I think their intensity and focus
and physical presence has been dominating.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been devastating to the Knicks' spirits. But as Ewing
proclaimed last week, ``It's a new day.'' That is how the Knicks
are treating it. They believe in their preparation, their ability
to flip a switch for instant intensity, and their pattern of
inhaling the air of desperation and turning it into adrenaline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally and physically, we'll be ready,'' Sprewell said. ``I
know this team. I don't think we're intimidated by anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The Raptors' initial wave of energy is daunting, though. In each
game, they have come tearing out with the enthusiasm of Pop Warner
football players bursting through poster paper. So far, the Knicks
have failed to match them. In fact, they have come unglued in the
first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of moving the ball, the Knicks panic. In their last
three games against the Raptors, the Knicks had a total of seven
assists in the first quarter, while their more fluid opponents in
purple combined for 32. As a result of rushed shots, quick jumpers
and failed one-on-one attempts, the Knicks are often out of the
game before it even begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely have to look for each other more,'' Sprewell
said. ``We have to find each other, play unselfish. That's when
we're at our best.''
</P>
<P>
   They have to unearth their defense, as well. That means not
getting lost in the Raptors' pick-and-roll routines. And that means
confronting their fear of Carter. So far, Sprewell and Johnson _
both of whom will spend time guarding Carter _ have allowed the
Raptors' sleek superstar to shoot 60 percent and average 33 points
a game.
</P>
<P>
   After inspecting reels of film, Van Gundy could come up with a
different look to start the game. Maybe the Knicks will double-team
Carter, funnel him into help or mix up the coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can do new things,'' said Van Gundy, who did not disclose
what his matchups would be. ``But I don't think in two days you can
reinvent yourself. Whatever you do, you have to do it with passion.
A lot of different guys will have the opportunity to play Vince
Carter. It can be anybody, and it will probably be everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is not just Carter who has unsettled the Knicks. It is
the way Houston has been shut down by the long-armed McGrady. ``I
just have to be more assertive, and I will,'' Houston vowed.
</P>
<P>
   And it is the way Oakley has inserted his elbows into the
Knicks' subconscious. ``I've said it before,'' said Ewing, who has
been roughed up by the gruff veteran who used to protect him as a
Knick. ``Oak has been in a lot of wars with us. Unfortunately, he's
on the other team now. We have to do our job just like he does
his.''
</P>
<P>
   At least until now, the Knicks have been procrastinators against
the Raptors. They have waited to see how the Raptors will come out
and have paid dearly with an ominous deficit. This time, they want
to make the Raptors adjust. This time, they want to beat Toronto, a
team stocked with young, untested stars, with their experience and
savvy.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy could surprise the Raptors with the big backcourt. At
times, Van Gundy will probably use Sprewell and Houston as a
counter to Christie and McGrady.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we're holding it in hiding,'' Van Gundy said.
``We've used the big backcourt to start the last home game we had
with them, and we were down, 31-23. So can it be effective? Sure it
can. Has it been ineffective against them like everything else?
Absolutely. Everyone whips it out as the cure-all. It's not the
cure-all.''
</P>
<P>
   The solution may be found at the start. Can the Knicks be the
aggressors? Can they dilute Carter's immediate impact? Can they
take control of Game 1? To lose it would be mentally devastating,
considering it would be the Knicks' fourth loss in a row to the
Raptors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't shoot ourselves in the foot,'' Houston said. ``We
have to set the tone from the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   If Van Gundy is forced to call a timeout _ maybe four or six
minutes into the game _ there is trouble, big trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always digging holes and trying to crawl out of them,''
said Marcus Camby, whose challenge is to be the X-factor in the
playoffs that he was last season. ``It's almost impossible to do,
especially if Vince starts scoring a lot of points. Our starters
have to get us off to a good start, and us bench guys have to come
in with that spark that we need. We can't start by trailing.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
