<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4367 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ESTATE0423-COX     04-22 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESTATE0423-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Repeal of the estate tax may be well on its way
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Some of the wealthiest people in the country could
get an enormous break, because growing opposition to estate tax may
lead to its repeal or reduction.
</P>
<P>
   Very few Americans ever come face to face with the estate tax,
the levy assessed by the government on what wealthy Americans leave
behind when they die. The first $675,000 is exempt from taxes this
year, and that figure will rise to $1 million by 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 2 percent of the 2.5 million Americans who are
expected to die this year will leave estates large enough to be
taxed, according to an estimate by Congress's Joint Committee on
Taxation.
</P>
<P>
   Why then does a majority of the House of Representatives back a
bill to repeal the tax House Majority Leader Dick Armey (R-Texas)
calls ``the despicable death tax''?
</P>
<P>
   Armey promises the House will take up the subject when lawmakers
return from their Easter vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Similar legislation in the Senate has 24 sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   And George W. Bush, the presumptive Republican presidential
nominee, favors eliminating the estate tax, which his tax plan
calls ``the antithesis of the American Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   To hear the tax's defenders tell it, Republicans _ who
predominate in the opposition to the estate tax _ are speaking up
for their political benefactors. Estate taxes, its supporters say,
help keep the tax system progressive and spur charitable giving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compared to other ways of paying for government, who could
quarrel with a tax that raises a good deal of money without
bothering almost 99 percent of us?'' said Robert McIntyre,
executive director of the liberal Citizens for Tax Justice, in a
posting on the think tank's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, leaders of the movement to abolish the tax have
recognized some of the obstacles they face. They studiously avoid
calling it an estate tax, preferring the harsher-sounding death tax
instead.
</P>
<P>
   And they have attempted to remake their image to look more like
America. It used to be the public face of the lobbying effort was
``middle-aged white guys who were well off,'' said Frank Blethen,
publisher of The Seattle Times.
</P>
<P>
   Blethen, 54, who fits the category he described, is among the
more vocal newspaper owners who call for getting rid of the estate
tax as a way to keep family owned papers from going public or being
gobbled up by large chains.
</P>
<P>
   The National Black Chamber of Commerce argues the estate tax
deprives African-Americans of the means to economic empowerment.
And the issue is a growing concern to women who own businesses,
according to a study by the Center for the Study of Taxation, a
California group that staunchly opposes estate taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The chief argument of many owners of family businesses,
including family farms, is the estate tax takes such a large bite
out of their holdings the value is vastly diminished when it passes
to the next generation.
</P>
<P>
   The tax is especially hard on land-rich but cash-poor farmers
who may have to sell off land to pay the government.
</P>
<P>
   Studies cited by opponents of the tax say the estate tax's
consequences are dire for many business owners. One figure cited by
Armey states flatly that ``70 percent of family businesses fail to
survive the first generation because of this unjust tax.''
</P>
<P>
   Blethen, who has spent tens of thousands of dollars over 25
years to ensure his newspaper will remain in the family, conceded
the possibility Blethen might lose control of The Seattle Times is
at least two generations away.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the reason I've become so passionate is that I don't want
anyone else to go through what I and my family have gone through,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another statistic sometimes cited by proponents of repeal is
family businesses make up less than 10 percent of the estates that
are subject to estate taxes each year.
</P>
<P>
   Even academics who favor the taxation of wealth at death support
changing the tax structure to take care of not liquid family
businesses. ``Most large estates are very liquid, and exempting
farms and small business would cost a relatively small part of the
revenue,'' said Michael Graetz, a Yale Law School professor and tax
expert.
</P>
<P>
   One obstacle to full repeal may be the budgetary constraints put
in place by the Republican-controlled Congress. The estate tax will
generate nearly $30 billion this year, and any plan to forgo that
money has to replace it, or eat into anticipated budget surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the estate tax is just one of several tax
provisions Republicans are eager to send to President Clinton. They
have little hope of enacting major tax breaks this year, but want
to be able to use the topic in this fall's election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In the event Bush is elected and Republicans retain control of
Congress, next year could bring substantial tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Even with soaring home values and retirement savings plans that
have boosted many Americans' wealth in recent years, most Americans
will remain unaffected by the 84-year-old estate tax, according to
projections.
</P>
<P>
   The tax was created to keep the wealthy industrialists of the
early 20th century from passing too large a share of their fortunes
to succeeding generations.
</P>
<P>
   The tax may have failed in that respect. Families like the
Carnegies and Rockefellers have done well.
</P>
<P>
   But as George McGovern learned when he proposed startlingly high
taxes on inheritances during his 1972 presidential campaign, voters
object to the government taking too much of what parents save for
their children, even when the threshold approaches $1 million a
parent.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 1537EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
