u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-GIULIANI-NY     04-22 0391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI SAYS CASTRO ORCHESTRATED GONZALEZ RAID 
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani lashed out at the Clinton
administration Saturday for the early-morning raid that snatched
Elian Gonzalez from the home of his Miami relatives, saying that
the government had sent ``storm troopers using guns'' to do the
bidding of Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is one of the saddest days we've seen,'' Giuliani said at a
press conference at the Jacob K. Javits Convention Center. The
mayor condemned the Justice Department's use of armed federal
agents ``pointing guns at people to rip a boy away from a family
that is caring for him, and a boy who has at least indicated an
interest in growing up in democracy and freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, a former federal prosecutor, said the government had
been a pawn of the Cuban dictator. ``You would have to have ignored
the whole history of communism not to realize that this is an
orchestrated plot by Castro,'' he said. ``It is even said that when
he goes back to Cuba he will have to go into an indoctrination
camp. I can't imagine that the American administration has lost its
way so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has said repeatedly that Elian should be granted asylum
in the United States, and has focused on what he calls White House
ineptitude in the case in his Senate campaign against Hillary
Rodham Clinton. He harshly criticized Attorney General Janet Reno,
saying, ``She should have negotiated as long as it took.'' He
added: ``She has had some pretty disgraceful situations as attorney
general, but this one probably ranks right up there. It has been a
heck of tenure as attorney general.''
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani focused his most passionate remarks on President
Clinton, who he suggested had given in to influence from Castro and
had ignored the threat of communism. Giuliani has frequently warned
of the dangers of being complacent about communism in campaign
appearances and remarks to reporters at City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   When asked why he thought the White House had decided to
forcibly remove Elian, he said: ``I have to imagine it has to do
with deals, arrangements, negotiations with Fidel Castro. The
person calling the shots here as usual in foreign policy is not
President Clinton; the person calling the shots is Fidel Castro.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 1541EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000422.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4369 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OUTDOORS-TURKEYS-NYT &LR;      04-22 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-TURKEYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS: TIME TO PRACTICE THE CALL OF THE TURKEY 
</HEADLINE>
   By NELSON BRYANT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many veteran turkey hunters are already prowling hardwood
hillsides trying to locate male wild turkeys, which will become
legal game when New York state's monthlong spring season for them
opens May 1. Although gobblers are bagged by those who eschew this
preseason ritual, taking part in it improves your chances of
success.
</P>
<P>
   The spring season, limited to bearded birds _ females are rarely
so adorned _ comes when most hens are on their nests. There will be
a few still seeking impregnation, and they are the ones the
impassioned toms are after. Hunting ends at noon each day because
the females don't usually take a daily break from sitting on their
10 to 12 eggs until that time. Hens have to eat, too, and once the
heady business of mating is done, the gobbler's contributions to
the various females he has serviced are over. Thus, the eggs of a
deceased hen are abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   Few hens are shot by mistake. In addition to almost never having
a beard, the hen is smaller and of a much lighter hue than the
male, and its approach to the hidden hunter's yelping is totally
unlike the strutting arrival of the gobbler. His tail feathers are
usually spread out like a fan and his wing tips drag along the
ground. Also, the male's head is a garish mixture of red, white and
blue, while that of the hen is a muted blue-gray and gray.
</P>
<P>
   Fully camouflaged, the human hunter sits down in a likely spot,
back against a tree _ one, hopefully, within hearing distance of a
gobbler _ and begins talking turkey, which is defined by the
dictionary as blunt or candid communication. For the hunter's
purposes, brevity is a quality also much desired. If you give vent
to a hen's yelp and a gobbler answers, control your ardor; don't
launch into a continuous spate of yelping. Wait five or 10 minutes
or more and perhaps you'll hear the tom's gobble close at hand or
hear him running through the forest duff. Unless you are a master
caller, fewer yelps are always better than more. You may hit a sour
note and spoil the whole gambit.
</P>
<P>
   It's important to get an early start. Most spring gobblers are
taken in the first hour of daylight, so you have to make your way
to your chosen location in darkness and be in position before dawn.
Make yourself as comfortable as possible, be sure you have a good
field of view and remember that toms sometimes have a disconcerting
habit of approaching from behind. As an aside, if you've got the
yen for it, and the stamina, you can devote the afternoons of your
New York state turkey hunting to trout fishing.
</P>
<P>
   In spring, the yelp of the hen is the basic call. The
swinging-lid box call is the easiest to master and has the greatest
range. Its disadvantage is that you can't operate it and hold your
gun at the ready at the same time. Turkeys have marvelous vision
and can spot hand movements. The so-called diaphragm call, which is
held in your mouth, does away with this problem, but its range is
more limited and it takes quite a bit of practice to learn how to
use it.
</P>
<P>
   Spring turkey hunters sometimes gobble. The purpose of this is
to attract a tom who is enraged that another male has invaded his
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey hunting equipment is becoming increasingly sophisticated.
The March 28, 1999, catalog of Uncle Lee's Wing Supply in
Greenville, Ky., lists hundreds of turkey calls, including box
calls, diaphragm calls, push-button box calls, slate calls, glass
calls, copper pot and pump action calls, gobbler shaker calls and
even owl calls. The last-named are sometimes used to locate
roosting gobblers at dawn. Such birds will also occasionally
respond to a crow call. Wing Supply also offers dozens of turkey
decoys. Spring hunters often use decoys, a common combination being
a jake and two hens. A jake is a young male turkey whose presence
with the hens is calculated to raise the ire of the area's dominant
gobbler. Decoys are also used in the fall when hunting with dogs is
allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Only shotguns and shells loaded with bird shot may be used when
hunting turkeys with firearms in New York State. Shot size cannot
be larger than No. 2 or smaller than No. 8. Full choke is
recommended. A special turkey permit is needed in addition to a
hunting license. The bag limit is one bird a day, two for the
season.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't already done it, it's wise to draw the head and
neck of a turkey to size on a sheet of paper and fire at it from a
distance of 30 or 40 yards with the load you intend to use. If the
shot pattern is evenly dispersed, centered on the head and neck
with no so-called ``blown'' areas, and there are several pellets in
vital areas, you're in business. You can usually deal with a blown
pattern by changing the load or the choke, or both, but if the
pattern isn't centered on the target, you'll have to remind
yourself to compensate for this at the moment of truth by holding a
bit high or low or left or right. A few turkey hunters use shotguns
equipped with adjustable iron sights or scope sights. Such sights
can be adjusted for windage and elevation.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Cole, wildlife manager for New York state's Region 3,
said: ``This past winter wasn't bad, so it probably didn't have
much effect on turkey populations. We've also had a lot of turkey
sightings. We should have a good season.''
</P>
<P>
   The turkey take is usually higher in the spring season. In New
York state, the spring kill, 1996 through 1999, was, in order,
10,341, 9,159, 9,189 and 8,973; the fall kill for the same years
was 5,043, 7,464, 5,985 and 7,666.
</P>
<P>
   And if you've ever wondered why this splendid, wily bird that is
indigenous to North America was named after another country, the
Pilgrims are to blame. They believed it to be a species of New
World guinea fowl. Guinea fowl had been brought to England by
Turkish traders, and the English called them turkey hens and turkey
cocks. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 1544EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
