<DOCNO> NYT20000422.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4370 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-SHAQUILLE-ART-970     04-22 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SHAQUILLE-ART-970(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ IS TALK OF THE TOWN IN FLOURISHING L.A. STORY
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT14 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ He knows they are whispering about him. He hears
the chatter between mother and daughter at the red light on the
corner of Sepulveda Boulevard and Lucerne Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is, Mom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would he be in traffic, riding a big, red motorcycle in
the middle of the afternoon?''
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal turns around and smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I want to?''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal guns his candy-apple red, custom Titan with the obscenely
long forks and motors from a light practice to his acupuncturist in
Thousand Oaks for a blood-letting treatment, has a couple of slices
of pizza at a place off Ventura Boulevard and then peels off into a
parfait sunset, toward the Santa Monica Mountains, where the
biggest star in the NBA lives.
</P>
<P>
   On his way through the traffic-choked streets of L.A., he barks
back at a miniature schnauzer in a minivan.
</P>
<P>
   You follow him down Sepulveda for miles, hitting each traffic
light.
</P>
<P>
   At one intersection, O'Neal points to an American Express
billboard with his mammoth smiling face beside the words,
``Invincible since '92.''
</P>
<P>
   He points and opens his arms wide, a big man living large,
inhaling everything about the town he has enraptured.
</P>
<P>
   ``This city has been patient, they've been good to me,'' Shaq
said. ``They've been very good. They're just waiting for us to
bring it back. What's it been, a 12-year drought?''
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Lakers have not won a championship since
Showtime started its decline in 1988. They are not long-suffering
fans, but they miss the way Magic Johnson distilled a city with his
boyish exuberance.
</P>
<P>
   Magic may be gone, but here comes Shaq, pulling up to the red
light with a helmet to match his bike, a helmet that bears the
Superman logo and barely fits his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a city filled with celebrities like L.A. _ all the
so-called Hollywood glitz and glamour _ it's nice to have the best
player in the league on that team,'' said Rick Fox, O'Neal's
teammate and a part-time actor who is married to Vanessa Williams.
``As animated as Shaquille is, it's pretty clear he's best suited
for this city.''
</P>
<P>
   Today is a very L.A. kind of day for O'Neal on his motorcycle.
After his acupuncture treatment, he will eat, visit a friend, then
retreat to his 15,000-square foot home in Mulholland Estates.
O'Neal is allowed to drive a motorcycle, but he has a contract
clause that prohibits him from sky diving. ``I don't think I can
scuba or water ski either,'' he said. His neighbors in Mulholland
at various times of the year include Wayne Gretzky, Tom Arnold and
Loni Anderson _ ``that woman who took all of Burt Reynolds'
money,'' O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, the game's most awesome force leads the Lakers on
a path many believe will take them to a championship. ``This is the
way I thought he could play basketball,'' said Phil Jackson, the
Lakers' first-year coach who always coveted a center of O'Neal's
stature while building a dynasty in Chicago. ``All of a sudden he's
becoming a dominant player, starting to make an escalation we
haven't seen. I expect even more out of Shaq. He's just touching
the area.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal's last trip to the NBA finals, when he played for
Orlando, is mostly forgettable, a four-game sweep to the Houston
Rockets in 1995. He came to the Lakers via free agency before the
1996-97 season. Though his teams have won a lot of games during the
regular season, O'Neal has battled nagging injuries and the
criticism accompanying an All-Star center swept from the playoffs
in three of the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   But he has just completed a most valuable player-type season,
his best in his eight seasons in the league. He led the NBA in
points (29.7), field-goal percentage (.574) and double-doubles
(63), and he ranked in the top five in six major statistical
categories. On March 6 _ his 28th birthday _ he exploded for 61
points against the Clippers. Everything he puts up, it seems, is
caught by the net.
</P>
<P>
   If he is still on his way to becoming king of his sport, he is
already approaching royalty away from the game.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the sprawling, beige-toned Santa Monica office of Leonard
Armato, O'Neal's agent whose big-man clientele once included Hakeem
Olajuwon and Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, another O'Neal empire takes
shape.
</P>
<P>
   Armato is finishing an agreement with Digex, one of the largest
Web-hosting companies in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The agent has also entered O'Neal into an agreement with
FreeInternet.com. O'Neal and Bob, the talking baby in recent
advertisements, will appear in commercials together over the next
few weeks
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Shaq.com _ the site where you can watch O'Neal morph from
a gallery of baby and adolescent photos into a 7-foot-1-inch,
330-pound man with size-22 feet _ there is Dunk.net, an online
company that allows anyone to design his or her own custom-made
apparel and footwear.
</P>
<P>
   ``The era of `Be Like Mike' is over,'' Armato said. ``We don't
want you to be like Shaq. Shaq is going to inspire you to build
your own product. He wants you to be a mouse click away from the
selection you're going to make.''
</P>
<P>
   In Forbes magazine's Celebrity 100 issue released in March,
O'Neal was listed at No. 35 _ his $31 million in salary and
endorsements surpassing David Letterman and Howard Stern. His net
worth is believed to be more than $100 million. Including a
collection of his greatest rap hits, O'Neal has released five CDs
and starred in two heavily panned movies, ``Kazaam'' and ``Steel.''
Armato said he is holding off on another film until he wins a pro
basketball title.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done movies, he's done rap CDs,'' Jackson said. ``And now
he's moving into the technology areas. He's been there and done
that, and seen what it can bring you and what it can't bring you. I
admire his perspective. Enterprising guy that he is, he has also
been able focus on what's important.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In November, that meant spending an extra hour after practice to
work on his free throws. Today, it means taking care of his body
with a visit to Shen Hsu.
</P>
<P>
   Hsu (pronounced Soo) is the director of Harmony Center
Acupuncture, Inc. Several of the Lakers receive treatment from Hsu,
including the veteran John Salley.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, who has an inflammation in his right hip, ducks under a
6-10 doorway and into a cramped room. He removes his shirt, his
massive frame spilling over the treatment table. He plants his face
firmly in the headrest as Hsu goes to work, rubbing small plastic
suction cups along O'Neal's oiled back.
</P>
<P>
   Cupping and scraping are part of the Chinese folk medicine
tradition. Among other results, the process is said to purify the
blood and increase blood-cell production. The surface of the skin
is strongly sucked by the vacuum pressure in the cup, opening
capillary vessels and pores. It allows toxins to be excreted. It
also hurts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like a tattoo,'' O'Neal said. ``Not that bad.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Certain days last season, I couldn't move my leg.
Shen would fix me up.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal's lower body was in such pain from an abdominal strain,
he said: ``Without Shen, I couldn't have played last year. I'm
serious.''
</P>
<P>
   The most painful process is yet to come. Hsu gently lances a
small, circular area on the right side of O'Neal's lower back, near
the top of his buttock. Placing the cup over the area, he holds it
there for several seconds until O'Neal's bright, red blood rises to
the surface. The process is continued for several minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe he let you watch the bloodletting,'' Salley
said while Hsu worked on O'Neal. ``I don't know how that'll go over
with people. I mean, we're Americans. This is Western civilization.
They might frown on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Hsu said: ``You see the movie `Sense and Sensibility'? They used
leeches for the bloodletting. It goes back to 18th-century England.
The farm-raised leeches are very expensive. The cupping is just as
good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you this, Shaq won't be walking like Patrick when
he's finished,'' Salley said, referring to the Knicks' Patrick
Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's ingesting ginseng or eating healthful foods, O'Neal
is taking care of his body like never before. He lives with only a
personal chef, who prepares chicken, fish and vegetables. ``I'll
eat steak now and then, but I'm not a big red meat eater,'' he
said. ``My partying days are over. I've gotten serious about taking
care of my body. See, I don't get tired. I get beat up. You keep
chopping on a tree, you need to give the tree some rest so the
chlorophyll will fill back up and the tree gets its energy back.''
</P>
<P>
   After the acupuncture session, O'Neal walks down a flight of
stairs and sits in a mahogany-stained booth at a New York-style
pizzeria. He orders a plate of spaghetti with marinara sauce, two
slices of thin-crust cheese pizza and a large Sprite.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging nearly everyone who walked past him, O'Neal caught
a 10-year-old boy off guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's up?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey,'' the kid replied nonchalantly.
</P>
<P>
   Coming to a sudden halt behind O'Neal and taking one step back
to make sure it was indeed Shaq, the boy slowly mouthed to himself,
``Oh ... my ... God,'' before nearly running to tell his family.
</P>
<P>
   In the parking lot, O'Neal was approached by more people.
``Shaq, I don't know if you remember me,'' a young woman began,
``but I worked with you on `Kazaam.' I'm with Interscope.''
</P>
<P>
   She asked for an autograph for her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cost you a dollar,'' he said to the woman, smiling. ``OK, I'll
let you go this time.''
</P>
<P>
   On this afternoon, he looks into people's vehicles at nearly
every stoplight, acknowledging everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's slowly returning to that people-person side of him,'' Fox
said. ``The last few years, he's been stressed by the losing. But
you can see him start to come out of his shell, being playful and
enjoying himself. He is asked if he cares about his place in NBA
history. ``People are going to say Wilt is the greatest, Kareem is
the greatest,'' O'Neal said. ``I'm very honored to even have my
name mentioned. They don't even mention Ralph Sampson, and I
thought he was pretty good. They don't even mention Artis Gilmore.
Those guys were good. If my name is mentioned with Kareem or Wilt,
that's the ultimate.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampson? ``Big Ralph,'' O'Neal said. ``He had skills.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal straddles the handlebars on his Titan in the parking lot,
leans back and slowly pulls out. He motors up Ventura Boulevard,
merging into traffic, toward the hills, his sweatshirt and jeans
flopping in the breeze, blending seamlessly into the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
