<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: KNICKS ARE OFFICIALLY ON BASEBALL'S CLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Somebody, please tell the New York Knicks to either
be very good or very brief. They and their entire league are
indulging in their annual habit of getting interesting just when it
is time to go outdoors and sniff the pollen.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball was so captivating in the first three weeks of the
season that the Knicks would never be missed if the Toronto Raptors
blew them away in three or four games. This is not to be construed
as a prediction or blatant rooting, just a humble observation.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how much its chieftains monkey around with rocket
balls and interleague play and the threat of realignment, baseball
somehow bounces back in the spring as tenacious as dogwoods and
forsythia.
</P>
<P>
   Long ago, basketball had the good taste to get out of the way
right about now. The least the Knicks could do is match the Yanks
and Mets for plot and performance.
</P>
<P>
   The Yanks are compelling because of their generally unbeatable
mixture of skill and luck. The Mets are fascinating because of
their shock troops named Mora and Payton and Agbayani. Not only
that, but minor league baseball is also breaking out on Long Island
and in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Hunkering down in the middle of all this are the Knicks _ still
potentially ornery enough and talented enough to grind down the
youthful Raptors, run away from the transitional Pacers and
outbounce the staggering Heat, all for the privilege of being
stuffed by Shaq.
</P>
<P>
   It would be admirable if the Knicks played with panache en route
to their ultimate thwacking. But the evidence is that these guys
lurch from one stinker of a game to one showcase of a game, with
almost no gear in between.
</P>
<P>
   That is not good enough. Either play consistent ball or bring on
Hefty Bag Day. At least the other team from Dolanland, the hapless
Rangers, had the class to not qualify for the playoffs, to get out
of our ocular and olfactory senses.
</P>
<P>
   From here on in, the Knicks need to justify their existence.
There is no great need for them anymore, it says here. Baseball
season commenced in Japan, where guys like Mark Grace of the Cubs
and Mike Piazza of the Mets seemed to get it, that it was really
cool to play games that count on the other side of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Then they started to play back in North America. One of my
favorite snapshots of this early season was out of Seattle, where
Japan's career leader in saves, 31-year-old Kazuhiro Sasaki, stood
up in the Mariners' dugout while Mariano Rivera pitched in relief
for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Sasaki was more than watching. He was observing. He was
studying. He was staring. His intense eyes seemed to say: ``So this
is Rivera-san. What's he got? Can I be as good as he is?''
</P>
<P>
   Another snapshot from this young season came from the Mets'
series in Pittsburgh last weekend. Jason Kendall, the Pirates
catcher, his ankle reconstructed from the ghastly injury last
summer, is back.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall leads off. Kendall hits with power. Kendall steals
bases. Kendall handles everything behind the plate. And with easy,
compact motions, Kendall fires strikes to second base. It was sheer
enjoyment to watch Kendall match his varied skills with Piazza's
innate offensive power and earnest defensive klutziness.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees. Good grief. The Yankees. Already, they are a whole
highlight film, including the umpire's blown call on Jorge Posada's
unassisted double play at the plate on a ball that bounced off the
batter's leg. Some of us have been watching grotesquely lucky
breaks like that for decades. Decades.
</P>
<P>
   But don't forget this one: David Cone in trouble. Batter slaps
ball toward the mound. Cone can do no more than deflect it. Ball
bounces directly to Derek Jeter, who smoothly, softly, almost
arrogantly, charges, throws home for the tag at the plate. Yankee
luck? You bet. Yankee skill? Yeah, that too.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Met finesse. Last Wednesday night, Derek Bell
slapped not one but two singles through holes just vacated by
Milwaukee fielders. The Mets have often lacked for such
professional legerdemain with runners in motion.
</P>
<P>
   Bell apparently carries his bats with him wherever he goes, the
great bags under his eyes making him look as old as Wee Willie
Keeler, the turn-of-the-previous-century batsman, whose slogan was,
``Hit 'em where they ain't.'' He also makes sliding catches in
right field a la Ron Swoboda in the magic autumn of '69.
</P>
<P>
   With all these good things going on at ballparks near us, New
Yorkers really don't need one of those hot-cold playoffs by the
Knicks, when Patrick Ewing takes clueless fallaway jumpers one
night, and gallant buzzer-beating jumpers the next night.
</P>
<P>
   We don't need these mood swings, but the Knicks could
alternately trudge and saunter right through the Kentucky Derby,
right through lacrosse season, right through Venus Williams'
retirement before the French Open, right through the Indy 500,
right through the Stanley Cup finals _ maybe decided by a
legitimate goal, for a change _ right through a few Tiger Woods
victories, right up to Venus Williams' comeback before Wimbledon,
just in time for a John Rocker sighting in Flushing on June 29.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks could eat up the springtime with Van Gundy-sighing,
Houston-disappearing, Sprewell-chucking, Thomas-fighting,
Camby-fouling, Johnson-scowling, Ewing-fumbling.
</P>
<P>
   They could obstruct truly worthy things like El Duque's poise
and Edgardo Alfonzo's swing. You would like to think the Knicks
could at least hog the springtime with style and grace. Nah. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 1600EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000422.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4375 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     04-22 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FUTURE MAY BE LATER FOR PRESENT RAPTORS
</HEADLINE>
  By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Take a good look at the future of professional
basketball over the next week to 13 days. That's all it may last
if, as expected, those hardened ratings-killers from Madison Square
Garden measure up to veteran playoff form.
</P>
<P>
   By sending Vince Carter back to his room after one measly round,
the New York Knicks could very well be dooming The Chosen One to a
succession of first-round defeats, to a prolonged state of Grant
Hill-hood. And if the Toronto Raptors don't make some postseason
noise, Carter may realize that all of the made-for-TV marketing and
magazine covers have come with a stiff price _ the one player he
will need to continue at his current Air Canada altitude and
address.
</P>
<P>
   If they lose, the Raptors will immediately have to turn their
attention to what would be a far more devastating defeat, the
potential free-agent defection of Tracy McGrady. ``He's in a
position to make a lot of money,'' said Marcus Camby, who played
one season in Toronto with McGrady, then right out of high school.
``I'm happy for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Money is one thing. Attention is another. David Stern cannot be
pleased that McGrady will soon have the unencumbered right to cash
in his Canadian currency, to instantly become the generic go-to guy
in Orlando or Chicago. Without McGrady, Carter's cousin, his
Scottie Pippen, the Raptors would become Carter and the nonspeaking
cast of Jurassic Park, at least until Carter figures out a way back
to the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Try to ignore all the network blather about the baby Raptors,
who are in the NBA playoffs for the first time during their
five-year history. Charles Oakley is not young, and nor are Antonio
Davis, Dell Curry, Kevin Willis, Muggsy Bogues, Dee Brown and, for
that matter, Doug Christie. If Toronto has a future, it is because
fate brought them Carter and McGrady, who, physically and
stylistically, are about as close as you get to Jordan and Pippen,
without cloning.
</P>
<P>
   Asked the other day who McGrady most reminds him of, Jeff Van
Gundy paused fairly ponderously between ``You could easily'' and
``compare him to a Pippen.'' No coach and astute basketball mind
wants to make the cheap Next Jordan or Next Anyone comparison those
of us in the news media and in the league's overzealous marketing
department are so good at. Van Gundy couldn't help it, though,
after watching the 6-foot-8-inch McGrady do terrible things to
Allan Houston and the Knicks in the Raptors' home-court blowouts of
the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the wingspan,'' Van Gundy said, ``and the ability to
have a dramatic impact on the game, and he doesn't have to have the
ball. People don't realize that he is the premier perimeter shot
blocker in the league, and he may be the premier perimeter defender
in the league. When you find a guy who doesn't have to have the
ball to have an impact, then you have a unique player.''
</P>
<P>
   The Raptors had another such player, but they traded him to the
Knicks for an older, more earthbound model. That's a different
story entirely, but the reality is that without Camby and his
unique wingspan, the Knicks' frontline is as creaky and
unimaginative as Toronto's.
</P>
<P>
   Remember how Indiana's Davises were going to dominate the Knicks
last spring in the conference final? Van Gundy had better hope that
Camby is healthy enough to again torment Antonio Davis, now manning
Toronto's middle, as well as Miami and Indiana, or whomever comes
next. The playoffs are all about improvisation, the element of
surprise. With all due respect to Patrick Ewing, Camby is as
central to the Knicks' championship hopes as McGrady is to Carter's
future in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   David Stern's minions just couldn't stop from getting way ahead
of themselves, from panicking over the regular-season ratings
plunge and rushing Carter into America's living rooms. The strategy
was short-sighted, begetting what could be a classic double
negative. What message will the public have received when Carter is
gone by the first week in May and what missive has McGrady possibly
rejected with regards to his own 20-year-old's ego?
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit A, of course, was the former can't-miss tandem of
Stephon Marbury and Kevin Garnett, the Next Stockton and Malone.
Marbury leveraged his way out of Minnesota as soon as he realized
whose team that was, and always would be.
</P>
<P>
   It took Jordan and Pippen several years to become what they
finally were, to realize how much they needed each other to survive
the daunting playoff wars. Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant seem to
have finally figured it out, with a little help from Phil Jackson.
The Knicks, a team with no players among the leaders in most
statistical categories, at least know what these tension-filled
games are about. The Raptors, cast in the mold of the modern NBA,
will soon find out.
</P>
<P>
   Check your personal agendas at the door, or lose.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 1602EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
