<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4376 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ELIAN-REUNION-0423-CO     04-22 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-REUNION-0423-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ELIAN, JUAN MIGUEL REUNITED AT ANDREWS AFB
 &HT;    With CUBA-ELIAN-0423.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANDREWS AIR FORCE BASE, Md. - After five months of separation,
young Elian Gonzalez was reunited Saturday morning with his father,
Juan Miguel, at this closed air force base outside Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Delivered here about 9:20 a.m. EST on a government plane after
being forcefully removed from his Miami relatives' home four hours
earlier, Elian spent the day in private on the base with his
father, step-mother, Nersy, and baby brother, Hianny.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Miguel Gonzalez's lawyer, Gregory Craig, praised U.S.
Attorney General Janet Reno for going the ``extra mile'' to get the
boy and his family together. In a telephone interview aired on CNN,
Craig said Elian appeared relaxed and happy in his father's arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was totally at ease,'' Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   A photograph taken by U.S. Marshals released showed a smiling
Elian being held by his beaming father and surrounded by Nersy and
baby Hianny. A second picture showed Elian again smiling, and
playing with Hianny.
</P>
<P>
   The hordes of media reporters, who were banned from the air
force base, congregated outside the main gate _ along with dozens
of protesters carrying rosaries and Cuban flags.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am incensed . . . that a child could be taken in this way,''
said Ivette Curros, a Cuban-American immigrant and Miami resident
who was in the Washington D.C.-area en route to a convention in
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Curros said she came to the base to protest the federal
government's effort to reunite the boy with his father, who plans
to return to communist Cuba following the current appeals process
in federal courts. ``I thank God every day that my mother risked
her life to come to this country,'' she said, adding that Elian,
whose mother died trying to reach the United States, should not be
returned to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Blazquez, who fled Cuba in 1967 and now lives in the
Washington area, agreed, saying the removal of Elian from the Miami
home was ``a stab in the back'' of the Cuban-American community.
</P>
<P>
   But while perhaps a dozen protesters opposed the government's
action, a roughly equal number supported the father-and-son
reunion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elian is not an orphan; it's not fair to keep him away from
his father,'' said Wanda Davis, a Washington-area resident who
stopped to cheer Elian's return to his father.
</P>
<P>
   She said while the 6-year-old was in Miami, Elian ``was being
used as a political pawn'' by Cuban-Americans. ``Now he is free,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's cousin and primary caregiver, Marisleysis Gonzalez, and
other Miami relatives arrived late Saturday afternoon on an
American Airlines flight into Washington-Reagan National Airport.
They hope to visit with the father and boy at Andrews, where they
are expected to remain sequestered for the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   Andrews Air Force Base, just outside the nation's capital, is
the secured base used for the president's travels.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   Immigration and Naturalization Service: http://www.ins.usdoj.gov
</P>
<P>
   Miami relatives: http://libertyforelian.org
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 1608EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000422.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4377 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ELIAN-RIOTS-0423-COX     04-22 1635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-RIOTS-0423-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MIAMI ERUPTS FOLLOWING FEDERAL GOVERNMENT SEIZURE OF ELIAN
 &HT;    (1200&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With CUBA-ELIAN-0423.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Cuban exiles raged through the streets of Miami's Little
Havana Saturday, burning tires, overturning dumpsters and tangling
with roaming squads of riot-clad police who fired tear gas to quell
the outburst triggered by the pre-dawn removal of Elian Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a terrible day,'' said Nancy Milian, 33, a
Cuban-American who joined the crowd on N.W. 27th Avenue. ``I'm
ashamed to be an American. Clinton is definitely leaving a legacy.
Cubans will never forget this.''
</P>
<P>
   The lightning-strike raid to take the boy caught Miami's exiles
completely by surprise. Reporters estimated that only about 30 to
50 demonstrators were outside the house at 5:10 a.m. EST when
several white mini-vans pulled up to the home on N.W. Second
Street.
</P>
<P>
   A team of about one dozen black-clad officers fired a chemical
gas to disperse the crowd, while eight other officers wearing
helmets, flak jackets and carrying semi-automatic weapons battered
open the door of the house and swept inside. They held lawyers and
family members at gunpoint and snatched the boy from the arms of
one of the fisherman who rescued him at sea last Thanksgiving Day,
witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard Elian screaming in English, 'Help me, help me,''' said
Donato Dalrymple, the fisherman, who was standing in a closet with
the boy. ``I just held his head. My God, America, what did you do
to this boy.''
</P>
<P>
   An Associated Press photographer who had been invited into the
home pointed his camera and captured an image that was flashed
around the world within minutes: an agent wearing goggles, a
helmet, a bullet-proof vest and aiming a semi-automatic black rifle
reached out to Dalrymple to take the boy.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's face wore a look of stark terror.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a white T-shirt and plaid shorts, wrapped partially in a
sheet, the boy was whisked from the home, crying as a female agent
who spoke Spanish carried him to a waiting van. The textbook-like
operation lasted three minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Elian was taken to a waiting helicopter about 10 miles away and
flown to Homestead Air Force Base south of Miami, where a doctor
examined him. By 6 a.m. EST, he was put on board a government jet
and flown to Andrews Air Force Base outside Washington, D.C. He
reportedly played with Play-do and other toys on the flight.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-morning, Elian was reunited with his father, leaving
behind a family devastated by grief and anger and a community
boiling with rage and feelings of betrayal.
</P>
<P>
   Word of the raid spread like wildfire through Little Havana. By
6:30 a.m. EST, several hundred people milled around the house, some
yelling at reporters, others crying. Faces were etched with rage,
dejection and disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no words to express my anger and hurt,'' said Susana
Ruiz, 43, who stood outside the home, her eyes brimming with tears.
``I hurt for this family. I hurt like you wouldn't believe. I can't
believe what they have done. I can't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami police took no part in the raid, although a top-ranking
officer from the department rode in the lead car of the federal
caravan so that local officers would know the action was
legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   Miami Police Chief William O'Brien said he learned of the
impending strike at 4:15 a.m. EST, and for security reasons he told
only a few top assistants. He did not notify Miami Mayor Joe
Carollo, who afterwards lashed out at the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Federal agents went in as if they were assaulting a military
bunker,'' Carollo said. ``This family is decent, law-abiding
people, and they came in with machine guns and gassing people. This
is America. This is not Cuba or Hitler's Nazi Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the morning, Carollo appealed for calm.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien said he did not notify Carollo out of concerns for the
security of the operation. ``I'm a policeman, not a politician,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes after the boy was gone, Miami police began
mobilizing, and quickly set up perimeters around an area of about
40 square blocks. By 8 a.m. EST, roaming crowds of demonstrators
began congregating at major intersections.
</P>
<P>
   By 9 a.m. EST, sporadic outbursts erupted. Along N.W. 27th
Avenue _ also named ``Unity Boulevard'' _ a crowd of about 50
people set fire to a tire at a major intersection. Men tossed heavy
benches with wooden backs and cement legs into the street. They
overturned newspaper boxes and tossed around trash cans, contents
spewing across the pavement.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, a team of riot-clad officers raced to the scene
to reinforce the dozen or so officers stationed at the
intersection. The team rode in unmarked sedans, which screeched to
a halt, all four doors flying open and the officers piling out.
</P>
<P>
   Some carried weapons rigged to fire tear gas. Others carried
cans of the chemical, ready to fling them into the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   One man was in the street, overturning a newspaper box, but ran
as the cars blazed in. An officer chased him down and rolled him to
the ground in a flower bed, pinning him with his knees while
another officer slapped on metal handcuffs.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, the crowd dispersed, most walking south on Unity
Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, small caravans of cars _ apparently from homes
inside the perimeter _ crept down the broad boulevard, horns
blaring, passengers waving Cuban flags and yelling as crowds along
the sidewalks cheered. Police cars whisked up behind the caravans,
lights and sirens blazing, moving them out of the area.
</P>
<P>
   News helicopters hovered overhead, filming everything.
</P>
<P>
   The disturbances seemed unorganized and spontaneous, an
outpouring of emotion. Many people walked peacefully, holding flags
or signs, standing on sidewalks and merely watching.
</P>
<P>
   And most of sprawling Miami-Dade County's 2.5 million residents
went about their normal Saturday business, or stayed in their homes
watching the melee unfold on television. Outside Little Havana,
businesses were open and traffic moved normally.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   The city's Miami Heat professional basketball team held their
first play-off game at the downtown American Airlines arena,
tipping off at 12:30 p.m. EST as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Three miles away in Little Havana, chaos roamed in ragged
groups.
</P>
<P>
   The outbursts were unpredictable, flaring up all through the
long, hot day.
</P>
<P>
   Around 10:30 a.m. EST, the crowd at N.W. 27th Avenue and Flagler
Street was calmly standing on the four corners of the intersection
as about 20 police milled around in the middle of the street. A
woman driving a red car stopped in the intersection, opened her
door, stepped out and began yelling at the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   A policeman walked over and ordered her back into the car.
Within seconds, dozens of protestors surrounded the car, screaming,
``Let her go, let her go.''
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of officers with plastic shields and nightsticks rushed
to the group. A tall officer grabbed a man in a green shirt who was
screaming and flailing his arms. The crowd surged. People started
running, some being shoved around by the jostling crowd. Two
teen-aged girls cried and screamed as officers brushed them out of
the way.
</P>
<P>
   A woman on one of the corners threw part of a broken broomstick
in the general direction of the officers and was immediately
wrestled to the ground and handcuffed by four men wearing helmets.
Several officers ran to their cars for gas canisters, while others
with plastic shields formed a line and began pushing the crowd
back.
</P>
<P>
   In the street, officers jammed several men to the ground,
mashing them into the pavement, twisting their arms and cuffing
their wrists. One man was led away with angry red scraps on his
forehead. Sweating and heaving for breath in the hot sun, he was
led to an old school bus painted white and stenciled with the
words, ``Miami Police.''
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, the bus was filled with detainees. The windows
were covered with heavy metal mesh. The people inside stamped their
feet and rocked the bus.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   There were no immediate reports on the number of people arrested
or how many police or demonstrators suffered injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Fire trucks roamed the area, extinguishing the tires that
protestors set ablaze in the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Black smoke roiled into the sky, followed at times by clouds of
choking gas fired as officers moved from one hot-spot to the next.
</P>
<P>
   Protestors threw rocks and bottles at police and media crews.
Roaming demonstrators smashed the windows of one television truck.
</P>
<P>
   Two men ran down Unity Boulevard, carrying a large U.S. flag
turned upside down, the Stars and Stripes dragging the pavement.
Two women carried an American flag tied at the center with a black
band.
</P>
<P>
   A woman stood off to one side as officers moved toward a large
clump of protestors, holding a bright green sign emblazoned with
one word: ``Nazis.''
</P>
<P>
   Another woman yelled ``assesinos'' _ ``assassins.'' A man ran up
to a reporter, grabbed his shirt and screamed into his face: ``You
better write the truth. You better write that this was murder here
today what you saw.''
</P>
<P>
   And everywhere, people carried copies of the famous photograph
snapped before dawn as the riot-clad, gun-totting federal agent
reached out for Elian.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no need for this,'' said Hope Kahn, who saw the
photograph for the first time as she stood near Unity Blvd. ``There
was no need to use weapons. He wasn't a drug dealer. He was a
little boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Williams' email address is: mikew(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
