<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4380 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-NJ-ART-NYT &LR;      04-22 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-NJ-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBAN-AMERICAN PROTEST IN NEW JERSEY TIES UP TRAFFIC AT TUNNEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: NYT Photos 3,5,6 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chanting ``Libertad para Elian!'' scores of angry demonstrators
staged a raucous, traffic-blocking march through the Cuban-American
stronghold of Union City, N.J., on Saturday to protest the forcible
removal of Elian Gonzalez from the home of his Miami relatives in a
predawn raid by armed federal agents.
</P>
<P>
   About 70 protesters, clotting a highway intersection, tied up
traffic in and out of the Lincoln Tunnel, one of the transportation
links between New Jersey and New York City, for nearly half an hour
shortly after noon, and slowed traffic on nearby John F. Kennedy
Boulevard to a trickle. Hundreds of car horns blared, but _ judging
by Cuban flags waving out windows _ there seemed to be as many
sympathizers in the chorus as drivers angered by the delays.
</P>
<P>
   Enraged by televised images of agents in riot gear waving an
assault rifle in front of the boy and carrying him away as he
sobbed for help, protesters denounced President Clinton and
Attorney General Janet Reno, calling them tools of President Fidel
Castro and likening the raid to the tactics of a dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are here to reaffirm the value of a single human life, of a
6-year-old child who has in fact not received a full hearing in a
competent court of law,'' Lazaro Alvarez, a human rights and
anti-Castro activist, shouted as protesters in the nation's
second-largest Cuban-American community waved flags and banners,
honked horns and voiced dismay over the sudden turn of events.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after Elian was seized and flown to a reunion with his
father near Washington, political leaders in New Jersey joined
protesters in expressing disgust and resentment over the Clinton
administration's decision to use force in the midst of negotiations
to resolve an international custody battle that has been under way
for nearly five months.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Robert Menendez, a Union City Democrat who has been
involved in the negotiations, called the raid ``a despicable use of
the force of the federal government against a humble, unarmed and
law-abiding family, who had only one interest: Elian's future and
his best interests as a child.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Menendez, a Cuban-American and a frequent
critic of the Castro government, said: ``It's really a day of
infamy. To take a child out at gunpoint, awakened from his sleep in
the dark of night by masked agents, reminds us of the tactics of
the Castro dictatorship, not of the democracy we enjoy in the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Reno, Menendez said: ``Now that she has made this
decision to use the full force of the federal government to uphold
the father's rights, I hope she's going to use the full force of
the government to uphold the boy's rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The protesters, Cuban-Americans and recent Cuban immigrants,
began gathering in a light rain at about 10:30 a.m. at Bergenline
Avenue and 41st Street, the main intersection in Union City, which
for decades has been a center of Cuban-American life in the
metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   A few were wrapped in Cuban flags. Some held American flags
upside down. Others held banners proclaiming ``First Waco, Now
Elian,'' and ``Reno-Clinton-Gore, you can celebrate with your
friend Castro.'' They blocked traffic, sang the Cuban national
anthem and chanted ``Liberty for Elian.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Frontela, who lives in North Bergen, N.J., and came to
the United States six years ago from Santa Clara, Cuba, was angry
and sad. ``Fidel Castro bought Bill Clinton and Janet Reno,'' he
said. He said he had heard Clinton on the radio, addressing the
nation after the raid, and said: ``The Bill Clinton who was
speaking today was Fidel Castro.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before noon, the demonstrators left the center of Union
City, and marched south on Kennedy Boulevard, snarling traffic in
the four northbound and southbound lanes. As car horns blared,
Cuban flags appeared out the windows of many cars, and it appeared
that as many drivers were sympathetic to the demonstrators as not.
</P>
<P>
   But when the protesters reached the intersection of Interstate
495, the main highway feeding traffic into and out of the Lincoln
Tunnel, the sympathy evaporated and for nearly half an hour,
traffic was stalled and drivers were clearly angry. The police did
nothing to break up the protest, however, and the demonstrators
dissolved the clot voluntarily and returned to downtown Union City
without further incident.
</P>
</TEXT>
