</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
  
 JETS WOULD WANT RICE IF 49ers DO NOT KEEP HIM  
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a great debate within the San Francisco 49ers
organization _ to keep Jerry Rice or not to keep him. Depending on
whom you talk to on the team, the 49ers either want to cut Rice
after June 1 to save valuable salary-cap room, or have Rice take a
dramatic pay cut so he can stay one more season and then retire as
a 49er.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco will most likely try to figure out a way to keep
Rice. It would be a major embarrassment to the team, and to the
league, if Rice played in a uniform other than the 49ers. Still,
there is a chance it might not be worked out. If that happens,
would Rice be willing to play for another team? And will other
teams be interested in signing Rice?
</P>
<P>
   The answers are yes and yes, and one of the teams that might
take a hard look at Rice, should he become available, is the New
York Jets, a team that, like the 49ers, is battling its own
salary-cap problems.
</P>
<P>
   A Jets team official said his team would examine the possibility
of signing Rice to a short-term deal if the 49ers discard him.
Again, chances are the Jets will not get the opportunity to sign
him, because Rice wants to work something out with San Francisco.
``He wants to stay with the 49ers,'' his agent, Jim Steiner, said.
``It's just a matter of working out the numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   And if the 49ers and Rice cannot reach an agreement to
renegotiate Rice's contract, would he play elsewhere? ``Jerry
believes he still has good years left in him,'' Steiner said. Would
Rice consider retiring? ``That is definitely not in his plans right
now,'' Steiner said.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins may also want to sign Rice, and another impediment
to Rice joining the Jets is the Jets' interest in Carl Pickens, the
Cincinnati Bengals wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets are not allowed to publicly comment on another player
under contract, as Rice is. But make no mistake: if Rice is
available after June 1, and the Jets have not signed Pickens, they
will definitely take a long look at the player many consider the
greatest receiver in history.
</P>
<P>
   Teams know Rice is no longer the player he once was. At 37, he
cannot separate from defensive backs because he has lost the burst
that once made him among the most feared offensive players in
history. But despite age and knee surgeries, he can still be quite
effective. On a bad team last season, with a terrible quarterback
and offensive line, Rice still led the 49ers in catches (67), yards
receiving (830) and touchdowns (5).
</P>
<P>
   The Jets think Rice could jump-start his career with them the
same way quarterback Vinny Testaverde and linebacker Bryan Cox did.
Remember, there was a time when many in the NFL thought Testaverde
and Cox were finished as players, but both were invaluable to the
Jets when the team was one victory from the Super Bowl two seasons
ago. And the Jets have precedent in terms of snagging longtime
great 49ers. The Hall of Famer Ronnie Lott left San Francisco to
join the Jets for the last few years of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Rice is under contract until 2004, and next season has a $5.49
million salary-cap number. The 49ers have maintained they will not
keep Rice unless he drastically reduces that figure. Last week Rice
and general manager Bill Walsh met privately, and Walsh has
expressed optimism that Rice would remain with the team. However,
others in the organization are not so sure.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers and Jets both have salary-cap problems, the main
reason the Jets let Johnson go to the Bucs.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Jets were $3.5 million under the $62.172 million
cap. But that cap room is an illusion. It will take about $6
million to sign their draft picks, so the team will have to do some
serious renegotiating of veterans' contracts just to bring their
picks into the fold. Such renegotiations are believed to already be
under way, and will continue in the summer, especially after June
1, when the Jets can cut players without serious salary-cap
ramifications.
</P>
<P>
   Worse yet, by 2002, Testaverde and running back Curtis Martin
will count $20.4 million against the cap, and defensive back Ray
Mickens is scheduled to earn $5.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   So, unless those contracts are restructured, the Jets will have
three players counting for more than $25 million against the cap.
That is an intolerable situation. And if the Jets had signed
Johnson, it would have been a total salary-cap crisis.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that the Jets' four first-round draft picks will earn
combined signing bonuses of around $13 million, the same bonus
Johnson received from the Buccaneers. The difference is that the
Jets are paying that amount to four players, not one. That is the
trend many teams, like the Giants, are following _ staying away
from paying a handful of players the bulk of the salary-cap money,
and spreading it out more sensibly.
</P>
<P>
   If San Francisco lets Rice go, the Jets could sign him
relatively cheaply. Maybe he has enough left _ just enough _ to
help fans forget about Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Marketing Kearse
</P>
<P>
   The Tennessee defensive lineman Jevon Kearse, last season's
defensive rookie of the year, is finding out just how busy, and
financially rewarding, stardom can be.
</P>
<P>
   There are now massive demands for his time, some because of the
marketing deals he is signing. Kearse is shooting Reebok
commercials, has been approached about a Kearse sports drink, and
even his own mustard.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Kearse, nicknamed ``The Freak'' because of his
dazzling physical skills, shied away from endorsement deals, mainly
because he wanted to focus on football. Now, thanks to his agent,
Leigh Steinberg, Kearse is going to cash in on his great year, one
that included a Super Bowl appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Kearse will most likely earn millions of dollars in future
endorsements. The real challenge for Kearse in the face of all this
newfound popularity and money will be to do what he did last season
_ stay focused.
</P>
<P>
   Beathard's Legacy
</P>
<P>
   It could be only a matter of months, maybe weeks, before Bobby
Beathard, San Diego's general manager, retires from football.
</P>
<P>
   There was no better evaluator of talent than Beathard when he
was with the Washington Redskins and helped to build the franchise
that dominated the National Football Conference East in the late
1980s and early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   But his reputation will be tarnished by his disastrous draft
picks as general manager of the Chargers. One of the worst in NFL
history was Beathard's selection of quarterback Ryan Leaf as their
No. 1 pick in the 1998 draft. It is possible Leaf could turn his
career around, but so far he has proved to be lazy and immature, to
the point where his own teammates are publicly calling him a baby. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 1616EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000422.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4387 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-BOOKS-BIOGRAPHIES0423     04-22 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-BIOGRAPHIES0423-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What's new in biography, autobiography and memoir
 &HT;    Compiled by Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   M A Y
</P>
<P>
   _ Life So Far: A Memoir. By Betty Friedan. Simon &AMP; Schuster.
$26. In her own words, her singular story of the lonely child and
unhappy housewife who went on to write the landmark ``The Feminine
Mystique'' and help found the National Organization for Women _
including details of dirty tricks and political infighting within
the women's movement.
</P>
<P>
   _ American Pharaoh: Richard J. Daley and His Battle for Chicago
and the Nation. By Adam Cohen and Elizabeth Taylor. Little, Brown &AMP;
Co. $26.95. The enthralling saga of the mayor who ruled Chicago
with an iron fist for more than 20 years, who proved the maxim
``all politics is local'' by perfecting the use of the Democratic
machine to help elect, among others, President John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Measure of a Man: A Spiritual Auto-biography. By Sidney
Poitier. HarperSanFrancisco. $26. A thematic, rather than strictly
chronological recounting of a life that began in poverty in the
Bahamas and includes an Oscar for ``Lilies of the Field.'' From Jim
Crow to morality, Poitier looks at themes that helped shape that
life.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rosa Parks. By Douglas Brinkley. Lipper/Viking's Penguin
Lives. $19.95. A fresh look at the Alabama seamstress whose 1955
refusal to give up her seat on a segregated bus thrust her and the
civil rights movement center stage. Who was Parks before and after
this seminal moment?
</P>
<P>
   _ Herman Melville. By Elizabeth Hardwick. Lipper/Viking's
Penguin Lives. $19.95. One novel established Melville in America's
literary pantheon. A century after his death, Hardwick studies the
master.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Leap: A Memoir of Love and Madness in the Internet Gold
Rush. By Tom Ashbrook. Houghton Mifflin. $25. An award-winning
reporter chucks it all to join a friend in an Internet start-up
venture _ lacking much in the way of technical knowledge or money.
In the process, he rediscovers his family and himself.
</P>
<P>
   _ Experience: A Memoir. By Martin Amis. Talk Miramax Books.
$23.95. The famous-novelist son (``Heavy Water,'' ``London
Fields'') of a famous novelist (Kingsley Amis) writes candidly
about his life.
</P>
<P>
   J U N E
</P>
<P>
   _ Groucho: The Life and Times of Julius Henry Marx. By Stefan
Kanfer. Knopf. $30. From childhood in turn-of-the-century New York
to Hollywood's biggest star with his brothers, then decline and
then resurrection with ``You Bet Your Life.'' Shows the legendary
comic's impact on everything from ``MASH'' to ``Seinfeld,'' but
also delves into the complex personal life behind the jokes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Me and Hank: A Boy and His Hero, 25 Years Later. By Sandy
Tolan. Free Press. $23. As a boy, the author _ who is white _ wrote
letters to Henry Aaron and kept a scrapbook of Hammerin' Hank's
pursuit of Babe Ruth's record, never realizing how racism stalked
the Atlanta superstar. A story of childhood dreams, prejudice in
baseball and the two men's meeting a quarter-century later.
</P>
<P>
   _ Miriam's Song: A Memoir. By Miriam Mathabane as told to Mark
Mathabane. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $25. The acclaimed author of ``Kaffir
Boy'' tells the story of his sister, who grew up with him in
apartheid-era South Africa _ and then stayed behind when the family
moved to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   _ Susan Sontag: The Making of an Icon. By Carl Rollyson and Lisa
Paddock. W.W. Norton. $29.95. The first _ and unauthorized _
biography of the enigmatic intellectual, author of ``The Volcano
Lover.''
</P>
<P>
   J U L Y
</P>
<P>
   _ The Black Rose: The Magnificent Story of Madame C.J. Walker,
America's First Black Female Millionaire. By Tananarive Due.
Ballantine. $25.95. Born to former slaves on a Louisiana plantation
in 1867, Madame C.J. Walker founded a successful line of hair-care
products and became a leading philanthropist in African-American
causes.
</P>
<P>
   _ William Shakespeare: The Man Behind the Genius. By Anthony
Holden. Little, Brown. $29.95. Yes, another bio of the Bard, though
this one promises to be a bit less reverent (the illegal training
to be a Catholic priest, the bad acting stint) and to ``prove or
puncture'' all rumors, including why Shakespeare stopped writing.
Or did he?
</P>
<P>
   _ Can't You Hear Me Callin': The Life of Bill Monroe, Father of
Bluegrass. By Richard D. Smith. Little, Brown. $25.95. The man with
the mandolin is widely credited with creating the high, lonesome
sound of the distinctive American genre. A shy Kentucky boy, he
later was a Grand Ole Opry star and womanizer.
</P>
<P>
   A U G U S T
</P>
<P>
   _ The Gentleman From New York: Daniel Patrick Moynihan. By
Godfrey Hodgson. Houghton Mifflin. $35. In danger of being
remembered, at least temporarily, as the holder of the Senate seat
both Rudy Guiliani and Hillary Rodham Clinton wanted, Moynihan was
ambassador to India and the United Nations, and a social thinker
who hewed neither strictly liberal nor conservative. Written with
full access to Moynihan and his papers.
</P>
<P>
   S E P T E M B E R
</P>
<P>
   _ The Trumps: Three Generations That Built an Empire. By Gwenda
Blair. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $26. Meet the family whose entrepreneurial
savvy grew up with America's _ from the immigrant Friedrich who ran
a saloon and brothel during the Klondike gold rush, to son Fred,
whose real estate empire benefited from New Deal housing subsidies.
And then came Donald, one of the first Americans to realize he
could leverage his name and fame into even more wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
