<DOCNO> NYT20000422.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4390 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NY     04-22 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: AT 32, SCHUTZ STAYS DRIVEN BY HER JUDO 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Please note that the word AT within parentheses has been
used in the 12th graf instead of the symbol, which is
non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I don't know which side of the world I'm on,'' said
Celita Shutz, a 32-year-old Olympic judo player, cheerfully. ``So,
I sleep when I sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   No. 5 in the world, No. 1 in our hearts, Schutz is still out
there throwing people, 26 years after wandering into a New Jersey
dojo with a vague plan of learning how to trip her older brother.
She's still training there, but now her credit cards are maxed and
she is waiting for the U.S. Olympic Committee to reimburse her
travel expenses to international meets. That and the $500 a month
she receives from the national judo federation help with the
$35,000 a year she and her husband spend on her sport.
</P>
<P>
   She may be the last of the amateur athletes, although she hates
the word and its dilettantish implications; this woman consults
with two judo teachers, a psychologist, an orthopedic surgeon, a
physical therapist and a nutritionist. She hawks her poster,
T-shirt and autographed photo on her Web site. But she buys her own
New Balance running shoes. She canceled her ``elite athlete''
health card from the Olympic Committee because the taxes were
higher than the benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could we talk about the bright side?'' she said. ``Last month,
I got a call from a company in Canada, Toraki, and they offered to
make me free gi's. We're into sizing and tailoring right now.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Atlanta Olympics, where she was captain of the American
team, and at all the national and international tournaments since
then, Schutz had been wearing off-the-rack judo uniforms, or gi's.
Does she ever think she should have stayed with basketball or
soccer, which she played at Yale? ``I try to focus on positive
aspects,'' she said in her precise way. ``Better things will happen
if I produce results. The best thing is to concentrate on my own
improvement and not let other things distract me. Worrying about
the past and future is unproductive.''
</P>
<P>
   But isn't that how athletes get into trouble, stuffing down
emotions?
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not say stuffing down, let's say bouncing off,'' she
said, laughing. ``Between now and Sydney, when I wig out, I'll have
people there for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Schutz lost her only Olympic match in 1996, at 134 pounds (61
kilos). The USOC's female athlete of the year in judo the past two
years, she qualified for this team by placing fifth in the world
championships last October. After a realignment of weight classes,
she will be competing at 139 pounds (63k), a popular middleweight
division. She thinks she is stronger, better conditioned, more
technically competent now, smarter and, because of the Olympic
team's head coach Steve Cohen, better prepared; he's made sure, she
said, that team members see videos of potential opponents.
</P>
<P>
   One reason you've been hearing about Schutz now and then for the
past four years in this space is my fascination with her drive.
Bright, lively and open, she is also remarkably focused. At 12,
then a national junior champion, she was advised to quit after an
operation to try to stop the progression of Osgood-Schlatter's
disease, an inflammation in the knee joint.
</P>
<P>
   At 27, she shattered her leg in a tournament six months before
the Atlanta Olympic trials. Four years ago, she was accidentally
butted in training, and her forehead split open. Coincidentally
there, I drove her to the hospital. She seemed faintly bored by the
stitching process, relieved when she decided it wasn't going to
interfere with her weight-lifting program.
</P>
<P>
   Like many artists, elite athletes tend to be un-self-conscious
about their passion, their dedication and their sense of
entitlement. Be it a grant from a tax-exempt cultural foundation or
a stipend from a tax-exempt national sports body, the
artist/athlete thinks support is an appropriate response from a
grateful nation for talent and sacrifice. And maybe it is.
</P>
<P>
   Now that we have easy-mail (write to me at
thelipsite(AT)aol.com), there is no reason not to discuss this.
Beyond the obvious hypocrisies of student-athletes, the Dream Team
syndrome and role-model merchandising, all sitting ducks, what
about these hard-working true amateurs? Should they be supported?
By us? Isn't that the market's job? If they love it so much,
shouldn't they just get day jobs and shut up, the way so many
composers, writers and painters do? Or do athletes deserve more? Do
they give us more?
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, your response to thelipsite has been gratifying,
smart and more than I can handle quickly. I'll try to answer as
many as I can, but meanwhile, thanks for the fresh and thoughtful
insights, which you can be sure will inform the column.
</P>
<P>
   Recent messages have concentrated on attacking the NCAA, making
jokes about testosterone and shouting ``Racism!'' in a crowded
arena. Several readers think that coach John Thompson should not be
in the same uncomplimentary paragraph with Bob Knight and Jerry
Tarkanian because he is an educator and they are not. They think I
should apologize to Thompson and that I included him because he is
black.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, now retired, with his sneaker contracts and his
complicity in the perversion of higher education (which, truth be
told, does a good job of perverting itself even without sports), is
as much at fault as any of the white coaches _ Knight, Tarkanian,
Paterno, Coach K _ who have now and again operated teams that field
winning universities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
