<DOCNO> NYT20000422.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4393 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ELIAN-SEIZED-0423-COX     04-22 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-SEIZED-0423-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE FINAL HOURS BEFORE TAKING OF ELIAN THE MOST RIVETING
 &HT;    With CUBA-ELIAN-0423.
 &HT;    Moving in both International and Washington categories.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno had allowed
deadline after deadline to slip away in her attempts to reunite
6-year-old Elian Gonzalez with his Cuban father. At 4:00 Saturday
morning, as she polled her top aides around the long table in her
Department of Justice conference room after hours of fruitless
negotiations, Reno's patience was at last exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, she authorized a team of more than 130 armed
federal officials to pluck the youngster out of the modest home of
his Miami relatives who had been caring for him for nearly five
months and bring him to his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Here is how the final hours unfolded:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Friday 4:45 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Reno confers with President Clinton on the latest chapter in the
talks with Elian's great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez about handing over
the boy. The Miami family has faxed a final offer, which demands
that the father come to the Miami-Dade County- area and stay there
indefinitely while the two families reunited under the watchful eye
of an expert ``facilitator.'' That plan is nixed by federal
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Reno tells Clinton that she is continuing to talk with
intermediaries, including Miami attorney Aaron Podhurst, who are
offering new ideas for solutions.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Friday 8:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Just before joining visiting family members for a Good Friday
dinner, Clinton is given an update by Reno by telephone. White
House chief of staff John Podesta is assigned to monitors events
through the night.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Saturday 2:15 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Podesta calls Clinton with a somewhat hopeful report that, ``the
parties were continuing to try to work out a voluntary transfer of
custody,'' according to White House press secretary Joe Lockhart.
But Podesta tells the president that if talks break down, Reno is
prepared to send in her SWAT team. Clinton approves the approach.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Saturday 4:00 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   With Elian asleep in a bedroom, lawyers and others gather in the
living room of the Gonzalez home and continue the talks with
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Reno goes around the table and asks for the views
of her top assistants. She holds out until the last minute, but
after seeing the talks go nowhere, the attorney general tells the
Miami household that their time has run out. She gives the go-ahead
for the law enforcement team.
</P>
<P>
   From Miami, Podhurst and the other negotiators call back to
attempt one last counter-offer, and Reno continues to talk, even as
outside the home the law enforcement team is already in action.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Saturday 5:15 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Arrayed in combat gear with black helmets, visors and automatic
rifles, eight agents of the Immigration and Naturalization Service
pry open the Gonzales door, burst into the house and find Elian
inside a closet in the arms of Donato Dalrymple, one of the
fishermen who rescued him off the Florida coast.
</P>
<P>
   As the SWAT team moves in, an Associated Press photographer
climbs over the fence and enters the house in time to photograph an
agent, his rifle in hand, reaching for the boy. ``What's happening?
What's happening?'' the photographer hears Elian ask in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   A female INS agent, without a helmet or visible weapon, then
takes Elian and rushes him out of the house and into a waiting
unmarked white van. The bilingual agent has rehearsed her script,
which was prepared by experts. ``This may seem very scary right
now, but it will soon be better,'' goes her message, delivered in
Spanish. ``We're taking you to see your papa ...You will not be
going back to Cuba. You will not be on a boat. You are around
people who care for you. We are going to take care of you. Please
don't be frightened.''
</P>
<P>
   In three minutes, the agents are out of the house and clearing
the way with pepper gas to allow Elian's motorcade to drive away
from the startled gathering of protestors. Elian is driven to
Watson Island and flown by helicopter to Homestead Air Force Base,
where he receives a brief physical and is pronounced unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Saturday, shortly before 6 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Reno telephones Clinton to inform him of the action and he
expresses ``satisfaction over the manner in which it had been
carried out,'' according to Reno.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Saturday 7 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by a child psychiatrist and a flight surgeon, both
of them bilingual, Elian flies toward Andrews Air Force Base, in
the Maryland suburbs of Washington. On board he has a play pack
including Play-Dough, a map with a toy airplane and food. He spends
part of the trip speaking by phone to his father, who had been
notified just as the federal officials were breaking into the
house.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami's Little Havana, rowdy crowds briefly gather at
intersections, push garbage dumpsters into the street and set tires
afire. Police quickly disperse the crowds.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Saturday 7:50 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, Reno defends her decision to take Elian by
force in the dark, despite earlier promises not to do so. ``Earlier
we had hoped that the matter could be worked out, that it could be
done in an appropriate way. Then the crowds began to suggest that
they were going to prevent it from happening,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us give him and his father the space, the calm, the moral
support they need to reconnect and reaffirm their bond between
father and son,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Saturday 9:20 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's plane arrives at Andrews Air Force base where he is
reunited with his dad, his stepmother and his infant half-brother,
out of view of TV cameras and reporters.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Saturday 10:20 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton meets briefly with reporters outside the White
House. ``The law has been upheld, and that was the right thing to
do,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Saturday 1:20 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Miguel Gonzalez's lawyer Greg Craig releases photos showing
a happy reunion of Elian at Andrews Air Force Base, where the
family is expected to stay one or two nights before moving to an
undisclosed place in the Washington area to await the final court
rulings on his case.
</P>
<P>
   (Julia Malone's email address is: juliam(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
