<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, April 23, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Overcast, cool conditions will linger over most of the Northeast
as the center of sprawling low pressure drifts east near the south
coast of New England. Steady rain will fall from the central Hudson
River Valley through much of New England.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, scattered showers and drizzle will dampen areas
near the central Appalachians. Clouds will gradually break east of
the Appalachians in the Middle Atlantic States as breezes from the
northwest are dried on descent from the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of showers and some potent thunderstorms will surround
low pressure moving east across the southern Plains. Strong
shifting winds will impart rotation to some of the storms,
heightening the risk of a few twisters from eastern Texas and
Oklahoma to the southern Mississippi Valley. Meanwhile, clouds and
showers will cling to the east slopes of the central and northern
Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Virginia Hail
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of reports of large hail, some almost 2 inches in
diameter, in Virginia were made on Friday. The outbreak of severe
weather was associated with a low-pressure system that moved slowly
east from the Ohio Valley. Ahead of the low, some humid air near
the ground provided fuel for thunderstorms. Strong updrafts in the
thunderstorms suspended tiny balls of ice in the cold upper
atmosphere. The balls of ice gathered minute unfrozen water
droplets and grew into large hailstones that pelted the landscape.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
