<HEADER>
A4402 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-POLITICIANS     04-22 0392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-POLITICIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH FAULTS U.S. DECISION TO USE FORCE TO TAKE BOY 
</HEADLINE>
   By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In harsh language laced with outrage, Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas criticized the Clinton administration for its
decision to use force when it transferred custody of 6-year-old
Elian Gonzalez to his father early Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the photograph of the frightened boy being ``removed
from his home at gunpoint'' was ``chilling'' and ``not an image a
freedom-loving nation wants to show the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of the 5 a.m. raid Saturday, Bush, the presumptive
Republican nominee for president, seized on the government's
decision to use force to remove Elian from the house in the Little
Havana section of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am profoundly saddened and troubled that the administration
was not able to negotiate a resolution, and instead decided to use
force to take a little boy from the place he calls home in the
middle of the night,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief statement that avoided any mention of Saturday's
raid, Vice President Al Gore continued to distance himself from the
administration's handling of the 5-month-old custody case.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I have said, I believe this issue should have been handled
through a family court and with the family coming together,'' Gore
said.
</P>
<P>
   Other senior Republicans also condemned the action. So did Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani of New York, who is running for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Republican congressional leaders condemned the government's
action as heavy-handed, with the Senate majority leader, Trent
Lott, R-Miss., saying, ``My first thought was that this could only
happen in Castro's Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   Some law-enforcement officials said they also felt the raid was
heavy-handed. But others said the raid was successful, particularly
since no one was seriously injured and the federal agents were able
to move in and out quickly in what could have been a volatile
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was entirely appropriate,'' said John P. Julian, a
private investigator and a former Miami police officer who has
participated in raids. ``When you enter a home under these kinds of
circumstances, you have to expect, and be prepared for, the
absolute worst. You don't know what is inside that house. You don't
know what the reaction will be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 1703EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000422.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4403 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-POLICE-SHOOTING-NY     04-22 0391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE KILL MAN WHO THEY SAY ATTACKED HIS MOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Police officers shot and killed a 43-year-old man in
Queens on Saturday after he attacked his elderly mother and
threatened the officers with a knife and a gun, police officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Few details were available Saturday afternoon, but the officials
said preliminary reports indicated that the man, whose name was not
released, was shot after officers were called to his 70-year-old
mother's home about 9:30 a.m. A police official said that the man
appeared to be emotionally disturbed.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said the man was taken to Elmhurst Hospital
Center, where he was pronounced dead about 10:30 a.m. His mother,
who had apparently been beaten before the officers arrived, was
taken to St. John's Hospital, where she was in critical condition
Saturday afternoon, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Police Department was criticized after officers
shot and killed a Brooklyn man, Gidone Busch, 31, outside his home
on Aug. 30. The shooting of Busch, who was wielding a hammer and
had been committed to mental-care institutions twice, brought
hundreds of protesters to the streets of the Brooklyn neighborhood
where it occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to defend officers' actions in such situations, police
officials have pointed out that officers are having to quell more
emotionally disturbed people each year at the same time that
shootings by police have declined. In November a state grand jury
in Brooklyn decided not to bring charges against any of the
officers involved in the incident.
</P>
<P>
   But community leaders have asked the U.S. Justice Department to
investigate the case and to examine police policies on handling
emotionally disturbed people.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, at a funeral for a livery cab driver in Queens, the
Rev. Al Sharpton, who is among those who called for a federal
inquiry into police methods after the Busch shooting, said, ``We
are dealing with a rash, an epidemic, we are dealing with a
continued problem of where police policy is going in this city.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We must keep pressure to where the federal government comes
in,'' Sharpton added. ``A large part of the city doesn't believe
the police stories, and that is why we need the federal government
to come in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 1707EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000422.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4405 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-GIANTS-NYT     04-22 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WINNING BALLPARK, BUT A LOSING TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (With BBO-NOTEBOOK) 
By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine Peter and Debby Magowan dressed up for an evening out in
spiffy new tuxedo and gown. They walk out the door and a bus comes
by and splashes muddy water all over them. Magowan's San Francisco
Giants have had mud splashed all over them, including right there
in their new $319 million park.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants have played five games at Pacific Bell Park and lost
all five. Rain, not mud, forced postponement of a sixth game.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants haven't done much better on the road. They entered a
weekend series in Arizona with an overall 4-11 record, worst in the
major leagues, and in last place, an already distant 7 1/2 games
behind the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what's wrong,'' Magowan said. ``We thought it was
the best team we've had since we took over. Everybody expected us
to have an excellent team that would contend. It clearly hasn't
started off that way. There's plenty of time left, but it's a
disappointing start.''
</P>
<P>
   The poor start, which has included a seven-game losing streak,
has been a team effort. ``Everything's been bad,'' Magowan added.
``Defense, pitching, clutch hitting. We found new ways to lose.
It's not been a pretty sight.''
</P>
<P>
   To pronounce a series at the end of the third week of the season
as critical might seem foolish, but the Giants couldn't afford to
fall another three games behind the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't let anybody get too far out there,'' Dusty Baker, the
frustrated manager, said before the series opener Friday. ``That's
why this weekend is so big.''
</P>
<P>
   Magowan added, ``They sweep us in Arizona, we definitely are in
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Trouble, at least in a small dose, averted. The Giants won the
first game, showing signs of life they had seldom exhibited in
previous games. The strongest signs came from three regulars who
hadn't been hitting. Rich Aurilia (.176), Bill Mueller (.205) and
Marvin Benard (.208) combined for seven hits and five runs batted
in.
</P>
<P>
   But other signs remain to be seen. Livan Hernandez, for example,
has had the exact opposite experience that his half-brother has had
with the Yankees. Orlando Hernandez hasn't lost in four starts;
Livan hasn't won. He has a 0-4 record with a 5.61 earned run
average.
</P>
<P>
   The past few seasons Baker was given credit for getting more out
of his players than their talent indicated they were capable of
giving. This season, though, the Giants and others thought they had
a legitimate contender. The raised expectations have made the poor
start more difficult to accept. But poor it has been.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a period where whatever can go bad is going bad,''
Baker said. ``It's the toughest thing I've been through in a few
years. You blow a couple games, then you feel a little pressure and
guys start pressing. They want to do it all themselves. It starts
feeding on itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: The Giants were down a run to Cincinnati in the
ninth inning last week. Danny Graves had thrown six successive
balls with no one out, and Benard got the take sign for the
reliever's seventh pitch. But he missed the sign, swung and
grounded out. Graves got the next two batters, and the Giants had
lost another one.
</P>
<P>
   Baker was quick to point out that the hitters have failed to do
their jobs as much as the pitchers have even though the pitchers,
whose 5.58 ERA is the second highest in the league, have borne the
brunt of the criticism for the poor start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody talks about our pitching,'' the manager said, ``but
there have been games where we could've blown them open and didn't
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   This was going to be a glorious season for the Giants, the first
in their new home that has received unanimously rave reviews and
will be filled for every game because the Giants have sold 3
million tickets of about 3.1 million available.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be the best of times for the Giants since they moved
to San Francisco,'' Magowan said, ``but I think we have the worst
start since we moved.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' 4-11 record indeed matched the worst 15-game start
in the team's 43 years in San Francisco. The last time it was this
bad was in 1983. Never did the Giants expect to duplicate that
record in the year of their new park, which was built with private
money. Four times voters had rejected the idea of taxpayers' money
funding a replacement for Candlestick Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten reports from virtually everybody that it's the
best park they've ever seen,'' Magowan said. ``Even President
Clinton, who was in the park when the game was rained out last
Sunday.'' But can Clinton pitch?
</P>
<P>
   Magowan said the debt service will cost the Giants about $18
million a year, but the club's revenues will double, from $60
million to $120 million. ``We're ahead of the game,'' the owner
said. Not in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, however, can seek inspiration from an ancestral
team. The last time the Giants began a season worse than 5-11 was
the season that they had a 4-12 record. And when was that? In 1951,
the year the Giants won the pennant, the Giants won the pennant,
the Giants won the pennant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 1716EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000422.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
