<DOCNO> NYT20000422.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4413 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CIVILRIGHTS-ISLAM0423     04-22 1420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIVILRIGHTS-ISLAM0423-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dreaming with the imam
 &HT;    By Jingle Davis and Ernie Suggs
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE HALL, Ala. _ The beauty of spring-green pastures, swampy
woodlands and fields of red clover and wild yellow mustard softens
the poverty-roughened edges of this town of about 1,500.
</P>
<P>
   This is not your ordinary Southern backwater. Major civil rights
battles were fought and won here in White Hall and rural Lowndes
County. White Hall's four churches, each more than a century old,
sheltered thousands of people during the voter registration drives
and freedom marches of the 1960s. Thousands more, including a fiery
activist named H. Rap Brown, camped during those marches in tent
cities near the tiny town, which sits where the Black Belt crosses
the Bible Belt, halfway between Selma and Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   To commemorate the area's significance, the National Park
Service and the Alabama Department of Transportation plan to build
an interpretive center on U.S. 80, a few miles from White Hall's
mobile homes and small houses and enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   But the government's plans seem modest compared with one
envisioned by Brown, now known as Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin, the
Muslim cleric charged in the slaying of a Fulton County deputy and
the wounding of another in Atlanta's West End neighborhood. Four
days after the March 16 shootings, Al-Amin was arrested in this
town where he once helped register black voters.
</P>
<P>
   Before his arrest, Al-Amin, 56, had mapped out a plan for a $47
million rural Islamic complex in White Hall. In his written
proposal on the project, he said the money would come from
``investment funds over a five-year period.'' His proposal also
mentions a plan to build an urban Islamic complex in West End,
where he served for more than two decades as imam, or prayer
leader, at a mosque.
</P>
<P>
   The rural complex in White Hall, designed to occupy 100 acres
near the Alabama River, would include farms, stables, retail
stores, a meat processing and distribution plant, a conference
center with lodging, an exercise facility, a medical center and
pharmacy and even an airstrip, according to the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Sketches of the project show a grouping of buildings around a
large domed mosque flanked by tall minarets. Industrial smokestacks
tower above the trees.
</P>
<P>
   The complex would be surrounded by ``nine well-placed security
cabins,'' the proposal says.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin's followers in White Hall say there is nothing sinister
about the security cabins.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would just be to protect the children and people living
here,'' said Sharif Al-Malik, 53, of Cleveland, who moved here with
his wife and 15-month-old twin daughters about a month ago.
``They'd be like those guardhouses at the entrance of gated
communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Al-Malik's family is one of three who came to White Hall to help
build the rural community proposed by Al-Amin, who served as
spiritual leader of 31 mosques around the country. Now, with
Al-Amin in jail, the Muslims say they still plan to forge ahead
with the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dream has not died; it just may take a little longer,''
said Clarence A. Rasheed, 53, who moved to White Hall with his wife
and 15-year-old stepdaughter from Richmond, Va. about six months
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Rasheed said the idea of a rural Muslim complex appealed to him
because of the difficulties of being a Muslim in a predominantly
Christian culture. And he admired the Islamic community Al-Amin had
built in Atlanta, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the West End, Imam Jamil had people moving in close
proximity to the mosque and building a subculture where people can
look after each other, take care of the children and follow the
teachings of Allah,'' he said. ``We also wanted to get away from
big-city drugs and violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Sahib Al-Salaam, 52, a Marine Corps veteran from Norfolk, Va.,
was the first Muslim to settle in White Hall, coming here three
years ago. He said he and the others came at the invitation of
Mayor John Jackson, White Hall's first black mayor and a longtime
Al-Amin friend. The two worked together registering black voters in
the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Salaam said he hopes Muslims elsewhere in the country will
join them in rural Alabama _ something he believes will happen as
cities deteriorate. ``Once they find out they can't grow corn
through that asphalt, they will see,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin's brother, Ed Brown of Atlanta, said Al-Amin's major
goal in life was to spread the message of Islam around the country.
To do that, Al-Amin planned on building Muslim communities,
spiritually and physically.
</P>
<P>
   ``For him, it made more sense to create a homogeneous community,
more conducive to peaceful living and bringing up families,'' he
said. ``That is part of what his life's work is all about, building
Islam across the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin had followers across the country. Issa Smith, a computer
programmer for a refugee resettlement agency in Reston, Va., is
one. He said he had heard talk among other followers of the
creation of an ideal Muslim community.
</P>
<P>
   Both Smith and the White Hall Muslims said that while Al-Amin
communicated with them through letters, phone calls and visits,
none of them was privy to the details of how the community would be
built or funded.
</P>
<P>
   If the complex, or some semblance of it, is someday built, it
won't be the first of its kind. In rural Putnam County, Ga., an
estimated 500 people are aligned with the Nuwaubian National of
Moors. Based on a 475-acre farm, it is the brainchild of Malachi Z.
York, who moved there in 1993 from Brooklyn N.Y., where his
Muslim-oriented group had been called Ansaru Allah Community. After
numerous conflicts with officials about alleged zoning violations,
the Nuwaubian compound in Putnam County has been put up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   The Muslims in White Hall _ who have no affiliation with the
Nuwaubians _ say they still hope to find investors willing to fund
their complex, but they are struggling financially in the meantime.
Two of the men work nights polishing floors for businesses in
Montgomery. The group has two ice cream trucks, currently being
repaired, that it plans to operate this summer. Rasheed sells
incense, copies of the Koran and other small items from his van.
</P>
<P>
   He and his family live in public housing off Freedom Road, the
two-lane county blacktop that runs north from U.S. 80 into the
heart of White Hall. Al-Malik and his family live in a green frame
building on Freedom Road that houses the one-room mosque and the
Bismillah Cafe, which Al-Malik runs. White Hall's only other small
eatery, housed behind a grocery store directly across Freedom Road,
serves barbecued pork on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   So far, business at the cafe, which features barbecued goat and
goat burgers, fried whiting and a potato dish called mampi-tampies,
has been slow, Al-Malik said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a woman (who) tells people not to eat over here
because we put stuff in our food that will make them Muslims,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Five times a day, Al-Malik stands in front of the cafe, facing
east toward the grocery store and mobile homes, chanting the Muslim
call to prayer in a strong, melodious voice. Sometimes, smoke from
barbecuing pork drifts across the road to the Muslims, who are
forbidden to eat pork.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Salaam said locals are now accustomed to hearing the prayer
call ring out over the quiet woods and wetlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they first heard it, they thought our heads were hurting
or that we were going crazy,'' he said. ``But the White Hall
children started singing it, when they used to laugh and giggle.
Now, the people here are respectful because they know we don't
offer a threat.''
</P>
<P>
   With only three Muslim families in White Hall, making the
population only 11, the possibility of a $47 million community
seems like a distant dream.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff Willie Vaughner said he had never heard anything about
the project. Neither have members of the White Hall City Council,
although the city is listed in the prospectus as a supporter. Mayor
Jackson would not comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't see anybody putting $47 million in Lowndes
County,'' said Vaughner, 50, a lifelong resident of White Hall.
``It would take a long time to get your money back out of a project
like that here.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the White Hall Muslims remain optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not man's way,'' said Al-Malik, playing with his twin
babies. ``This is Allah's way. He will make things right.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
