<HEADER>
A4424 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-GORE-BOS &LR;      04-22 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-GORE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE, BUSH HIT PREDAWN ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore refused Saturday to support
the administration's intervention to return Elian Gonzalez to his
father, instead issuing a brief statement reiterating his view that
the conflict should have been resolved in a family court ``with the
family coming together.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore broke with the administration over Elian weeks ago, and has
weathered heavy criticism for it ever since, with opponents
accusing him of flip-flopping to appease the politically powerful
Cuban-American community in Florida, a state he hopes to carry ih
the presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   But he has hardly been the only politician feeling pressure to
take a stand on the Elian case.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Governor George W. Bush, the presumptive Republican
presidential nominee, issued a statement Saturday criticizing the
show of force and, tying his opponent to the actions in Miami,
blamed the tense events on the ``Clinton-Gore administration''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am profoundly saddened and troubled that the administration
was not able to negotiate a resolution and instead decided to use
force to take a little boy from the place he calls home in the
middle of the night,'' Bush said. ``The chilling picture of a
little boy being removed from his home at gunpoint defies the
values of America and is not an image a freedom loving nation wants
to show the world.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush did not stop there. After Gore released a two-sentence
statement essentially agreeing with Bush _ saying he wished the
matter had been resolved differently, and praising Miami residents
for their generally restrained behavior after the raid, a Bush
spokesman branded the Gore response as strangely bland and
inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It leaves so much out,'' spokesman Ari Fleischer said. ``This
statement lacks any emotion.''
</P>
<P>
   Different politicians chose different targets Saturday: The use
of force, the abrupt timing, the decision to have the Immigration
and Naturalization Service burst into the Miami relatives' home
less than 24 hours before Easter.
</P>
<P>
   US Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, Republican of Mississippi,
took issue with Reno's abandoning unarmed negotiations with the
family, and said his ``first thought was that this could only
happen in Castro's Cuba.'' US House Majority Whip Tom DeLay,
Republican of Texas, issued an apology to ``all Americans who are
morally offended by the Easter weekend police-state-type raid.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will never forget the sound of his pleas of `Help me! Help
me!' '' DeLay said. ``Can this poor child ever recover from a
machine gun waved in his face as he is once again pulled away from
the family he so clearly bonded with?''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the strongest criticism came from Florida Governor Jeb
Bush, a Republican, who said he spoke with President Clinton just
hours before the raid and was ``assured that the intention of his
administration was to resolve this matter in a voluntary,
nonforcible way through negotiated agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush, who is not up for re-election for another two years,
declined to question the need to return Elian to his father. Saying
he was disappointed by the show of force, Bush added: ``I remain
hopeful, however, that the president and his administration will
allow Elian's Miami relatives to see Elian soon and be active
participants in Elian's life during this period of transition.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration action did draw support from some quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who spoke out was Representative J. Joseph Moakley,
Democrat of South Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Patrick J. Leahy, Democrat of Vermont, also voiced
support for the action.
</P>
</TEXT>
