<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CUBAN-BOY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIVID IMAGES AGAIN MAKE MEDIA PART OF THE STORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN AND MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With explosive pictures flooding the airwaves Saturday morning
after federal agents seized 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez, CBS anchor
Dan Rather remarked that the US government ``badly needs'' a
``come-together, reuniting picture'' of Elian and his father, Juan
Miguel Gonzalez, in order to quell tensions in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Within two hours, such a picture had surfaced: a photo of a
smiling Elian in the arms of his father that quickly entered the TV
networks' rotation of compelling images.
</P>
<P>
   Once again Saturday, media coverage of an ongoing news story
became a factor in the drama, and once again, pictures held a
unique power to sway public opinion. The networks, especially the
all-news cable channels, repeatedly aired video footage of a crying
Elian being carried by a federal agent from the home of his Miami
relatives into a waiting van; Fox News Channel ran it in
slow-motion, heightening its emotional impact.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most potent image of the day was an Associated
Press photo of a federal agent pointing a gun in the direction of
the frightened child and Donato Dalrymple, one of the fishermen who
resued Elian last November. By early Saturday afternoon, that photo
appeared on a sign held by a protester, who made sure to stand
behind network correspondents during their standups, creating a
media-mirror effect. Even Gregory Craig, the attorney for Juan
Miguel Gonzalez, conceded that images of Elian's removal may have
``seemed shocking and scary,'' which may explain why Craig moved
quickly to supply the smiling-reunion picture of Elian and his
father to CNN.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, a home video of Elian saying he did not want to
return to Cuba became a weapon in the battle for public opinion. To
the end, both sides in the drama sought to use the media,
especially television, to bolster their case.
</P>
<P>
   After Elian had been removed, his cousin, Marisleysis Gonzalez,
emotionally reenacted the scene for the benefit of TV cameras while
giving a tour of her home to show the damage inflicted by
government agents. On the other side, Craig sent a letter to the
news presidents of the TV networks Friday night, asking that they
refrain from ``exploitative television coverage of the child,''
especially of him being removed from the home.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the networks mobilized quickly to cover the story
Saturday, although ABC's live coverage lagged nearly 45 minutes
behind CBS, CNN, NBC, Fox News Channel, MSNBC, and NECN.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, who was the first of the anchors from the three
broadcast networks to appear Saturday, asked a question that may
reverberate in the days ahead as the media mull their role in the
five-months-long Elian saga: ``Have we overcovered this story?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 1750EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
