<SLUG> BC-OLDWEST-HISTORY0423-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    History of the Old West is a hot topic
 &HT;    By Marla Pierson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ History professor Ty Cashion entered his first
semester of teaching at East Texas State University eager to
present the latest scholarship on the American West.
</P>
<P>
   Students came in expecting cowboys and Indians, Cashion said.
They got women and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   In history books such as the textbook Cashion assigned,
stereotypical Old West icons such as mountain men got little play.
</P>
<P>
   The attention they did get, Cashion noted, focused on how they
almost wiped out the beaver population and tipped the balance of
power among Indians by introducing diseases into tribes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The students almost rebelled,'' Cashion said. ``There were
happy to eat the $40 for the book if they could leave it at home. I
went back to giving them gunsmoke and horse poop and they loved
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor University history professor Tom Charlton said these
different views of the American West have made it one of the most
hotly contested areas of history today.
</P>
<P>
   Cashion, now professor of history at Sam Houston State
University in Huntsville, Texas, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be a very vicious thing,'' Cashion said. ``If you want
to get right down to it, old Western history focuses on great men
and sensational events. It has a frontier fixation and it's written
in a romantic tone.''
</P>
<P>
   The scribe of that old history was Frederick Jackson Turner,
whose writing on the frontier in the 1890s provided the lens
through which the West was seen for the next 90 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The focus was on opportunity,'' Charlton said. ``It was more
or less a heroic view. It was people conquering the West, taming
the West. The West was always something people took over.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner and followers of his school see the West as an unfolding
frontier experience that is generally positive.
</P>
<P>
   Turner's view, Charlton said, missed the point. ``The West was
not an unoccupied land waiting for people.''
</P>
<P>
   It focused on the availability of land. It didn't taken women
into account. It didn't deal much with the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a fairly limited view of what happened in the American
West. It was a patriarchal view,'' Charlton said.
</P>
<P>
   The old history focuses on individuals and skirts the federal
government's role in developing the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here again, that's not good news to a lot of people who want
to romanticize the West,'' Charlton said. ``They want to believe
people went out and conquered the West, not (that) the federal
government'' conquered it.
</P>
<P>
   Cashion said people are now asking, ``If there were winners of
the West, who were the losers of the West?''
</P>
<P>
   And what did the winners win? What did they do with the land?
</P>
<P>
   ``New Western historians, they have a more sober view of
history,'' said Cashion, who likes the interpretation but also
warns of transferring today's values and judgments to an earlier
time period.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the approach say the history focuses on the dark side
of the West and paints American expansion as ``an irresponsible
white man's adventure,'' Cashion said.
</P>
<P>
   Charlton sees the new interpretation as a tool to see the West
more broadly.
</P>
<P>
   ``They always come into my course carrying a lot of these
traditional views,'' Charlton said. ``Just about everything they
read is an eye-opener. I'm not trying to knock all of the myths out
of my students all all ... I'm trying to give them a larger context
to think about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
