<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4457 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-STOOGES-BOS &LR;      04-22 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-STOOGES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTS OF NYUKS, NOSTALGIA IN `THREE STOOGES' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE THREE STOOGES 
Starring: Paul Ben-Victor, Evan Handler, Michael Chiklis, John
Kassir 
Directed by: James Frawley 
On: ABC, Monday at 8 p.m. 
No rating 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Good network biopics are very hard to come by. From ``The Audrey
Hepburn Story'' and ``The David Cassidy Story'' to ``And the Beat
Goes On: The Sonny and Cher Story,'' they're enough to make even
the most rabid fame-seeker long for a life of obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   And so when a network biopic comes along that isn't exactly
excruciating, it's hard not to let out a little cheer. Which isn't
to say that ``The Three Stooges'' is a great biopic, or that it
equals any of the grittier life stories that regularly premiere on
the cable channels. For one thing, the movie does a quick
Curly-walk away from any of the Stooges' troublesome character
flaws. And for another, it relies too heavily on biopic cliches and
oversimplification as it crams the better part of a century and
four complicated characters into two scrawny TV hours.
</P>
<P>
   But ``The Three Stooges'' does have a few important pluses that
make it worth a look. Most notably, all of the actors do an
exciting job of re-creating, but not impersonating, the classic
slapstick trio. They look like the Stooges, but they don't look
like they're trying too hard to look like the Stooges. Even with
the presence of Moe's trademark bowl-cut bangs and Larry's insane
frizz, there's none of the cheesy mimickry and kitschy costuming
that belongs in the campier context of a nightclub impersonation.
The acting is natural and affectionate, not self-conscious and
artificial.
</P>
<P>
   The framing device of ``The Three Stooges,'' set in the late
1950s, centers around Paul Ben-Victor's Moe Howard, a proud man who
doesn't want to reunite the Stooges despite the enthusiasm of a
young entrepreneur. As Moe recalls the history of the Stooges, we
see it all in flashbacks, from the early vaudeville days to the
years making short films for Columbia. We see his oldest brother,
Shemp (John Kassir), drop in and out of the trio due to a nervous
condition that the movie never quite explains. We see his youngest
brother, Jerome (Michael Chiklis), shave his head, adopt the name
Curly, and take Shemp's place. We also catch a glimpse of Curly's
personal woes, including alcoholism and pill-popping, which bring
him to an early grave, but the movie doesn't give up those details
either. And we meet Larry Fine (Evan Handler), who becomes like a
brother to the Howards.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the better moments in ``The Three Stooges'' are the
reassembled Stooges skits, like the memorable ``Calling Dr. Howard,
Dr. Fine, Dr. Howard'' bit. These black-and-white scenes recapture
the joy and wackiness of the original versions, while they serve as
a reminder of the art behind this kind of comedy. A precursor to
the physical antics of Jim Carrey, the Stooges slapstick involved
careful three-person choreography and enough free-spiritedness to
look certifiably foolish. Their clowning was hard work.
</P>
<P>
   The skits in ``The Three Stooges'' also recall a time when
entertainment was so much more innocent than it is today. It's
amazing to see a few knocks on the head igniting hysterical
laughter in vaudeville audiences, and by the end of the movie you
may find yourself hankering for that same innocence and a few good
Stooges shorts (American Movie Classics airs them on weekend
mornings, from 8 to 11).
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for the real story behind the classic
eye-poking comedians, you will be disappointed with ``The Three
Stooges.'' It raises a number of interesting facts, from Larry's
gambling issues to the Howard family's strong Jewish identity
(their real last name was Horwitz), and then it leaves them
hanging. But if you're in the market for some light nostalgia, then
you have only one thing to say to yourself: ``Why soitenly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
