<HEADLINE>
SALARYMEN NO MORE: YOUNG ENTREPRENEURS SHAKE JAPAN INC. 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to change salary man/salary men to salaryman/salarymen in
text and hed.)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Starting this week, music fans across Japan will be
stepping up to a gadget that resembles a souped up, stand-alone
automated teller, plugging in a blank minidisk, dropping in some
coins and, 30 to 40 seconds later, walking away with their favorite
recordings. And they will not be limited to just a few selections;
thanks to a super-fast, high-capacity digital connection to a
central computer, thousands upon thousands of popular songs will be
potentially available at the touch of a few buttons.
</P>
<P>
   No more long waits. No more illicit downloading of MP3 files.
Just music fast, simple and cheap.
</P>
<P>
   It's called a Music POD, and while it may seem like just another
plaything for Japanese teen-agers, it is in fact a powerful
representation of the tectonic shifts taking place in the economy
here.
</P>
<P>
   What the Music POD embodies is the entrepreneurial vision of a
30-year-old college dropout and the business skills of a
40-something former salaryman, founders of a young company called
V-Sync. They are the sorts of men who five years ago would have
toiled anonymously inside a major corporation, climbing the ladder
of seniority and keeping their dreams tightly locked up in their
heads.
</P>
<P>
   But today changes in the relationship between employer and
employee, the liberalization of the financial markets and the
explosion of new business models in the freewheeling arenas of the
Internet and information technology are spawning a whole new breed
of entrepreneurs who care little for the conventions that have
dominated Japan Inc. for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be a gear turning the wheels of a big
company,'' said Katsuma Fujii, V-Sync's chairman and the younger of
its co-founders. ``It's difficult for a lowly gear to get his
bosses to listen to, let alone accept, his out-of-this-world ideas
in a traditional Japanese corporation. I want to do what I want to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   While the number of start-ups that can be counted is still low
in comparison with the United States, venture capitalists say they
began detecting a significant increase in activity last year that
is continuing today despite the weak economy. The number of initial
public offerings was up for the first time last year since the peak
in 1995, and the percentage of those companies that were less than
10 years old was the highest it had ever been, according to Jafco,
Japan's largest venture capital company.
</P>
<P>
   Japan, of course, has always been a nation with many small
businesses, despite its image as the land of corporate leviathans
manned by regiments of salarymen. And what gets forgotten is that
some of those leviathans _ Honda, Kyocera and Sony, to name a few _
were spawned by visionary entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   But the economic structure that evolved after World War II, with
its heavy emphasis on government-directed bank lending, its
punitive tax structure, its ban on stock options and its lack of
pension portability, stifled the entrepreneurial spirit here.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we would call the upside didn't exist under that
system,'' said Karl K. Fooks, managing director in charge of
deploying venture capital for J.P. Morgan in Tokyo, where it has
recently announced investments in three start-ups. ``The banks
forced you to pledge your entire family as collateral, and the tax
man took most of your profits.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, until the last year or so, when many of those
disincentives started eroding, entrepreneurs tended to be shackled
to the big kaisha, or corporations, which provided them with a
steady stream of orders, helped them establish a line of credit
with a bank and squeezed their profits in hard times. They were,
effectively, the minor outlying satellites of the business clusters
called keiretsu, and their fortunes very much depended on the
kaisha's patronage.
</P>
<P>
   So Japan's best and brightest made the rational choice to join
the big companies, where salaries were small but benefits like
cars, housing allowances and school tuition were generous and
untaxed. The further one climbed up the ladder, the better the
benefits became, making lifetime loyalty far more attractive than
striking out on one's own.
</P>
<P>
   ``People love to say the Japanese are risk averse,'' Fooks said.
``That simply isn't true. There was just no reward for taking
entrepreneurial risk in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   All that is now changing. For one thing, many big companies are
slowly realizing the benefits of competitive procurement practices
and the costs of providing life support to so many small partners.
Corporations are also struggling to pare their work forces, largely
by drastically cutting hiring of new employees. Unemployment hit
another high in March, and a record share of college graduates this
year will be unable to find established jobs, a trend that is
encouraging more and more people to start businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the big companies that still dominate the economy are
adopting compensation programs based on performance and abolishing
remuneration determined by seniority, fast diluting the attractions
of lifetime employment.
</P>
<P>
   The evolution of the financial markets here is also helping
entrepreneurs, as new stock markets emerge designed to foster young
businesses and a flood of venture capital provides money that once
was parceled out almost exclusively by big banks largely interested
in corporate customers and real estate developers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even go to a bank when I started my company because I
was pretty sure about the answer _ no,'' said Moto Kuroi,
co-founder of Neuromagic, a Web design and strategic consulting
firm. ``I started the company with money from my friends and
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, V-Sync and Neuromagic have a few beneficial ties to
big business. Sharp, Sumitomo Trust, Marubeni and other established
Japanese companies have invested in V-Sync. Similarly, Neuromagic
relies on Dentsu, the giant Japanese advertising agency, for some
of its orders.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is if either of these two companies were to lose
those backers, they would scarcely miss a beat. When Internet
Initiatives Japan, which specializes in connecting corporate
customers to the Internet, wanted to raise money here two years
ago, it was stymied. It finally went public last summer _ on the
Nasdaq market in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But since then, two new stock exchanges have been set up
specifically to foster fledgling enterprises _ Mothers, which made
its debut late last year, and Nasdaq Japan, which will open this
summer. Meanwhile, the pool of venture capital here is swelling.
Even the government is eager to develop entrepreneurs, earmarking
10.3 billion yen, or about $97 million, for new ventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry so much about finding money,'' said Kuroi, who
almost sold Neuromagic recently but decided he would rather remain
independent. ``I worry about getting the right people to back us.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the challenge for venture capitalists is that the large
majority of money available to finance new businesses arrived only
recently, so many of the entrepreneurs here have figured out ways
to build their operations without it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only one year ago, too little money was chasing too few
deals,'' said Mitsumasa Murase, chairman and president of Jafco,
the venture capital company. ``Now, we have too much money chasing
too few deals.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That is especially true now that barriers to taking young
companies public have been eased, making private capital less
crucial in nursing them. ``Previously, if you invested in early
stage companies, it would take 30 years to cash out and make money
on them,'' Murase said. ``Now, companies are going public at
lightning speed, 1 1/2 or two years after they are founded.''
</P>
<P>
   Just this week, V-Sync began making plans to offer shares to the
public on the Mothers exchange. ``We are rather like a telecom
company, so we need money to build a fiber optic infrastructure,''
said Takaya Ibe, V-Sync's president and co-founder. ``That requires
a huge amount of money, and we feel the stock market is the best
place to go for that.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Ibe is even more remarkable than his whiz-kid
partner, Fujii. To start with, after graduating from college, Ibe
went to work for Hoechst, the big German chemical company, rather
than a Japanese kaisha, a far rarer occurrence then than now.
</P>
<P>
   He eventually left for a company specializing in semiconductor
robotics, his second break from the traditional Japanese career
pattern that chains employees to companies for life. From there, he
went to Bandai, where he was part of a team that developed a
variety of popular gadgets using computer chips.
</P>
<P>
   But what most interested Ibe was developing circuitry to create
three-dimensional computer games. At that time, about 15 years ago,
Bandai was reaping the benefits of its simple, two-dimensional
Super Mario games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I explained to the board that if we could introduce 3-D, the
prospect for games would be great,'' he said. ``But they told me,
`This two-dimensional Mario is beautiful and fun. Why should we
create something new? What do we need 3-D for?'''
</P>
<P>
   Disappointed, he stayed at Bandai a few more years but then
struck out and founded his own company. On one project, he met
Fujii.
</P>
<P>
   The young Fujii was then working for a company that was a
subcontractor to Bandai. ``Even though I invented some smash hit
products,'' he said, ``the profit always went to Bandai. That's why
I decided to start my own company and asked Ibe to be my partner.''
</P>
<P>
   Ibe had not forgotten his dreams, either. ``I kept remembering
the whole 3-D thing with Bandai and how Playstation and Nintendo
had proven I was right,'' he said. ``I did not want to repeat that
mistake and miss out on an opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   So he and Fujii pooled their money and went into business in
hopes of exploiting the emerging network technologies already
taking off in the United States. They were lucky when they received
a research grant from Okayama Prefecture. They won a bid to supply
information kiosks in train stations, beating out corporate titans
like NEC and Fujitsu. And the giant Nippon Telegraph and Telephone
turned to V-Sync when Mitsubishi Electric failed to deliver an
information terminal.
</P>
<P>
   The genius of people like Fujii has been in recognizing that
subterranean Japan is a veritable spaghetti bowl of underutilized
fiber optic cable and finding ways of putting it to use. Indeed,
V-Sync's dreams go far beyond music; any kind of digital
information _ books, movies, software, games _ can be downloaded
through the POD.
</P>
<P>
   That understanding of the power resident in telecommunications
networks is what distinguishes many of the new entrepreneurs from
their predecessors and the big kaisha. They have largely had to
educate themselves, which has given them a self-confidence that is
rare in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Kuroi, the Neuromagic founder, was a philosophy major studying
at the International Christian University in Tokyo _ ``I wanted to
go to Hitotsubashi University,'' he said, ``but I wasn't a good
enough student'' _ when he discovered the potential of networked
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that time, there was no commercial Internet, everything was
operating at a speed of 2,400 baud, you couldn't send images or
pictures of any kind, only text,'' he said. ``I knew the technology
would change, but my friends said what I was talking about was
impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   After trying out a couple of different jobs, Kuroi met several
employees of Apple Computer. ``Those guys didn't think like
Japanese, and being around them helped me to realize I don't need a
protector.''
</P>
<P>
   So he started Neuromagic with a friend who left IBM Japan. They
are still the sole owners of the company, which now has 20
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Neuromagic, a pioneer in Japan's young Internet production
industry, has worked on more than 100 Web sites, including sites
for Sony Music Entertainment and Citibank Japan. It helped Gap plan
its new store in Tokyo's trendy Harajuku neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   But Kuroi is not sanguine. Web site design companies are
springing up all over, and he is well aware that his U.S.
counterparts are often operating outfits with 25 times the staff
that Neuromagic has.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be more competitive, offer customers more services
and ideas,'' Kuroi said. ``That will take money.''
</P>
<P>
   His parents initially objected to Neuromagic, asking Kuroi to
explain why they had wasted money sending him to college. ``My
father wanted me to work for Hitachi, Toshiba, Matsushita,'' Kuroi
said. ``That was his direction.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kuroi, who is 37, has now convinced his father that he made
the right choice. ``We are different from our parents'
generation,'' he said. ``We have different DNA.''
</P>
</TEXT>
