<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-TRAUMA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINGERING EFFECTS WILL DOG BOY THROUGH LIFE, EXPERTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He may suffer some temporary regression, perhaps by wetting his
bed or reverting to occasional baby talk. He likely will experience
nightmares or flashbacks, perhaps only for a while but maybe for
the rest of his life. And he almost certainly will have to cope
with various manifestations of clinical depression, with an
inability to attach to other people generally, and with a lingering
distrust, in particular, of close relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Mental-health and child-development specialists expressed deep
concern Saturday about just how wide a range of emotional and
developmental problems Elian Gonzalez will face for many years to
come as a result of the unrelenting series of traumas he has
endured since leaving Cuba on a rickety craft with his mother and a
group of other refugees last November.
</P>
<P>
   ``The level of psychic injury to him is obviously very high,''
said Peter Metz, director of Child and Adolescent Psychiatry at the
University of Massachusetts Medical Center in Worcester, Mass. ``He
will need help, a lot of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The experts said the image flashed across television screens
just hours after the boy's seizure _ that of Elian, back with his
father, smiling and seemingly doing fine _ probably partly
reflected his happiness at being back with a man he loves and with
whom he has a solid bond. But they added that a major reason Elian
appeared normal also was that he was in shock and/or denial,
dealing with horrific and incomprehensible events in a way that a
6-year-old is capable of doing: by behaving as if they didn't
happen because he doesn't know how to interpret them or how to
react.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd call him clinically numb,'' said Michael Brody, a
well-known specialist in childhood development and an officer of
the American Academy of Child and Adolescent Psychiatry.
</P>
<P>
   Later in life, however, most likely beginning in adolescence,
the memories invariably come trickling or flooding back. And then,
mental-health professionals agreed, even children who haven't
exhibited many adverse effects and have responded well to therapy
can begin manifesting symptoms ranging from relatively narrow
issues like sleeplessness or learning disorders, to far broader
problems such as depression, negative self-image, and even a
greater proclivity for violent behavior because of pent-up anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kid also is going to have to live with far more trauma
than most because he hasn't been given sufficient opportunity by
his caretakers to grieve,'' said Brody. He and others interviewed
Saturday explained that by concentrating on diversions such as
going to amusement parks and giving Elian new toys, the boy's Miami
relatives delayed the grieving process and thereby increased the
odds that he will suffer problems later in life because he hasn't
begun to resolve them at the time that they occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of a parent, especially a mother and especially by a
young child, is widely viewed as a potentially personality-altering
trauma in and of itself _ without the overlay, in Elian's case, of
having watched her die; of having been in a life-threatening
circumstance himself at the time; of living with relatives who
presumably displayed animosity toward and allowed him to engage in
a videotaped confrontation with his surviving parent; of having
been glorified as something akin to an idol by crowds outside his
door; and, finally, of having been aggressively removed from
whatever security he felt by government agents in forbidding
uniforms and bearing large weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's horrifying,'' Joyce Maguire Pavao, a prominent therapist
and founder of the Center for Family Connections in Cambridge,
Mass., said of the aggressive method Attorney General Janet Reno
authorized to get Elian. While Pavao stressed her belief that he
belonged with his father, she added that the government should have
acted sooner and in a less violent way, perhaps the night the
Gonzalez stayed at a nun's house in Florida 10 days ago.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, everyone interviewed layed most of the
responsibility for the potential psychic damage to Elian _ beyond
that from his mother's death _ mainly on his Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``They weren't able to put their egos aside and do what's best
for the child,'' said Pavao, who faulted both the relatives and the
government for having treated Elian as a pawn in a legal-political
game rather than as a small boy whose emotional well-being was at
risk. ``This is how we treat children all the time, as property,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Metz made a similar point, asserting that Elian's needs have
barely been addressed by anyone, including the media and public,
during discussions of his fate. ``To the extent that everyone is
focused on the asylum issue,'' he asserted, ``that's not honoring
this child.''
</P>
<P>
   All those interviewed Saturday remarked on how bright and
resilient a child Elian appears to be, both important factors that
will help him cope in the weeks and years to come. Moreover, the
experts agreed that Elian's prospects will be vastly improved if
two things happen: he receives long-term counseling, and all his
feuding relatives put aside their differences to ease the
transition for him and to show he is not to blame for the custody
battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be inevitable that he will have scars, but how
he functions here on in, especially as he becomes an adolescent and
gets older, will depend on how the adults deal with his needs
now,'' said Ann Sullivan, a child-welfare specialist with the Child
Welfare League of America.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the experts said, the healing period may not begin in
earnest for a long time because Elian seems likely to remain in the
spotlight during ucoming court fights, could be wrenched
emotionally again if his Miami relatives win asylum for him in the
United States, and seems certain to be the object of enormous
attention if he returns to Cuba within a few months with his
father.
</P>
<P>
   Rosanna Hertz, a professor at Wellesley College whose specialty
is family sociology, was among many who said Elian could suffer
even if his various relatives do behave well for his benefit. Among
the reasons they cited were that he already senses or knows he is
at the center of hostility among the people he loves most; he
senses or knows that his various parental figures have been
perceived as unfit to raise him, or ``have fallen from grace'' as
Hertz put it; and he has been elevated to such a high level of
recognition by family members, the Cuban American supporters
outside his door, and the media _ clinically called ``grandiosity''
_ that he cannot help but sustain serious psychic injuries when the
attention inevitably fades, and he plummets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this kid has been catapulted into a position so
high,'' said Hertz, ``that no child his age, or maybe any age,
could hope to handle it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
