<HEADLINE>
ANGRY DEMONSTRATORS QUICKLY GATHER OUTSIDE THE GONZALEZ HOUSE IN
MIAMI
</HEADLINE>
 (UPDATES thruout; ADDS photo note)  
(ART ADV: Photos NYT19-22 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 
 By JUAN FORERO  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Outraged that Elian Gonzalez was taken from them,
hundreds of Cuban-American protesters took to a major road here
Saturday, burning tires and throwing rocks as police officers in
riot gear moved in, firing tear gas and making several arrests.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd roamed along Flagler Street, a four-lane avenue that
cuts east-west through Little Havana not far from the house where
6-year-old Elian had been staying. The police initially appeared to
pull back, allowing protesters, many of them carrying Cuban flags,
to slow traffic. But by midmorning, officers moved in from several
directions across several blocks of Flagler, pushing protesters
back and firing tear-gas canisters.
</P>
<P>
   Sporadic protests continued throughout the day along the avenue,
leaving harried police officers to rush back and forth in response.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get out of here, out of here,'' one man shouted as heavily
armed officers ran at 1:15 p.m. to Flagler and 30th Avenue, where
dozens of protesters had set fire to a pile of tires. ``You don't
belong, this is our home.''
</P>
<P>
   Tear-gas canisters were then fired in several directions, with
dozens of stunned protesters _ many, if not most, residents of the
neighborhood _ running for the side streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not right to shoot tear gas at people who are in their
homes,'' said Hector Alvarado, 28, holding his shirt over his face.
``We were arguing with the police, asking for liberty for Elian.
Then they came and started firing.''
</P>
<P>
   Another protester, Eduardo Santana, said: ``They came right at
us, shooting tear gas at us. There were children there. The tear
gas hurt. I fell right there. I couldn't breathe, but they said,
`Go, get out,' and pushed me back.''
</P>
<P>
   Santana, 48, who held a Cuban flag, added: `This isn't right.
This is our country. We're Cubans, but we're U.S. citizens too.''
</P>
<P>
   Saul Mari, 62, who like many here believes that handing Elian
over to his father is akin to handing him over to the Cuban
government, said, ``I never thought they would take him; I thought
Clinton and Reno would respect the laws of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the home of Lazaro Gonzalez, the great-uncle who had been
caring for the boy, a young man burned a small American flag.
Others equated the operation to the government's disastrous raid on
the compound near Waco, Texas, which had been ordered by Attorney
General Janet Reno. Several people held up crosses, one with a baby
doll nailed to the wood, red paint smeared across its body.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is incredible that this happened,'' Jesus Jorge, 53,
muttered, shaking his head. ``Clinton and Reno will pay for this in
front of God's justice. This is unpardonable.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd broke into spontaneous chants, shouting ``criminals''
and ``assassins,'' referring to the government force that swept
into the home where Elian had been staying since he was found
floating off South Florida on Nov. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrators called for mass protests and hunger strikes, and
by midmorning hundreds of protesters hoisting the Cuban banner had
spilled onto nearby streets. Some overturned garbage cans and
newspaper boxes. By late morning, several protesters had been
arrested for trying to block traffic on the wide thoroughfares
nearby. Motorists, meanwhile, clogged up several routes nearby,
blowing their horns and waving Cuban flags.
</P>
<P>
   The political leaders of the city, whose careers flourished with
the political and economic strength of the Cuban-American
community, left no adjective unturned in their denunciations of
Reno and President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal feeling is that what our president of our country
and our attorney general ordered was one of the most shameful acts
I have ever seen,'' said Joe Carollo, the mayor of the city of
Miami. ``It is one of the most disgraceful and shameful acts in the
history of our government.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``People are in total shock to see our government come
in this morning, pointing automatic weapons at women and
children,'' and at ``seeing the picture of little Elian being taken
out screaming and crying.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in Miami, residents and tourists were falling into
their routines on this Easter holiday weekend. Cruise ships lined
the harbor and traffic sped along the freeways, windshields
glinting in the sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   Still, four local English-language television stations and their
two Spanish-language counterparts showed a very different reality:
videotaped reruns and live shots of demonstrators gathering and
shouting, and in a few instances burning tires. These were
interspersed with videotape of the predawn raid on Lazaro
Gonzalez's home.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all Carollo's fury, he said that his first concern was
``to keep peace in our community.'' He added: ``What I am asking
the people of Miami to do is act with their heads, not their
hearts. To use their heads and fight within the law.'' Any
violence, he added, ``will make Miami the loser, America a bigger
loser, and will only benefit the criminal dictator Fidel Castro.''
</P>
<P>
   Others expressed relief. Marvin Dunn, the chairman of the
psychology department at Florida University and the author of a
definitive history of the 1980 riots in Liberty City, a
predominantly black Miami neighborhood, said Saturday: ``I'm
thrilled. It is overdue.''
</P>
<P>
   The intensity of the debate over Elian, and the obsessive media
coverage, Dunn said, were ``putting this community through a
protracted and ugly crisis. I admire Janet Reno for taking action.
And I'm very happy for this boy's father.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn said he believed the confrontation over the boy was ``the
most divisive event in Miami's history, and a lot of non-Cuban
Hispanics have been on the sidelines.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
