<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL-SIGNATURES _ WASHINGTON _ Whether done with the flourish
of a quill spelling out ``John Hancock,'' or with a simple pencil
scratching out an ``X,'' Americans have long used their signatures
to seal a deal. But in the age of the Internet, business owners say
electronic commerce will never reach its full potential unless
people can complete a contract by using a computer to ``sign'' and
send legally binding documents. To speed the development of
e-commerce, Congress is now in the final stages of writing
legislation that would give consumers and business owners the
ability to close deals using ``digital signatures.'' (Geewax, Cox
News Service). With DIGITAL-CHART and an illustration from Austin.
</P>
