   BOOKS-SHIELDS _ Review of Carol Shields' stories ``Dressing Up
for the Carnival.'' (Vejnoska, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 14.
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-SKUBE _ Five years ago, when the Library of America series
inducted Raymond Chandler into what amounts to a hall of fame of
the native tongue, it was acknowledgment that the detective mystery
had achieved a certain respectability. ``As I look back on my own
stories,'' he wrote in ``The Simple Art of Murder,'' ``it would be
absurd if I did not wish they had been better. But if they had been
much better they would not have been published.'' Chandler wrote
pulp fiction, and he neither apologized for it nor thought it
literary. And yet literary it was _ in the creation of a believable
character and a psychological world, in the cadence of his
sentences, in the concrete images. (Skube, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 23. MOVED
</P>
