<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NC-DEVELOPMENT-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: LAWSUIT TO STOP MALL BRINGS DOWN ZONING PROCESS  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ Michael McKinney and 16 of his neighbors set
out to stop a shopping center, but they ended up freezing
development in one of the nation's fastest-growing metropolitan
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Their lawsuit to keep a new strip mall anchored by a Target
store out of their neighborhood brought down the city's entire
zoning process, which a judge called illegal.
</P>
<P>
   In a decision handed down on Monday, Judge Ben Tennille of
Superior Court ruled that the so-called fast-track process, which
decides about 80 percent of proposed construction in this booming
city of 500,000, is too fast, too informal and violates state law.
He halted 50 projects awaiting approval, and ordered the city to
design a more formal method for deciding zoning requests.
</P>
<P>
   ``It opened a can of worms,'' McKinney said on Friday of the
lawsuit he helped organize last year, after a congested residential
area was rezoned to allow the strip mall. ``We knew we were getting
into an area that was a broader issue, and we thought it would be a
good thing for Charlotte.''
</P>
<P>
   City and business leaders, who have cheered on a construction
boom that has raised property values and helped revive a
once-moribund downtown, are not so sure. They fear that a more
trial-like review process, possibly requiring lawyers, traffic
studies and expert testimony, will drive developers elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want the world out there to think Charlotte is not a
good place to bring their investments,'' said Walter G. Fields III,
who helped create the city's one-step approval process in the 20
years he worked on the planning committee.
</P>
<P>
   Under the old system, developers and residents could lobby City
Council members up to the time they voted on a project. The public
hearing before each vote typically lasted 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In his decision, Tennille gave the city 90 days to design a
two-step system, where a decision over property zoning is followed
by a quasi-judicial hearing on proposed construction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 1821EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000422.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4469 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-DECISION &LR;      04-22 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-DECISION </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE RELIEVED RENO ACTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the end, Janet Reno's patience ran out.
</P>
<P>
   Whipsawed by the Miami relatives who, she said, ``kept moving
the goal post,'' by Juan Miguel Gonzalez, whose anger at being kept
from his son grew by the day, and by a White House anxious to see
the endgame, the attorney general gave a predawn order to send
eight armed agents into a Little Havana home to seize six-year-old
Elian Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did, until the final moments, try to reach a voluntary
solution,'' Reno told reporters Saturday morning. ``I negotiated
through the night. At times I was very encouraged, and then at
other times it seemed to slip away. And finally, time ran out.''
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's decision to use force has put her on the
hot seat, a place she's been before. It was seven years ago last
week that, after protracted negotiations, she ordered the FBI's
botched assault on the Branch Davidian compound at Waco that left
some 80 people dead.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton did his best to distance himself from Reno
after Waco. Saturday he quickly went before the cameras to praise
the attorney general for her ``restraint, patience, and
compassion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She made the decision, she managed this, but I fully support
what she did,'' Clinton said. ``I think she did the right thing,
and I'm very pleased with the way she handled it.''
</P>
<P>
   The president certainly didn't want another Waco. To that end,
senior White House officials have been deeply involved in the Elian
case, to the point of micromanagement. It wasn't that they didn't
trust the attorney general, they say, though she and the president
have never been close. But they were concerned that Reno's unusual
sensitivity to what happened in Miami, her hometown, might paralyze
her from taking action to resolve a situation with wide political
implications.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been monitoring it from the day the child arrived in
the United States, and our regular communications with the Justice
Department have intensified over the last few weeks,'' said a
senior White House official who has been close to the case. ``We
knew the situation was potentially very explosive.''
</P>
<P>
   The official denied the White House pressured Reno to move
against the Miami relatives. But, the official said, top aides to
the president did urge her to ``bring more definition'' to the
option of using force after last week's US Circuit Court ruling
that will keep Elian in the United States until an asylum hearing
in May but did not transfer his custody to Juan Miguel, his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pointed out to the attorney general that with each passing
day, it became more and more difficult for the Justice Department
to maintain its credibility,'' the White House official said. ``We
were very careful to not say, `do X or Y,' because if something
went wrong, a lot of fingerpointing would be going on. But we did
say they should be ready with a plan, because a lack of action was
going to reflect badly on the department.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House Saturday provided an almost hour-by-hour
chronology, beginning late Friday afternoon, to show how the
president and his top aides monitored the Justice Department. The
president and Reno had thrashed out the administration's options
during a plane trip home from Oklahoma City Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   According to White House press secretary Joe Lockhart, the
president talked to Reno twice Friday, once in the late afternoon
and again at 8:30 p.m. In that conversation, he said, Reno briefed
the president on the status of 11th-hour talks between a group of
mediators Reno had drawn from the Miami community, including a
Roman Catholic priest and officials of the University of Miami, and
the Gonzalez family and their lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   After that, John Podesta, the president's chief of staff, stayed
in hourly contact with the Justice Department, Lockhart said. At
2:15 a.m., Podesta informed the president the negotiations in Miami
still were going on and that they would continue, perhaps for days,
if they showed progress. If the talks reached an impasse, however,
Reno had decided to move in with force.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president agreed with that approach,'' Lockhart said. At 5
a.m., Podesta called the president again to inform him that the
mediation had ended, and Operation Reunion, as the Justice
Department named it, was going forward. At 5:30 a.m., Lockhart
said, Podesta told the president the boy was out of the Miami house
and on his way to Washington. Thirty minutes later, Reno phoned the
president who, according to Lockhart, ``thanked her for her
leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the harrowing photographs of the agents forced entry
into the house to seize the frightened child, Lockhart said the
president would have preferred a voluntary transfer of the boy,
which is what Reno had also long sought. ``That did not happen,''
Lockhart said. ``We were left with no other alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials thought there might be a negotiated
breakthrough Friday night. Reno gave mediators meeting at the home
of Elian's great uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, a 3 a.m. deadline to
hammer out a plan that would have phased in the boy's transfer to
his father. As officials explained it, Elian would have stayed with
his cousin, Marisleysis, at a neutral site, with his father granted
expanding visitation rights. At an undetermined date, the father
would take full custody of the boy.
</P>
<P>
   But Juan Miguel said he was afraid to go to Florida, and the
Miami relatives refused the Justice Department order that the
neutral site be in the Washington area. The biggest sticking
points, however, were that Marisleysis would not agree to transfer
the boy to his father, and she and Lazaro insisted Elian should
have a say in the matter, a spokeswoman for the Immigration and
Naturalization Service said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like trying to nail Jello to the wall,'' the
spokeswoman said. ``The family refused to entertain any discussion
of whether they would transfer custody. Juan Miguel said, `This is
ridiculous. It's my kid.' &UR;  &LR; ''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Holder, Reno's top deputy at Justice, Saturday described
the negotiations as ``extremely frustrating,'' and said nobody was
more disappointed by the failure than Reno herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we thought we had achieved what (the Miami
relatives) wanted, it wasn't enough,'' said Reno, who could not
move the relatives when she met with them im Miami April 12. ``It
was a very frustrating experience. It was just one step after
another in which they moved the goal post.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, sitting behind her desk, surrounded by her aides, she
gave the order for an operation that, like Waco, is bound to haunt
her and mobilize her many critics in Miami and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   For the White House, the outcome of the order it sought could
have been much worse. ``We were all very glad it happened without a
hitch,'' a senior official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
