<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4470 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-CAMBY-LAWSUIT-NYT     04-22 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CAMBY-LAWSUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAPTORS COACH FILES DEFAMATION SUIT AGAINST CAMBY
</HEADLINE>
  By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ On the eve of the New York Knicks' first-round
playoff game with the Toronto Raptors, Marcus Camby Saturday had to
deal with questions concerning a lawsuit filed against him by the
Raptors' coach, Butch Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Camby was served papers late Friday night following a Knicks
practice. In the lawsuit, Carter claims he ``has been damaged and
suffered great pain and mental anguish, and has been held up to
ridicule and contempt by his friends, acquaintances and the
public.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter's suit was filed Friday afternoon in New York State
Supreme Court in White Plains, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Camby, traded to the Knicks from Toronto before the 1998-99
season, said this week that Carter had promised him that the
Raptors would build their team around him. The trade quickly
followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a liar,'' Camby said Wednesday before the Knicks played
their final regular-season game at Boston. ``I don't really like
him. No one likes him and no one wants to play for him. That's the
kind of guy he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't trust him. I think a lot of guys don't trust him. He's
just been ratting out people and doing things his way. From what I
hear, a lot of people are mad at him.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Camby declined to comment specifically on the lawsuit,
but when asked if he would be even more motivated to play against
his former team, he said: ``What do you think?''
</P>
<P>
   Carter, after several no comments following practice Saturday
regarding his lawsuit, responded to a question about the difficulty
of winning such a suit, because the threshold is higher for people
in the public spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I'm seeking is the truth,'' he said. ``There's an extreme
difference between sworn testimony. ...'' He paused a moment before
being prodded to finish the sentence. ``There's a difference
between sworn testimony and what was said.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he decided right away to sue or if it took him several
days to make that decision, he said, ``It's the only way I can
answer professionally.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Knicks found the timing of Carter's lawsuit curious,
considering the two teams will meet in Game 1 on Sunday at Madison
Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never happened before, but everyone has to do his own
thing,'' coach Jeff Van Gundy said Saturday after the team's
practice. ``We have to focus on the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy was asked about the timing of Carter's lawsuit. ``I'm
sure there is something psychological there,'' Van Gundy said,
``like trying to do something psychological, but they don't need
it. We're the ones who have to adjust to them. I don't care about
it, and I've talked to Marcus, he doesn't care about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Klempner, a lawyer with the National Basketball Players
Association, seemed incredulous over the lawsuit. ``Until we see it
in black and white, we can't comment on it because it's such an
incredible and unbelievable claim,'' he said. ``Any such claim
would be insufficient legally on too many grounds to even begin
counting. I don't think they want to have a precedent with players
starting to sue coaches for coaches' comments about players.''
</P>
<P>
   Camby's lawyer, Patrick Noonan, said: ``This is an absolutely
frivolous lawsuit. It appears that Carter would be better off
spending his time getting his team ready for the playoffs than
pursuing these legal shenanigans.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   General Manager Glen Grunwald of the Raptors said he could not
comment on a pending legal matter.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the team is giving Carter its support, Grunwald
said, ``It's an individual matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter on Thursday had questioned the timing of Camby's
criticism _ coming several days before the Raptors would play in
the first playoff series in the franchise's history _ and he
reiterated that complaint Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think there's a lot to be said about timing,'' Carter
said. ``My hat's off to them about the timing of what they did. You
know, we've played against them six or seven or eight times since
the trade and there never was a problem. It was a little strange.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on Thursday, Grunwald had said that the possibility of
trading Camby came up a day or two before the draft and Carter
``had no idea anything like that was brewing, so I don't think
that's a fair criticism to say he lied to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Grunwald said: ``Marcus is upset at us and I understand
that. I just think his criticism should be based on a little more
of the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Raptors players left the gym briskly Saturday, and only a few
addressed the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Vince Carter, Toronto's top scorer, said: ``I don't care about
that. That's between Butch and Marcus. It's Butch's problem. He can
handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Oakley, who was traded to Toronto from the Knicks for
Camby, said: ``I haven't got anything to do with that. We'll see
how it goes.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
