<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4471 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BOX-ALI-MAIN0423-COX     04-22 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-ALI-MAIN0423-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Onetime political lightning rod Ali has transcended divides to
remain a worldwide icon
 &HT;    By Mike Tierney
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFORT, Ky. _ Muhammad Ali stutter-steps into the Senate
chambers at the state Capitol to sustained, heartfelt applause. He
sits, trembly and somnolent, as his wife Lonnie implores the
lawmakers to cut loose some serious tax money for a proposed Ali
Center up the road in Louisville, their least-loved city. They toss
out a few softball questions, then wish the couple well without a
hint of reluctance to help bankroll the project.
</P>
<P>
   The Alis get their $10 million, along with a Senate resolution
lauding him for his ``lifetime role of goodwill ambassador of the
Bluegrass State to the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that. Thirty-four years ago, in this very room, another
resolution was passed:
</P>
<P>
   ``Whereas Cassius M. Clay, a Kentuckian and the heavyweight
boxing champion of the world, has recently evidenced his
determination to avoid service in the Armed Forces of the United
States of America; and
</P>
<P>
   ``Whereas, the notion that a young man of such athletic prowess
and verbose proclivity cannot serve his country is repugnant to all
true Kentuckians; and ``Whereas, this sudden aversion to fighting
on the part of Cassius M. Clay brings discredit to all loyal
Kentuckians and to the names of the thousands of them who gave
their lives for this country during his lifetime ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, therefore, be it resolved ... that Cassius M. Clay ... is
hereby urged to forthwith abandon his reprehensible efforts to
avoid duty to the country which afforded him the opportunity to
achieve eminence of the highest sort and to set a better example
for the other young men of this great nation by immediately
entering service.''
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, mainstream America pigeonholed Ali (nee Clay,
his ``slave name'') as an uppity, vain, trash-talkin', race-baitin'
conscientious objector hooked up with a way-out religion. Many
wished he would go away _ to jail, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forward to today, then cue up a true fairy tale. The
belittled has become the beloved.
</P>
<P>
   In public, where Ali, 58, prefers to live, he is a flesh magnet,
drawing all shapes, sizes, ages and colors, most of whom melt in
his presence. Professional photographers hand their cameras to
colleagues and beseech them to snap a picture with Ali. Dignitaries
who sign autographs for others ask for his. If there is a more
accessible icon, let him or her step forward and outdo Ali hugging,
kissing, playfully punching, performing simple magic tricks,
flirting and endearing for life.
</P>
<P>
   Once, he was shunned; now, we can't get enough of him. Ali's
farmhouse in Berrien Hills, Mich., needs a new wing to contain his
latest cache of awards, athletic and humanitarian, that were timed
to the 2000 changeover. One made-for-TV bio-pic has aired, a second
is in production, and Hollywood is preparing its version for the
big screen. There is a roving theater play. On the drawing board is
an $80 million Ali Center, a hybrid museum/learning facility
planned for his birth city.
</P>
<P>
   Without an amazing confluence of circumstances, Ali might be
regarded as just another punch-drunk ex-boxer, trying to make it to
the next day. His movements are staccato, his speech slurred and
barely audible, his stamina drained.
</P>
<P>
   The thief who ran off with his gift of gab and the remarkably
synchronized reflexes and strength is not named Spinks or Liston
but Parkinson. The rigid muscles and rhythmic tremor is better
explained by his Parkinson's syndrome than the cranium-crushing
blows he absorbed from padded fists.
</P>
<P>
   Seen through a prism, Ali is viewed with a blend of admiration
and pity. Unashamed of his physical limitations, he goes about his
business. The former human run-on sentence converses chiefly now
with his eyes and hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has adapted extremely well to Parkinson's,'' says his
physician, Dr. Mahlon DeLong, chairman of the department of
neurology at Emory. ``He doesn't let it bring him down. He
considers it a nuisance, more troubling to others than it is to
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, says Thomas Hauser, his biographer and admirer, ``If he
was able to speak his mind, a lot of people might not like (some
of) what he says.''
</P>
<P>
   What Ali does say is treat others with tolerance and
forgiveness. The one-time champ of the most barbaric of sports
wants us to turn the other cheek. To put a little love in our
hearts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
