A4473 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BOX-ALI-MUSEUM0423-CO     04-22 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-ALI-MUSEUM0423-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Proposed Ali museum to promote ideals
 &HT;    By Mike Tierney
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ So, William Qualles, what do you know about
Muhammad Ali?
</P>
<P>
   ``He was mad and threw his belt into the river,'' William, 8,
said. ``(Because of) the color of his skin, he couldn't get served
at a bar.''
</P>
<P>
   A school friend sitting nearby wondered aloud, ``Didn't he do
some rapping?''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the proposed Ali Center in Louisville might
clear up some myths about his life. A larger goal is to spread the
word about believing in yourself and respecting others, tenets that
Ali has practiced and preached.
</P>
<P>
   The Center would have the typical elements of a sports museum,
from videos to virtual-reality games. But its supporters envision
visitors taking away more than a souvenir photograph or even a wave
from Ali in his office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's urban males _ especially young black males _ do not
put much hope in tomorrow,'' his wife, Lonnie Ali, says in
promotional materials. ``This Center will give us a chance to
reignite those fires of hope and desire.''
</P>
<P>
   The recipe would include ingredients from Graceland to
presidential libraries, from the Carter Center to the Martin Luther
King Jr. Center, all of which project director Barry Alberts tapped
into for ideas.
</P>
<P>
   In one room, Alberts speculated, leaders of rival African tribes
could sit across a table to settle their differences. In the next
room, youngsters could hear how Ali sacrificed 3 1/2 years of his
fight career to resist military induction and rail against war.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of programs out there (for kids) about
tolerance,'' Alberts said. ``They're all good. And nobody gives a
darn about them.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's youngsters relate to money and the trappings of wealth,
he said. The center would convey how Ali forfeited millions of
dollars in earnings by declaring himself a conscientious objector,
thus freezing himself out of boxing's lucrative purses.
</P>
<P>
   A tentative target date for the center's opening is late 2002.
The price tag is $80 million, which includes a $20 million
endowment. Nearly $10 million has been donated by private sources,
while the state Legislature has kicked in another $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ali is active in the planning, from making sure no alcohol is
served to reminding designers to meet the needs of kids foremost.
</P>
<P>
   Alberts conceded amazement that kids are acutely aware of an
athlete two decades into retirement _ even if one maintains that
the teetotaling Ali once bellied up to a bar.
</P>
<P>
   As for being a rapper? Well, you could make the case that he is
the pop of hip-hop.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
