<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4474 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-EDITORIAL-B     04-22 0387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-EDITORIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By H.D. S. GREENAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one likes to see armed men break down the door and snatch a
traumatized boy, but make no mistake about it: Justice and right
were served in the early hours of Saturday morning in the Little
Havana section of Miami. ``The law has been upheld, and that was
the right thing to do,'' said President Clinton after the event.
</P>
<P>
   If humanity and the rule of law were to be preservered, the
federal government had no other choice. Attorney General Janet
Reno, herself from Miami, had exhausted every last avenue of
compromise _ even into early Saturday. But it had become
increasingly clear that Elian Gonzalez's relatives in Miami had
absolutely no intention of allowing the boy to return to his
father, even though they had won a court decision that Elian would
not be returned to Cuba without an asylum hearing. The relatives'
negotiating tactic was just to stall and stall again _ and all the
while Elian was in effect held hostage.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton got it right Thursday when he said there was
``no conceivable argument'' against reuniting the boy with his
father, but yet the Miami relatives refused to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The armed operation in Miami was no Waco, the doomed FBI raid in
Texas that so damaged Reno's reputation. The door to the house
where Elian was being held was broken down only after Elian's
relatives refused to open it. Only eight officers were inside the
house for a mere three minutes. Nobody was hurt. A potentially very
dangerous situation was defused.
</P>
<P>
   The Elian Gonzalez affair needed to be resolved, and resolved
quickly. It could not be allowed to drag on and on until the boy
was hopelessly and irrevocably alienated from his father, and all
the while the law defied. The Miami authorities, to their shame,
had threatened not to cooperate with the federal authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it was traumatic for Elian, but the blame lies squarely
with the Miami relatives who were willing to let politics separate
a father from his son. As Reno said, this is ``a child who needs to
be cherished . . . to be with his father. And that is what this
case is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(H.D.S. Greenway is editor of the Globe's editorial page.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 1825EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000422.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4476 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-CUBAN-BOY-COMMENT-BOS     04-22 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT ELSE FROM A COMMUNITY LIKE LITTLE HAVANA? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ ``Bingo! Bingo! Bingo!''
</P>
<P>
   With a code word, Operation Reunion ended, barely three minutes
after it began. By striking when the crowd of protesters was at its
ebb _ and when, perhaps, the Miami branch of the Gonzalez family
had been lulled into a false sense of security _ US agents brought
the Elian Gonzalez custody soap opera here to a decisive halt.
</P>
<P>
   The predawn raid set off a range of emotions among the
bewildered group outside the family's home Saturday. First came
shock as word of the seizure began to spread. After sunrise, that
was followed by anger and a sense of betrayal among people who had
come to believe their numbers might prevail.
</P>
<P>
   The raid itself was carried out with a minimum of wasted motion.
Witnesses described how they were quickly shoved aside, sprayed
with pepper gas, and overwhelmed by federal agents.
</P>
<P>
   Lydia Usategui, a child psychologist who had been advising the
Miami family, was keeping vigil when the caravan of white minivans
rolled in. She said she saw the family spokesman, Armando
Gutierrez, run from the back of the Gonzalez house with his arms
waving, urging the small crowd to try to block the transfer. Then
she was ordered at gunpoint to lie on the ground, and keep her head
down. Soon, she heard the agents signaling to one another that
Elian was in a blanket, and that the van doors were closing. As she
looked up, she was hit with a blast of pepper spray, like many
others at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was horrible, just horrible,'' she said. ``It was so
violent, so brutal. This was so uncalled for, it was just
unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   About an hour after the raid, disbelief began to harden into
anger. The first pictures from inside the house began to circulate,
including the ones showing a federal agent with a rifle on Donato
Dalrymple, who was holding Elian.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters began to roll American flags in black bands. The
swelling crowd was peaceful, but increasingly testy. The Miami-Dade
mayor, Alex Penelas, was jeered by some in the crowd for showing up
too neatly dressed, too pulled together _ and too far behind his
political rival, Miami's mayor, Joe Carollo. Many people held one
another and wept. One man carried a large crucifix with a male doll
and a sign in Spanish that said Predsident Clinton had crucified
Elian. Hundreds of people just milled around, wondering what to do
with the huge emotions that had built up over the past five months.
</P>
<P>
   The pepper spray unleashed in the raid was just the beginning of
the police work. As the day wore on, officers used tear gas as
their tool of choice in an effort to disperse crowds and maintain
the very shaky peace in Little Havana. The crowd fanned out along a
widening area, disrupting traffic, burning tires, and generally
causing mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami police were holding their own, but then they've had
more experience with unrest than most departments. There were four
major disturbances here in the 1980s, including a full-scale riot
in 1980 from which the neighborhood where I grew up has never
recovered. It was clear that the police were following a plan that
had been put together well in advance.
</P>
<P>
   In its zeal to affix blame, the crowd focused on the unholy
trinity of Reno, Clinton and Gregory Craig, the lawyer for Elian's
father. I think they were looking in the wrong places.
</P>
<P>
   It was Elian's great-uncle, Lazaro, and his high-strung cousin,
Marisleysis, who steadily raised the ante, putting the boy in
harm's way and inviting disorder in the streets. They allowed the
boy to be turned into a tool for their cause, allowing the
6-year-old to grant interviews and releasing that loopy videotape
of Elian declaring his supposed wishes. How was the government to
ignore that?
</P>
<P>
   We are not strangers to nutty behavior of any kind in Miami, but
never has so much anxiety resulted from the sheer recalcitrance of
a single stubborn family. While they were busy Saturday portraying
themselves as victims, the reality is that they overplayed their
hand, that they believed the cliche that possession is nine-tenths
of the law. The accounts of Gutierrez trying to rally supporters
are telling. The crowd was always their ace, and in the end it
wasn't nearly enough.
</P>
<P>
   To much of the rest of the fed-up country, the Elian affair
falls somewhere between an annoyance and a side show. But for
Miami, this is disastrous. The city is pulling out of both
bankruptcy and a huge political scandal that resulted in the
removal of the previous mayor. Businesses are leaving town, ethnic
unity is a distant dream, and the city has again been portrayed
nationally as a bizarre banana republic that shares virtually
nothing with the rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
   While the reunion was necessary and overdue, I can only think of
one good thing that will come out of it. This began as a tale of a
little boy, adrift in more ways than one, searching for his family.
Now that Elian has left Miami, probably for good, perhaps his fate
and future _ instead of his relatives, his supporters, and Cuban
politics _ can take center stage. It's sad to think that such
lengths were necessary to reclaim a childhood. But in this wildly
unhinged community, negotiation and peaceful resolution simply
proved too much to hope for. That's a familiar story for Miami.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Walker's e-mail address is walker(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 1827EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
