<SLUG> BC-BOX-ALI-TORCH0423-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Olympic caldron ceremony lit hearts
 &HT;    By Mike Tierney
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The venues were built. The participating nations were
signed up. The tickets were sold. Billy Payne imagined himself a
marathoner in the late stages of a race, most of the legwork behind
him.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Ueberroth disabused him of that notion. ``You haven't made
the hardest decision yet,'' the maestro of the 1984 Summer Games in
Los Angeles advised his Olympic descendent in Atlanta. ``Who is
going to light the flame in the Opening Ceremonies?''
</P>
<P>
   Nominations were pouring into Payne's office. Among them was an
intriguing pitch from NBC Sports president Dick Ebersol. He
advocated Muhammad Ali.
</P>
<P>
   Ali had an Olympic connection _ a boxing gold medal from 1960 _
and a face as familiar as any living person's. ``But,'' Payne said
recently, ``I was a little skittish at first on whether the
conscientious objection could diminish or erode the universal
acceptance.''
</P>
<P>
   Here was a man who declined to serve in the military. And here
was an Olympics in a region of the country that is conservative in
many ways.
</P>
<P>
   To ease any concern, Ebersol plied Payne with boxes of
videotapes documenting Ali's good works. ``To say I was totally
impressed would be an understatement,'' Payne said.
</P>
<P>
   About six months before Olympic liftoff, Ali was overwhelmingly
endorsed by Payne's inner circle. So, another imposing task arose:
keeping the identity of the last torchbearer a secret. ``The
surprise would be part of the magic,'' Payne said.
</P>
<P>
   He even fibbed to Howard Bingham, the champ's aide-de-camp,
saying that a substitute was lined up if Ali spilled the beans and
was disqualified.
</P>
<P>
   A 2 a.m. dress rehearsal two weeks before the ceremony produced
a new set of headaches. Ali strained mightily to hold the torch
steady, raising doubts whether he could conquer the trembling and
ignite the caldron. Then Payne spied a German TV reporter in the
vicinity and feared that he would blare details of the practice run
across the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Payne awakened the next day with his secret intact, and he took
Pentagon-like measures the rest of the way. When the Alis flew into
town for the Games, they entered a limousine with blacked-out
windows and were unloaded at a high-rise apartment building. Ali
emerged from the car covered by a blanket and rode a freight
elevator to his room. Janet Evans, the penultimate torch escort,
learned whom she would hand off to only moments before she began
her jog. The torch was filled with extra fuel to guard against the
flame burning out before Ali could complete the task. Evans
received special instructions in case Ali dropped it. She was to
reach down, pick it up and place Ali's hand on it alongside hers.
They then would light in tandem the wire that ran up to the
caldron.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Ali was able to go solo but a seeming eternity
passed before his shaking limbs allowed him to put the flame to the
fuse. ``He has the heart of a champion,'' Payne said. ``I knew he
would perform when the time came.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly four years later, the memory burns bright for much of the
two-thirds of the world's population that watched _ outshining
other scrapbook moments of the Games, from Michael Johnson to
women's soccer and even the park bombing. People have told Payne
that the ceremony was the emotional highlight of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't bad for the Alis, either. ``We had the best time,''
Lonnie Ali said. ``What an honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
