<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-AIRPORT-STORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINDSTORM DAMAGE SLOWS BOSTON AIRPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Airplanes arriving at Logan Airport in Boston will
face delays for the next several days, and possibly longer, because
of a windstorm that knocked down the airport's main radar tower
early Saturday, according to the Federal Aviation Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The tower, located on the airfield, was sheared off its base at
about 4:15 Saturday morning, said Frasier Jones, a spokesman for
the FAA. ``It took a pretty major hit,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours the agency had found replacement parts at its
supply depot in Oklahoma City, he said, but the parts were too big
to fly on a conventional airplane.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday afternoon, the agency was looking for a military
cargo plane or a truck to transport the parts.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile controllers in the tower at Logan and at the Terminal
Radar Approach Control, which handles planes as they approach or
leave the airport, were using radar data from the Boston Air Route
Traffic Control Center, in Nashua, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   But that radar is farther away and provides less precise
information. As a result, controllers must keep planes flying at
the same altitude separated by five miles. Normally, such planes
can be safely separated by two miles.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the larger separations, Logan was accepting only 16
planes an hour Saturday, compared with the normal 38.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a safety issue,'' said Jones, because the spacing of
airplanes had been adjusted to the capabilities of remaining
equipment. But installing and testing the new equipment would take
several days, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
