<HEADER>
A4482 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-CUBAN-BOY-NYT &LR;      04-22 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CUBAN-BOY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A PRECIPITOUS RAID 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Sunday, April 23:
</P>
<P>
   The sight of heavily armed federal agents breaking into Lazaro
Gonzalez's Miami home before dawn Saturday to take custody of Elian
Gonzalez is a disturbing picture for all Americans, and is likely
to haunt the country for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno should have given the two branches
of the Gonzalez family more time to try to resolve the case
amicably, and she should have applied more legal pressure on the
Miami relatives before battering down their door to remove Elian.
</P>
<P>
   The first question that must be answered in the days ahead is
why Reno, who had shown admirable restraint, did not let the latest
round of negotiations over Elian's fate proceed until any hope of
settlement was exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that the Miami relatives had used discussion and
mediation as a stalling tactic in recent weeks, always introducing
yet another condition when a resolution seemed within reach. For
the last nine days, they had also defied the law by refusing to
turn over Elian after their right to care for him had been revoked
by the Immigration and Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   But there seemed to be some prospect Friday night that
conditions for transferring Elian to his father could still be
worked out in talks that lasted past 3 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Before subjecting the boy to a forcible night-time raid, Reno
should have directed escalating law-enforcement pressure against
the adults in the Miami family. Though the issue of whether the boy
is entitled to apply for asylum has yet to be decided by the
courts, there was no doubt about the legal obligation of the Miami
relatives to comply with the INS order to return Elian to his
father.
</P>
<P>
   To reinforce that ruling, Reno should have sought a federal
court order instructing Lazaro Gonzalez to produce the child. If he
still refused, he could have been held in contempt of court and
faced arrest and criminal penalties.
</P>
<P>
   It is fortunate that the raid ended without bloodshed, and that
there was not a confrontation with Cuban American supporters of the
Miami relatives. But the emotional wounds for Elian will not be
easy to heal. He is back with his father, where he belongs, but
Saturday's traumatic events can only compound the child's
psychological distress.
</P>
<P>
   The rule of law is sacred in America, and the Miami relatives'
defiance was unacceptable. But the manner in which the law is
upheld in a free society can be as important as the law itself. In
this case, the methods used by the government are likely to
overshadow and diminish the principle that Reno and President
Clinton set out to defend.
</P>
<P>
   The first icon of the new century for those who question the
administration of justice in America is certain to be the
photograph of a federal agent in assault gear approaching Elian in
the middle of the night with an automatic rifle at the ready.
</P>
<P>
   Reno was quick to note that the agent did not have his finger on
the trigger, and was not pointing the rifle at Elian, but that
offers little solace to a nation that is wondering on Sunday why
the government, with all its power, could not have acted with
greater restraint and continued patience.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
