<HEADLINE>
ALFRED PECK O'HARA, 80, FORMER BACARDI PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Calif., Puerto Rico)  By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Alfred Peck O'Hara, a Manhattan lawyer, former
federal prosecutor and past president of Bacardi Corp., died April
15 at his home in Patterson, his birthplace in Putnam County. He
was 80.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his death, O'Hara, known as Pete, was with the
Manhattan-based international law firm of Kelley Drye &AMP; Warren,
which he joined in 1986. Before that, he was a senior partner in
Rogers Hoge &AMP; Hills, dealing chiefly with trademark and
unfair-competition matters.
</P>
<P>
   From 1976 to 1987, he was president and chairman of Bacardi
Corp. of San Juan, Puerto Rico, the liquor concern.
</P>
<P>
   He also sat on the boards of numerous companies and
organizations, including the National Association of Manufacturers
and Bacardi Capital Ltd. He was a chairman of Guiding Eyes for the
Blind, which provides guide dogs to the blind and sight-impaired.
At the time of his death, he was a member of its board.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1940s he handled the incorporation of the National Cancer
Foundation, now known as Cancer Care. He was also the
organization's trustee and national campaign chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Pete O'Hara graduated from Syracuse University in 1940 and
received his law degree at Fordham University two years later. He
started his legal career as secretary to a U.S. District Court
judge and went into private practice in 1946.
</P>
<P>
   He was an assistant U.S. attorney and chief of the civil
division for the Southern District of New York in Manhattan for
three years during the 1950s. He handled major cases involving tax
fraud and racketeering before joining Rogers Hoge &AMP; Hills as a
senior partner in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   He was a counsel to the U.S. Trademark Association and secretary
of the City Bar Association. He also taught trial practice at New
York University for several years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, he oversaw successful litigation in foreign
jurisdictions over the issue of private ownership of trademarks.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hara is survived by his wife, Martha Stein O'Hara; his two
daughters, Jane Ann O'Hara of Woodstock, Ga., and Margaret O'Hara
Vodrey of Los Angeles; two sons, Peter J. of Poughquag and John E.
of Pawling; 10 grandchildren; and four great-grandchildren. His
first wife, Muriel Sandberg O'Hara, died in 1969 after 29 years of
marriage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
