<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS-LAKERS SERIES WOULD THRILL NBA  
 HILL-DUNCAN GUESSING GAME  
 AESTHETICS OF THE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Phil Jackson sidled up to an NBC producer nearly a month ago and
offered up a rhetorical proposition: ``I bet you guys would love to
see the Knicks and the Lakers in the finals, wouldn't you?''
</P>
<P>
   The producer smiled at the Lakers' coach and left it at that. No
use adding to the conspiracy theories harbored by dozens of
small-market fans who think their Pacers, Jazz or Spurs won't get a
referee's call when it matters most.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, too, they will be crying foul _ the moment Vince
Carter is sent to the free-throw line because Latrell Sprewell
breathed on him in the final seconds of a tight game. After all,
Carter, the skywalking Raptor forward, was pictured in all his
airbrushed, angelic glory this week on the cover of ESPN Magazine
with the heading: ``Must See VC.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Carter and players with flair and panache like
Sacramento's Jason Williams and Chris Webber generate better
ratings, just as genuine rivalries like New York-Los Angeles
generate more fan interest. And at a time when numbers have dipped
considerably, the National Basketball Association and its broadcast
partners are dying for viewers.
</P>
<P>
   But the idea that someone is pulling strings in either the NBA
or NBC corporate offices seems a bit of a reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always amazes me every year there's this conspiracy to get
certain teams into the finals or the conference finals for ratings
or whatever, and I think that takes away so much,'' Doug Collins,
the NBC analyst and former coach, said last week. ``I've never been
one to believe that. Maybe I'm naive, but I think that puts a World
Wrestling Federation mentality on a sport that I think has a lot of
integrity. I hate to see that come up all the time: `NBC wants
so-and-so in the finals so they can get ratings.'''
</P>
<P>
   Just the same, someone out there needs to start watching more
regularly if the league plans to return to the sweeping popularity
it enjoyed in the late 1980s and early 1990s. In 34 NBC telecasts
this season, ratings dipped 21 percent below those for last
season's 28 telecasts. Since Michael Jordan retired before the
1998-99 season started, ratings are down 29 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson might be understating the possibility. Knicks-Lakers may
not only be good for the league and network _ it may be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be great,'' Lakers forward Robert Horry said.
``Hopefully it would bring a lot of happiness back to the NBA.
Because right now, it doesn't seem like the NBA is too happy.
They're trying to bring some happiness back. Cameras in the locker
rooms. Cameras at the end of practice. Microphones everywhere.
After a while, something has to give. Maybe it's us in the
finals.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill, Duncan and Economics
</P>
<P>
   Grant Hill recently laughed at the notion that he was recruiting
his friend and Olympic teammate, Tim Duncan, to join up in Orlando
next season after the two become free agents in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard someone said I was calling him on the cell phone,
lobbying him,'' Hill said. ``I don't even think Tim owns a cell
phone.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan, meanwhile, shot down another rumor that the Spurs had
offered their All-Star center a four-year contract to keep him in
San Antonio until after the 2003-4 season.
</P>
<P>
   When their respective teams are knocked out of the playoffs, the
speculation and rumors about Hill and Duncan will grow
exponentially. Especially because the two share the same attorney,
Lon Babby.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all sounds plausible, but nothing is on the table from
anyone,'' Babby said Friday afternoon by telephone from his
Washington office. ``People can guess all they want and some will
probably be right. But it's really a non-issue with both Grant and
Tim right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Babby said he will sit down with Hill and Duncan independently
after the season. Orlando and Chicago are the major players in the
free-agent market, having cleared millions in salary-cap room to
lure the top players. But the Pistons and the Spurs can negotiate
more lucrative deals to retain their respective franchise players.
</P>
<P>
   Hill is the more likely to leave in a potential sign-and-trade
deal, especially if the Pistons fall short in the first round
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way it'll work is, I'll give them packets analyzing a
team's strength, salary-cap history and whether they're better off
with a short-term or long-term deal,'' Babby said. ``It'll have
what cities have fewer taxes and which ones tax heavily. But the
answer right now to the question `Are they leaning anywhere?' is
no. Not that they've told me.''
</P>
<P>
   There is one player in line for a substantial pay raise this
off-season. Shaquille O'Neal is about to reap another windfall. He
is expected to take advantage of a contract-extension clause in his
seven-year, $121 million deal this summer, a possible three-year
extension that could land him an additional $76 million.
</P>
<P>
   The way the raise-increase works for players whose contracts
were grandfathered into the collective bargaining agreement signed
last year is this: You can get a 5 percent raise over the last year
of your current deal. In O'Neal's case, that would make his salary
nearly $23 million. In the next two years, players are entitled to
a 12.5 percent raise over the last year of their deal.
</P>
<P>
   If the Lakers offer the maximum and O'Neal accepts as expected,
he would earn $24.15 million in the 2003-4 season, $25.875 million
in the 2004-5 season and another $25.875 million in 2005-6 _ at the
age of 34. With the current rules, only Kevin Garnett stands to
make more over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal said his agent, Leonard Armato, convinced him to
renegotiate after four years rather than just sign for the long
term. He was able to exercise an escape clause with Orlando in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where a lot of veterans messed up and didn't realize
the economics had changed,'' O'Neal said. ``Like Karl Malone. When
they first started giving out big money, Malone said, `OK, I'll
take 10 years with no outs.' Scottie Pippen did the same thing.
Then when the money game changed, those guys were upset about the
deals they had. Oh well.''
</P>
<P>
   Better Stats Through Rules
</P>
<P>
   Whether a migration of underskilled underclassmen was to blame
or merely a heavy concentration on defense, the aesthetic quality
of the NBA has taken its hits over the last few years. The mix of
bruising and sometimes bad play has resulted in low scores, fewer
offensive possessions and eyesores on the court.
</P>
<P>
   But the rule changes implemented this year to prevent much of
the chucking and grabbing by defensive players have apparently made
for at least a more appealing product.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in three years, scoring and field-goal
percentage improved. Teams scored an average of 97.5 points per
game this season, up nearly six points from last season's 91.6
average. Teams shot an average of nearly 45 percent from the field,
as compared with .437 during last season's truncated season. Teams
also took about four more shots per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if the rules had everything to do with it, but
that's what people have always wanted to see _ a more wide-open
game,'' the Lakers' Kobe Bryant said recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``For so long, the Eastern Conference was all about who could
stop who on defense. Now, you look at Vince Carter, Tracy McGrady,
Eddie Jones, Sprewell; they have some real athletes out there.
Things are changing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 1837EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
