<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PLAYOFFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON HOCKEY: UPSETTING DEVELOPMENTS, BUT FEW UPSETS
</HEADLINE>
  By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Angry about a slashing penalty, Chris Simon of the
Washington Capitals took a seat in the penalty box but he did not
sit still Friday night. Simon began bashing a television camera and
then he threw an extra puck onto the ice. When this earned him an
additional 10-minute misconduct penalty, Simon left the box for the
locker room, smashing his stick along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in this first-round series of the Stanley Cup playoffs,
Simon missed a game while suspended for cross-checking Pittsburgh's
Peter Popovic in the head. With the Capitals now out of the
tournament and idle until October, Simon can begin serving a
five-month misconduct for trashing, if not trash-talking. But he
also deserves some credit. The man with hockey's longest hair and
the most goals on his team behaved in a way that was appropriately
symbolic of Washington's shabby play.
</P>
<P>
   After finishing second in the Eastern Conference in the regular
season, Simon and the Capitals left the playoffs Friday night after
losing for the fourth time in five games against the Penguins. The
score was 2-1, the winning goal coming when Jaromir Jagr of
Pittsburgh passed a puck that deflected off Washington defenseman
Calle Johansson and behind goalie Olaf Kolzig. There have been a
few strange goals like this around the NHL in a first round that is
coming to an end either Monday or Tuesday. But there have been very
few upsets.
</P>
<P>
   Some favorites won easily, like Detroit sweeping Los Angeles and
New Jersey sweeping Florida. Only five games were needed for
Philadelphia to eliminate Buffalo, for Dallas to oust Edmonton and
for Colorado to finish the Phoenix season. The most surprising
series may be St. Louis-San Jose; the league-champion Blues trail
the eighth-seeded Sharks, three games to two.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL can be grateful for that one. Without a 5-3 victory by
the Blues on Friday night, the league would be without a Sunday
afternoon game for the ABC network, its new partner. However, in
view of hockey's recent low ratings, it may be just a mixed
blessing. Bigger audiences are found for the Weather Channel, which
people tune in to watch spring flowers grow. Oh, but they are
watching _ and listening to _ Hockey Night in Canada for the Battle
of Ontario. Going into Game 5 last Saturday night, Toronto and
Ottawa were tied at two victories each.
</P>
<P>
   Goalie madness is the theme here. Not to be outdone by Curtis
Joseph of the Maple Leafs, who accidentally knocked down a referee
during a display of temper, Tom Barrasso of Ottawa got even by
cursing on air during an interview on the Canadian Broadcasting
Corp. ``I could really give a hoot what you people think,'' is the
PG translation of Barrasso's words. This was after a victory in
Game 4. This is Barrasso in a good mood! Where was this ray of
sunshine when the edgy Fox network had the U.S. television rights?
</P>
<P>
   Barrasso is not the only one proving that, while sticks and
pucks may break your bones, words can hurt you, too. After the
Penguins ousted the Capitals, Matthew Barnaby of Pittsburgh
reflected again on the proclamations of Ron Wilson, the Washington
coach. When told his team would have to play an extra early game in
Pittsburgh because of a building conflict, Wilson said the Capitals
could play all seven on the road and still win the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an embarrassment to the whole Capitals organization,''
Barnaby said of Wilson's comments. ``Why come in and embarrass a
team and give them life? That's what he did. Total disrespect for
our team. Our biggest motivation was him. We ended it in five. I
don't think he'll be talking too loudly.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnaby and the Penguins have a few days to talk about the next
round against the Flyers, who usually beat them in both the regular
season and the playoffs. The Flyers will still be without Eric
Lindros, their former captain, who is recovering from a concussion.
Another return in doubt is that of Roger Neilson, the Philadelphia
coach, who wants to come back after cancer surgery. Management,
taking a wait-and-see position, plans to talk with both Neilson and
doctors. The fourth-seeded Devils will play either No. 3 Toronto or
No. 6 Ottawa. The Devils would have a home-ice advantage against
only the Senators.
</P>
<P>
   In the Western Conference, Detroit, Colorado and Dallas all
await the St. Louis-San Jose result. If the Blues win, they play
the Red Wings. If the Sharks win, they play the defending-champion
Stars. The West winner has taken the trophy in the last four
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   For those planning their viewing that far ahead, some games in
the finals will be on ABC with Al ``Miracles'' Michaels at the
mike. The few viewers who watched last week might have noticed that
ABC has retained the aggravating Fox habit of showing long
stretches of action from low cameras behind the net.
</P>
<P>
   This takes a sport that is difficult to televise and makes it
almost impossible for even devoted fans to comprehend. ABC had
better hope Chris Simon watches on Canadian television instead of
American. If he gets frustrated, he may destroy some more cameras.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
