<HEADER>
A4490 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-WELFARE-HIRINGS-NY     04-22 0282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WELFARE-HIRINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR DEFENDS WELFARE HIRINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A day after the Manhattan district attorney's office
said it had begun an investigation into the activities of a
Virginia company when it was preparing a bid for New York City
welfare contracts, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said the accusations the
company faced were ``created stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody acted appropriately,'' the mayor said at a news
conference Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's remarks were his first on the subject since The New
York Times reported on Thursday that the Virginia company, Maximus,
had acknowledged hiring the father-in-law and a family friend of
the city's welfare commissioner, Jason Turner, just as it was
trying to secure $100 million in contracts to administer the city's
welfare-to-work program, a cornerstone of the mayor's welfare
overhaul package.
</P>
<P>
   Turner's staff has released a letter that the city's Conflict of
Interest Board sent to Turner in February advising him, in an
informal opinion, that his father-in-law's work for Maximus did not
appear to be a problem. But Turner had sought the opinion on Feb.
8, two months after his agency had selected Maximus for a major
contract, which officials said ran counter to a preferred procedure
of seeking an opinion before contracts are awarded.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Giuliani said Turner and Maximus were blameless.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will turn out that everybody gets cleared,'' he said. ``The
New York Times will write all sorts of stories making it appear
they did something wrong, and they will be all cleared and they
won't write all kinds of stories saying we were wrong to malign
them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
