<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4491 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-POLICE-SHOOTING-1S     04-22 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-SHOOTING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE KILL MAN WHO THEY SAY ATTACKED HIS MOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Rewrites story throughout.) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A mentally disturbed man accused of beating and
slashing his elderly mother before storming onto a Queens County
street with a handgun and knife raised in the air was shot at least
seven times and killed Saturday morning by police officers, the
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The man, James Murphy Jr., 43, was killed in a shootout with the
police on his street after he walked toward a group of officers,
dropped a knife and his light-blue denim jacket into a puddle of
water, pointed a black Luger handgun at them and began yelling,
according to law-enforcement officials and accounts from witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The officers began firing, witnesses and police officials said,
after Murphy refused to comply with repeated demands for him to
drop the weapon. The officers had gone to the Murphy home, on 53rd
Avenue, after receiving a 911 call alleging that Murphy was beating
and slashing his 70-year-old mother in the front yard.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses and police officials said that a neighbor, Michael
Koto, 31, had helped the woman get away from her son, who was
wielding a knife, before officers arrived at about 9:30 a.m. By
then, Murphy had gone back into the house and retrieved a handgun,
the witnesses and officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said that Murphy fired shots at two officers,
who ran for cover, on 53rd Avenue, before heading in the opposite
direction. ``He fired several rounds at us, and our officers began
returning fire,'' said Deputy Chief Thomas Fahey, a police
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   At the corner of 53rd Avenue and 74th Street, witnesses and
police officials said, Murphy was confronted by a group of
officers. He shed his jacket, and, they said, began yelling ``I
guess you got me now,'' as the officers pleaded with him to drop
his weapon. ``It looked like `High Noon,''' said Frank Connolly,
68, a neighbor of the Murphy family.
</P>
<P>
   The officers fired at least 14 shots, after Murphy refused to
drop the weapon, officials said. Witnesses said that Murphy
stumbled across a sidewalk to a fence, where he stayed until an
officer ran over and placed his boot on the Luger handgun. Murphy
was taken to Elmhurst General Hospital, where he was pronounced
dead at 10:17 a.m., officials added.
</P>
<P>
   One police investigator at the scene, where dozens of residents
congregated during or immediately after the shootout, said that
Murphy apparently began attacking his mother after she told him
that she did not support his plan to leave the United States and
move to Poland. The mother, who had been slashed on the shoulder
and bruised, was taken to St. John's Hospital where she was in
stable condition Saturday afternoon, the officials added.
</P>
<P>
   Koto's mother, Emmi, who harbored Murphy's mother in her home
until the police arrived, said the woman was afraid her son was
going to kill her husband, who was in the house at the time, or the
family's animals.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors said that in recent weeks, Murphy, who had spent much
of his career in the U.S. Navy and as a teacher at the U.S.
Merchant Marine Academy in Kings Point, had begun to show signs of
being troubled, including rambling, walking the streets all day
with his head low, and losing 20 pounds in one week.
</P>
<P>
   Connolly, the neighbor, said he became so concerned that a few
weeks ago he asked Murphy's father to see if he could hide the
handgun and rifle that were in the house from his son.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 1853EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000422.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4492 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-BLUEJAYS-NY     04-22 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-BLUEJAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONE, STILL SEARCHING FOR HIS FIRST VICTORY, IS ROUGHED UP BY THE
BLUE JAYS
</HEADLINE>
  By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The New York Yankees came here looking to extend an
eight-game winning streak against a Toronto pitching staff that
sported a 7.25 earned run average. But in the first two games of
the series, the Yankees and the Blue Jays have reversed roles.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' offense has hardly made a ripple, and their
starting pitching is being pounded. David Cone was hammered for
eight runs in three-plus innings and Toronto's Kelvim Escobar
allowed nine hits in pitching the Blue Jays' second consecutive
complete game against the Yankees in an 8-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Cone has yet to get a win in any of his four starts, and his ERA
is 10.70. And while there have been times when his stuff has been
better than his results this year, Cone had a terrible game
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Cone tinkers continually, with his delivery, with his arm angle,
with the position of his foot on the rubber. Manager Joe Torre made
a more substantive adjustment before Saturday's game, inserting Jim
Leyritz into the lineup as the catcher for Cone.
</P>
<P>
   The first reason Torre presented for the change was to give
Jorge Posada a day off, but there was probably more to it than
that. The Yankees, after all, just had a day off Thursday, and
Torre and some of the players had grumbled about having so many
scheduled days off early in the season.
</P>
<P>
   Cone preferred the veteran Joe Girardi to be his catcher in
recent seasons, and it may be that the coaching staff sensed that
Posada and Cone were not working together. Torre said Posada came
to him and mentioned that Cone seemed frustrated with Posada _
something that Posada might not have volunteered a year ago, Torre
said, because Posada was used more sparingly. The working
discomfort between Cone and Posada, Torre mentioned, had more to do
with pitch selection than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Torre started Leyritz in an effort to aid Cone, leaving open the
possibility that he might maintain the pairing if it worked. But
Cone may have been beyond help Saturday. He had good stuff in his
first two outings _ a good fastball and not enough control _ and
surrendered 12 runs in 7 2/3 innings. It appeared Cone was facing
the Blue Jays with almost no pitches at his disposal.
</P>
<P>
   Cone jogged out of the visitors' bullpen to pitch the bottom of
the first inning, rather than out of the dugout, a routine he
adopted before starting against Texas earlier in the week; this
might help him stay loose before the first inning. When he reached
the mound, Cone kicked at the dirt in front of the rubber for
almost a minute, creating a small canal, before warming up. He took
his place on the right side of the rubber and looked for the sign
from Leyritz.
</P>
<P>
   Fastball. Cone nodded, threw a ball inside.
</P>
<P>
   Fastball. Jose Cruz Jr., crushed a tremendous home run, an
estimated 429 feet; if you were sitting at a table in the
restaurant in center field, there might have been an instant of
fear before you remembered the glass would protect you from any
monstrous home run. It was the second time in four starts that Cone
permitted a home run to the first batter he faced; Darin Erstad
slugged a homer against him April 5.
</P>
<P>
   Like Erstad's home run that day, Cruz's was a portent, despite
Cone's incredible history of success against almost every hitter in
the Toronto lineup. Cruz came into the game with one hit in 12
at-bats against Cone, Homer Bush 1 for 8, Carlos Delgado 1 for 27
with 14 strikeouts, Tony Batista 2 for 19, Darren Fletcher 4 for 18
and Marty Cordova 1 for 9.
</P>
<P>
   But after shortstop Derek Jeter made a throwing error on a
routine grounder with one out, Delgado ripped a double inside the
right-field line, Raul Mondesi scoring after the ball bounced
awkwardly against a ball boy's stool. Brad Fullmer dumped a double
into left-center field. Blue Jays 3, Yankees 0.
</P>
<P>
   Cone tried a breaking ball against Batista, hung it, and the
Blue Jays' third baseman bashed it over the wall, his eighth homer
of the year. Cone's face is usually flushed from effort when he
pitches. At this moment, his face mostly showed self-loathing.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Grimsley scrambled to warm up, before Cone closed out the
inning with back-to-back strikeouts. Torre undoubtedly wanted to
give Cone as much time as he could to settle down, to find a
groove, to gather command, and Cone shut out the Blue Jays in the
second and third innings. The Yankees scored a run against Escobar
in the fourth inning, Paul O'Neill driving home a run after Jeter
tripled.
</P>
<P>
   Cone hit Cordova with a wayward pitch in the fourth inning _
this didn't appear to have anything to do with the numerous hit
batsmen Friday _ and Alex Gonzalez pulled a single through the hole
between short and third. Grimsley jumped up in the bullpen and
resumed warming up, joined shortly thereafter by Allen Watson.
</P>
<P>
   Cruz was next and Cone fell behind two balls and no strikes. He
threw split-fingered fastballs on consecutive pitches to even the
count _ this is the conventional wisdom on Cruz, that he will
murder fastballs and has trouble hitting anything with unusual
movement. Then Cone tried to jam Cruz with a fastball but left it
over the inner half of the plate, and again, Cruz bashed it. Even
before the three-run homer landed inside the right field foul pole,
Cone was grimacing.
</P>
<P>
   Cone's day was over, as was the game, for all practical
purposes. The Yankees' offense, which had forced Chris Carpenter to
throw just 88 pitches Friday, was stifled again with ease. Escobar
averaged about 10 pitches per inning, as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
