<DOCNO> NYT20000422.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4493 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ELIAN-RAID-0423-COX     04-22 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-RAID-0423-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SURPRISE SEIZURE OF ELIAN 'HAPPENED SO FAST'
 &HT;    With CUBA-ELIAN-0423.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Dr. Lydia Usategui and her husband Alfredo Manrara spent
Friday night at the house of Elian Gonzalez's Miami family, certain
that something bad might happen.
</P>
<P>
   A child psychiatrist, Usategui had examined Elian months ago,
and recently joined with other members of the Cuban-American
Psychiatric Association in strongly criticizing the plan by federal
officials to immediately take Elian from the home of his Miami
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   At 5 a.m. EST Saturday, she and her husband were sitting on the
steps of a large apartment building immediately next door to the
Gonzalez home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw them pull back the barricade at the end of the street
and I told my wife,'' said Manrara. ``Then Armando (Gutierrez, the
family spokesman) ran out of the house yelling, 'They're coming,
they're coming.'''
</P>
<P>
   A small caravan of stark white minivans sped to the front of the
house. The doors flung open and out poured black-clad federal
officers, Manrara said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran to the front of the house and they came up,'' he said.
``They had guns and . . . ordered everybody back and sprayed us
with gas. They stormed the door, breaking it down with some kind of
ram. They ran inside the house. It all happened so fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Usategui, meanwhile, ran around to the small home's back door,
and found three officers with guns trained on several Gonzalez
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told them to get on the ground and they had rifles
pointing at them,'' she said. ``They told me to get down so I got
down on all fours. They told me to look down. I imagined that if I
moved I'd get killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the home, officers held family members and their lawyers
at gunpoint, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   Donato Dalrymple, one of the the fisherman who rescued Elian on
Thanksgiving Day, was asleep on a couch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grabbed the little boy,'' he later told reporters. ``He was
screaming in English, 'Help me, help me.' They busted the door down
and it was if they were taking a terrorist. They grabbed him
physically. He was terrified. They threw a blanket over his head.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside, Usategui said she suddenly heard someone in the house
shout, ``Bingo, bingo, bingo,'' the apparent sign that the boy had
been taken.
</P>
<P>
   As the officers exited the front door, ``they yanked people out
of the way,'' Manrara said. ``They sprayed everybody again. I was
thrown against the fence and my jacket was torn. It was brutal and
provocative.''
</P>
<P>
   Usategui was still shaken hours later, saying she had never seen
anything like it in her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so fast,'' she said. ``This was the most dramatic and
traumatic thing they could have done to this boy. It was
inflammatory to the community, done just after the anniversary of
the Bay of Pigs, on Easter weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 1856EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
