<P>
   (NYT13) DILI, East Timor -- April 22, 2000 -- TIMOR-LANGUAGE --
East Timor has not been on its own as a modern nation, its history
overlaid by more than 400 years of Portuguese colonialism followed
by 24 years of Indonesian occupation that ended last year. An East
Timorese boy in a classroom in Los Palos, about 250 kilometers150
miles east of the capital, Dili. The language in which its children
will be taught has yet to be determined in East Timor. (Anastasia
Vrachnos/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) DENVER -- April 22, 2000 -- EARTH-DAY -- Earth Day
participants celebrated around the globe on Saturday in an
extravaganza of entertainment, advocacy and politics.
Environmentalists and supporters participated in events in 183
countries for the 30th Earth Day. Echo, a three-year-old Augur
Buzzard, a member of the hawk family, takes flight toward a log
baited with dinner as part of his training exercises under the
watch of handler Molly Maloy. Vienna will took part in festivities
at the Denver Zoo, Saturday. (Kevin Moloney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) BELLEVUE, Wash. -- April 22, 2000 -- DOTCOM-FUTURE --
Jackie Erickson, the customer retention manager for drugstore.com,
an online pharmacy, says she is focused more on keeping
drugstore.com's business than on stock prices. Erickson has no
problem with the notion that a shakeout is looming in the Internet
industry. ``Pretty soon,'' she says, ``the market will separate the
men from the boys.'' (Larry Davis/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) AMARGOSA VALLEY, Nev. -- April 22, 2000 --
NUCLEAR-MOUNTAIN-3 -- Ian Zabarte, the Secretary of State of the
Western Shoshone Tribal Council, secures the Western Shoshone flag
near a campsite at the foot of Yucca Mountain. Tribal members
gathered this spring to organize ways to prevent a proposed high
level nuclear waste repository from being built at Yucca Mountain
which the Shoshone say is on their land. The mountain is a sacred
site for the tribal nation. (Monica Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) AMARGOSA VALLEY, Nev. -- April 22, 2000 --
NUCLEAR-MOUNTAIN-2 --Raymond Yowell, chief of the Western Shoshone
National Council, the traditional governing body the Western
Shoshone Nation. Yowell lead the fourth annual spring gathering of
of his people and other Indians at Yucca Mountain. The social
gathering was a strategy session for Native Americans to discuss
ways to stop the government from making the mountain a nuclear
dump. (Monica Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) AMARGOSA VALLEY, Nev. -- April 22, 2000 --
NUCLEAR-MOUNTAIN-1 --For members of the Western Shoshone Nation in
Armagosa Valley, Nev., Yucca Mountain, slated to become the home
for all eternity to 77,000 tons of highly lethal nuclear waste from
across the United States, is sacred. The land, 100 miles northwest
of Las Vegas by the Nevada Test Site, the proving ground for the
atomic bomb, is part of what was once a vast territory the Western
Shoshones roamed, and still claim as their own. Western Shoshone's
Silver Eagle Youth Dancers perform at Yucca Mountain. (Monica
Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) ANDREWS AIR FORCE BASE, Md. -- April 22, 2000 --
CUBAN-BOY -- Members of the media gather outside an entrance gate
of Andrews Air Force Base where Elian Gonzalez was taken following
a flight from Miami, Saturday. Seized by armed agents before dawn,
Gonzalez was reunited with his father after a frantic and forceful
end to a five-month standoff between the government and the Cuban
boy's Miami relatives. (Justin Lane/The New York Times)
</P>
