<P>
   (NYT18) SHELTER ISLAND, N.Y. -- April 22, 2000 --
NY-ISLAND-SENIORS-2 --Because the nation is aging rapidly, what is
happening on Shelter Island, N.Y., while unusual, may be the
harbinger of a returning way of life; the old here aged here and
stayed here. Henrietta Roberts, 67, the part-time coordinator of
Senior Services, checks in on residents like Peggy Joyce, 91, who
has Alzheimer's. Roberts likes the idea of an all-senior center on
Shelter Island because of the services and personnel it could draw,
but she is torn; her 15-year-old grandson also needs a safe place
to drop in with his friends. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) SHELTER ISLAND, N.Y. -- April 22, 2000 --
NY-ISLAND-SENIORS-1 --More than a third of Shelter Island's 2,300
winter residents are over 60, which is twice the average nationally
and in the metropolitan area. The percentage may be even higher in
summer when the population swells to about 10,000. Snugly sheltered
by geography and sensibility from the workaday bustle of Long
Island's North Fork and the antsy glamour of the Hamptons to the
south, this summer resort island has become a kind of year-round
Elder Dorado. Shelter Island as seen from a departing ferry. (Ruth
Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
