<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4498 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-NJ-1STLD-WR     04-22 1309
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-NJ-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGRY CUBAN-AMERICANS DEMONSTRATE IN NEW YORK AND NEW JERSEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to rewrite with reporting on scene in New York and other new
material.)  
(ART ADV: NYT Photos 3,5,6 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Chanting ``Libertad para Elian!'' scores of angry
protesters mounted raucous demonstrations in New York City and in
the Cuban-American stronghold of Union City, N.J., Saturday against
the forcible removal of Elian Gonzalez from the home of his Miami
relatives in a predawn raid by armed federal agents.
</P>
<P>
   About 70 protesters, clotting a New Jersey highway, tied up
traffic in and out of the Lincoln Tunnel, one of the transportation
links between New Jersey and New York City, for nearly half an hour
just after noon, and slowed traffic on nearby John F. Kennedy
Boulevard to a trickle. Hundreds of car horns blared, but _ judging
by Cuban flags waving out windows _ there seemed to be as many
sympathizers in the chorus as drivers angered by the delays.
</P>
<P>
   In Manhattan, about 250 demonstrators gathered at 39th Street
and Lexington Avenue behind barricades, a block from the Cuban
Mission to the United Nations. They blocked traffic briefly, waved
Cuban flags, denounced President Clinton and Attorney General Janet
Reno as tools of President Fidel Castro and likened the Miami raid
to the tactics of a dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the Manhattan rally were non-Cubans who, like protesters
on both sides of the Hudson, had been enraged by the striking,
nationally televised pictures of a free-lance photographer who had
been in the Miami house at the time of the raid. The pictures
showed an agent in riot gear holding an assault rifle in front of
the cowering boy and carrying him away as he sobs for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of a role model do we have in Clinton?'' asked Peter
Brennan, one of the demonstrators. ``The picture of the machine gun
on the kid? That is cruel. How could the president allow this to
happen?''
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Conlon, another non-Cuban protester, was also
disillusioned. ``To threaten a child like this?'' he said. ``I am
deeply ashamed.''
</P>
<P>
   And Judy and Richard Kemp said they were stunned that the
government had taken the action, especially on the eve of Easter.
``The fact that on Holy Saturday they ripped him out of his home is
the most atrocious thing,'' Mrs. Kemp said.
</P>
<P>
   Pictures of Elian bobbed on poles in the crowd, with freshly
painted signs proclaiming: ``What rule of law?'' and ``Child abuse,
Reno style.''
</P>
<P>
   The Manhattan demonstration was noisy but peaceful, for the most
part, but several protesters burned flags and tried to cross police
barricades, and one man was arrested and accused of assaulting a
police captain. Later, the group marched to the U.N. headquarters,
where the protest disbanded.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after Elian was seized and flown to a reunion with his
father near Washington, political leaders in New York and New
Jersey joined protesters in expressing disgust and resentment over
the decision to use force in the midst of negotiations to resolve
an international custody battle that has been under way for nearly
five months.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the Republican mayor, Rudolph Giuliani, angry and
using extremely harsh language, said the Clinton administration had
disgraced itself in what he called ``an orchestrated plot by
Castro,'' and had sent ''storm troopers'' to ``rip a boy away from
a family that is caring for him.''
</P>
<P>
   New York Gov. George Pataki, also a Republican, also expressed
shock. ``It's very upsetting and offensive that people with machine
guns and fatigues would break down a door to take a child out of a
home in America,'' he said at an Earth Day ceremony in Westchester
County. ``This is something that would happen in the Soviet Union,
not in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, U.S. Rep, Robert Menendez, a Union City Democrat
who has been involved in the negotiations, called the raid ``a
despicable use of the force of the federal government against a
humble, unarmed and law-abiding family, who had only one interest:
Elian's future and his best interests as a child.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Menendez, a Cuban-American and a frequent
critic of the Castro government, said: ``It's really a day of
infamy. To take a child out at gunpoint, awakened from his sleep in
the dark of night by masked agents, reminds us of the tactics of
the Castro dictatorship, not of the democracy we enjoy in the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Reno, Menendez said: ``Now that she has made this
decision to use the full force of the federal government to uphold
the father's rights, I hope she's going to use the full force of
the government to uphold the boy's rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Raul Garcia of Union City, a Democrat who was born in Cuba
but grew up in Union City, called the Miami raid ``despicable'' and
added, ``It's a sad day for the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey protesters began gathering in a light rain about
10:30 a.m. at Bergenline Avenue and 41st Street, the main
intersection in Union City, which for decades has been a center of
Cuban-American life in the metropolitan region.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are here to reaffirm the value of a single human life, of a
6-year-old child who has in fact not received a full hearing in a
competent court of law,'' Lazaro Alvarez, a human rights and
anti-Castro advocate, shouted as protesters in the nation's
second-largest Cuban-American community waved flags and banners,
honked horns and voiced dismay over the sudden turn of events.
</P>
<P>
   A few protesters were wrapped in Cuban flags. Some held American
flags upside down. Others held banners proclaiming ``First Waco,
Now Elian,'' and ``Reno-Clinton-Gore, you can celebrate with your
friend Castro.'' They blocked traffic, sang the Cuban national
anthem and chanted ``Liberty for Elian.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Frontela, who lives in North Bergen, N.J., and came to
the United States six years ago from Santa Clara, Cuba, was angry
and sad. ``Fidel Castro bought Bill Clinton and Janet Reno,'' he
said. He said he had heard Clinton on the radio, addressing the
nation after the raid, and said, ``The Bill Clinton who was
speaking today was Fidel Castro.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before noon, the demonstrators left the center of Union
City, and marched south on Kennedy Boulevard, snarling traffic in
the four northbound and southbound lanes. As car horns blared,
Cuban flags appeared out the windows of many cars, and it appeared
that as many drivers were sympathetic to the demonstrators as not.
</P>
<P>
   But when the protesters reached the intersection of Interstate
495, the main highway feeding traffic into and out of the Lincoln
Tunnel, the sympathy evaporated, and for nearly half an hour
traffic was stalled and drivers were clearly angry.
</P>
<P>
   As cars, trucks and buses backed up for miles and motorists
honked in frustration, the protesters shouted, ``You're going
nowhere!'' A man with a megaphone screamed continuously, ``Free
Elian!'' and ``Freedom!''
</P>
<P>
   Three boys, 8 to 11 years old, lay in the westbound lanes in
front of a Greyhound bus. One, Julio Flores Jr., 11, of Union City,
gave an interview flat on his back. ``The U.S. government is
contradicting itself,'' he said. ``They say they don't want to
traumatize the child, but they go into the house with guns pointed
at him. Reno and Clinton are tools for Castro and communism.''
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of police officers lined the roadway on both sides, but
did nothing to break up the protest, and the demonstrators
dissolved their clot voluntarily and returned to downtown Union
City without further incident. The Union City police later
described the demonstration as peaceful, and said there had been no
complaints and no arrests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
