<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4499 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-SWM-POPOV-NYT &LR;      04-22 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWM-POPOV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPOV'S LOYALTY TO RUSSIAN WAYS COMES AT AN IMMEASURABLE PRICE
</HEADLINE>
  By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THREDBO VILLAGE, Australia _ Alexander Popov was talking about
his wife and young son, about the demands of being a new
International Olympic Committee member and about struggling to find
the motivation to keep pulling his long, lean, extraordinarily
supple body out of bed and through the water well before dawn. And
as he talked about the changes in his life and his attitude on the
terrace of a hotel in this mountain resort, he calmly brushed away
fly after fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Australian salute,'' he joked, as his big hand moved
languidly left and right in the midst of a southern hemisphere
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Popov, the most successful Olympic swimmer of the 1990s, has
been living in Australia since 1992, long enough to pepper his
English with colloquialisms, long enough to begin building a house
in the Australian capital of Canberra, but not long enough to
change his mind about the nation he represents.
</P>
<P>
   A number of other coaches and athletes from the former Soviet
Union have switched allegiances, including the women's pole vaulter
Tatyana Grigorieva and the men's pole-vaulter Dmitry Markov, who
both compete for Australia, or Lenny Krayzelburg, the backstroker
who is now breaking world records for the United States after
moving there with his parents from Ukraine as a teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   But Popov has remained loyal to Russia in name if not address.
He reads as much Tolstoy as his weary body will allow him to keep
his eyes open for; he watches the Russian language news, which is
aired each morning on an Australian cultural channel. His wife is
the former Russian Olympic swimmer Daria Shmeleva, and their
2-year-old son, who not surprisingly has already begun to swim, is
named Vladimir.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made my reputation as a Russian swimmer, and I plan to
remain a Russian swimmer,'' Popov said.
</P>
<P>
   Nationality is an increasingly anachronistic distinction in a
sports world in which more porous borders have blurred identities.
What should it matter if Popov is Russian or Australian?
</P>
<P>
   But Popov's decision is costing him, particularly with the
Summer Olympics in Sydney coming into full view and his sport about
to be showcased as it has rarely been in this country, where
swimmers are icons and their races often televised in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   If Popov, the two-time defending Olympic champion in the 50- and
100-meter freestyle, were Australian, he would be on billboards and
television screens pitching goods and services, and feathering his
nest for the retirement that is expected to come in the wake of his
third Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he were Australian, he'd probably be making close to one
million Australian dollars a year in endorsement deals,'' said Rob
Woodhouse, an agent, who won a bronze medal in the 1984 Games in
Los Angeles in the 400 individual medley.
</P>
<P>
   That would mean more than $600,000 U.S. a year for the world's
greatest freestyler. Instead, he must settle for considerably less
than that and considerably less than the annual amount earned by
his training partner Michael Klim or the world's latest freestyle
sensation, a 17-year-old swimmer from Sydney, Ian Thorpe.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Klim nor Thorpe has won a medal in an Olympics. And
while their training is generously subsidized by the Australian
swimming federation, Popov must pay 100 Australian dollars a day to
train at the Australian Institute of Sport with his coach Gennady
Touretsky, the former Soviet national sprint coach who works for
the Australians but has remained Popov's mentor and guide through
often troubled waters since 1990. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The financial thing is very difficult for Alex,'' Touretsky
said. ``He has sponsors, a few, but here in Australia he has none.
There is basically an embargo for him here because he swims for
Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no embargo on more gold, but the situation will be
quite different in Sydney than it was in Atlanta, where Popov held
off the young American Gary Hall Jr. to become the first man to
defend the 50 and 100 Olympic titles. In 1996, Popov was still a
technical and physical cut above the opposition, but his aura of
invincibility is no longer intact.
</P>
<P>
   The first blow came the month after the Atlanta Olympics, when
he was stabbed in the abdomen with a knife during a late-night
altercation with three watermelon vendors on a Moscow street. The
knife sliced an artery, grazed one of his kidneys and damaged the
pleura, the membrane that encases the lungs.
</P>
<P>
   But Popov's lungs were essentially untouched and after emergency
surgery in Moscow and three months of rehabilitation he returned to
the pool and then managed to defend his European sprint titles the
following August in Seville, Spain.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1998, he was beaten in the final of the 50 in the world
championships in Perth by the American Bill Pilczuk and last August
in Istanbul, he was beaten in both the 50 and the 100 at the
European championships by the new Dutch star, Pieter Van den
Hoogenband. Popov is still the world record-holder in the 100, but
his record time of 48.21 seconds is now six years old and while
young men like Van den Hoogenband, Klim and Thorpe are improving in
the 100, the 28-year-old Popov must now find a way to improve once
more, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``They seem to be going in progression: Atlanta was harder than
Barcelona, and Sydney will be harder than Atlanta,'' Popov said.
``I'm not 21 or 24 anymore. Maybe you're a bit more experienced,
but there are some other guys in the field who are pretty fast at
the moment, and they are young and sort of hungry, and you are sort
of the lazy cat who sits in the chair and asks, `What am I here
for?'''
</P>
<P>
   Lazy or not, the cat is still spending up to six hours a day in
the water and another hour or more in the gymnasium with Touretsky
watching over him, just as he watches over Klim, the world
record-holder in the 100 butterfly and the winner of four gold
medals in the last world championships in Perth. As usual, the two
trained in adjacent lanes during a recent training session at the
Thredbo pool, which at 1,360 meters is the closest thing this
sprawling continent has to a high-altitude training center.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are writing Alex off, but I'm not,'' said Klim, who
also plans to swim the 100 and 200 freestyle events in Sydney.
``I've seen him achieve some great things, and I've learned so much
from him, and I'm thankful he's still around and we can work
together toward the Olympics. Last time, he was still ahead of me,
but now I can sort of relate to him a bit more. But he's going to
be ready for more great things I'm sure when it comes to the
Games.''
</P>
<P>
   Touretsky agreed. ``I know he will win the 100 again,'' he said,
laughing. ``The difference this time is I don't know how.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
