<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4503 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BBO-MINORS-NEWPARK042     04-22 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MINORS-NEWPARK0423-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chattanooga embraces new park
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. _ In the hit movie ``Field of Dreams,'' a
voice tells Iowa farmer Ray Kinsella, ``Build it and they will
come.'' Frank Burke had a different ballpark dream, but one that
was not much more improbable.
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of Harvard Business School, the Chattanooga Lookouts
president knew there was only one way to ensure the future of
minor-league baseball in this city of 150,000 on the banks of the
Tennessee River: ``If you come, we will build it.''
</P>
<P>
   With that slogan, Burke, 39, began a three-month stadium drive
in the fall of 1998 that was a longshot at best. If fans would
agree to buy at least 1,800 season tickets, the Class AA Southern
League team promised to build a downtown ballpark on Hawk Hill near
the Tennessee Aquarium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did I think we had a chance?'' Burke asked. ``Well, we had
never sold more than 800 season tickets before. But I knew we
couldn't keep playing at Engel Stadium, and I didn't want to sell
the team and have Chattanooga left without baseball. That would
have been awful. We didn't buy the team (in 1995) to sell it. I had
to try.''
</P>
<P>
   Chattanooga baseball fans responded with a home run. By early
1999, more than 2,000 season tickets had been sold and the deadline
met. Construction began in May. Ten months later, the $10 million
stadium came in on time and on budget, with $1 million in naming
rights from BellSouth and the sale of 12 luxury boxes helping to
pay the bill. However, Burke, the proud father, had plenty of
anxious moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting this built almost killed me,'' said Burke, who owns
the team with his father, Daniel Burke, and Charles Eshbach. ``But
it was worth it. I think this is one of the most beautiful stadiums
in the minor leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth Park opened April 1, with 6,512 cramming into the
stadium that normally seats 6,157 to see the Cincinnati Reds _ the
Lookouts' parent team _ play the Baltimore Orioles in an exhibition
game. Ken Griffey Jr. and Cal Ripken were playing in Chattanooga
for the first time, but the superstars had to share the spotlight
with the stadium, which drew rave reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Historic Engel Stadium _ home to baseball in Chattanooga for 70
years _will be remembered fondly by older fans. But it offered none
of the features of modern stadiums, and it couldn't match BellSouth
Park's view.
</P>
<P>
   From the top of the grandstand or the picnic pavilion in right
field, you can see the Tennessee River winding around the outfield
and the mountains rising on the other side. Downtown Chattanooga
looms the other way, with the Tennessee Aquarium only about 200
yards away.
</P>
<P>
   ``People kept telling me there wasn't enough room for a stadium
up here, but I knew this was the perfect spot _ the only spot,''
Burke said. ``This area of downtown has really enjoyed a revival,
and 1.5 million people come to the Aquarium each year. When they
see the stadium, I'm sure a lot of them will come to our games,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lookouts expect to set a Chattanooga attendance record this
season by drawing more than 300,000 fans. Season-ticket sales
topped out at 2,400 and the team averaged 3,637 per game for its
opening homestand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw my first game at Engel Stadium in 1932 and really loved
going to games there,'' fan Jim Hatchcock, 82, said. ``Harmon
Killebrew will always be my favorite player, but you can't keep
hanging on to the past, even when you are old like me. This stadium
is beautiful, and I know it will help draw more fans.''
</P>
<P>
   The only things that Judy Hudnall, 81, misses about Engel
Stadium is the roof over the grandstand and the easy walk from the
parking lot. But she rides the escalator up the hill from Third
Street and brings an umbrella to protect her from the sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sure is pretty looking out to the mountains,'' said the
loyal Lookout fan, who has missed one home game since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The Lookout players are as happy with BellSouth Park as the
fans, although the pitchers temper their enthusiasm a little.
</P>
<P>
   ``Engel Stadium was great to pitch in, because it was so big,''
said reliever Scott MacRae. ``But this park is beautiful and you
can't beat the new clubhouse. It's almost like being in the major
leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Engel Stadium, with its cramped clubhouse, little dugouts and
grandstand ceiling fans, is used now for high school and
junior-college games. But some of the features have made the
two-mile trip to BellSouth Park.
</P>
<P>
   The Coke bottles now sit on the top of the new scoreboard, and
the Chattanooga Choo-Choo train engine rolls out from behind a sign
in right-center after each Lookout homer. Looie the Lookout, the
team mascot with the bug eyes, patrols the grandstand and you can
get an in-game haircut in the barber chair near third base.
</P>
<P>
   Third base is as far as the grandstand goes on the left side of
the field. U.S. 27 cuts close to the stadium, with a 42-foot high
screen protecting drivers from batted balls. ``Even with the
screen, it will be a while before I stop worrying about a car
getting hit,'' Burke said.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime former Lookouts owner Joe Engel _ a small-town Bill
Veeck _ was a pioneer in minor-league promotions; he gave away a
house before a Depression-era record crowd of 24,839. Engel's
used-car night will come to BellSouth Park, but Burke said the team
will cut back on promotional giveaways.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this stadium, we can just sell baseball,'' said Burke,
who was a pitcher at Middlebury College in Vermont. ``That's the
way it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
