   Elian was taken to a waiting helicopter about 10 miles away and
flown to Homestead Air Force Base south of Miami, where a doctor
examined him. By 6 a.m. EST, he was put on board a government jet
and flown to Andrews Air Force Base outside Washington, D.C. He
reportedly played with Play-Dough and other toys on the flight.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-morning, Elian was reunited with his father, leaving
behind a family devastated by grief and anger and a community
boiling with rage and feelings of betrayal.
</P>
<P>
   Word of the raid spread like wildfire through Little Havana. By
6:30 a.m. EST, several hundred people milled around the house, some
yelling at reporters, others crying. Faces were etched with rage,
dejection and disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no words to express my anger and hurt,'' said Susana
Ruiz, 43, who stood outside the home, her eyes brimming with tears.
``I hurt for this family. I hurt like you wouldn't believe. I can't
believe what they have done. I can't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami police took no part in the raid, although a top-ranking
officer from the department rode in the lead car of the federal
caravan so that local officers would know the action was
</P>
<P>
   legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   Miami Police Chief William O'Brien said he learned of the
impending strike at 4:15 a.m. EST, and for security reasons he told
only a few top assistants. He did not notify Miami Mayor Joe
</P>
<P>
   Carollo, who afterwards lashed out at the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Federal agents went in as if they were assaulting a military
bunker,'' Carollo said. ``This family is decent, law-abiding
people, and they came in with machine guns and gassing people. This
is America. This is not Cuba or Hitler's old Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the morning, Carollo appealed for calm.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien said he did not notify Carollo out of concerns for the
security of the operation. ``I'm a policeman, not a politician,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes after the boy was gone, Miami police began
mobilizing, and quickly set up perimeters around an area of about
40 square blocks. By 8 a.m. EST, roaming crowds of demonstrators
began congregating at major intersections.
</P>
<P>
   By 9 a.m. EST, sporadic outbursts erupted. Along N.W. 27th
Avenue _ also named ``Unity Boulevard'' _ a crowd of about 50
people set fire to a tire at a major intersection. Men tossed heavy
benches with wooden backs and cement legs into the street. They
overturned newspaper boxes and tossed around trash cans, contents
spewing across the pavement.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, a team of riot-clad officers raced to the scene
to reinforce the dozen or so officers stationed at the
intersection. The team rode in unmarked sedans, which screeched to
</P>
<P>
   a halt, all four doors flying open and the officers piling out.
</P>
<P>
   Some carried weapons rigged to fire tear gas. Others carried
cans of the chemical, ready to fling them into the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   One man was in the street, overturning a newspaper box, but ran
as the cars blazed in. An officer chased him down and rolled him to
the ground in a flower bed, pinning him with his knees while
another officer slapped on metal handcuffs.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, the crowd dispersed, most walking south on Unity
Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, small caravans of cars _ apparently from homes
inside the perimeter _ crept down the broad boulevard, horns
blaring, passengers waving Cuban flags and yelling as crowds along
the sidewalks cheered. Police cars whisked up behind the caravans,
lights and sirens blazing, moving them out of the area.
</P>
<P>
   News helicopters hovered overhead, filming everything.
</P>
<P>
   The disturbances seemed unorganized and spontaneous, an
outpouring of emotion. Many people walked peacefully, holding flags
or signs, standing on sidewalks and merely watching. Some youths
mugged and danced for television cameras.
</P>
<P>
   And most of sprawling Miami-Dade County's 2.5 million residents
went about their normal Saturday business, or stayed in their homes
watching the melee unfold on television. Outside Little Havana,
businesses were open and traffic moved normally.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   The city's Miami Heat professional basketball team held their
first play-off game of the season at the downtown American Airlines
Arena, tipping off at 12:30 p.m. EST as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Three miles away in Little Havana, chaos roamed in ragged
groups.
</P>
<P>
   The outbursts were unpredictable, flaring up all through the
long, hot morning.
</P>
<P>
   Around 10:30 a.m. EST, the crowd at N.W. 27th Avenue and Flagler
Street was calmly standing on the four corners of the major
intersection as about 20 police milled around in the middle of the
street. A woman driving a red car stopped in the intersection,
opened her door, stepped out and began yelling at the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   A policeman walked over and ordered her back into the car.
Within seconds, dozens of protestors surrounded the car, screaming,
``Let her go, let her go!''
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of officers with plastic shields and nightsticks rushed
to the group. An officer grabbed a man in a green shirt who was
screaming and flailing his arms. The crowd surged. People started
running, some being shoved around by the jostling crowd. Two
teen-aged girls cried and screamed as officers brushed them out of
the way.
</P>
<P>
   A woman on one of the corners threw part of a broken broomstick
in the general direction of the officers and was immediately
wrestled to the ground and handcuffed by four men wearing helmets.
Several officers ran to their cars for gas canisters, while others
with plastic shields formed a line and began pushing the crowd
back.
</P>
<P>
   In the street, officers jammed several men to the ground,
mashing them into the pavement, twisting their arms and cuffing
their wrists. One man was led away with angry red scrapes on his
forehead. Sweating and heaving for breath in the hot sun, he was
led to an old school bus painted white and stenciled with the
words, ``Miami Police.''
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, the bus was filled with detainees. The windows
were covered with heavy metal mesh. The people inside stamped their
feet and rocked the bus.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Fire trucks roamed the area, extinguishing the stacks of tires
that protestors set ablaze in the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Thick black smoke roiled into the sky, followed at times by
clouds of choking gas fired as officers moved from one hot-spot to
the next.
</P>
<P>
   Protestors threw rocks and bottles at police and media crews.
Roaming demonstrators smashed the windows of one television truck.
</P>
<P>
   Two men ran down Unity Boulevard, carrying a large U.S. flag
turned upside down, the Stars and Stripes dragging on the pavement.
Two women carried an U.S. flag tied at the center with a black
band.
</P>
<P>
   Another woman stood off to one side as officers moved toward a
large clump of protestors, holding a bright green sign emblazoned
with one word: ``Nazis.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet another woman yelled ``assesinos'' ``assassins.'' A man ran
up to a reporter, grabbed his shirt and screamed into his face:
``You better write the truth. You better write that this was murder
here today what you saw.''
</P>
<P>
   By late Saturday, garbage crews were cleaning up the mess left
by the demonstrators, loading debris into dump trucks and running
street-sweepers along Unity Boulevard. Police maintained their
barricades, still on full alert should new disturbances break out.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before 7 p.m. EST, about 50 riot-clad officers marched
down N.W. Second Street after protesters reportedly attacked a
television crew from CNN, which has a bureau in Havana. A few
arrests were made, but most people walked quietly away from the
line of police.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're asking the media to leave because we can't guarantee
your safety,'' said Miami Police spokesman Carlos Alfaro. ``Some
people in the crowd may perceive some media as in cahoots with
foreign governments.''
</P>
<P>
   All through the crowds that raged earlier in the day, people
carried copies of the famous photograph snapped before dawn as the
riot-clad, gun-toting federal agent reached out for Elian.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no need for this,'' said Hope Kahn, who saw the
photograph for the first time as she stood near Unity Boulevard.
``There was no need to use weapons. He wasn't a drug dealer. He was
a
</P>
<P>
   little boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Williams' email address is: mikew(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
