<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4511 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-CAMBY-LAWSUIT-1ST     04-22 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CAMBY-LAWSUIT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAPTORS COACH FILES DEFAMATION SUIT AGAINST CAMBY
</HEADLINE>
  (REWRITES; ADDS 300 words)  
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ Even against a backdrop of surreal
circumstances that have whirled around the New York Knicks during
the playoffs over the years, Marcus Camby was confronted with
perhaps the most bizarre when he walked into his Larchmont home
Friday night after practice.
</P>
<P>
   His girlfriend handed him papers detailing a defamation lawsuit
against him that Raptors coach Butch Carter had filed about
critical comments that Camby, one of his former players, had made
about him last week. The papers had been delivered to the house
earlier in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Camby was stunned. Was Carter serious? Was this some sort of
extreme psychological ploy by Carter for the playoffs? Saturday, on
the eve of the Knicks' first-round playoff series against the
Raptors, the team shrugged off the timing and merit of Carter's
actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly curious,'' coach Jeff Van Gundy said Saturday
after the team's last practice in preparation for Game 1 at Madison
Square Garden Sunday afternoon. ``Out of 2 hours and 15 minutes, we
spent 12 seconds addressing it, and 8 seconds of that laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there is something psychological to it, but they
don't need to do it. We're the ones who have to adjust to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks have lost their last three regular-season games to
Toronto by double-digit margins. Even so, the overnight controversy
was a distraction. Camby declined to comment specifically on the
suit Saturday, but when asked if he would be even more motivated to
play against his former team, he said: ``What do you think?''
</P>
<P>
   Carter, after several no comments following Toronto's practice
Saturday, responded to a question about the difficulty of winning
such a suit, because the threshold is higher for people in the
public spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I'm seeking is the truth,'' he said. ``There's an extreme
difference between sworn testimony. ...'' He paused a moment before
being prodded to finish the sentence. ``There's a difference
between sworn testimony and what was said.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter claims in the lawsuit, filed in New York state Supreme
Court in White Plains, that he ``has been damaged and suffered
great pain and mental anguish, and has been held up to ridicule and
contempt by his friends, acquaintances and the public'' by Camby's
comments about him last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Camby said that day that before he was traded to the Knicks from
Toronto in June 1998, Carter had promised him that the Raptors
would build their team around him. Still, the trade quickly
followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a liar,'' Camby said Wednesday before the Knicks played
their final regular-season game at Boston. ``I don't really like
him. No one likes him and no one wants to play for him. That's the
kind of guy he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't trust him. I think a lot of guys don't trust him. He's
just been ratting out people and doing things his way. From what I
hear, a lot of people are mad at him.''
</P>
<P>
   Camby is not the first player to lash out at his former team.
While league officials had no comment on the lawsuit, Ron Klempner,
an attorney with the National Basketball Players Association,
seemed incredulous over it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we see it in black and white, we can't comment on it
because it's such an incredible and unbelievable claim,'' he said.
``Any such claim would be insufficient legally on too many grounds
to even begin counting. I don't think they want to have a precedent
with players starting to sue coaches for coaches' comments about
players.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released Saturday, Camby's lawyer, Patrick
Noonan, said: ``This is an absolutely frivolous lawsuit. It appears
that Carter would be better off spending his time getting his team
ready for the playoffs than pursuing these legal shenanigans.''
</P>
<P>
   Toronto's management might feel the same way. Distancing himself
from the legal issue, Raptors General Manager Glen Grunwald
classified the suit as an ``individual matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue has become very personal, though. On Thursday, it was
Carter who questioned the timing of Camby's criticism of him _
which came four days before the Raptors would play in the first
playoff series in the franchise's history _ and he reiterated that
complaint Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think there's a lot to be said about timing,'' Carter
said. ``My hat's off to them about the timing of what they did. You
know, we've played against them six or seven or eight times since
the trade and there never was a problem. It was a little strange.''
</P>
<P>
   The odd juxtapositions may have just begun. On Sunday, the
plaintiff will be on one end of the sideline, while the defendant
will be on the other. When Camby is on the floor, only the width of
that sideline will separate the two. If Camby were ever inspired to
play on a high level against the Raptors, it would be in this
playoff series. Last year, Camby was the Knicks' energy source
throughout the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emotions are good if you channel them the right way,'' Allan
Houston warned. ``I've always been fired up to play in the
playoffs, but that doesn't mean I go out and run around like a
crazed rabbit. You've got to channel it the right way.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter's legal action against Camby, for $5 million, could be a
detriment to his own team. Raptors players left the gym briskly
Saturday, and only a few addressed the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care about that,'' said Vince Carter, the superstar
forward who has been the bane of the Knicks this season. ``That's
between Butch and Marcus. It's Butch's problem. He can handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Oakley, who was traded to Toronto from the Knicks for
Camby, said: ``I haven't got anything to do with that. We'll see
how it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter's lawsuit will go down as another strange twist in a
Knicks playoff run. Over the last four years, there have been
fights with the rival Heat, miracle shots, controversial statements
by Larry Johnson during last year's finals and a string of
suspensions in between. Saturday, the swirl of attention around the
Knicks marked another sideshow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a part of one before, unfortunately,'' Van Gundy
said with a smile. ``I was on someone's leg. I didn't plan that
one, though. I didn't say before the game, `If Larry Johnson and
Alonzo Mourning get in a fistfight, I'm going to go out there and
do what I did.' You know what? I'm not going to judge what others
do. All I care about is the game on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   But could any psychological ploy _ if that is part of the motive
behind Carter's lawsuit _ disrupt the Knicks' focus?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you know our minds, nothing could throw us out of whack,''
Van Gundy said. ``We're unwhackable. Thank God there were only
three days before the game and not another two days. Let's just
play the game, and I hope that's good enough.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
