<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000422.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4512 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0423-1STLD     04-22 1745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0423-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: updates with Miami relatives turned away from Andrews Air
Force Base, other events throughout . . .
 &HT;    FEDERAL OFFICIALS SEIZE ELIAN IN EARLY-MORNING RAID ON MIAMI
RELATIVES HOME
 &HT;    With ELIAN-RIOTS-0423; ELIAN-REUNION-0423; ELIAN-SEIZED-0423.
 &HT;    Moving in both International and Washington categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Elian Gonzalez was reunited with his father at a
nearby Air Force base Saturday just hours after armed federal
agents seized the Cuban shipwreck survivor from a closet in his
Miami relatives's home in a three-minute predawn raid ordered by
U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   But the reunion of Elian and Juan Miguel Gonzalez did not end
the ferocious tug-of-war over the 6-year-old castaway, now elevated
to icon status on both sides of the Florida Straits.
</P>
<P>
   The distraught relatives from whom the child was taken earlier
in the day arrived Saturday evening at Andrews Air Force Base
demanding to see Elian once again. They were accompanied by Sen.
Bob Smith, R-N.H., a leading critic of the federal government's
efforts to reunite the child with his Cuban father.
</P>
<P>
   However, the relatives were denied admission to the base, a top
security facility where the president's fleet of aircraft is
housed. They did not say how long they would be in the Washington
area, or whether they would make another attempt to see the father
and son.
</P>
<P>
   Influential Washington attorney Greg Craig, who represents Juan
Miguel Gonzalez, had discouraged the Miami relatives from making
the trip.
</P>
<P>
   The seizure of Elian triggered an outpouring of anger in the
Little Havana area of Miami, where much of the heart-tugging
international drama has unfolded over the five months since Elian
was rescued at sea, having lost his mother in a desperate attempt
to flee Fidel Castro's dictatorship in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   As Elian and his father celebrated their reunion at the air
base, Cuban Americans took their anger into the streets of Miami,
waving Cuban flags, setting fires, throwing rocks and bottles and,
in one instance, punching a police officer. One protester also
tried to burn an American flag.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, with the sun setting on the famous resort
city, a heavy force of Miami police moved into the streets with
tear gas as local officials pleaded for calm. Some of the
protesters accused the media of sympathizing with Castro, and riot
police warned reporters of possible violence directed at them.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of protesters, some waving American flags, also gathered
at the gates of Andrews, which is located in the Maryland suburbs
of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Craig released photographs of a smiling Elian with his father,
stepmother and baby brother at their reunion. The photos contrasted
sharply with the news images earlier in the day of federal agents
removing the screaming boy from the Miami home of his great-uncle,
Lazaro Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed to be very happy to be back with his father,'' Craig
said. ``It is amazing how quickly that bond re-established itself.
It was almost instantaneous.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no independent corroboration of Craig's account of the
reunion.
</P>
<P>
   In Havana, Fidel Castro led a rally of jubilant Cubans. State
television used U.S. television networks's footage to provide
blow-by-blow coverage. The Cuban government called the events ``a
favorable movement,'' but cautioned that ``the need to fight for
Elian has not ended'' because of pending legal proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Elian and his father are expected to remain in the United States
until a federal appeals court decides whether he can be returned to
Cuba. He and his family will live at an undisclosed location in the
Washington, D.C. area after spending a few days at Andrews,
according to federal immigration officials.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's Miami relatives lost a U.S. District Court battle to get
a political asylum hearing for the boy. An appeals court has
ordered Elian to stay in this country until it decides that case.
But it did not bar Reno from switching custody. A hearing is set
for May 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we all await the outcome of the appellate process, I think
it is important for us all to accept Elian's long-overdue reunion
with his father,'' Reno said during a Saturday morning news
conference at the Justice Department. ``It is time to heal wounds
that have divided a community. It is time to help this little boy
heal from the tragedies that he has experienced. Let us give him
and his father the space, the calm, the moral support they need to
reconnect and reaffirm their bond between father and son.''
</P>
<P>
   But the dramatic images of the frantic and forceful removal of
Elian from his relatives' home in Miami following the collapse of
negotiations for a voluntarily surrender of the child to his father
did nothing to promote peace. Neither did the fiery political
rhetoric triggered by the surprise Easter weekend events.
</P>
<P>
   Miami Mayor Joe Carollo, in a round of television appearances,
denounced the federal agents as ``thugs'' and ``atheists,'' called
their actions ``a crime'' and declared that he ``could not trust
our government any longer.''
</P>
<P>
   House Republican Whip Tom DeLay of Texas called the seizure of
Elian a ``police-state-type raid'' by the Clinton administration.
And Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi said, ``My
first thought was that this could only happen in Castro's Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   The events in Miami also reverberated in the American
presidential campaign, with Vice President Al Gore distancing
himself from the administration's actions and Texas Gov. George W.
Bush, the presumptive Republican nominee, questioning the
administration's claim that it had no alternative but to reunite
Elian and his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I have said, I believe this issue should have been handled
through a family court and with the family coming together,'' Gore
said in a brief statement released by his campaign office in
Nashville rather than his vice presidential office at the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said, ``All sides have claimed to be acting in Elian's best
interest, but surely no one can argue that taking a young boy at
gunpoint is in his best interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's statement echoes the claims made by Elian's Miami
relatives that the boy was taken at gunpoint by the eight federal
agents who rushed into their home shortly after 5 a.m. EST
Saturday. An emotional Marisleysis Gonzalez, Elian's 21-year-old
cousin and primary caregiver, claimed that agents had placed a gun
to Elian's head at one point during the raid.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters brandished copies of a news photograph showing a
federal agent wearing green riot gear, a helmet and goggles and
carrying an automatic rifle as he confronts a man clutching a
frightened Elian in a closet.
</P>
<P>
   The man holding Elian in the photograph is Donato Dalrymple, one
of the fishermen who rescued Elian last Thanksgiving Day from an
inner tube in the open Atlantic Ocean an incredible 48 hours after
a crowded boat carrying him and his mother capsized. His mother and
10 others drowned.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, at her news conference, said the ``paramount concern''
throughout the operation was ``the well-being of Elian'' and ``the
safety of the agents and others.'' She noted that law enforcement
officers ``must be prepared for the unexpected,'' but insisted that
the photograph of the agent confronting Dalrymple was proof of the
caution with which the raid was conducted.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the beauties of television is that it shows exactly
what the facts are,'' Reno said. ``And as I understand it, if you
look at it (the photograph) carefully, it shows that the gun was
pointed to the side, and that the finger was not on the trigger.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno said she ordered the boy taken from the relatives who have
cared for him since his rescue at sea because they had rejected her
latest proposal for surrendering the child to his father. ``The
Miami relatives rejected our efforts, leaving us no other option
but the enforcement action,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal that had been under discussion called for Juan Miguel
Gonzalez and Elian, Lazaro and Marisleysis to move to one of two
foundation-owned conference centers near Washington, with formal
custody being transferred immediately to the father. The two sides
could not agree on the custody issue or how long they might live
together pending the end of the court battle.
</P>
<P>
   As the negotiations collapsed, armed federal agents arrived in
white minivans at the Little Havana home of Lazaro Gonzalez,
entered the house and removed Elian, all in about three minutes. As
the van carrying Elian departed, agents used pepper spray to
prevent protesters from approaching.
</P>
<P>
   Elian was carried out of the home by a Spanish-speaking female
agent who had informed him that he was to be reunited with his
``papa,'' that he would not be going back to Cuba and that he would
not be placed in a boat.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who was briefed through the night on the
Justice Department's plans, told reporters at the White House
Saturday that he supported the decision to use federal agents to
reunite Elian with his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support the decisions that were made ... and I believe that
it was the right thing to do,'' Clinton said. He credited Reno with
exploring ``every conceivable alternative'' before taking action.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was, in the end, about a little boy who lost his mother
and has not seen his father in more than five months,'' the
president said. ``I hope, with time and support, Elian and his
father will have the opportunity to be a strong family again.''
</P>
<P>
   But the case of Elian Gonzalez is far from ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's miraculous rescue from the sea took on Biblical
dimensions to some of the hundreds of Cuban Americans who have
surrounded the boy's Little Havana home in recent weeks. He has
even been compared to Moses, who, according to Jewish and Christian
faiths, led the children of Israel from bondage in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   And the timing of the raid, on Holy Saturday, or the Angelic
Night, a time of sadness and joy for Christians, led some
protesters to compare the events to the crucifixion of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like crucifying the Messiah all over again,'' said
Ralph Anrrich(CQ), a social worker helping Elian's Miami relatives
Saturday. ``This is a slap in the face to the Cuban-American
community and the Christian community.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
