Ruiz, 43, eyes brimming with tears. ``I hurt for this family. I
hurt like you wouldn't believe. I can't believe what they have
done. I can't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   The still photograph of a goggled and helmeted federal agent
pointing an automatic rifle toward Elian and family friend Donato
Dalrymple was soon displayed on demonstrators' placards with the
words ``Federal Child Abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Dalrymple, one of the fishermen who pulled Elian from the ocean
last Thanksgiving, urged a crowd of about 300 in front of the
Gonzalez home to remain calm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask in the name of Elian, let's keep peace in Miami,''
Dalrymple said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone listened.
</P>
<P>
   Cries of ``to the streets'' arose from many in the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters pounded on the hood of a patrol car, forcing the
sergeant to flee in reverse gear. The same thing happened when a
city fire-rescue car tried to cross the intersection.
</P>
<P>
   Police retreated after filling a bus with arrestees.
</P>
<P>
   With no police in sight, demonstrators set tires and dumpsters
ablaze and tossed newspaper racks into the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Police returned to the area within 30 minutes carrying shields
and batons and shooting tear gas cannisters into the crowd to
reclaim the intersection.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an abuse of the Latin people,'' Xiomara Quintana screamed
as the tear gas drove the crowd away. ``I'm angry.''
</P>
<P>
   The street violence appeared to be instigated by no more than
three dozen young men who wrapped shirts around the faces to
conceal their identities. One of them yelled, ``Viva la revolucion,
(Long live the revolution.), a slogan most often associated with
supporters of Castro. Bystanders said the youths were members of
street gangs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not gang members,'' insisted one youth whose face was
masked by his shirt. ``The government is turning us into
terrorists.'' The man refused to give his name.
</P>
<P>
   As the crowd was pushed farther back, a white truck filled with
used auto tires drove by slowly, giving the youths an opportunity
to grab tires from the truck. About a dozen were tossed into a pile
and set on fire in the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just want to create trouble,'' said Alex Fernandez, a
Cuban-American who emerged from his apartment on the street to see
the chaos. ``But this is what they are going to put on the evening
news and all Cubans will be blamed for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Another exile, Ramon Cisneros, said he didn't agree with the
disorder but said he understood why his fellow exiles are angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very frustrated because we had trusted in the laws and
the human rights in this country,'' said Cisneros, 55, who had
ducked into a Walgreens to buy poster board for a protest sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't approve of burning tires, but we have the right of a
protest'' said Alejandro Ramirez, 33, a Cuban American engineer who
said he left Cuba five years ago and will become an American
citizen next month. ``We are just using the tools that people in a
democracy use.''
</P>
<P>
   In the street, people carried copies of the Associated Press
photograph showing an armed federal agent grabbing Elian. Some had
already made T-shirts with the photograph, accompanied by a photo
of Janet Reno and a swastika.
</P>
<P>
   The same photo was on the front page of an special edition of El
Neuvo Herald, The Miami Herald's Spanish-language daily, under a
banner headline reading: What a shame!
</P>
<P>
   Several standing outside the home were overcome by emotions,
tears streaming down their pained faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``God please help Elian,'' a young woman cried as she looked up
at the sky. The woman, Lisette Soler, said the early morning raid
will traumatize Elian for the rest of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the day, Miami Mayor Joe Carollo appealed to residents
to obey the law, ``no matter how much our hearts ache. That is the
best way we can help.''
</P>
<P>
   Police said that 180 people had been arrested during the day.
</P>
<P>
   Sister Jeanne O'Laughlin, the Miami Beach nun who fought to keep
Elian in the United States, said the community should pull
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enough pain has been done, enough sorrow has been spread,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
