<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4518 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-YOUNG-REDS-LADN     04-22 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-YOUNG-REDS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DMITRI YOUNG FINDING RIGHT MINDSET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEATHER GRIPP  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baseball never seemed like a kids' game to Dmitri Young.
Football, maybe, but not baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is the sport Young begged his dad to let him play when
he was too big to play on youth football teams. Although his skills
often allowed Young to compete against older players, he learned
that size and power are not all he needed to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Young was playing professionally by the time he was 17. The more
the Cincinnati Reds outfielder plays the game, the more emphasis he
places on his early realization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I signed and worked my way up, I came to find this game
is more and more mental,'' Young said. ``The talent that you
display in high school is what got you drafted. The same talent you
display while you're in the minor leagues gets you to the big
leagues. And the same talent you display to get to the big leagues
keeps you there, but the mental part is huge.''
</P>
<P>
   The talent that got Young, 26, where he is was developed through
hours of work with his father Larry, who said he knew little about
the sport until Dmitri wanted to play. Larry wanted Dmitri to try
karate, but Dmitri cried at the idea, so Larry studied baseball and
sought help from coaches so his oldest son was taught properly.
</P>
<P>
   Discipline was a must in the Young family, and it's something
Dmitri tries to pass to brother Delmon, who is living up to high
expectations as a freshman at Camarillo (Calif.) High School.
</P>
<P>
   Dmitri Young was a first-round draft pick _ fourth overall _ by
the St. Louis Cardinals in 1991 after earning All-America honors as
a senior at Rio Mesa High of Oxnard, Calif., where he set several
state batting records. The 6-foot-2, 235-pound switch-hitter, who
is in his fourth full season in the majors, won the American
Association Triple-A batting title in 1996 and has hit at least
.300 the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Young entered this weekend's series against the Dodgers hitting
just .211, but he doesn't dwell on stats.
</P>
<P>
   He studies the opposition to learn players' tendencies and what
he should expect to have to do, but he realizes he can only control
his own actions. Not worrying about things out of his control like
whether or not he's going to play, or where he's playing help Young
stay focused.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mental preparation is a big part of the game and he does it
well,'' Reds manager Jack McKeon said.
</P>
<P>
   Coping with things like travel, the media, fans and being away
from family are as vital as what happens on the field, Young said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have so much to deal with on an everyday basis, people
can't even begin to understand or realize,'' he said. ``There's a
general appreciation. Every ballplayer looks at each other like, `I
know, you're doing it.' It's hard being up here every day, the
everyday grind. That's why they say when you get to the big
leagues, it's 90 percent mental and 10 percent physical.
</P>
<P>
   ``The physical part is what got you to the big leagues. The
mental part is what keeps you there. You swing a bat, that's
physical. You catch a ball, that's physical. ... The mental part is
the strategy part of the game and everything surrounding it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot behind this game. It's a kids' game at the
beginning, but it's just like checkers and chess.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 2030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
