<DOCNO> NYT20000422.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4520 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ELIAN-REUNION-0423-1S     04-22 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-REUNION-0423-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: updates with Miami family attempting to see Elian, Juan
Miguel . . .
 &HT;    ELIAN, JUAN MIGUEL REUNITED AT ANDREWS AFB
 &HT;    With CUBA-ELIAN-0423.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANDREWS AIR FORCE BASE, Md. _ After five months of separation,
young Elian Gonzalez was reunited Saturday morning with his father,
Juan Miguel, at this closed air force base outside Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Delivered here about 9:20 a.m. EST on a government plane after
being forcefully removed from his Miami relatives' home four hours
earlier, Elian spent the day in private on the base with his
father, step-mother, Nersy, and baby brother, Hianny.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's cousin and primary caregiver in Miami, Marisleysis
Gonzalez, and other Miami relatives followed the boy Saturday
afternoon, arriving on an American Airlines flight into
Washington-Reagan National Airport. They had hoped to visit with
the father and boy at Andrews, but Juan Miguel Gonzalez refused to
allow them to see Elian.
</P>
<P>
   The family arrived in the Washington area, and promptly drove to
Capitol Hill to meet with Sen. Bob Smith, R-N.H., who has been
sympathetic to their efforts to keep the boy here in the United
States. Smith then escorted them to Andrews in a minivan, but they
were turned away at the gate.
</P>
<P>
   The family attempted to hold a news conference at a hotel across
the street, but were visibly shaken by hundreds of reporters and
protesters as they got out of the minivan. They climbed back into
the minivan without speaking to the crowd about their plans while
in the Washington area.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Juan Miguel's lawyer, Gregory Craig, praised U.S.
Attorney General Janet Reno for going the ``extra mile'' to get
Elian and his immediate family together. In a telephone interview
aired on CNN, Craig said Elian appeared relaxed and happy in his
father's arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was totally at ease,'' Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   A photograph released by Craig showed a smiling Elian being held
by his beaming father and surrounded by Nersy and baby Hianny. A
second picture showed Elian again smiling, and playing with Hianny.
</P>
<P>
   The hordes of media reporters, who were banned from the air
force base, congregated outside the main gate _ along with dozens
of protesters carrying rosaries and Cuban flags.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am incensed . . . that a child could be taken in this way,''
said Ivette Curros, a Cuban-American immigrant and Miami resident
who was in the Washington D.C.-area en route to a convention in
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Curros said she came to the base to protest the federal
government's effort to reunite the boy with his father, who plans
to return to communist Cuba following the current appeals process
in federal courts. ``I thank God every day that my mother risked
her life to come to this country,'' she said, adding that Elian,
whose mother died trying to reach the United States, should not be
returned to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Blazquez, who fled Cuba in 1967 and now lives in the
Washington area, agreed, saying the removal of Elian from the Miami
home was ``a stab in the back'' of the Cuban-American community.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, the cluster of protesters grew, peaking at
perhaps 150, many carrying signs with slogans such as, ``Bill &AMP;
Janet are communist thugs,'' and ``Who runs out country - Clinton
or Castro?''
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   Immigration and Naturalization Service: http://www.ins.usdoj.gov
</P>
<P>
   Miami relatives: http://libertyforelian.org
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 2032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
