<DOCNO> NYT20000422.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4521 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-NL-NOTEBOOK-LADN     04-22 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NL-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDS TRYING TO IMPROVE GRIFFEY JR.'S SWING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ So you thought Ken Griffey Jr. had the perfect
swing, something that doesn't need tinkering and will always be
true? Apparently not.
</P>
<P>
   Not willing to leave greatness alone, the Cincinnati Reds are
making alterations to the swing that made Griffey the youngest
player in baseball history to hit 400 homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to shorten his swing a little,'' said Ken Griffey
Sr., the Reds' hitting coach. ``The National League is a little
different from the American League. In the AL, he saw a lot more
breaking pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's seeing more fastballs in this league. He's been a little
late on his swing, and they're jamming him. Once he gets his hands
through the ball and on top of the ball, it's the same swing. With
quicker hands, he won't get jammed.''
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, it'll work out for Griffey and the Reds. But in
the short term, it's not going as planned. Griffey leads Cincinnati
with five homers and 18 RBI, but the career .298 hitter is batting
a paltry .203.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Giants left fielder Barry Bonds, a close friend of
Griffey's, said not to underestimate the pressure of returning to
play at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt a lot of pressure,'' Bonds said of leaving Pittsburgh
for the Bay. ``It was just a lucky year (in '93). It's tough to
come back to your home town. It's not that easy. Kenny will be
fine, though. Kenny's a great ballplayer. If Kenny's happy, that's
all that matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny's had great years his whole career. I don't see any
reason why he won't now. I went from one National League team to
another. It's a big difference. I already knew all the pitchers.
He's going from the American League to the National League. That's
another change for him that I never had to go through.''
</P>
<P>
   GWYNN RETURNS: San Diego's Tony Gwynn returned to the Padres
lineup Wednesday after missing seven games, which equates to about
30 plate appearances, with elbow and knee problems.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the Padres are glad to have him back in the lineup,
but there is a personal issue at stake for Gwynn. He signed a
contract extension in the spring in which he'll be paid $6 million
next season. It's an option extension that the club can pick up at
any time. The contract vests if Gwynn reaches 502 plate
appearances, but it's not a guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   Due to injuries, Gwynn hasn't amassed 502 plate appearances
since 1997. He's reached the mark twice since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   BOHANON TRADE BAIT: Brian Bohanon, the former Dodger who won 12
games last season, is on the trading block in Colorado after being
sent to the bullpen. He lost 20 pounds during the offseason and
weighs 250 and is finally pitching without pain after being
bothered by bone chips last season, but it hasn't helped.
</P>
<P>
   He's allowed 21 hits in 10 innings, has a 15.68 ERA and was
banished to the Rockies bullpen after three starts. General manager
Dan O'Dowd is trying to move Bohanon, set to make $5 million in
2000 and 2001, for another starting pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what this is (going to the bullpen), just to get myself
right,'' Bohanon said. ``Its been a combination of a little bit of
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   ODDS AND ENDS: Arizona had no Matt Mantei and no Matt Williams
for the first two weeks of the season, but the Diamondbacks still
have the best record in the National League. Mike Morgan has three
saves, but gave the closer role back Friday to Mantei. Meanwhile,
Williams had the stitches taken out of his foot and is walking with
a cast. ... Atlanta right-hander John Smoltz, who had elbow surgery
four weeks ago, is still months away from picking up a ball, but
he's surprised how good he feels. ``I have no reason to be ahead of
schedule, but in my head I am,'' Smoltz said. ... Cubs righty Kerry
Wood was 2-0 with a 1.50 ERA for Single-A Daytona and general
manager Ed Lynch said it's almost time. ``I'd say he's getting
very, very close,'' the GM said. ... Phillies righty Curt Schilling
is eyeing an April 30 return date. ... The Padres solved the case
of the missing batting cage. A club employee thought it was an
extra one and gave it to a local high school, St. Augustine. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 2032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000422.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
