<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-NGUYEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS LINEBACKER NGUYEN IN POSITION TO START
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The first Vietnamese-American to play in the
National Football League is on the verge of becoming the first
Vietnamese-American to start in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Dat Nguyen will get his first look as the Cowboys' starting
middle linebacker during minicamp Friday through next Sunday at
Valley Ranch. The first of the two camps will be followed by the
first of two quarterback schools May 1-4.
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen, the 1998 Lombardi Trophy winner from Texas A&AMP;M, played
mostly in nickel packages and special teams for the Cowboys as a
rookie last season. He doesn't exactly measure up to NFL standards
for a middle linebacker at 5-foot-11, 231 pounds. One exception is
Zach Thomas (5-11, 235), who is working on a five-year, $22.5
million contract as the perennial leading tackler for the Miami
Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys may have some trepidation about their overall lack
of size and depth at linebacker, but Nguyen is considered nothing
less than Randall Godfrey's successor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We drafted Dat to start,'' Cowboys coach Dave Campo said,
``and now he's getting his opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   It makes sense to the Cowboys from a business standpoint. In
February, Godfrey signed a five-year. $25 million contract,
including a $5 million signing bonus, as an unrestricted free agent
to play for the Tennessee Titans.
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen, a third-round pick in 1999, will play this season for a
$250,000 base salary, while counting a modest $366,7000 against the
Cowboys' salary cap. He received a $350,000 signing bonus a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics look at the Cowboys' starting linebackers and wonder
how the team can afford to play both Nguyen and weakside starter
Dexter Coakley (5-10, 228) in the base defense, even though Coakley
made the Pro Bowl last season, his third year in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``That really doesn't bother me,'' Campo said. ``I'm a big
proponent of speed. And I think you always move your front four
around to create some different looks. Sure, physically (at
linebacker), there may be a problem at times. But in my opinion,
all that will be overcome by instinctiveness and speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum sees Nguyen moving up the NFL ladder
because he has a knack at achieving the next level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dat is so alert, so instinctive,'' said Slocum, recalling
Nguyen's many College Station accomplishments that were
Bunyanesque.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had an onside kick once. You're just hoping somebody falls
on the ball ... but Dat picked it up and ran for a touchdown,''
Slocum said.
</P>
<P>
   Campo argues that Nguyen isn't small; he's just short by NFL
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen's disadvantage comes in locating the ball at the line of
scrimmage amid so many bigger bodies on both lines. He also has
tremendous lower-body strength and puts himself in good positions
to make the tackle. And once in the open field, Nguyen is adept at
swatting the ball loose.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys might add a linebacker through free agency after
June 1. Philadelphia and Seattle have released William Thomas and
ex-Cowboy Darrin Smith (1993-96), respectively, and both would
interest the Cowboys at the right price.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Bowden, who started at outside linebacker for the Super Bowl
Titans, is an unrestricted free agent who faces a numbers crunch in
Tennessee. The Titans drafted three linebackers, including
Syracuse's Keith Bulluck in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I feel very good about our starting linebackers,'' Campo
said of Coakley, Nguyen and Darren Hambrick. ``I'm fully expecting
Dat to step in there and start, and for him to be effective for us
right away.''
</P>
<P>
   No question, it's a tall order. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
