<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-ANALYSIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIAN'S STORY IS FAR FROM OVER, BUT WHAT NOW? 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``Que pasa? Que pasa?'' Elian Gonzalez apparently
kept asking as federal agents seized him Saturday in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   What, indeed, was happening?
</P>
<P>
   That is a question that will be asked for a long time and in
many contexts _ as the inconsistent law enforcement legacy of the
Clinton administration and its attorney general, Janet Reno, is
considered; as the presidential campaign plays out nationally and
particularly in Florida; and as the United States ponders its
tortuously evolving relationship with Cuban dictator Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Reno claim to hold the legal and sociological high
ground by having relied on the rule of law to reunite Elian with
his father and only surviving natural parent, Juan Miguel Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's relatives in Miami, other Cuban exiles and their
conservative supporters believe they have the moral upper hand in
seeking to have the boy remain in the United States; thereby,
denying Castro a 6-year-old human trophy to exploit and brainwash.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the Cuban-American community, of course, want to exploit
the boy in their own way and for their own symbolic purposes.
That's regrettable, even given how understandable is their distrust
of Castro, an egregious leftover from the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   As is so often the case in any dust-up involving the United
States and Cuba, the simple answer _ in this case giving a minor
child to a parent, minus some showing of utter unsuitability _ may
not be the correct one, or at least not one easily arrived at.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law, international law (such as it is) and common sense
have to contend with the competing demands of a 4-decade-old
geopolitical blood feud.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, Elian's story has been a harrowing part of
that continuing saga. Clinging to an inner tube, he watched last
November as his mother  &UR;  &LR; and nine others drowned while they floated
toward the United States. Elian's rescue, as a Florida writer
noted, was ``a sparkling moment of fate.'' The succeeding months
have not been so.
</P>
<P>
   In Cuba, Castro has played the boy's plight for all the
gratuitous publicity and rabble-rousing he could muster. So what's
new? His government continued to try to stage manage the reaction
Saturday, with state-owned radio in Havana advising Cubans not to
celebrate publicly lest it look bad to the international audience.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, better was to be expected _ but was not always
forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the Immigration and Naturalization Service said
questions about Elian's custody should be left to a family court in
Florida. But in January, the INS ruled that the boy should be
returned to his father. Reno signed off on the decision, and
Clinton said the agency did the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals said, in effect, not so fast,
and has ordered that Elian not be removed from the United States
until the legal string has been played out. It is incumbent on the
Clinton administration to make certain this order is observed.
</P>
<P>
   Uncharacteristically, the Clinton administration has never been
able to get control of this story in terms of the politically
important imagery. By turns, it has looked ham-fisted or indecisive
as the Justice Department and INS dithered over how to enforce its
will. Early on, Clinton himself looked like he was willing to hang
Reno out to dry on the matter, but more recently he has been
supportive.
</P>
<P>
   As the dramatic chapter of the story initially unfolded
Saturday, the administration fell further behind the curve. The
pictures from inside the Miami home during the raid were exactly
what Reno _ and the White House _ had hoped to avoid: a beefy
federal agent, in riot gear and toting an assault rifle, snatching
Elian from the arms of his fisherman-rescuer in the middle of the
night. It wasn't a burning compound outside Waco, but it was an
unpleasant face of American authority.
</P>
<P>
   Even Juan Miguel Gonzalez' lawyer, Gregory Craig, had to concede
in a CNN interview that ``it looked shocking and scary.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House certainly breathed easier later in the day as
the seemingly unforced happy snapshots of the reunion of Elian and
his father were made available by the U.S. government and began to
chase the earlier, dire pictures around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the administration's missteps throughout the
high-profile standoff, Clinton has had what any politician wants in
such a fix: public support for his position. Polls have shown that
a clear and slowly growing majority of Americans believe Elian
should be given to his father, while a consistent one-third of
survey respondents believe he should remain in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Elian affair has proved to be an especially slippery slope
for Vice President Al Gore in his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gore went into the full-straddle mode Saturday, repeating his
attempt to pander to Cuban-Americans (in which he broke with the
administration and said Elian's case should have been handled by a
family court) but yet not criticizing the federal seizure of the
boy.
</P>
<P>
   He felt called on to conclude a written statement with the
anodyne phrase of the day: ``I ask all Americans, no matter what
their position on this issue, to obey the rule of law.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the presumptive Republican
presidential nominee, took a few predictable shots at the INS
operation to seize Elian. Particularly rich, in light of Bush's
apparent problems with the gun-control issue, was his declaration:
``Ours is a nation of laws, not guns.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush made a better effort than Gore to get into the serious
part of the Elian debate. He recalled the INS' initial decision to
leave the custody issue to a Florida family court and said: ``The
administration should have followed that legal and responsible
course. ... The more authority of our law comes from the
understanding that it will be applied in a fair and measured way.''
</P>
<P>
   Those certainly will not be the last words from Gore or Bush on
the issue. Or from Clinton or Castro. Or their biographers or the
historians.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXX &QL; 
 &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
