<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-SUNS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LETHARGIC SPURS FALL IN OPENER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The San Antonio Spurs' quest to repeat as NBA
champions just got a little bit tougher.
</P>
<P>
   With MVP candidate Tim Duncan out with an injury, Phoenix
quickly snatched homecourt advantage away from the Spurs as the
Suns captured Game 1 of the opening-round playoff series, 72-70,
Saturday at the Alamodome.
</P>
<P>
   Each team set playoff lows for points scored in a game. The 142
points tied the playoff record set by Atlanta and Detroit on May
12, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Game 2 will be played here Tuesday before the series shifts to
Phoenix for Game 3 next Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs were flat offensively and failed to protect the ball.
On the flip side, the Suns swarmed David Robinson, who made just 3
of 12 shots and finished with only 11 points and 11 rebounds in 30
foul-plagued minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the homecourt advantage that the Spurs secured in the
final game of the season no longer belongs to the defending NBA
champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did a nice job of fronting me,'' Robinson said. ``We need
to find a better way to be effective. Yeah, we need Tim. He brings
the size that we need. Everybody has to do their thing, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan has missed the past five games because of a slight tear
of the lateral meniscus tear in his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   Former Mavericks first-round draft pick Samaki Walker, starting
in place of Duncan, had 13 points and a game-high 16 rebounds, and
blocked three shots. But his stellar performance was not enough to
offset 17 points apiece from Cliff Robinson and Penny Hardaway, and
15 points off the bench from steady Rodney Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first playoff start for Walker.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we would have had about two or three more guys with that
same effort (as Walker), we wouldn't be having this discussion
about how we lost,'' guard Terry Porter said. ``But we did welcome
him to the real NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs trailed by 11 midway through the third period, but
clawed their way back and had a chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   With the Spurs behind, 71-70, Sean Elliott passed up a wide-open
long jumper for a 15-footer that missed everything. Suns center
Corie Blount rebounded and was fouled with one second left.
</P>
<P>
   Blount made his first free throw, but missed the second attempt,
which was rebounded by Walker with 0.7 seconds remaining. After a
Spurs timeout, Mario Elie's inbounds pass at halfcourt for Walker
was intercepted by Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not done by a long shot,'' said Rogers, who grabbed an
offensive rebound and muscled in a shot over Malik Rose that gave
the Suns a 69-68 lead. ``We are just getting started.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't get the big head. We have to maintain our cool. We
can't sit back and relax. We know they will come back strong on
Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither team came out strong. The Suns won despite shooting 36.6
percent from the field. The Spurs struggled, too, missing 9-of-21
free throws, committed 18 turnovers and shot 37 percent from the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our offense could not get it done on a consistent basis, and
that hurt us,'' Spurs coach Gregg Popovich said. ``The free throw
situation obviously was not good.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had taken care of business at the line we would have
been in good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   As it is, the Spurs are not in the best of shape. And Duncan,
who is questionable for Game 2, is not 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think it's easier when you've got the MVP of last
year's Finals at the top (of the key), who can shoot jumpers or
take it to the basket,'' Spurs guard Avery Johnson said. ``We're
putting a lot of pressure on the rest of our (power forwards) to
make plays that we've been programmed to make with the MVP out
there.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
