<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN JOSE LOOKS LIKE EASIER WAY FOR STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Dallas Stars' yearly dispatching of the Edmonton Oilers has
been handled.
</P>
<P>
   Show them what they won, Gary Bettman ...
</P>
<P>
   Well, for our defending Stanley Cup champions, we have a
second-round series against either the Colorado Avalanche or the
San Jose Sharks. Both teams are playing especially well right now,
and both won the season series against the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very interesting,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said
Saturday. ``This could be the first time in a long time we'll be
the underdog in a playoff series.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time he could remember was Detroit in 1998. And that
didn't turn out too well for the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   So while Stars coaches and players huddle around their TV sets
this afternoon to find out who they'll play in the second round,
here are some questions for Stars fans to ponder:
</P>
<P>
   WHO WILL THE STARS PLAY IN THE SECOND ROUND?
</P>
<P>
   There are two possibilities, and the Stars could find out as
early today which one they'll face.
</P>
<P>
   If the San Jose Sharks beat the St. Louis Blues in Game 6 today
in San Jose, Calif., the Stars will play the Sharks. If the Blues
win Games 6 and 7, the Stars would play the Colorado Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   So tune into the Sharks-Blues game at 2 p.m. today on
WFAA/Channel 8.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, ABC could use the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   DOES IT MAKE A DIFFERENCE?
</P>
<P>
   Nobody will ever say it, but the Stars would much rather play
the Sharks.
</P>
<P>
   While San Jose would've been a pain-in-the-butt, first-round
opponent, the Sharks would be just what the doctor ordered for the
second round.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of having to play the red-hot Avalanche, the Stars would
play a Sharks team that already has been extended by the Blues. The
Avs and Detroit Red Wings are then forced to slug it out in the
other Western Conference semifinal series.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Stars are sticking to the company line when asked if
they care who they play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' Stars captain Derian Hatcher said. ``I said one
time I cared and we lost.''
</P>
<P>
   DO THE STARS BECOME THE NO. 1 SEED IF ST. LOUIS LOSES?
</P>
<P>
   Kind of.
</P>
<P>
   If the Blues are eliminated by the Sharks, the Stars become the
highest seed left in the Western Conference. As a result, they'd
play the lowest seed left in the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars also would get home ice all the way through the
Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   WILL DEFENSEMAN SERGEI ZUBOV AND WINGER JERE LEHTINEN BE READY
FOR GAME 1 OF ROUND 2?
</P>
<P>
   Zubov? Very likely.
</P>
<P>
   Lehtinen? Possibly.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said Saturday that Zubov, who hasn't played since
March 29, continues to skate at Dr Pepper StarCenter and should be
ready for the first game. Lehtinen, meanwhile, is going slowly on
his tender right ankle that caused him to miss all but 17 of the
Stars' 82 regular-season games.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Zubov nor Lehtinen played in the first round against
Edmonton. The Stars didn't miss a beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I think you're not going to be able to go through the
playoffs without adversity,'' Hitchcock said. ``Our residue from
the season gave us the ability to persevere. We weren't overwhelmed
when this happened.''
</P>
<P>
   CAN THE STARS REPEAT AS STANLEY CUP CHAMPIONS WITHOUT A POWER
PLAY?
</P>
<P>
   The Stars did a lot of things right in their first-round series
against Edmonton. The power play wasn't one of them.
</P>
<P>
   They finished 2-for-26, which equates to converting about 8
percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche and Red Wings are scoring on about one in every
four chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think at this time of the year it's all about wins not about
percentages,'' Hitchcock said. ``But you give yourself a better
chance to win if you have a lot of elements going well for you.
Obviously, power play is one of those elements.''
</P>
<P>
   Can they win without a great power play? Yes.
</P>
<P>
   Can they win at 8 percent? Probably not.
</P>
<P>
   DO THE STARS HAVE THEIR MO-JOE BACK?
</P>
<P>
   Mike Modano was the Stars' best player in their first-round
series. Hands down.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars can't live on Mo alone. They need Joe Nieuwendyk
playing well, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got a lot better,'' Hitchcock said about Nieuwendyk. ``He
dug into the series in the last two games, which was very good for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Much like Austin Powers, the Stars aren't going very far without
their Mo-Joe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are the Stars playing as well as they can play?''
</P>
<P>
   We'll let Hitchcock handle this question.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no and no,'' he said. ``We're going to have to be a lot
better. Every round, we're going to have to be better.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
