<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-REDS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS POUND REDS, 16-2
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Eric Karros was in a 3-for-22 slump and Shawn Green
had three hits in 19 at-bats with runners in scoring position, and
yet few words were spoken of their early futility.
</P>
<P>
   Part of it is because Gary Sheffield is crushing the baseball.
The bigger reason is because the Dodgers have a deeper lineup than
years past, and they're knocking opposing pitchers around despite
the struggles of their fourth and fifth hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Karros showed signs of breaking out of his funk with a three-run
homer and a double, and the bottom of the order again produced
wonderfully as the Dodgers pounded three Cincinnati pitchers in a
16-2 pasting of the Reds on Saturday at Cinergy Field.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield and Kevin Elster added two-run homers, and Todd
Hollandsworth started the game with a homer as the Dodgers backed
Chan Ho Park with 15 hits. The 16 runs were the most the Dodgers
scored since May 6, 1995, in a 17-11 win at Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got out of that smog in L.A. to clear our minds. We're road
warriors,'' said Elster, alluding to the Dodgers averaging 7.5 runs
per game on the road. ``I think, mentally, for our big guns, it's
so nice the bottom is doing something. That way, they don't have to
think they have to carry the load all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The lone downer for the Dodgers (10-6), who go for the
three-game sweep today, was a blister Park developed that could
knock him from his next start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, we go up against some pretty good pitchers, and
we give them a different look all the time,'' Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson said. ``Our lineup is not easy to pitch to. We scored a
bunch (nine) of runs (Friday) without a major contribution from
Sheff and Green. Sheff chipped in today, but Green was a little
quiet, and we still scored a bunch of runs.''
</P>
<P>
   The middle of the order _ Sheffield, Green and Karros _ offers
the intimidation factor. But it's the sixth, seventh and eighth
spots that's been so crucial in the Dodgers' early success.
</P>
<P>
   The three in the middle of the lineup are batting .337 with 13
homers, 36 RBI and 34 runs scored. Todd Hundley (or his backup Chad
Kreuter), Adrian Beltre and Kevin Elster, who comprise the bottom
part of the order, are hitting .295 with 11 homers, 33 RBI and 37
runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of strengths in a lot of areas, where if we're
not playing well we could still score runs,'' said Sheffield, who
leads the club with seven homers, 16 RBI and a .382 average.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're ready to get back to the park the next day, you're so
relaxed (when the whole order is producing). It's fun to be here
when you have a team like we have, when you have the balance we
have in our lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   In winning the first two games of this series, the Dodgers
scored 26 runs. Of course, they might need that many with lefty
Carlos Perez going today.
</P>
<P>
   The support of Park began quickly against Pete Harnisch (0-2)
when Hollandsworth hit his first homer of the season to lead off
the first. Michael Tucker tied it in the bottom of the inning with
a one-out homer, the only hit Park allowed in five innings.
</P>
<P>
   But in the second, Kreuter singled in a run and Elster homered
for the second straight day, a two-run shot that gave the Dodgers a
4-1 lead. They broke it open with five runs in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're clicking as a group,'' Hollandsworth said.
``Some of the hot guys we had early are rubbing off on other guys,
and we're picking it up and getting it going. It's a situation
where everybody's feeding off each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The only starter not to get a hit was Green. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
