<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENALTIES A STICKY ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL McDONOUGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The National Football League is facing one of the
stickiest issues it has ever had to deal with, and when a solution
is reached, some of the bigger names in the game are going to get
hurt. Although no one wants to talk on the record about it, there
was a tough debate between the owners and players this past week on
what to do about the San Francisco 49ers and some of the top agents
in the game, who the league feels worked in concert to circumvent
the NFL salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, they cheated.
</P>
<P>
   Some owners want Carmen Policy, current president of the
Cleveland Browns, to be suspended for a year for his role in the
deals that took place when he was heading up the 49ers. During that
period, the league says, the 49ers wrote contracts for Steve Young,
Brent Jones, and Jim Druckenmiller that violated salary cap rules.
Dwight Clark was general manager in San Francisco at the time, and
his name is on the contracts. When Policy left San Francisco for
the expansion Browns, he took Clark with him.
</P>
<P>
   Some time after that, John York became the top man in San
Francisco. His wife, Denise DeBartolo York, had taken control of
the 49ers when her brother, Eddie DeBartolo Jr., got into trouble
with the law in Louisiana and stepped away from the team at the
request of commissioner Paul Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   York became alarmed when Jones reportedly came looking for
$500,000 he said was owed to him after he retired. This prompted
York to look at other 49er contracts, and when he discovered what
he thought was cheating, he turned the team in to the league.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Judge David Doty in Minnesota ruled that the player
agents _ Leigh Steinberg (representing Young), his partner David
Moorad (representing Jones), and Gary Wichard (representing
Druckenmiller) _ are punishable under the collective bargaining
rules. The agents had argued they are not part of the CBA and
therefore are not subject to punishment. Doty ruled against them.
</P>
<P>
   This set the stage for a meeting in New York this past week, and
reportedly an owners committee wants the scalps of Policy, Clark,
and the agents involved. However, insiders say, the union feels all
involved should be punished in some fashion, but that Policy should
not be suspended for the year because Eddie DeBartolo Jr. was the
owner of the club at the time. The union argued that DeBartolo was
in charge and that nothing could be done without his approval, and
now that he is out of the league, there is no way he can be
punished. The union also feels that the present ownership and
management of the 49ers should not be punished because they had
nothing to do with the contracts in question and turned themselves
in.
</P>
<P>
   On the owners' side, the feeling is Policy should be fined and
suspended, and the 49ers should lose some draft choices.
</P>
<P>
   The alleged cheating with Jones and Young reportedly took place
in the year of San Francisco's last Super Bowl championship, and
some say the illegal salary cap maneuvers helped the 49ers win it
all.
</P>
<P>
   Under the collective bargaining agreement, the league and the
union must agree on the punishment, to a degree. Insiders say the
union will not go along with a suspension of Policy for a year but
does believe there should be fines for everyone involved.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the players want tough punishment for the agents, who come
under the domain of the players and can be fined as much as
$250,000 each. Steinberg, Moorad, and Wichard, three of the top
agents in the game, may find themselves out of business in the NFL
for a time.
</P>
<P>
   So, in the end, Policy, Clark, and the agents likely will be
fined, and some, or all, may be suspended.
</P>
<P>
   The action on Policy puts Tagliabue in a tough situation. They
have been good friends for a long time. When Tagliabue and the late
Jim Finks were competing to replace Pete Rozelle as commissioner a
decade ago, it was Policy who led the drive to an upset victory for
Tagliabue. Then, when Policy had a falling out with DeBartolo two
years ago, Tagliabue reportedly was the one who sold him to Al
Lerner as the best president for the Browns.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a good situation for the NFL, and there is no easy way
out for all involved.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here is some interesting behind-the-scenes stuff that took place
on the first day of the draft. After the New York Jets took
quarterback Chad Pennington of Marshall with the 18th pick overall,
the Pittsburgh Steelers offered to trade Plaxico Burress, whom they
had chosen at No. 8, to the Jets for Pennington and defensive
lineman Shaun Ellis. The Jets coveted Burress, the 6-foot-6-inch
wide receiver from Michigan State, and tried to trade up to get him
from Pittsburgh, but the Steelers stood firm and took Burress. With
the 12th pick, the Jets took Ellis and with the 18th pick they took
Pennington. This is when the Steelers offered a one (Burress) for
two (Ellis and Pennington) and the Jets said no. Meanwhile,
Carolina had been gearing up to get Pennington. Carolina coach
George Seifert and Seattle coach Mike Holmgren had a deal in the
works that would let Carolina move up from 22d to l9th to get
Pennington, but the Jets, in a surprise move, took Pennington one
spot in front of the Panthers, canceling the Carolina-Seattle deal.
Baltimore, after selecting Jamal Lewis of Tennessee with the fifth
pick and Travis Taylor of Florida with the 10th pick, still tried
to make a deal to get a late first-round choice. The guy they were
after was Louisville QB Chris Redman. The Ravens couldn't make the
deal but were stunned when Redman was still on the board for them
to take in the second round . . . John Scarpellini of Woods Hole
has done it again. Scarpellini, the national sales rep for Jostens
rings, has won the bidding to make the Super Bowl rings for the
world champion St. Louis Rams, and the AFC championship rings for
the Tennessee Titans. This is the 22d time Scarpellini has won the
bid. The league allows $5,000 per Super Bowl ring for 125 rings,
and $2,500 for the conference championship ring.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With just a little over two minutes left to play in the Super
Bowl, and St. Louis and Tennessee tied, 16-16, the Rams got the
ball on their own 20-yard line after the Titans kicked it into the
end zone. Tennessee, after trailing by 16, had the momentum. What
was Rams coach Mike Martz, then the offensive coordinator, thinking
when he called the next play, which turned out to be an 80-yard
scoring bomb from Kurt Warner to Isaac Bruce? ``Time dictated what
we did,'' said Martz, explaining perhaps the most explosive play in
Super Bowl history. ``I said to myself, `Let's go for something
deep with all four of our guys (receivers) and see if we can hit a
big one.' I thought, at best, we might get into field goal range.
There were five seconds left before the two-minute warning. So we
could run the deep pass routes, and our guys could rest during the
two-minute warning to catch their breath. If we were under two
minutes, or coming out of the two-minute warning, we wouldn't have
called that play, because if it didn't work, our guys would have
been tired and had trouble running the next few plays after that.
Bruce was our first look. He had the man-to-man when Kurt threw the
ball out there. I thought we had a chance for the catch, but I
couldn't believe it when I saw Bruce make a move after the catch
and get the touchdown. But if the time on the clock had been
different, we wouldn't have called that particular play.'' . . .
Most teams thought the Raiders were off the wall when they picked a
placekicker, Sebastian Janikowski, with the 17th choice on the
first round, but not one of the smarter people in the game, Bill
Polian, general manager of the Colts and Executive of the Year in
the NFL. ``He has the kind of talent to be picked there,'' said
Polian. ``If he doesn't have any problems in his deportation case _
and I'm sure the Raiders have done all of their research _ he
should be a great addition for them. However, my only question is,
what are they going to do about his salary down the line? How will
his next contract impact their salary cap, when it comes about?
That would be my big concern. But as far as talent, this kid has
it.'' Janikowski, a native of Poland who played at Florida State,
has been charged with trying to bribe a police officer, and faces
possible deportation if found guilty . . . In the two weeks before
the draft, just about every NFL general manager, player personnel
director, or team psychiatrist was on the record somewhere in the
media across this great land of ours talking about teams looking
more carefully than ever at the ``character'' of players in the
draft. And guess what? They were right: Every single ``character''
on the board was taken by someone, which just shows that, no matter
what a player has done in the past, talent will outweigh character
every day in the NFL. Teams will find an excuse, or invent one, to
take someone who can play, and it isn't going to change no matter
how much they talk about it. Winning is still No. 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 2133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
