<DOCNO> NYT20000422.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4544 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-FREEAGENTS-BOS &LR;      04-22 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FREEAGENTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDRAFTED, UNDAUNTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ You are a member of the Undrafted. You watch the NFL's
selection show for two days, knowing in all likelihood your name
won't be called. As the last round commences, you feel fortunate
that you didn't put all your hopes into a childhood aspiration.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately following the draft, just as you begin envisioning
life after college football, the phone rings. Is it the NFL scout
who said, ``Stay close to the phone,'' during Round 5? No.
</P>
<P>
   It's your agent. Another team wants to sign, ``So let's go for
it,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   This is how it happened for University of Massachusetts
defensive back Jerard White, who was fortunate enough to sign with
his team of choice _ the Tennessee Titans _ after the Washington
Redskins' interest in him waned.
</P>
<P>
   Northeastern linebacker Zach Falconer, who signed with the
Oakland Raiders, had all but given up after the draft and was
considering a co-op job _ until his agent called and relayed the
news that a contract was in the mail.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Eitzmann, the Harvard tight end who was signed by the
Patriots, was among the fortunate ones, as he had a choice between
New England and the Baltimore Ravens.
</P>
<P>
   They are among several players from local schools who made NFL
rosters as rookie free agents, and they hope to take advantage of
the 11th-hour opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always hear people say that guys from smaller schools
can't play with players from larger schools,'' said Eitzmann. ``I'm
going to find out if that's true.''
</P>
<P>
   Other area players who signed include New Hampshire running back
Dan Kreider, who signed with the Pittsburgh Steelers, and
Connecticut defensive back Jordan Younger, who signed with the
Arizona Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Maine sports information officials said Black Bears linebacker
Brent Naccara has been invited to the New York Jets camp and soon
will sign a free agent contract.
</P>
<P>
   Though the three free agents from the Massachusetts schools come
from different backgrounds _ Eitzmann is from Hardy, Neb., White
from Fort Washington, Md., Falconer from Boston _ their stories are
quite similar and probably typical of many players who sign as free
agents.
</P>
<P>
   They grew up with NFL aspirations but had shelved those dreams
for more reachable goals by the time they reached college.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted to work in communications, and I was just
using football as a means of earning a college degree,'' said
White. ``Just shows that anything can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until they were well on their way toward obtaining a
degree (White and Eitzmann have degrees, Falconer graduates this
spring) that the idea of making it to the NFL resurfaced.
</P>
<P>
   For all three, the idea came about after a shift in fortunes.
None was more striking than that of White, who in 1997 merely
wanted to finish up school after the Minutemen endured their worst
season (2-9) of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Then came new coach Mark Whipple, who brought in a winning
philosophy, a few skilled players, and a scheme that led to a
national championship.
</P>
<P>
   He also moved White from safety to cornerback, and as the team
drew more attention, so did individuals like White. He had 15 pass
breakups in 1998, second on the school's all-time list.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, he led the team with 7 interceptions and 13 pass
breakups to go with 43 tackles and 2 fumble recoveries. That earned
him an invitation to the NFL combine, but even before that, he
began following the Titans, hoping they would sign him.
</P>
<P>
   ``My agent (Alan Herman) called me right after the draft,'' said
White, who thought he had a chance after teammate Khari Samuel was
drafted by the Chicago Bears in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't upset that the Redskins didn't call back because I
always wanted to go to Tennessee anyway. Everything worked out to
my advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even before they got to the Super Bowl, I began following
them, and they do a lot of things on defense similar to what we do
at UMass, the way their corners and safeties play aggressively.''
</P>
<P>
   Eitzmann had a stellar career as a tight end, but he benefitted
from the attention given to Harvard teammate Isiah Kacyvenski, who
was drafted by Seattle in the fourth round.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely tougher for someone from a small school to get
a real good look,'' said Eitzmann. ``I think he did a lot for me.
He showed at the Blue and Gray game that Ivy League guys could play
with the big guys, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many players, Eitzmann had an opportunity to become
acquainted with the team that would eventually sign him. He worked
out for Patriots scouts and coach Bill Belichick.
</P>
<P>
   The Ravens called him during the seventh round and again after
the draft, expressing interest in him and another player. But he
told them he was signing with the Patriots, a team he was more
familiar with, and one on which he would have a better opportunity
because of uncertainties at tight end.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I was so excited that they were showing interest,''
he said. ``It's a good situation for me because I know a lot about
the organization.''
</P>
<P>
   For Falconer, a two-thirds qualifier entering Northeastern, the
idea of making it to the NFL began making sense to him over time _
after he was switched from fullback to linebacker after his second
day at camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's been a work in progress, something that has come
along slowly,'' said Falconer.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Eitzmann and White, Falconer didn't receive word for
two days and had all but given up.
</P>
<P>
   That was until his agent, former NU and Raiders standout Sean
Jones, called and told Falconer that his former team had invited
him to camp, and that the contract would be mailed to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still haven't spoken to them,'' said Falconer. ``My agent
has handled everything.''
</P>
<P>
   For all three undrafted players, getting a shot at the pros as
free agents has more than offset the disappointment of not seeing
their names and images flashed on the screen during the draft show
last weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
