<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO-WIN SITUATION FOR STAR-CROSSED PLAYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Glen Day, Olin Browne, Rich Beem, Brent Geiberger, Paul
Lawrie, J.L. Lewis, Tom Pernice Jr., Kirk Triplett, Jim Carter,
Brian Henninger, and Dudley Hart. Pretty good golfers, but you
wouldn't place them ahead of Ernie Els, David Duval, Davis Love, or
Nick Price.
</P>
<P>
   Yet each of those players has cashed a winner's check since the
last time Els, Duval, Love, or Price won a PGA Tour event. Heck,
Duffy Waldorf, David Toms, and Notah Begay have won twice since any
of those four superstars finished first.
</P>
<P>
   Which proves what?
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of good players capable of winning at any
particular time.
</P>
<P>
   And?
</P>
<P>
   The best players don't always win _ but you'll drive yourself
crazy trying to figure out why.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Duval squandered a great opportunity to win the
Masters. Last week, Els fell apart down the stretch at the MCI
Classic. In both events, Love was on the leaderboard, only to fall
short. Combined, these four greats have played 131 times without a
win, dating back more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Duval hasn't won since the BellSouth in March 1999, an 0-for-23
stretch. That triumph culminated an amazing period of 11 wins in 34
starts, so you could say things have changed for him. He concedes
that he put too much emphasis on winning the Masters at the expense
of other tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Els last won in Los Angeles a year ago February. Not that he has
disappeared (he's put up 11 top 10 finishes since then), it's just
that he may have forgotten how to close out a tournament. Is that
it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what happened,'' said Els after blowing a
four-shot lead early last Sunday at the MCI. ``I just lost it. What
can you do?''
</P>
<P>
   Don't ask Love. His last win was at the MCI in 1998. Since then?
Zero for 52. And Price? He's 0 for 30 since taking the FedEx St.
Jude Classic in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
   If he were playing poorly, he'd be worried, but Love said,
``I've been close and had a lot of exciting things happen in
between. So it hasn't been grinding on me or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The others may subscribe to that thinking, too, since all are
playing well this year. Els, Duval, Love, and Price are ranked
seventh, eighth, ninth, and 16th, respectively, on the money list
and have 14 top 10s among them. But each has achieved a status
where the primary goal is to win _ so on that count, they are
coming up short of expectations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As tough as things may seem for Els, Duval, Love, and Price,
there are others off to slow starts in 2000, equivalent to batting
below .200 in April. To wit:
</P>
<P>
   --Steve Elkington has gone 15 rounds since he last broke 70. In
23 rounds, he has shot under par just six times, and he missed the
cut at Doral, where he was defending champ.
</P>
<P>
   --In 14 tournaments, Ted Tryba has not finished better than
T-21, and he has missed the cut six times. His first round of the
year was an 80 at the Mercedes, and in each of his last three
tournaments before this week's Greater Greensboro Classic, he has
had at least one round of 80 or worse.
</P>
<P>
   --Steve Pate had his best finish of the year (T-15) at the MCI
last week, just the third time in 10 starts he was able to have at
least two sub-70 rounds in the same event.
</P>
<P>
   --In eight starts, Justin Leonard has yet to finish in the top
10. In his last 19 medal rounds, he has broken 70 just three times.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With very little fanfare, Seve Ballesteros defeated Colin
Montgomerie in singles, 2 and 1, to lead Continental Europe past
Great Britain &AMP; Ireland in a competition called the Seve
Ballesteros Trophy. What happened Sunday was vintage Seve. He is
ranked 590th in the world now (which means there's probably a
player from Newton Commonwealth ahead of him) and should have been
swamped by the planet's third-best player. But Ballesteros did the
unthinkable: He found a few fairways, and even his errant drives
were playable. Consequently, he was often around the putting
surface in regulation, and his genius could shine through there.
And shine it did. Ballesteros birdied three of the first four
holes, had seven one-putts, and needed just 27 putts overall to
dispose of Montgomerie, an overwhelming favorite, who conceded:
``This was a point we felt was secure.'' Usually, the putting
stroke and short game fade first with older players, but
Ballesteros is a maestro with the flat stick and anything he chips
with. A generation of fans has witnessed only a glimpse of
Ballesteros _ his refusal to exit gracefully. The 81-81 at the
Masters, which included a 9 at the par-5 13th Thursday and a 9 at
the par-5 15th Friday, was sad, particularly for those of us who
consider Ballesteros one of the genuine heros of the sport . . .
Montgomerie, by the way, reportedly is set to put the new Callaway
ERC driver in his bag, even though the club has failed USGA tests
and is banned in this country. The Royal &AMP; Ancient, however, does
not adhere to the same springlike effect test applied by the USGA,
so the club _ which has an ultra-thin face and has been billed as
the company's ``hottest driver ever'' _ has been sold in Japan and
put into play on the Australasia Tour by Michael Campbell . . .
Move over Aaron Baddeley, there's another amateur from Australia
making noise. His name is Adam Scott, 19, and he shot a 63 in the
Greg Norman Holden International this winter. He is playing in
Morocco this week and has sponsor's exemptions into a few more
European Tour events this year . . . Baddeley's next start will be
in the GTE Byron Nelson Classic in three weeks, a tournament to
which former US Amateur champ Hank Kuehne has been invited . . . So
there was Annika Sorenstam lining up a birdie putt when a member of
the animal kingdom entered the picture: a wild turkey. Sorenstam
calmly chased the intruder off the 10th green at last week's Longs
Drugs Challenge, then made her putt . . . Karrie Webb goes for her
fifth win in five starts this weekend at the Chick-fil-A Charity
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Palmer considered doing something he has not done in a
long, long time: withdrawing from an event. Despondent after
opening with an 87 in the PGA Seniors Championship last week,
Palmer told his partners, David Graham and Andy North, ``I'm not so
sure I'll see you on the first tee.'' Graham wouldn't hear of it.
``I told him he'd never quit in his entire life,'' said Graham, who
encouraged Palmer to try out a new set of clubs. Sure enough,
Palmer dug into the trunk of his car, brought out a set of Callaway
Hawk Eyes, and shot a 1-under 71, his first sub-par round this
year. Had Palmer drained a birdie putt on the 18th, he would have
shot his age, a fact that did not escape North. ``If he'd made that
last putt, I wanted a copy of the scorecard I was keeping when he
shot his age,'' said the two-time US Open champion. The King missed
the cut, but the 71 had him in great spirits. ``It makes me want to
play again,'' he said . . . Jack Nicklaus followed his spirited
opening act at the Masters with a solid effort at the PGA Seniors
Championship. He shot 71-71-72 and finished in a tie for 12th, then
said he most likely wouldn't tee it up on the Senior Tour until the
US Senior Open in late June, two weeks after the US Open at Pebble
Beach, which Nicklaus will play . . . Speaking of the Seniors
Championship, it will move next year to Ridgewood CC in Paramus,
N.J., ending a long and sometimes quiet run at PGA National in Palm
Beach Gardens. Crowds were very small for the tournament and it was
somewhat fitting that its farewell was tortured by the weather (it
took five days to play three rounds) . . . Can you say, ``Look out
below''? Leonard Thompson was 4 under entering the final round of
the Seniors Championship when he got into the express elevator
going down, shooting an 85 to lose a bunch of cash. Had he closed
with an even-par 72, Thompson would have made $58,000; instead, he
got $3,400. The biggest hurt came at the par-3 15th, when Thompson
hit four in the water and took an 11 . . . Still, he whipped Phil
Tataurangi by seven. The New Zealander shot 92 Thursday in the
first round of the Greater Greensboro Classic, somehow managing
more double bogeys or worse (seven) than pars (six). Amazingly, he
was 2 under through four holes on the back before going 8 over on
the next five holes to make the turn in 42. He hit three balls out
of bounds at the par-5 second, took an 11, then made three more
doubles and two bogeys for a 50 on the front. He was trying to play
with a pinched nerve, just making ``half swings.'' . . . John
Bickerton of England was lining up a putt on the second hole at
Sunningdale during the Seve Ballesteros Trophy when he got smacked
in the right thigh by a ball struck by Lee Westwood _ his teammate,
no less. Seems Westwood, who had hit a short drive and was unable
to see Bickerton on the sunken green, thought the group ahead had
moved to the third tee. Bickerton said the ball stung, though his
sense of humor was intact. He told Westwood, ``I'm only sorry it
bounced so far from the pin.'' . . . Lawrie, by the way, is not
exactly taking the US pro tour by storm. He finished eighth at the
Mercedes but has missed three cuts in four medal-play events,
finishing T-73 in the other.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
