<HEADLINE>
TV SCHEDULE KEEPS TEAM ON THE BENCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Did you notice that the NBA playoffs started Saturday?
If you did, you can take that three-day vacation and not miss a
thing.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Boston, we look at the NBA playoffs the same way Bob
Hope used to regard the Oscars. As in, ``Gee, I wonder what it must
be like?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, even those who are still playing are angry _ there's
negativity elsewhere _ and with good reason. The NBA, in its
infinite wisdom, is kowtowing to TV once again with scheduling, and
it's worse than ever. Teams are being told to play a game, wait a
few days, play another, wait a few days, and so on. What is this,
the NFL?
</P>
<P>
   Now, Rick Pitino would gladly trade places with any of the 16
men still on their coaching feet, but that misses the point. Pat
Riley called the scheduling ``absolutely insane'' and he's
absolutely right.
</P>
<P>
   Look what the Knicks have in store. They open Sunday afternoon
against Toronto, with Game 2 Wednesday and Game 3 next Saturday in
Toronto. That's three games in seven days. The reason? NBC wants to
have Vince Carter on at least twice, which wouldn't be the case if
the schedule were normal and the Knicks swept the Raptors.
</P>
<P>
   The Heat opened with Detroit Saturday and will host Game 2
Tuesday. Game 3? Saturday. Game 4? The following Wednesday.
Charlotte and Philadelphia play Saturday, Monday, Friday, Monday.
</P>
<P>
   I must be mistaken. I always thought the goal of television was
to increase viewer interest in the playoffs. Let's say,
hypothetically of course, that there's a down-to-the-wire decision
in Game 1 somewhere. And Game 2 would be when? 2007? That is not
how you hold viewers. It's how you push them away.
</P>
<P>
   We all know television has been running the playoffs for years.
It's television that blocks off two weeks for each series. It's
television that insists the NBA Finals are on after the May sweeps,
even though the Finals, with the exception of last season,
generally get pretty good ratings.
</P>
<P>
   But where was the voice of reason when this first-round schedule
was decided? The NBA is not a league that plays every third day.
It's a league that plays three games in four days, four days in
five, back to back. Most teams have maybe three or four breaks over
six months when there are no games over a three-game stretch. The
Celtics had one stretch this season in which they played fewer than
five games in a two-week stretch. And that was unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're allowing people to almost get bored, waiting four days
for games in the playoffs when people want it now,'' Riley said.
``You've been making them wait all year long, 82 games, and now
you're going to make them wait two weeks to get through five
games.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're going to devote two weeks to the playoffs, make them
all best-of-seven. Otherwise, do what you used to do and end the
season on a Sunday, with the playoffs starting Thursday. That
allows for a far more reasonable playoff schedule, not the
silliness we have now. But after the kind of season we've had, why
did we expect common sense to prevail?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mark Cuban, the ubiquitous owner of the Mavericks, no doubt made
a lot of friends among his peers with his comment in Friday's
Dallas Morning News. Cuban isn't afraid to spend money, that's for
sure. ``We're going to push the envelope,'' he said. ``I don't give
a care about the luxury tax.'' Cuban also said he fully expected
the Mavericks to make the playoffs next season. ``I won't accept
anything else,'' he said. Sentiment is growing among some Mavs to
keep Don Nelson aboard for another year. The Mavericks were an
eye-opening 9-1 in April, although Nellie lost out to Charlotte's
Paul Silas for Coach of the Month honors (the Hornets were 9-2).
Dallas, by the way, was 31-21 after Cuban emerged as the
owner-to-be. Throw out the ridiculous Dennis Rodman experiment, and
the record was even better . . . Dallas wasn't the only lottery
team that, like the Celtics, finished strong. The Mavericks beat
the Lakers, Seattle, and Portland in April. Houston won 10 of its
last 15, and that included wins at Portland, Seattle, and Phoenix
as well as a home win over Utah. The Nuggets won their last four,
beating Utah and Portland. Did you notice that the Trail Blazers
were casualties of all three teams? Hmm. Vancouver, meanwhile, lost
seven of its last eight, leaving soon-to-be-released coach Lionel
Hollins with an 18-42 record. That happens to make him the
winningest coach, percentagewise (.300) in Vancouver history. The
Grizzlies' best player, Shareef Abdur-Rahim, met with new owner
Michael Heisley last week. Abdur-Rahim said he might seek a trade
if Heisley, as expected, cleans house and gets rid of Hollins and
GM Stu Jackson . . . The Hornets-Sixers series and the Pacers-Bucks
series have one thing in common: Neither is deemed acceptable fare
for NBC. Each of the other six series will have at least one game
on network television. Those two are condemned to cable . . .
Speaking of the 76ers: They won 17 games by 3 points or fewer
(including two against the Celtics). That's one shy of the record
set by the 1966-67 St. Louis Hawks, who happened to have a player
named Paul Silas on their roster . . . Here's something to take
from the Celtics' season. They won 35 games. Twelve, or more than
one-third, were wire-to-wire wins in which they never trailed. The
Bulls played 96 minutes in the FleetCenter and never had a lead.
The Knicks, by contrast, won 50 games, but had only five
wire-to-wire wins . . . While we're on the subject of the Celtics,
it might be prudent to address the one thing they did more than any
other team: foul. We can't single out the press; they didn't press
that much. The Celtics also were the leaders in opposition free
throws (which, of course, is a cause/effect kind of thing).
Opponents took more than 31 free throws per game against the
Celtics. No other team was as high as 30. The Celtics also finished
next-to-last in blocked shots and, for the first time since
1979-80, no Celtic averaged as much as one block per game.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pervis Ellison is not coming back. We know that. He knows that.
He knew that a long time ago. But that did not stop him from trying
to play the gray eminence role after the Celtics went Jerry
Springer during the game at Orlando. (Apparently, Pitino has
forgotten that incident, as he glowingly talks about how much he
loves his team and how great they are to be around. Remember the
``major suspensions'' and ``major trades''?) It can be hard for a
veteran who rarely plays to be taken seriously. But Ellison, who
knew he wasn't going to be around, nevertheless spoke like someone
who would be and like someone who cared. ``My concern was for those
guys to have a mental approach going into next season that was not
damaged. If you have a losing season, it's tough to get out of that
mindset. It's tough to lose. Take Antoine (Walker). He's been on a
losing team since he's been in the league. That's tough. Anytime
some kind of adversity comes up next year, you can't have someone
saying, `Here we go again.' It's more. You have to have an
understanding of why things happened. I mean, really understand.
You can sit down and have meetings all day, but if you don't
understand why you're losing, you'll be in the same boat next year.
Paul (Pierce) and Antoine are two great pieces. But they're also
young pieces. It's tough on those guys. Losing has an effect on
you. The big thing is: don't let this carry over to next season.
Have the guidelines in place, as opposed to dealing with it when it
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jayson Williams, who missed the entire season, appears to be the
only Net left in Don Casey's corner. Reports out of New Jersey
indicate Casey is a goner. It's the life of a coach. Casey never
had a full deck, but neither did P.J. Carlesimo or Alvin Gentry.
They're out, too. Casey is approaching impending dismissal with his
typical, self-effacing style, which endears him to so many. ``The
only thing I ever plan is a pension,'' he said. ``In this league,
you could literally have a bus crash and every player has a broken
leg and you bring in a CBA team and lose and they'll say, `You
didn't win.' That's hard.'' Meanwhile, Keith Van Horn was talking
about the Nets being cursed with bad luck, which led the New York
Post's Fred Kerber to observe, ``Obviously, this young man has not
been around the Nets long enough. At .378, this was their second
most successful season since 1994 and their fourth best since
1986.'' . . . Ron Mercer had some interesting comments regarding
his wish to remain in Orlando. ``I learned about playing hard every
night,'' he said. ``I never did that before.'' . . . If Darrell
Walker has, indeed, coached his last game for the Wizards, he
certainly went out of town in a blaze of glory. His comments
following the Wizards' pathetic performance against Boston were
right on target. How many coaches would dare to call their players
``gutless'' and suggest that several should be shipped out of town?
``I know what kind of player I was,'' Walker said. ``Maybe not the
most talented, but pretty talented. I came to play every night.
This did not make sense. You have guys who don't need to be on this
team whether they can play or not.'' Walker may be given a job in
the organization, since Michael Jordan is determined to add
basketball people to the basketball operations staff. Among those
Jordan reportedly is interested in: Buzz Peterson (who withdrew
from consideration at the University of Houston) and B.J.
Armstrong. The latter is expected to be offered a job in the Bulls'
organization as well . . . The Celtics and Nuggets finished with
identical records, so there would be a coin flip to determine the
10th pick in the draft. The loser gets the 11th.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
