<HEADLINE>
THE `NAMES' ARE DROPPING IN CHICAGO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Mike Smith, calling the shots in the Chicago
Blackhawks' front office since December, will take another couple
of weeks before deciding what to do about his club's coaching
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no rush,'' said Smith prior to leaving Chicago for a
scouting mission in Zurich. ``You have that luxury in the
offseason.''
</P>
<P>
   If Smith decides to give Lorne Molleken his walking papers,
don't be surprised if the new head coach is not a household name.
The job of being a bench boss, Smith believes, has evolved to the
point that clubs no longer are concerned about hiring ``name''
coaches. He also doesn't believe it's critical to hire someone with
NHL experience, be it as a player or coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's vital is that he has head coaching experience
somewhere,'' said Smith. ``And the key there is not so much knowing
X's and O's. What's most important is that he can get a team to
overcome adversity, because that's what this business is about,
getting over adversity, putting a team together.''
</P>
<P>
   Molleken began this season as Chicago's head coach after taking
over for the final 23 games of the 1998-99 season. But that changed
when the Hawks opened the season a miserable 5-15-4. In the
overhaul, GM Bob Murray was fired and Bob Pulford was brought out
of mothballs to work the bench with Molleken. When the smoke
cleared, Smith was brought aboard as GM and the Pulford-Molleken
combination steered the Hawks to a 33-39-10 finish _ the third
straight year Chicago missed the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's coach, wherever he's coached, has to have dealt with
today's athlete,'' said Smith. ``We are in different times now.''
</P>
<P>
   Gone, said Smith, are the days of the whip hand. Players have
money in the bank. Some are teenaged millionaires. It isn't the
money alone that makes them different, or indifferent, but
financial security somehow triggers a numbing effect, leading
players to tune out coaches who try to rule and instruct through
intimidation. They're immune to the scare tactics of old, when
coaches waved bus tickets before their eyes or caught their
attention with an old-fashioned two-handed stranglehold.
</P>
<P>
   ``The yellers and screamers aren't entirely extinct,'' said
Smith, ``but it's getting close. Today's players don't want to hear
that. They don't want to be humiliated in front of other players in
the room. The days of intimidation are over. Screaming and berating
didn't have long-term effectiveness anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   So where does all this leave Molleken? Probably out in the cold.
</P>
<P>
   The working assumption around Chicago is that because Smith did
not endorse Molleken after the season, a change will be made.
Working Wisdom Part 2 has Smith hiring Maple Leafs assistant Alpo
Suhonen as head coach. Smith was the GM in Winnipeg when Suhonen
worked for the Jets and was instrumental in bringing Suhonen to
Toronto when he was restructuring the Leafs. Now an assistant with
Rick Ley in Toronto, working behind coach Pat Quinn, Suhonen will
be contractually free when the Leafs' season comes to an end.
</P>
<P>
   Next season the Penguins will have Ivan Hlinka, once head coach
of the Czech National Team and now working aside Herb Brooks in
Pittsburgh, as head coach. The 51-year-old Suhonen, who once
coached the Finnish National Team (1982-86), could be the second
European to head an NHL bench.
</P>
<P>
   Suhonen is not exactly a household name, but if Smith is right,
the name game among coaches is going, going, and almost gone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Word is that Bruins defenseman Don Sweeney, a free agent July 1,
doesn't plan to return to Boston. ``It certainly would be prudent
for him to listen to things,'' said his Boston-based agent, Mark
Witkin. ``Honestly . . . I think . . . well, there's nothing
happening now. Don's away right now on vacation, and when he gets
back, he'll probably sit down with Harry (Sinden) and talk.
Certainly it's not a guarantee that he'll stay, but I don't think
he's come to any decision. He's still decompressing.'' . . . Plans
remain in the works for ex-Bruin Ray Bourque to develop a twin-rink
facility north of the city, in conjunction with the Commonwealth of
Massachusetts and the Bruins. ``It's still very much in the
preliminary stages,'' said Bourque's longtime agent, Steve Freyer.
``Construction prices can be frightening for a project like this,
and right now we're trying to get those numbers in focus.'' . . .
While the Calgary Flames are on a mission to get season tickets
boosted from 9,000-plus to 14,000, the expansion Minnesota Wild
already cracked the 13,000 barrier. The Wild's new rink, about 75
percent complete, will include a hockey museum that will display
everything related to Minnesota hockey, including sweaters from
high school teams and those of the NHL North Stars and the WHA
Fighting Saints . . . The Wild hired Brian Israel from the Celtics'
staff to be media relations coordinator, working alongside Bill
Robertson, long one of the NHL's top PR directors . . . What about
Curtis Joseph's five-star nutty Monday night, bolting from the
Toronto net like an escapee from ``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's
Nest''? Referee Mick McGeough was upended, another sad display of a
player's lack of control. Some of these guys (hello, Marty
McSorley) might want to band together and get a group rate for an
anger management course . . . Seeing the overflow crowds in Denver,
it was hard not to think about how the scenario might have played
in Quebec City, former home of the Nordiques/Avalanche. But
consider this: When the Providence Bruins recently played two
playoff games there against the Citadelles, the average crowd was
about 2,000. The night after Game 2 of that AHL series, some 14,000
filed into Le Colisee for a junior game between the hometown
Ramparts (owned by Avalanche goalie Patrick Roy) and Moncton. The
fact that the Citadelles are affiliated with Montreal, a hated
rival from the Nordiques' days, might have been a contributing
factor for the downsized AHL crowd . . . A beer commercial touting
Molson Canadian has rocketed to instant cult status throughout the
provinces. The spot, called ``The Rant,'' has actor Jeff Douglas
(``I am Joe Canada'') espousing the many virtues of his homeland,
underscoring and celebrating how it differs from the US. When it is
shown on rink messageboards, Canadian fans embrace it almost as a
second national anthem. Hardly fair, is it? After all, they already
have the best national anthem. Douglas showed up in Toronto last
week and recited the spot live before a frenzied Air Canada Centre
crowd. He then journeyed to the Corel Center for another command
performance, this time making it a pro-Ottawa soliloquy that poked
fun at the evil empire in Toronto . . . MIT/NHL brain teaser of the
week: If the net were 3 feet by 8 feet instead of 4 x 6 _ but still
a 24-square-foot hole _ would it lead to more or less scoring?
Caution: Answer cannot be given in smoots.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Kings went into their first-round series with little chance
of beating the powerful Red Wings anyway, but ex-Bruins Glen Murray
and Bryan Smolinski were of little help with lackluster play in the
4-0 sweep . . . Garry Galley, an unrestricted free agent July 1,
has had some preliminary talks with LA management about returning
next season . . . The Hawks have the Nos. 10 and 11 picks in the
June amateur draft. ``I don't think we'd make a deal to move up,''
said Smith. ``But it could make sense to move down with, say, one
of those picks and add a pick in the process.'' Smith on the draft
in general: ``It's a better year in Europe (for picks/prospects)
than it is in North America. It seems that way more and more,
doesn't it? But you can't fix your team through the draft. The
draft is a future fix.'' . . . Another Witkin client, ex-BC Eagle
Jeff Farkas, came to terms with the Maple Leafs on a two-year deal
that included a reported $675,000 signing bonus. While the Leafs
were facing the Senators in Ottawa, Farkas was working out at Maple
Leaf Gardens. If the Leafs decide against pushing him into the
playoffs, Farkas will head for the World Championships in St.
Petersburg, Russia, which begin Saturday . . . Don't be surprised
if Eric Lindros ends up in Toronto next season, especially if the
Leafs don't make a return trip to the Eastern Conference finals.
Toronto is one of the few clubs with the kind of income to pay
Lindros $8 million-plus. The Flyers won't get much in return, but
letting Lindros go would be addition by subtraction, and not just
to the bottom line . . . Anyone notice that Paul Allen dumped a
load of Microsoft stock late last month, bringing in a gross $2.3
billion? Allen would be the prime bidder for the Flames, should
they bolt Calgary, and he would move them to Portland, Ore. What's
$70 million or so for a man with that kind of wad in his pocket? .
. . No word on a front-runner for the Rangers' GM vacancy. In
contention: Don Maloney (current assistant GM), Colin Campbell
(ex-Ranger coach and now NHL disciplinarian), and John Davidson
(multimedia legend). Rest assured, former coach Mike Keenan already
has inquired about both jobs. One NHL insider is positive that
Oiler boss Glen Sather, fed up with the Byzantine ownership
situation in Edmonton, will make a serious play for the Rangers job
. . . Ex-Bruin defenseman Jim Schoenfeld, last seen as head coach
in Phoenix, has surfaced as a pitchman for a mattress company in
the Buffalo/lower Ontario area. Always good to have a fallback
position. He is also working for ESPN and showed up in Phoenix as
color man for the Avalanche-Coyotes series . . . Arthur Pincus, the
NHL's vice president of public relations from 1993-99, recently
signed up with WeMedia.com as VP for programming and content.
WeMedia.com will provide webcasts from the Sydney Paralympics in
Australia Oct. 18-29, and plans extensive, year-round internet
coverage of sports events for the disabled . . . NHL commissioner
Gary Bettman brokered the Coyotes sale, with Richard Burke handing
over ownership to the Ellman Co. for a reported $87 million. Word
around Phoenix is that Ellman will retain ownership for
approximately three years, then flip the club to a new owner when
the Coyotes' sparkling new home is built. Hall of Famer Wayne
Gretzky is mentioned as a possible suitor for the Desert Dogs.
Can't you picture the Great One's Coyotes going up against Mario
Lemieux's Penguins one day in the Cup finals?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
