<HEADLINE>
EASLER HAS CARDINALS ON POWER TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ No one blinks anymore, of course, at the news that home
runs are flying out of St. Louis at a record pace. As long as Mark
McGwire is wearing a Cardinals uniform, visitors will assume that
the Arch was designed to replicate the flight of one of Big Mac's
blasts.
</P>
<P>
   But here's the unexpected aspect of the Cardinals' power surge:
Big Mac has been a spectator for much of it. McGwire was sidelined
as of April 11 with back pain (inflammation of the lumbar region of
the spine) until returning to the lineup Thursday, but in his
absence, his teammates took aim at the fences on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   The Cards came into the weekend leading the majors in home runs
with 39, which puts them on pace to hit more than 400 this season.
They had hit at least one in 12 consecutive games. They've hit
back-to-back home runs in seven games. Catcher Eli Marrero last
week hit the first grand slam of his career, and then hit a
412-foot solo home run. Rick Ankiel, the rookie pitcher, followed
Marrero's second home run and went deep as part of a 3-for-3 night.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen of 14 position players had hit home runs for the
Cardinals, the only exception being leadoff man Fernando Vina, who
has been a terrific table-setter, with a five-hit game and a
four-hit game.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the damage the Cards may do when McGwire is healthy
again and Ray Lankford, who as late as Wednesday was hitting just
.120 and was 1 for 16 with runners in scoring position, begins
swinging like he's capable.
</P>
<P>
   And who oversees this collection of Cardinal mashers? None other
than the Hit Man, former Red Sox coach Mike Easler, who is in his
second season as St. Louis hitting coach. Easler, best known for
being Mo Vaughn's personal tutor, has made an impressive return to
the big leagues after it appeared his string had run out when he
left the Sox after the '95 season and became head coach at National
Christian University in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   There were snickers when Easler surfaced as manager of the
independent Nashua Pride in 1998, but no more, not after Tony La
Russa reached out and added him to his staff.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tim Johnson, who returned to the big leagues this season as an
advance scout for the Brewers only to quit for what he called
personal reasons, will manage the Mexico City Reds of the Mexican
League again this summer. Johnson, who lost his job as manager of
the Blue Jays a year ago after being caught lying about serving in
Vietnam, led Mexico City to a championship last season. Johnson,
who distinguished himself in the minor leagues with the Dodgers and
Cubs and as Kevin Kennedy's bench coach with the Sox, hopes someone
will give him another chance in the majors . . . Cincinnati Reds
manager Jack McKeon thinks Holyoke's Mark Wohlers may be back in
the big leagues by June 1. Wohlers, who experienced a Steve
Blass-like loss of control and then underwent elbow surgery,
recently had a bullpen session in Cincinnati in which Sean Casey
and Ken Griffey Jr. swung at 27 of his 35 deliveries. He was
clocked in the low 90s . . . It hasn't taken long for former Sox
outfielder Damon Buford to hear that his job might be at risk in
Chicago. Buford, dealt to the Cubs for utility infielder Manny
Alexander, entered the weekend with a .186 average after a 4-for-28
slump and was benched twice last week, replaced in center field by
Tarrik Brock and Sammy Sosa. Meanwhile, highly touted Cubs prospect
Corey Patterson, playing for Double A West Tennessee, broke out of
a slump of his own Wednesday by going 4 for 7 with two home runs
and seven RBIs in a doubleheader. Cubs manager Don Baylor, who
played with Buford's dad, Don, with the Orioles, said the
20-year-old Patterson is at least a month away from a promotion.
``But the more he hits,'' Baylor said, ``the more we'll be talking
about it.'' . . . Ex-Sox player of the week: How about Elvis,
a.k.a. Mike Benjamin, who came into the weekend hitting .500 (9 for
18) for the Pirates . . . Vaughn, after missing third base to cost
the Angels a run in a 7-1 loss to the Blue Jays: ``I've been in
this league 10 years. I've been around too long for something like
that to happen. It's just stupid. Really. I'm disgusted.'' . . . A
pleasant surprise for the pitching-challenged Angels has been
lefthander Scott Schoeneweis, who is 3-0 and has given up just
three hits in each of his last two starts. Schoeneweis, 26, is a
former Duke University All-American who graduated with a degree in
history and cracked Mike Scioscia's starting rotation after making
31 appearances out of the bullpen last season. Lynn's Ken Hill,
meanwhile, has been bombed (15 runs on 16 hits in 7 IP) his last
two starts, and has a 1-3 record with an 8.84 ERA. Hill insists his
elbow is OK, but speculation has begun that Tim Belcher could claim
Hill's spot when he comes back from a rehab assignment . . . The
Big Unit, Randy Johnson, faced 102 consecutive batters without
issuing a walk until Larry Walker drew a base on balls in the
fourth inning Thursday night. Johnson, who averaged 120 pitches per
start last season and threw more pitches than any other big
leaguer, has gone 133, 112, 109, and 101 pitches in his four
starts, the last three of which have been complete games. He also
has had the first two three-pitch innings of his career, against
the Giants and Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While Pat Rapp continues to be a pleasant surprise for Baltimore
after being cut loose by the Sox, the Orioles believe Scott
Erickson is just one rehab start away from returning to the
rotation. Erickson, who had surgery to remove bone chips from his
elbow, is due to pitch Tuesday for Single A Frederick. Rapp,
meanwhile, is 2-0 for the O's, who have gotten off to a much better
start under new manager Mike Hargrove (9-5 entering the weekend)
than they did against the universally discredited Ray Miller
(3-11). ``For any club it's essential to get off to a good start,''
Hargrove said. ``It makes things so much easier. I don't know that
many pennants are won in the first two, three weeks of the season,
but I guarantee there have been a lot lost.'' . . . Some thought
they'd detected slippage in Billerica's Tom Glavine in 1999, when
he won just 14 games after winning 20 the year before, and his ERA
climbed from 2.47 to 4.12. But the Braves lefthander, who held the
Phillies to a run in seven innings last week, is 3-0. In his last
22 starts dating to last June 15, Glavine is 14-4 . . . The
American League's most potent offense three weeks into the season?
No, not the usual suspects, like the Cleveland Indians. And no, not
the Blue Jays or Mariners, who took turns last week running up
football scores. Try the White Sox, who began the weekend hitting a
league-best .305, with 105 runs, and were second in slugging and
on-base percentage. Quietly, GM Ron Schueler has assembled some
good-looking kids who have been bashing the ball, including Magglio
Ordonez, Carlos Lee, Paul Konerko, Greg Norton, Jeff Abbott, and
Chris Singleton. By the end of the season, they may be joined by
Joe Crede, who was the Carolina League MVP in 1998 before
undergoing foot surgery last year . . . The Blue Jays' seven-game
homestand was a shocking display of pitching ineptitude for a team
that came into the season touted as having one of the best young
staffs in the league. In seven games against the Angels and
Mariners, the teams combined for 201 hits _ that's nearly 29 a game
_ and 142 runs (63 for the Blue Jays, 79 for the opposition). There
were 84 extra-base hits, including 33 home runs. With one pitching
coach in the division already gassed _ Rick Williams of the Devil
Rays, since hired by the Marlins as a big league scout _ it wasn't
a comfortable week for Rick Langford, Toronto's first-year pitching
coach . . . They were finally cooled off by the Blue Jays Friday
night, when their eight-game winning streak came to an end, but the
Yankees woke up Saturday morning with the best record in baseball
and are off to their best start since 1988. What has to be most
discouraging to the Bombers' pursuers is that they've been winning
with lefty Andy Pettitte and third baseman Scott Brosius on the
disabled list, no production from their DH, and ace closer Mariano
Rivera proving mortal for the first time in almost a year. Rivera
gave up a game-tying home run to Texas catcher Pudge Rodriguez. How
deflating was that to the Bombers? The next inning, little-used sub
Clay Bellinger hit a winning home run on an 0-and-2 pitch. As
usual, the Yankees have showcased their phenomenal depth: Ramiro
Mendoza, Lance Johnson, and Bellinger have emerged from the
background to play big roles in wins. Jorge Posada, handed the
everyday catching job when Joe Girardi was allowed to leave, is off
to a great start, as is 37-year-old right fielder Paul O'Neill,
mocking the Yanks-are-getting-old theorists. And you will find a
growing list of people, Joe Torre included, who will argue that El
Duque, Orlando Hernandez, is the best pitcher in the American
League outside of Boston's No. 45 . . . Until Rodriguez took him
deep, Rivera had converted 27 straight save opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who thought the presence of Tommy Harper was going to
jump-start Boston's running game must not have noticed that the
former base-stealing champion is confined to the first-base
coaching box. The Sox tied their own big league record by not
stealing a base until their 14th game, when Trot Nixon swiped one
against the Tigers Wednesday night in Detroit. The Sox of Sam Horn
in 1987 were the last team to go that deep into the season without
a theft. But Harper notes that with Donnie Sadler in the minor
leagues and Darren Lewis primarily on the bench, the Sox have just
two legitimate stealers in Jose Offerman and Carl Everett. What
this team does have, Harper insists, is a number of players who run
the bases well, who know how to go first-to-third, second-to-home,
and make intelligent decisions. That list would include not only
Offerman and Everett but Nomar Garciaparra and Nixon . . . The
Yankees are running more this spring than in the recent past. With
new first base coach Lee Mazzilli in charge of base-running, the
Bombers were successful on 14 of their first 20 steal attempts.
That included Derek Jeter stealing five times in his first six
attempts after stealing 14 bases all last season . . . Hipolito
Pichardo, who pitched two hitless innings in Sarasota, may be no
more than a week away from a promotion to Pawtucket and could loom
as another successful Dan Duquette reclamation project. Pichardo,
who when healthy was one of the Royals' better starters, hasn't
pitched in the big leagues since having elbow reconstruction
surgery that cut short his '98 season . . . Indians catcher Sandy
Alomar has been an All-Star six times. Alomar, out with a strained
hamstring, has now gone on the disabled list eight times . . .
Texas outfielder Rusty Greer reluctantly underwent surgery to
remove bone spurs from his right ankle, but the Rangers figure the
long-term benefits outweigh losing him for 4-6 weeks . . . The
Dodgers claim that Orel Hershiser, who hit four batters in 1 1/3
innings to tie a big league record last week, didn't have enough
time to warm up before the game because the starting time was
pushed up five minutes for TV. Manager Davey Johnson took the rap
for not informing Hershiser of the change.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
