<HEADLINE>
PLETCHER LEADS DERBY CHARGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Trainer Todd Pletcher was once an assistant to D. Wayne
Lukas, but he never thought he'd come close to starting as many
horses in one Kentucky Derby as his prolific former boss.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas, who has saddled the most starters overall with 33,
started a record five in the 1996 Derby, including winner
Grindstone. He also had Prince Of Thieves (third), Editor's Note
(sixth), Victory Speech (11th), and Honour And Glory (18th).
Pletcher won't match his mentor's mark, but, barring injury, he'll
come close, with four starters in this year's Run for the Roses.
</P>
<P>
   Pletcher, who worked for Lukas from 1989-95, intends to enter
Trippi, More Than Ready, Graeme Hall, and Impeachment. Pletcher had
a big day April 15, when Graeme Hall won the Arkansas Derby at
Oaklawn with Impeachment third, and More Than Ready ran second to
High Yield, trained by Lukas, in the Blue Grass at Keeneland.
Trippi has earned his chance to run at Churchill Downs by winning
all four career starts, including the Flamingo Stakes at Gulfstream
April 8.
</P>
<P>
   The son of trainer Jake Pletcher, Todd, 32, saddled his first
winner, Majestic Number, at Gulfstream Park in February 1996 and
came to prominence in 1998, when he scored the most stakes wins in
New York (13) while winning 20 races at Saratoga to lead the
standings. This year will mark his first try at the Derby, and
he'll be involved in a major way, as all four of his colts have
talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how to feel,'' said Pletcher in a conference call
from Keeneland. ``It's a strange and unusual situation. It is a
dream everyone dreams. If you had told me everything would come up
so well in April, I wouldn't have believed you. I'm surprised and
delighted. Wayne had tremendous success while I was with him, and I
don't see how that can't help me. I was part of his organization at
the time Thunder Gulch won the (1995) Derby.''
</P>
<P>
   More Than Ready, a son of Southern Halo, out of a Woodman mare,
was a star as a 2-year-old, winning five of seven starts. However,
he faded in the fall, running third in the Belmont Futurity and
fifth in the Champagne, and was held out of the Breeders' Cup
Juvenile. He came back this year to win the Hutcheson at Gulfstream
(in a dead heat with Summer Note) and run second to Mighty in the
Louisiana Derby, and proved he could handle 9 furlongs by finishing
a close second in the Blue Grass. His career record is 10-6-2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Trippi is a son of End Sweep, out of a Valid Appeal mare. He has
high speed and should be a prominent pace factor in the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Graeme Hall, a son of Dehere, out of a Crafty Prospector mare,
has been steadily improving, and his Arkansas Derby victory put him
over the top. He has a career mark of 8-3-3-1.
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment is a son of Deputy Minister, out of a Misconduct
mare, and is a deep closer. He was flying at the end of the
Arkansas Derby, coming from last, some 30 lengths behind, to lose
second (to Snuck In) by a bob of the head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three of my horses are somewhat speed-oriented,'' said
Pletcher, who rides John Velasquez on More Than Ready but is
holding the other three mounts open. ``Trippi is the fastest,
though, and he'll be forwardly placed. More Than Ready will be
somewhere close if there's not a problem on the first turn. But he
won't be on the lead. Graeme Hall is not necessarily a
front-running horse. That's just the way it worked out (when he
went wire-to-wire in the Arkansas Derby). He controlled a
comfortable pace, but that's not the way it has to be. Impeachment
will trail the field into the first turn. He's absolutely a one-run
horse. As for the distance of the Derby, the question of 10
furlongs is one everybody's got to answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is not to have a speed duel, per se. More Than Ready
is comfortable wherever you put him. Trippi has a lot of speed.
Graeme Hall is versatile. But I certainly hope I don't see all
three of them battling for the lead. I don't think it will happen
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   While presumptive Derby favorite Fusaichi Pegasus was earning
the lion's share of the publicity by winning the Wood Memorial at
Aqueduct April 15, Pletcher's charges were displaying promise in
Arkansas and Kentucky. More Than Ready, Impeachment, and Graeme
Hall were all shipped to Churchill Downs Monday, joining Trippi,
who was already stabled there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pleased with the overall outcome last Saturday,'' said
Pletcher. ``But we wanted to win the Blue Grass, of course. All our
horses are settling down nicely at Churchill. Trippi worked 5
furlongs in 1:01 on Tuesday, and he handled the track very well.
I'm delighted that he got over it so well. Churchill can be a
tricky surface, and not all horses get over it. We'll see about the
others, but More Than Ready can run well over any surface. He
doesn't need to carry his track with him.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing Pletcher may have learned from Lukas, who is a
consummate salesman, is how to juggle multiple owners. Keeping the
people who pay the bills happy is never easy, especially when their
horses are competing in the same race.
</P>
<P>
   Trippi and Impeachment are owned by Dogwood Stable, a public
outfit managed by Cot Campbell, a fine horseman himself. More Than
Ready is owned by James Scatuorchio, who made his money on Wall
Street and is retired. Graeme Hall is owned by Laura and Eugene
Melnyk, who live in Barbados. Eugene is chairman of the board of a
pharmaceutical company, and they name all their horses after
Barbados landmarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prepare each of the horses the best way I can,'' said
Pletcher. ``I hope all four run well. There are no favorites to be
played, and we are doing the best job we can. We try to do the best
with every horse in the barn. Hopefully, that's what gives our barn
an edge, and that's why we've been successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only one winner of the Derby, no matter how many
horses you start. And winning is what we're interested in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
