<HEADLINE>
FOR WALTRIP, IT WAS A MARATHON WEEKEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ NASCAR Winston Cup driver Michael Waltrip says he was
compelled to participate in last Monday's 104th running of the
Boston Marathon _ after driving 500 hard miles a day earlier in the
DieHard 500 at Talladega, Ala. _ for no other reason than this: ``I
just did the Boston Marathon because I could. It's kind of like
getting the chance to play Augusta National or something like that.
If you get that kind of an opportunity, you about have to do it. I
think it's just fun to do.''
</P>
<P>
   And so he did.
</P>
<P>
   After finishing 31st in the 43-car field at Talladega, Waltrip
climbed out of his No. 7 Nationsrent Chevrolet Monte Carlo, hopped
a jet to Boston, and toed the starting line the next morning in
Hopkinton with more than 17,000 other runners. He finished 14,316th
in a time of 4 hours 42 minutes 20 seconds, earned the distinction
of being the only entrant in the field to have run both the Boston
Marathon and the Daytona 500, and dispelled the notion that race
car drivers aren't really athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing at all that compares a marathon to what I do
in the race car,'' Waltrip said. ``Racing is my job and I'm very
serious and very intense about it. I want to beat everyone on the
track. I just did the Boston Marathon for the experience of it, to
see what it's like to run through where all of those college kids
are screaming and to come in at the end in front of all of the
crowds. That is the sole reason I did it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't put a competitive spin at all on my running, unless it
is with myself. Nor do I compare running the Boston Marathon to
running the Daytona 500 or vice versa. One's for fun and the other,
while I enjoy doing it and I love my job, there is a switch that
goes on once I get into the race car that separates me and my focus
from, say, the people who have done the Richard Petty Driving
Experience (driving school).
</P>
<P>
   ``I have people who come up to me all the time saying, `I've
done the Richard Petty Driving Experience. I know what it's like
for you.' Well, that's like me going up to one of those Kenyan
dudes and saying, `I know what it's like.'
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know what it's like.''
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip said his goal was to finish in 4:34, but a 20-minute
delay at the start cost him.
</P>
<P>
   ``After making the first 13 miles in two hours, I saw that
wasn't going to be possible,'' he said. ``I walked through the
watering stations and then got on down the road. I was running in a
pretty large group the whole time. If I would have had a little
kick to give it there at the end, I probably could have passed
1,000 of them. But that wasn't what I was there for.''
</P>
<P>
   He was there to soak up the atmosphere and the pageantry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's the nature of this world to ask, `Where'd you
finish?' or `How come 14,000 people beat you?' '' Waltrip said.
``That's not what running is about to me. I have to be so
competitive and so intense with my job that when I get out on the
road, I just run. I enjoy running. I do it for the fun of it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Going winless over a span of 13 races might not be such a long
period for most NASCAR drivers, but given his track record, it
seemed like a drought for Jeff Gordon, who returned to Victory Lane
with last Sunday's triumph in the DieHard 500. Gordon became the
ninth different winner this season and captured his 50th career
victory, becoming the second driver this season to do so, after
Rusty Wallace won his 50th at Bristol, Tenn. Gordon and Wallace are
now tied with Ned Jarrett and Junior Johnson on the career victory
list. ``This has been a great treat for all of us on the team,''
said Gordon, who delivered his new crew chief, Robbie Loomis, his
first victory with the No. 24 DuPont Chevrolet. ``But one victory
doesn't make a season. We know that we still have a lot left to
accomplish.'' What was most amazing about Gordon's victory was the
fact that he came from the 36th spot in the starting grid. Also
astonishing was the crowd's reaction: They cheered Gordon, who had
come to be resented by fans for his winning ways. It was just two
years ago that he tied a NASCAR record with 13 victories. ``I can't
say that I took them for granted,'' Gordon said. ``I think the
whole time we knew how special of a season we were having in '98,
but I've got to be honest with you, when you pull into Victory Lane
the 10th, 11th, 12th, 13th time, it's not the same feeling. I think
when you work hard and you don't go to Victory Lane and time goes
by, I think you do start to respect it a lot more and realize how
hard it is and how competitive it is to get into Victory Lane.'' .
. . Geoffrey Bodine, who celebrated his 51st birthday Tuesday, got
back behind the wheel of his No. 60 Power Team Chevrolet for a
NASCAR test session Wednesday in Richmond, Va., just 61 days after
suffering extensive injuries in a horrific truck crash at Daytona.
``It was great,'' he said. ``I really missed this _ I missed the
people, the team, and the challenge. I was worried because I didn't
know how long it would take (to get the feel back) but it took
about two laps.'' In all, Bodine did 10 laps, with eight at full
speed. He is aiming to get back to full-time competition for the
NAPA Auto Parts 300 next Sunday at California Speedway in Fontana.
But car owner Joe Bessey isn't pressing Bodine. ``We've got a lot
of re-understandings about a lot of things that need to happen
before Geoffrey gets back in the car,'' Bessey said. ``The main
thing is he's able to get back in the car. I don't think there's
going to be any question about his ability. I'm sure it'll take a
week or two for him to get comfortable.'' . . . Though he has yet
to record a Winston Cup victory, Matt Kenseth moved ahead of Dale
Earnhardt Jr. in the race for Raybestos Rookie of the Year honors.
With his 18th-place finish at Talladega, Kenseth took a 2-point
lead (94-92) over Little E . . . Meanwhile, Tony Stewart, last
year's Rookie of the Year, is struggling. A sophomore jinx,
perhaps? Stewart has yet to lead a race this season and has had to
rely on provisionals to make the field in his last three races.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Simmons, 23, of East Granby, Conn., made his Indy Lights
debut last weekend at Long Beach, Calif. Simmons, a 1998 Boston
College graduate, was impressive in starting fifth and finishing
fourth for Team Kool Green. ``I thought it was a great way to start
the season,'' said Simmons, who made the jump to the Indy Lights
after winning back-to-back titles in the Barber Dodge Pro Series.
``But I still feel like I have a lot to learn yet.'' Simmons spent
the last few days testing at Laguna Seca in Monterey, Calif., and
at Portland, Ore. Though he is familiar with several of the venues
on the 12-race Indy Lights schedule, Simmons will have to make a
transition to the high-speed ovals at Michigan and California
speedways. ``I don't think it's going to be a shock,'' he said.
``But it's going to be one of those tracks where you're (going)
over 200 miles per hour with about 20 cars all around you, so it'll
get your attention real quick.'' . . . It was a banner weekend all
around for Team Kool Green, which had its banner raised by Paul
Tracy's victory in the CART FedEx Championship race. Tracy captured
his first victory of the season after starting 17th, weaving his
way through the pack on the winding street circuit at Long Beach,
where passing historically has been difficult . . . Greg Ray and
Juan Montoya, the reigning open-wheel champions of the Northern
Lights Indy Racing League and CART FedEx Championship Series,
respectively, were 1-2 in a veteran open testing session April 10
at Indianapolis Motor Speedway. Ray posted the fastest speed with a
hot lap of 220.713 miles per hour, while Montoya, whose previous
oval experience earned him advanced placement among the crop of
Indy 500 rookies, was second-fastest in 219.780. ``I don't feel
like a rookie,'' said Montoya. ``I was able to come out with some
very fast times in practice. It hasn't been too hard to adjust to
the new track. Every time I go out in the car, my adrenaline gets
flowing. I'm always trying to push the car to the limit.'' . . .
Sarah Fisher, 19, who is aiming to become the youngest female to
start the Indy 500 as driver for Derrick Walker Racing, took a step
toward that objective by passing her four-phase rookie orientation
with flying colors. ``Indy is probably the neatest place I've ever
run, and it's an honor to pass the rookie test here, especially
with Derrick's return here and my beginning,'' Fisher said. ``I'm
really proud to be here. It's a difficult racetrack to learn, and I
think the most difficult thing I'm learning is the line. Every time
I go around, I gain more and more confidence. I still have some to
gain from a driver's perspective, and we still have some more work
to do on the car, but it's definitely starting to come together. We
just need more practice and more laps, and then we will be
flying.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
