<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4653 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-JUSTICE-1ST     04-22 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-JUSTICE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO MAKES TOUGH CALL MINUTES BEFORE DEADLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for new material, expands to two takes; adds some detail
about Clinton)   (ART ADV: Photo NYT4 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Their self-imposed deadline was 5 a.m., and as the
minutes ticked away before federal law-enforcement officials had to
decide whether to seize Elian Gonzalez at gunpoint, Attorney
General Janet Reno was on the phone to lawyers for the boy's Miami
relatives, appealing to them one last time to end the impasse.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are running out of time,'' an aide to the attorney general
recalled Reno as having said, describing her voice as emphatic but
laced with emotion and fatigue after all-night negotiations.
``You've got to decide now,'' Reno said. ``That's all the time you
have.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, as Reno held the phone in her office at the Justice
Department, a team of eight agents, some of them armed and wearing
body armor and jumpsuits, swarmed into the house of Elian's
great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez. It was just the kind of raid, armed
and confrontational and carried out under darkness, that the
officials had said for weeks was the situation they wanted to
avoid. In fact the image of an armed federal agent flushing the boy
from a closet was displayed on television all day.
</P>
<P>
   Within three minutes the agents were gone, taking the child to a
waiting minivan, ending a five-month-long custody battle that had
haunted Reno, who had tried, and repeatedly failed, to conclude the
case without the use of force.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday morning after the raid, President Clinton said that
Reno had made the right decision and that he supported her. ``The
law has been upheld,'' he said, ``and that was the right thing to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She made the decision,'' Clinton said. ``She managed this. But
I fully support what she did. And it was clear to me from our long
conversations that we were in agreement about this.'' He added, ``I
think she did the right thing, and I'm very pleased with the way
she handled it.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal law-enforcement officials, who had scheduled the
operation for Saturday, had said that they had to begin the
operation no later than 6 a.m., when traffic lights in the area
would change from flashing amber to the normal red and green and
when crowds were expected to gather.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the relatives complained that they were on the phone
with Reno asking for more time as the agents stormed the house.
Reno aides confirmed the account, but said that she had warned them
for hours that time for negotiations was rapidly coming to an end.
</P>
<P>
   Doris Meissner, the immigration service commissioner who was by
Reno's side throughout the night, said the agents' commanders had
asked to be told no later than 3 a.m. whether to begin the raid, a
deadline that stretched another hour as the talks dragged on.
</P>
<P>
   About 4 a.m., Reno warned representatives of the relatives that
time had all but expired. ``At one point she said, `Don't make us
do what we don't want to do,''' an aide said. ```We're going to
take a law-enforcement action and we don't want to do it.'''
</P>
<P>
   The final assault team left its staging position around 5 a.m.,
which Justice Department officials said was the last possible
moment when the raid might have been called off. They said Reno
gave the relatives a final five-minute warning before the operation
began.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, which agents had rehearsed for nearly two weeks,
hinged on their ability to carry out a lightning raid, with little
warning to local authorities, who federal authorities feared were
sympathetic to Cuban-Americans in Miami and might compromise
operational security.
</P>
<P>
   The agents, from the immigration service, some wearing shirts
indicating they were U.S. Border Patrol officers, arrived in force,
some carrying automatic weapons, sidearms and pepper spray. The
weaponry, officials said, was needed to ensure the safety of Elian
and the agents. The authorities were concerned about the
possibility of violence from small numbers of political extremists
believed to be among the demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Saturday, Reno said that she had received
information that there might be guns ``perhaps in the crowd,
perhaps in the house'' and that agents were armed as a justifiable
precaution.
</P>
<P>
   She said Elian's Miami relatives left the government no
alternative but to take the child by force.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   ``I informed the parties that time had run out,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   She expressed frustration over the actions of the relatives in
the long standoff. ``Every time we thought we had achieved what we
wanted, it wasn't enough,'' Reno said. ``It was just one step after
another in which they moved the goal post.''
</P>
<P>
   Photographs taken by a photographer for The Associated Press who
was in the house during the raid showed one of the fishermen who
had rescued Elian at sea five months ago backed into a closet,
holding the startled-looking boy, as a helmeted agent in assault
gear held them at bay.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the photograph, Reno said the gun ``was pointed to
the side'' and the agent's ``finger was not on the trigger.'' Reno
did not say whether any weapons had been found in the house.
</P>
<P>
   As the hours ticked down to minutes, Reno held out hope for a
settlement as civic leaders in Miami tried to broker a deal. From
her office, Reno relayed proposals and counteroffers between
lawyers for Elian's father and the Miami relatives, keeping hope
alive for a negotiated outcome, aides to Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   The relatives' first proposals were so vague, the aides said,
that Reno demanded specifics before she took them to Gregory Craig,
a lawyer for Elian's father. ``The attorney general said she wasn't
going to take an offer that did not contain the components that we
knew would be required,'' an aide said.
</P>
<P>
   As the talks continued, Justice Department officials said, they
began to doubt that the lawyers in Miami were getting cooperation
from the family, who seemed to remain unwilling to surrender the
child unconditionally to his father.
</P>
<P>
   Prodded to come up with a more concrete proposal, the relatives'
lawyer suggested that Elian be moved to a group home in a neutral
location in which father and son would live with the Miami
relatives while a federal appeals court decides whether the child
should remain in the United States, aides to Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   Craig rejected the idea, officials said, countering with the
father's longstanding demand that Elian be turned over immediately,
but agreeing to move to a residence where the relatives would be
able to visit the child.
</P>
<P>
   The indirect discussion, carried out by telephone and fax
between Washington and Miami, bogged down and collapsed. Reno
polled her aides on whether time had finally come for the
law-enforcement action, officials said. Eric H. Holder Jr., the
deputy attorney general, said Reno's advisers were unanimous in
urging her to go forward.
</P>
<P>
   After two telephone conversations on Friday night between Reno
and the president, she advised Clinton of the status of the final
efforts to break the impasse, but did not focus on the timing or
specifics of the use of force to retrieve the child.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Reno had already discussed the potential risks of
such an operation on Wednesday night while returning from Oklahoma
City. Aides said they agreed to use a force that was large enough
to defend itself but one that would be the least traumatic to the
boy.
</P>
<P>
   Then at 2:45 a.m. the White House chief-of-staff, John D.
Podesta, who was receiving hourly updates from the Justice
Department, telephoned Clinton in the White House residence. The
president had postponed a trip to Camp David on Friday night, but
aides said it was because of weather. The aides said Clinton had
said he would support the tactical operation if the negotiations
seemed fruitless.
</P>
<P>
   Podesta woke the president just before 5 a.m. to advise him that
the talks were at a stalemate and that Reno had ordered the raid.
Half an hour later, Podesta called back to report that the
operation had been a success.
</P>
<P>
   At the Justice Department, as officials watched the raid, Holder
said he felt sadness. ``It was not an easy thing to see a boy of
that age carried out like that,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
