<HEADER>
A4754 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-PIRATES042     04-22 0430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-PIRATES0423-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Burkett hurt; Chen steps in
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Braves' intentions for their fifth starter's job
became less clear Saturday night. Or did they?
</P>
<P>
   When John Burkett left the game after three innings with
stiffness in his right shoulder, Bruce Chen threw three scoreless
innings to earn a 4-2 victory over Pittsburgh. After frittering
away the No. 5 job with a dismal spring camp, the left-hander might
wind up with the job anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves won their sixth game in a row and their seventh out
of eight. Though the bullpen game up its first run in a week, John
Rocker worked the ninth for his second save.
</P>
<P>
   Andruw Jones' solo homer in the fifth inning, his fourth of the
year and his second in four games, gave the Braves a 2-1 lead. That
advantage grew to 3-1 the following inning, Keith Lockhart's
fielder's choice with the bases, loaded scoring Wally Joyner.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates scored one run in the seventh, Jason Kendall coming
in from third on a Kevin Young ground-out. That run, off Braves
rookie Luis Rivera, was the first score yielded by the Braves
bullpen in 13 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett was gone before it was dark. After hurting himself while
pitching to Brian Giles in the third, he was able to finish the
inning, facing three more hitters, but was replaced by Chen, who
was recalled from Class AAA Richmond on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   While manager Bobby Cox had said beforehand he hoped to get five
to seven innings from him, Burkett needed 68 pitches just to get
through three. Noted for his control, Burkett threw just 38 strikes
(55 percent) and went to ball-three counts against six of the 15
hitters he faced. He threw nine balls in 11 pitches at one point in
the third, when the Pirates got their first run, but then struck
out John Vander Wal on three pitches.
</P>
<P>
   But Cox refused to view Burkett's first start as a determinant
of his status with the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's savvy,'' Cox said before the game. ``He's only as old
(35) as the rest of our starters. People are talking about him like
he's 50 years old. I mean, the guy can still pitch. I don't put any
emphasis on tonight's game at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves opened the bottom of the first with three straight
singles to load the bases but got only one run out of it. After a
sacrifice fly by Wally Joyner, Andruw Jones and Chipper Jones were
stranded by Brian Jordan's strikeout and Javy Lopez's ground-out to
Pirates starter Kris Benson.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
