<DOCNO> NYT20000422.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4760 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBC-NORTHTEXAS-RECOVE     04-22 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NORTH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH TEXAS FOOTBALL PLAYER MAKING PROGRESS AFTER FIGHTING FOR HIS
LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 TEXAS-RECOVERY-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J. DOUGLAS FOSTER 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENTON, Texas _ Shawn Kramer lay motionless in a hospital bed
with tubes and machines connected to his 6-foot-7, 270-pound body.
His size-17 shoes on the floor only a few feet away, this giant
young man struggled as a petite, dark-haired nurse commanded him,
at times without response, to simply squeeze her hand.
</P>
<P>
   Kramer was fighting for his life in the days following his Feb.
26 collapse at North Texas' first spring football scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we met with the doctors that Sunday,'' said Gary Kramer,
Shawn's father, ``they didn't think he was going to live.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two months later, Kramer continues making a remarkable
comeback. Emergency neurological surgery at Dallas' Methodist
Medical Center kept Kramer alive after he incurred a blood clot on
his brain and two collapsed lungs. He spent 10 days in a coma, 24
days in critical condition and 35 days at the Dallas hospital
before being allowed to go back to his hometown of Topeka, Kan., to
enter a rehabiliation center.
</P>
<P>
   Kramer is far from recovered, but his medical turnaround has
been near miraculous in the eyes of his parents. His father said
his son is in a state of lethargy that varies between unconscious
and complete consciousness. The physical rehabilitation is
progressing, his father said. Shawn walked with a walker for the
first time last week and he has had conversations with family and
friends in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The mental recovery, as the doctors expected, is going slower.
He can hold a conversation but often can't remember it later. And
even through three hours of daily physical and speech therapy, it
likely will be a long time, if ever, before Kramer can remember the
events leading up to his mysterious collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing very well in therapy,'' said Chris Palmer, a
representative of the Kansas Rehabilitation Center. ``He's
progressing fine, but in his mother's words there's still a long
ways to go.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the strides he's made, however, that have his parents
eyeing a new goal _ having him back in classes at North Texas this
fall. That might be wildly optimistic, but his father isn't
doubting his son can do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's already surpassed anything they said he could do,'' Gary
Kramer said. ``If praying helps, he'll be fine, because he's had
plenty.''
</P>
<P>
   Through prayer, the Kramers hope they discover the mystery to
their son's plight. No teammate saw Kramer, an offensive lineman,
take any serious blows at that Feb. 26 scrimmage. After the first
offensive series, he walked to the sideline, sat down on the bench,
then collapsed. Emergency personnel rushed him by helicopter to
Methodist Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the play before, I looked in his face and he was red,''
running back Ja' Quay Wilburn said. ``I just thought it was from
being in the heat of the battle. We got to the sidelines and his
eyes just closed. It was like he was asleep.'' SHOW OF SUPPORT
</P>
<P>
   Kramer's parents recall Shawn telling them he had taken a blow
to the head during workouts on Tuesday that week. They said he was
having headaches afterward and that he sat out of practice on
Wednesday, and was off with the rest of the team on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   UNT head coach Darrell Dickey said Saturday the school is not
allowed to comment on an athlete's medical condition.
</P>
<P>
   His parents praised UNT for its quick response once their son
collapsed, and the university's support. Care Flight was at Fouts
Field in less than five minutes, and Kramer was in surgery less
than seven hours after his collapse. And care during the first 24
hours, one medical expert said, is often the key to first survival
and then recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see a lot of traumatic brain injury cases where the
recovery seems like an absolute miracle,'' said Dr. Mary Carlile,
medical director of traumatic brain injury at Baylor Institute for
Rehabilitation in Dallas. ``If so, it can be credited to early
care. When you get proper early care you see a lot of good
outcomes.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past two months, the Kramers have had a flood of support
from old friends in Topeka to others who never have met their son.
His high school coach, Tom Stringer, and his junior college coach,
Skip Foster, were by his bedside by Monday following his collapse.
He was visited by residents of his dormitory and by high school
buddies. Others sent e-mails to the university, which were
delivered in stacks to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was a genuine and very sincere concern from the
students and administration here,'' UNT athletic director Craig
Helwig said. ``Lots of support, lots of prayers. I know the family
was touched by the show of support.''
</P>
<P>
   Kramer's parents seemed surprised at the volume of letters and
e-mails wishing Shawn well, considering their son's short stay on
campus. Kramer transferred to UNT in January from Coffeyville
(Kan.) Community College.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had only been here two months, and I'm sure the parents
were concerned about him going to a school where he didn't know
anybody and whether or not he was fitting in,'' Dickey said. ``It
was basically the opposite. They found out he was really fitting in
well and meeting lots of people.'' FITTING IN
</P>
<P>
   For those at UNT who didn't get to know Shawn Kramer, friends
and family from Kansas were more than willing to shed light.
</P>
<P>
   To his parents, he always has been sort of a gentle giant,
usually the biggest kid in his class, which is something he
struggled with at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always the big kid,'' Gary Kramer said. ``Sometimes the
big kids don't always have it so easy. My wife and I called him our
big teddy bear. No matter what people said to him, we always told
him, `You can't be fighting people, you're too big.' And he never
did. He just wouldn't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kramer looked past the adolescent teasing to become the epitome
of a student-athlete at Hayden High School in Topeka. He played
football, basketball and baseball and was selected to the National
Honor Society with a perfect 4.0 grade-point average.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't earn a Division I scholarship, but he was determined
to get one. He went to Coffeyville in hopes of improving his
chances. He stayed on track, both athletically and academically,
while at Coffeyville. He started both years and earned a sparkling
3.9 GPA. UNT offered a scholarship last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Denton, friends say, was a perfect match.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shawn's kind of a cowboy,'' said Jeremy Branson, a friend from
Topeka. ``He likes those cowboy boots, and his dad just bought him
a truck. Living in Texas fit him.''
</P>
<P>
   It did, at least until his first scrimmage. Shawn's collapse put
the family's life in turmoil. They tried to cope with what
happened, figure out what they could do to help their suddenly
helpless son and all the while wonder if and when he would improve.
</P>
<P>
   They are not worried about medical bills, at least not yet. Gary
Kramer said the bills will first go through their personal
insurance, then through the UNT athletic department's insurance. He
has been told the NCAA's catastrophic insurance policy will cover
any remaining expenses.
</P>
<P>
   No one is sure how much more progress Shawn Kramer can make, or
whether returning to UNT is a dream or a possibility. But P.J.
Prellwitz, a longtime friend and student at Pittsburg State
University in Kansas, said Kramer has made a habit of beating odds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't the best player (in football),'' Prellwitz said.
``But he would work harder than anybody else. There are a lot of
guys who may have been better than Shawn who aren't playing
football right now, and he still was.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
