<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. CYCLISTS PUT FAITH IN HUMANS, NOT MACHINES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last we saw of them, they were up to their handlebars in
disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   Their Olympic medal expectations had fallen dismally short.
Their team leader/coach was under fire. Their most-decorated
athlete, though she had one Olympic event still to go, had walked
off the team in disgust, leaving only the message, ``No one
cared.''
</P>
<P>
   But, boy, they sure had a nifty-looking bike.
</P>
<P>
   For the U.S. cycling program, the Atlanta Olympics prompted a
tempest of emotions. Some saw it as merely a three-week glitch in
what had been a glorious three-year run. Others harked to the
bottom line _ three medals won, no golds, millions of dollars spent
_ and demanded that somebody clean house.
</P>
<P>
   It is, therefore, a humbled and wiser USA Cycling that will
parade its best track racers in front of the Superdrome crowds this
week at the U.S. Olympic trials in Frisco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The lessons, they say, have been learned. The stars of this show
will be the athletes sweating and competing on the track.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, the rallying theme had been Project '96, a
multimillion-dollar training and technology program that was
supposed to reverse the United States' long run of cycling
frustrations at the international level. Its star and semi-secret
weapon was a $30,000, custom-made, carbon-fiber,
zero-wind-resistance gazelle called the Superbike II.
</P>
<P>
   But as the U.S. cycling people soon learned, any bike can look
super when you put a primed, wily, world-class veteran cyclist atop
it. The Americans won no events.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly there was a lot of excitement and interest around
the Superbike,'' said Texas A&AMP;M graduate Sean Petty, USA Cycling's
director of athlete performance. ``Upon reflection, the bike alone
wasn't going to win any medals. I think one of the lessons learned
from '96 was that we needed to focus on the engine and not the
machine.''
</P>
<P>
   The world governing body of cycling, UCI, made that point
somewhat moot by outlawing the Superbike technology after the
Atlanta Games. This, after all, wasn't Formula One auto racing.
Turning Olympic cycling into a technology contest would have priced
many countries out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we've gone to pretty much a retro bike,'' Petty explained.
``We're riding bikes that in terms of design, in a way, we would
have ridden 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in a lot of ways, it's definitely helped, because it's put
everyone's focus on preparing the athletes physically and
mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the names will be new at this week's Olympic trials.
Gone are three-time Olympian Connie Paraskevin-Young, who medaled
at Seoul in 1988, and Rebecca Twigg, the two-time medalist whose
abrupt departure underlined the problems at Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Among the relative newcomers, Jennie Reid, 21, and Tanya
Lindenmuth, 20, are being counted upon to step up in the sprints.
With Twigg retired, the focus has shifted to Erin
Veenstra-Mirabella, 21, as a medal contender in the points race in
Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   On the men's side, two-time Olympic medalist Erin Hartwell, who
rode the Superbike II, is trying to make the transition from the
kilometer time trial to team pursuit. Marty Nothstein, 29, is back,
after riding to a silver medal in Atlanta in the match sprint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last few years, we learned a lot,'' said Petty, whose
job entails coordinating the program's coaches. ``Atlanta was the
first Olympic Games where professionals were allowed to compete. We
knew they would have a great impact in the road events. But I don't
think anyone saw the impact that the pro road riders would have on
the track events.
</P>
<P>
   ``In team pursuit this year, then, we expect a majority, if not
all, of our team will be made up of pro road riders.''
</P>
<P>
   Gone is coach Chris Carmichael, the architect of the program's
1995 success who was vilified in Atlanta. Carmichael had summed up
the team's disappointing showing with a breezy ``that's sports.''
</P>
<P>
   With new ``old'' bikes, a new team leader and four years of
humble pie on its plate, USA Cycling will parade its hopeful new
look in front of what should be large crowds at Frisco.
</P>
<P>
   Call it Project '00. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
