<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-LAPTOP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MISSING COMPUTER' MAY BRING SECURITY CHANGES AT STATE DEPT. 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER MARQUIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The State Department is considering a
reorganization of its security system after the disappearance of a
laptop computer from an intelligence office with highly sensitive
files about weapons proliferation, a senior administration official
said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright may recommend stripping
the department's Bureau of Intelligence and Research of its power
to manage its own security and place it under the aegis of the
Bureau of Diplomatic Security, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The disappearance of the laptop was reported two months ago by
the Office of Intelligence and Research.
</P>
<P>
   The incident stirred an outcry among some Republican lawmakers.
Rep. Benjamin A. Gilman of New York, the chairman of the House
International Relations Committee, said it was the latest in ``a
long string of security failures'' at the State Department,
including the recent discovery of an eavesdropping device in a
conference room that was believed to have been placed there by
Russian spies.
</P>
<P>
   Although investigators have not determined that the laptop was
stolen, its theft would represent the highest possible breach of
classified material, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The computer contained files designated ``code-level,'' a status
beyond top secret. Officials declined to elaborate on the contents
of the missing material, but confirmed that it involved sources and
methods relating to weapons proliferation, including data gathered
from satellites, and human and electronic sources. New details of
its contents were reported by The Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   The Bureau of Intelligence and Research has been under fire as
having lax security for several years. Department officials
recently considered and rejected a proposal to transfer the
bureau's security to the Bureau of Diplomatic Security, which
protects United States diplomats and foreign dignitaries and fights
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department internal audit in December found that the
department allowed contractors and maintenance staff in the
building without escorts.
</P>
<P>
   Gilman, who plans to hold hearings into the recent breaches,
charged that the department lacks a ``professional environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Some foreign policy analysts ascribed the problems to a culture
that is resistant to onerous security measures, and to budget
cutbacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 2324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
