<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 30)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE WONDERS OF THE INVISIBLE WORLD: Stories &LR;  By David Gates.
Vintage Contemporaries, $12. These mordant tales are filled with
aging male hipsters whose ironic detachment and heightened
self-awareness leave them unable to connect with the real world.
``Gates can be very funny,'' Gerald Marzorati wrote in The New York
Times Book Review last year, but mostly he ``is concerned with
creating characters you haven't met in fiction before, getting just
right the words they use to disengagedly engage their women and
their friends and even their inner selves.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE IMMACULATE INVASION &LR;  By Bob Shacochis. Penguin, $14.95. A
novelist turns journalist in this account of the 1994 American
intervention that returned Haiti's first democratically elected
leader to power. The mission is depicted as a hopelessly absurd
affair in which the Americans' main objective was (despite their
good intentions) not to stop brutality but to protect themselves.
``Shacochis proves that he is a writer of rare grace and
intuition,'' Amy Wilentz wrote last year. He ``never stumbles and
never turns a blind eye.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHY THE COCKS FIGHT: Dominicans, Haitians, and the Struggle for
Hispaniola &LR; , by Michele Wucker (Hill &AMP; Wang, $14), explores the
complex cultural divide between the two nations that share
Hispaniola _ French-speaking Haiti and the Spanish-speaking
Dominican Republic _ and reveals how racism and migration have
shaped their history. This account ``weaves together five centuries
of tragic conflict with a subtle picture of the island today,''
Patrick Markee wrote in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BOY ON THE GREEN BICYCLE: A Memoir &LR;  By Margaret Diehl.
Soho, $12. The author describes how her privileged childhood was
shattered by the death of her older brother and her father's
suicide soon after, and how she retreated into an ultimately
destructive fantasy world. ``Diehl's descriptions of both the
terrible events in her family and the golden stuff of her own
interiority are so entrancing that one realizes too late ... that
fairyland can be a gravityless hell,'' Stacey D'Erasmo wrote last
year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BROKE HEART BLUES &LR;  By Joyce Carol Oates. Plume, $13.95. The
author's 29th novel, which revolves around a Brando-like heartthrob
who disappears mysteriously after captivating the student
population of a small town, is about the mythologizing of
adolescence by unhappy adults. The book ``displays great
inventiveness and a justified belief in its relevance to our own
emotional lives,'' D.T. Max wrote in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SEDUCTIVE JOURNEY: American Tourists in France From Jefferson
to the Jazz Age &LR;  By Harvey Levenstein. University of Chicago, $17.
A history professor chronicles the changing attitudes of American
travelers toward France, blending frank and amusing comments from
tourists' diaries with new insights into the cultural history of
going abroad. ``The result is a thoroughly readable and highly
likable book,'' Deirdre Bair wrote in The New York Times Book
Review in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE LADIES' MAN &LR;  By Elinor Lipman. Vintage Contemporaries, $12.
Harvey Nash is a womanizer in his 50s who reappears in Boston one
day to shake up the well-ordered life of the woman he jilted at the
altar 30 years earlier. ``I loved every page of this very funny,
insightful, sophisticated yet good-natured'' novel, Anita Gates
wrote in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SHAKESPEARE: A Life &LR;  By Park Honan. Oxford University, $17.95.
More is known about Shakespeare's life than most people realize,
and Park Honan does an ``admirable job of collecting, synthesizing
and judging'' the data, Lois Potter wrote in 1999. ``His book _
comprehensive, up-to-date and agreeably written _ is exactly what
it was meant to be: a definitive (for the time being) life.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE LATE MR. SHAKESPEARE &LR; , by Robert Nye (Penguin, $13.95), is
a sprightly tale whose fictional narrator, an actor named
Pickleherring, crams his version of his mentor's life with red
herrings, gossip, trivia and true-to-life details. ``Nye's novel
has more of the real Shakespeare in it than the souffle-light
`Shakespeare in Love,'`` Allen Lincoln wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE COWBOY WAY: Seasons of a Montana Ranch &LR;  By David McCumber.
Bard/Avon, $14. The author, a journalist who signed on for a year
as a hand on a 6,000-acre ranch, describes the hardscrabble culture
of the modern cowboy. ``With uncluttered prose and a laid-back
sense of humor, he underscores the nobility in hard work, personal
responsibility and love of the land,'' one critic wrote in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE TRAVELLING HORNPLAYER &LR;  By Barbara Trapido. Penguin, $12.95.
This novel tracks the intersecting lives of two sisters, one of
whom dies in a traffic accident, and a British novelist and his
dyslexic daughter. ``Trapido keeps us happily engaged in the lives
of her clever, warmhearted characters,'' Edward Hower wrote in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE LAST KABBALIST OF LISBON &LR;  By Richard Zimler. Overlook,
$14.95. In this novel, a young follower of the mystical Jewish
tradition tries to track down his uncle's killer in 16th-century
Lisbon. In 1998 the reviewer Erik Burns admired the ``many-layered
narrative, in which a suitably complex cast of characters plays a
dangerous game with fate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-22-00 2353EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000422.0273 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4783 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-PREVIEW-LA     04-22 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-PREVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREEN, HORRY MAY BE KEY TO LAKERS' SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ Maddeningly unpredictable, uncommonly
aggressive up and down the court, gambling, chaotic and absolutely
unique in oh-so-many facets. That's one way of viewing the
Sacramento Kings, the Lakers' first-round foe and a challenge like
no other they have faced in recent postseasons.
</P>
<P>
   But really, the task at hand is not so different at all. This is
a fill-in-the-blank exercise that stays consistent from one spring
to the next:
</P>
<P>
   If the Lakers' unheralded power forwards, (name 1) and (name 2),
can at least contain All-Star forward (name of player) of the (name
of opposing team), they can win the series.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Webber of the Kings simply has stepped into the
well-established tormenting role that has in previous years been
manned by Tim Duncan of San Antonio, Karl Malone of Utah, Charles
Barkley of Houston, Rasheed Wallace of Portland and, in his
pre-bloated days, Vin Baker of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   New face, same challenge. Old hat to Robert Horry, the Lakers'
lithe forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, you could just take a tape of what I said last year
and reuse it over and over,'' Horry joked on the eve of today's
series opener. ``Those guys are all great players. They're going to
get their points, they're going to get theirs, usually. It's up to
us to go out and just try to do as much as we can to equalize it.''
</P>
<P>
   Same challenge, same philosophy. New tag-team partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know,'' said Lakers forward A.C. Green, ``that we have a
challenge. But it's nothing that we're not used to. It's nothing
that's not expected. We have to go out and play our game. Rob and I
are very capable of doing what we're used to doing all year long to
try and help the team win.''
</P>
<P>
   Horry has been fighting these uphill playoff battles for the
last three years. He now shares the pain with Green, re-acquired by
the Lakers last summer. Green starts, Horry often plays more
minutes and the fourth quarter. Both have the same unenviable task.
</P>
<P>
   Stopping Webber won't be realistic. Limiting his effectiveness
is the only realistic goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is,'' said Kobe Bryant, ``the heart and soul of their
team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' six-year veteran had an MVP-type season, averaging
24.5 points, 10.5 rebounds and 4.6 assists. Against the Lakers, he
was even better. In four games, he averaged 27.0 points, 11.0
rebounds and 5.0 assists, shooting 48.4 percent from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Webber can hurt the Lakers inside and out, with the pass as well
as the shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that if you spoke to (Kings coach) Rick Adelman right
at this moment, Rick would tell you that they probably don't want
him to score 35 points,'' Lakers coach Phil Jackson said, ``but
they sure like those 15 rebounds and 10 assists. He is a player
that plays all aspects of the game, and they run their offense
through him.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's very important for us to play him well, and make him
earn everything. ... But yet they have a lot of complementary
pieces around him that can also do a lot of damage in (Peja)
Stojakovic and (Nick) Anderson and (Jason) Williams and (Corliss)
Williamson and (Vlade) Divac. All these players played very well
during the course of the year. They have (six) guys that have
averaged double figures. We have three. So that makes them a much
more diverse team than us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers don't generally rely on a lot of double-teaming, so
the majority of the burden falls to Horry and Green _ the former
using quickness and length to offset a lack of strength, the latter
using muscle and veteran savvy to offset an inch-height deficit,
20-pound weight deficit and advancing age (36).
</P>
<P>
   Green and Horry represent the latest version of the Lakers'
perpetual presumed Achilles' heel. It became a nonissue in playoff
series wins over the Sonics (1998) and Rockets (1999), but a
glaring weakness in sweeps by the Jazz (1998) and the Spurs (1999).
</P>
<P>
   ``Webber's a dominant power forward,'' the Lakers' Shaquille
O'Neal said. ``We have some pretty good power forwards, but not
many power forwards with big size.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Lakers' defensive philosophy is likely to mirror the
Kings' strategy against O'Neal: concede what you have to concede,
nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let him score, you know?'' Green said. ``Just keep everybody
else down. It's one of those type of situations, really, more than
anything. The other guys, you know certain guys are going to score.
It's the other guys who can really put a nail in you. ... By and
large, you just want to try and keep him close to the averages of
what he had (during the season) and other than that, it's about
playing team defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of Webber's success against the Lakers has come early
</P>
<P>
   in four games, he averaged 10 points in the first quarter, on
Green's watch. He averaged seven points in the second quarter,
primarily with Horry in the game. But in the fourth quarters,
against Horry, Webber averaged just 5.5 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if we can just start on him and keep him at bay, don't
let him come out hot like he usually does, that makes it easier for
everybody else,'' Horry said, ``because they're more concentrated
on Webber and then everybody else gets involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever guarded, the Lakers won't hint at their game plan _ ``Just
play him hard, I don't want to say what we want to do,'' Horry said
_ but they like the contrasting styles they can use.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to do whatever. Sometimes I change it up, sometimes I
don't,'' Horry said, ``but I try to force him to Shaq as much as
possible, try to get a little help from him. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, (using different types of forwards) is a good style
going against Webber, but you never can tell. I think A.C. plays
him better than I do, because A.C.'s a lot stronger than I am. I
contest his shot a little bit better, but that doesn't help,
because he still makes it. So hopefully he'll just have an off
series.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Green, ``We've been very supportive of one another and
sort of have our own strategy going against whatever the opponent
might be for that night.''
</P>
<P>
   It might be a punishing postseason Duncan, Wallace and Malone
might appear here down the road but for Green, any postseason is
welcome. He won two championships with the Showtime Lakers but
hasn't seen the playoffs since 1996 with Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just excited, I'm very thankful to God, just for the
opportunity,'' he said. ``Just playing my 15th year and playing on
a good team, a team that's in the playoffs. I have been out of the
playoffs the last couple years, and so it's a lot of little things
that I'm just appreciative of. And so I don't want to overlook
those things. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to be on a very dominant team. But I know being a
paper team is nothing. That's what this team is used to being, good
on paper but not good at getting final results. So hopefully we can
change that now.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
