<HEADER>
A4784 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-ADVISORY-NY     04-22 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times devoted approximately 3 pages to stories and
photos concerning the Elian Gonzalez affair in editions for Sunday,
April 23:
</P>
<P>
   The NYT News Service has moved the following stories:
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-2NDLD-WRITETHRU (Miami) _ Armed U.S. immigration
agents smashed their way into the Little Havana home of Elian
Gonzalez's Miami relatives before dawn Saturday, took the sobbing
6-year-old boy from a bedroom closet and flew him to a reunion with
his father outside Washington. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-JUSTICE-1STLD-WRITETHRU (Washington) _ Their
self-imposed deadline was 5 a.m. Saturday, and as the minutes
ticked away before federal law-enforcement officials had to decide
whether to seize Elian Gonzalez at gunpoint, Attorney General Janet
Reno was on the phone to the boy's Miami relatives, appealing to
them one last time to end the impasse. By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo NYT4)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-REUNION (Washington) _ Moments after 6-year-old Elian
Gonzalez was taken from a bedroom closet and the arms of a
Cuban-American fisherman, a female voice cooed into his ear. ``This
may seem very scary,'' the woman, a U.S. immigration agent, told
him in Spanish. ``It will soon be better.'' With that modest
promise amid a burst of terror, Elian Gonzalez began a wild ride
Saturday morning that reunited him with his father, Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, who had pressed for his son's return for nearly five
months. By Christopher Marquis.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-SCENE (Miami) _ In minutes, it seemed, the street in
front of the home where Elian Gonzalez had been sleeping awoke to a
loud and raucous protest, as neighbors spilled from their homes and
Cuban-Americans summoned by cell phone rushed to the scene. Their
little boy was gone _ taken by federal agents who stormed the house
at 5:15 a.m. _ and they were not going to keep quiet. By Juan
Forero.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-NJ-1STLD-WRITETHRU (New York) _ Chanting ``Libertad
para Elian!'' scores of angry protesters mounted raucous
demonstrations in New York City and in the Cuban-American
stronghold of Union City, N.J., Saturday against the forcible
removal of Elian Gonzalez from the home of his Miami relatives in a
predawn raid by armed federal agents. By Robert D. McFadden.
</P>
<P>
   (With NYT Photos 3,5,6.)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-MEDIA (Undated) _ It was unintentional that a still
photograph became an instant icon of the television-driven saga of
Elian Gonzalez. The photograph of a federal agent in riot gear,
with a gun pointed in the direction of the little boy in the arms
of the man who had rescued him from the sea, was shown and
discussed all day, rarely mentioned without the words ``searing''
or ``chilling'' attached. And though the photograph demonstrates
the power of a single dramatic image, the Gonzalez family intended
the taking of Elian to be televised live. (A Critic's Notebook.) By
Caryn James.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo NYT7)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-NEWSPHOTO (Undated) _ Early television coverage of the
Elian Gonzalez situation relied heavily on a photograph by The
Associated Press that quickly became a focal point in the debate
over whether the Justice Department had used excessive force when
it removed the boy from the Miami home of his relatives early
Saturday morning. The photograph showed a federal agent in green
riot gear and goggles carrying a machine gun and facing off against
a frightened-looking man who was holding Elian. By Jim Rutenberg.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-POLITICIANS (Washington) _ In harsh language laced
with outrage, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas criticized the Clinton
administration for its decision to use force when it transferred
custody of 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez to his father early Saturday.
Bush said the photograph of the frightened boy being ``removed from
his home at gunpoint'' was ``chilling'' and ``not an image a
freedom-loving nation wants to show the world.'' By Don van Natta
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-GIULIANI (New York) _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani lashed
out at the Clinton administration Saturday for the early-morning
raid that snatched Elian Gonzalez from the home of his Miami
relatives, saying that the government had sent ``storm troopers
using guns'' to do the bidding of Fidel Castro. By Thomas J. Lueck.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-HAVANA (Havana, Cuba) _ They are calling it the rescue
of Elian. ``Through a police operation, Elian Gonzalez was rescued
from his kidnappers in Miami,'' was how the excited commentator on
Cuban state radio described it 90 minutes after the raid, an
unusually swift delivery of news. But as this city awoke to the
news that U.S. agents had taken Elian from the Miami home where he
has stayed with relatives opposed to President Fidel Castro, the
streets appeared calm and normal. The government here had broadcast
warnings not to celebrate because ``that could negatively affect
the outcome of the case.''By Randal C. Archibold.
</P>
<P>
   EDIT-CUBAN-BOY _ The sight of heavily armed federal agents
breaking into Lazaro Gonzalez's Miami home before dawn Saturday to
take custody of Elian Gonzalez is a disturbing picture for all
Americans, and is likely to haunt the country for years to come.
Attorney General Janet Reno should have given the two branches of
the Gonzalez family more time to try to resolve the case amicably,
and she should have applied more legal pressure on the Miami
relatives before battering down their door to remove Elian.
</P>
<P>
   (From a New York Times editorial appearing in editions for
Sunday, April 23.)
</P>
<P>
   From The Week in Review section:
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-BOY-REVIEW (Undated) _ If the Elian Gonzalez case
illustrates anything, other than the peculiarly overheated state of
Cuban-U.S. relations, it is that courts run on adult time, with
unhappy consequences for the children they are trying to help. By
Somini Sengupta.
</P>
