<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS READY TO GET DOWN TO BUSINESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ Kobe Bryant, model citizen and
ever-available for a quote, rushed out of the building. Coach Phil
Jackson made a brief appearance, then bolted. Ron Harper conducted
interviews from the driver's seat of his silver luxury sedan.
</P>
<P>
   It was not business as usual at the Lakers' practice site
Saturday, 24hours before they open the playoffs against the
Sacramento Kings at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anxious,'' Rick Fox said of the team's mood. ``I think we've
worked on everything we could possibly work on, from the
understanding of what they do, to what we want to do ... but
knowing that it's the first round and you have to `come with your
best game,' as TNT says, `or go home,'we have to be prepared to do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was displeased with his team's practice Friday, so how
about Saturday's? ``What did he say?'' Fox wondered. Told Jackson
left without being interviewed, Fox said, ``Well, that should tell
you.''
</P>
<P>
   This will be Fox's third postseason in L.A., but as everyone has
noted, this one is unique the Lakers are the clear favorite to win
the championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does it feel different? No, because we've felt it before,''
Fox said. ``It feels different than last year; I don't think we
were expected to do much last year after a season of such turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, yeah, since I've been here, we've never been the best
team record-wise and we've never been defending NBA champions, but
for some reason, we've become the hunted after obviously going out
and doing all the hunting during the regular season. So it's a
strange feeling to know that here you have the San Antonio Spurs,
who are defending NBA champions, and no one's even talking about
them defending their title.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are trying to maintain a sense of perspective, and
Harper who won three titles with the Chicago Bulls
</P>
<P>
   offered his teammates a final bit of wisdom Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ron put it best when he said, `Don't believe the hype. We
haven't won anything yet. And no one's going to go handing us any
rings (today) atStaples Center.' And it's true,'' Fox said. ``It's
so true. We've had agreat regular season, but that means nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   SILENT TREATMENT: Jackson, possibly tempting an NBA fine,
decided not to take questions from the media Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nothing to say,'' Jackson told a room full of
reporters. ``I've said everything I have to say the last two days,
and I just thought I'd come out here and just nod to you all and
say thank you for showing up today. It's a pleasure to see you. And
seeing that I have an appointment that's pressing, I will leave you
all here and see you again tomorrow before the game. Thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   PLEASED TO MEET YOU: This is only the second time the Lakers and
Kings have faced each other in the playoffs. The other meeting was
a first-round series in 1984, when the Kings were still based in
Kansas City. The Lakers swept 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   THE DRILL: Keep history in mind today: The winner of Game 1 has
gone on to win best-of-five series 83.3 percent of the time (130 of
156). The team with home-court advantage has won 114 of 156 series
(.731).
</P>
<P>
   TICKETS AVAILABLE: A limited number of tickets, to today'sgame
only, will be released this morning, the Lakers announced Saturday.
Tickets can be purchased through Ticketmaster and at the Staples
Center box office. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
