<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4787 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     04-22 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS COULD HELP L.A.'S IMAGE WOES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When L.A. looks into the mirror, it doesn't see
its fair weather, its mesmerizing shoreline, its mountainous
curves, its exotic features, its nose for innovation.
</P>
<P>
   Like a bodybuilder who stares in the mirror and sees a 98-pound
weakling, L.A. suffers from a distorted self-image. It can't see
its many positive qualities because it is fixated on its muscles.
</P>
<P>
   They appear to have atrophied the past few years. In the 1980s
L.A.'s muscles commanded everybody's attention, but now L.A. flexes
them on the stage that is the professional sports scene and nobody
so much as blinks.
</P>
<P>
   Some people have even taken to laughing L.A. off the stage.
Don't think that hasn't worked on the city's psyche some.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that L.A. still has plenty to preen about. It simply
can't get over all that definition that has just disappeared
despite its best efforts to regenerate it. Where oh where did the
Pedro Martinezes, the Henry Rodriguezes, the Danny Mannings, the
Vlade Divaces, the Al Davises and the Georgia Frontieres go?
</P>
<P>
   It hurts L.A. deeply to see lesser rivals such as St. Louis
muscle their way past it on sport's biggest stages. Don't think
L.A. didn't notice the Rams' Super Bowl win this year or Jim
Edmonds' super start for the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   It was just more salt applied to the open wound that is the
city's self-image.
</P>
<P>
   If L.A. visited Dr. Melfi's couch, you can be sure it wouldn't
take Lorraine Bracco's ``Sopranos'' character long to get the city
to own up to feelings of inadequacy.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to play a psychiatrist on television to recognize
the root of the problem: The Dodgers, Clippers, Kings, Lakers,
Angels, Galaxy and Mighty Ducks haven't had a loving cup to spit in
since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   After winning eight pro team championships in the 1980s (five by
the Lakers, two by the Dodgers and one by the Raiders), L.A. went
0-for-the-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Marty McSorley's illegal stick threw the Kings a curve in 1993
and it's almost as though all of L.A.'s muscles went into oxygen
debt after that. It really has been painful to watch L.A. stagger
to the finish line of the 20th century, what with the Clippers
stringing together 13 losing seasons and the Dodgers, Lakers and
Kings each having gotten swept off the road in their past two trips
to Playoffland.
</P>
<P>
   Lose Angeles, indeed. The city has been so busy picking broom
bristles out of its teeth it really hasn't joined the chorus of
people singing the praises of this year's Lakers squad.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Lakers under first-year coach Phil Jackson looked
impressive in compiling a league-best mark of 67-15. And yes, only
one time in NBA history, in 1973, has a team been as successful
during the regular season and not waltzed away with the
championship.
</P>
<P>
   The city wants to stand as tall as the Riddler's Revenge at Six
Flags or the First Interstate World Center, but this thought keeps
weighing it down: If the Boston Celtics could lose in 1973, why not
the Lakers now?
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, L.A.'s psyche these days is more fragile than Kobe
Bryant's sprained right wrist or Shaquille O'Neal's gimpy left
ankle.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. doesn't want to have that beaten feeling. It wants to
scream ``Sacramento (Stinks)'' and have it not come off sounding
mickey mouse.
</P>
<P>
   The city desperately wants to believe Divac, the former Lakers
forward turned Sacramento stalwart, won't expose the Lakers's
low(ly)-post defense. The city wants to believe the Kings'
fast-break will crash and burn when it hits the Lakers' wall of
defense.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. is trying to think positive. Which is why, everywhere
Bryant goes, he hears a familiar refrain. The city is telling him
to ``bring home a championship,'' and that ``the time is now'' for
the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant is only 21 years old, which is too young to understand
that what L.A. really is saying is it's high time L.A. got its
groove back.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, more of a stranger to L.A. than Bryant but infinitely
more familiar with the symbiosis between sporting success and a
city's psyche, said, ``The 90s haven't been a whole lot of fun for
us. (But) We're coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeing is believing. Forget the mirror; for the next few weeks
the basketball court is where L.A. will see itself reflected. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Karen Crouse's column appears in the Daily News four days a week.
She can be reached at (818) 713-3619. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
